m politician involved and party leader. no pickup</note>
national assembly candidate luis mejia miranda on monday ridiculed reports he was involved in misusing u.s. aid money. ``can you imagine that if i had ... ($2 million) i would still be in this country?,'' he asked
president jose napoleon duarte's son denied he was trying to protect mejia, a fellow christian democrat who was reported under investigation in the case
i deny any tie because i am not protecting him and because i am against corruption,'' said alejandro duarte, candidate for mayor of san salvador in the march 20 elections
the new york times said sunday that mejia is being investigated for allegedly misusing up to $2 million of u.s. aid
it said the money was part of a $10 million program to assist war-ravaged areas and help win the support of salvadorans in the war against leftist rebels
the newspaper quoted unidentified salvadoran and u.s. officials as saying it could be the largest case of theft of u.s. aid money during the administration of president duarte, elected in may 1984 for a five-year term
in an interview with local newspapers, mejia said ``that news (about alleged misuse of funds) surprises me because it is totally false.''
rodolfo castillo claramount, duarte's vice president and secretary-general of the governing christian democratic party, said the article was ``full of vagueness and imprecisions with the political intention of damaging the party.''
he said it was written ``within a strategic conception of the ultra-right of the country.''
he also read a communique saying the party backed alejandro duarte as ``an absolutely honorable, capable and honest man.''
referring to allegations against mejia, the communique said ``we abstain from making a value judgment because we do not know if there is evidence.''
alejandro duarte denied being an associate of mejia and said he had urged mejia to cooperate with any investigation
it is vital that the truth be arrived at,'' he told reporters. ``if he (mejia) is clean, he does not have to be afraid. if he feels he is outside of the accusations, then he should submit himself to any investigation.''
all this is a dirty political game and i feel indignant for having been involved,'' alejandro duarte said
asked about his relationship with mejia, he replied, ``i have no personal friendship with him. i know him like the majority of the members of the party.''
the new york times said mejia resigned three months ago as director of the national commission for the restoration of areas, but president duarte agreed to allow him to become a party candidate for the national assembly on the recommendation of alejandro duarte
a u.s. embassy source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said ``these allegations are being studied.''
at this time the inspector general of aid (the u.s. agency for international development) has made no determination of bad use of funds in this program,'' the source said. ``however, other recent studies have identified certain aspects of financial control and management of conara (the restoration commission) and since january of this year there have been some changes in the method of management.''
castillo claramount said the party asked for an investigation of the alleged theft of funds. if there is evidence it occurred, the party will ask the assembly to remove the immunity merida enjoys as a substitute deputy and will ask the electoral council to revoke his candidacy, he said
two french-cooking schools _ one the oldest, the other the newest _ are giving the world's gastronomic capital yet another culinary lift
cordon bleu, the oldest and most prestigious, has taken on a high-tech image at a new location in a five-story building that once was an infirmary
the luxurious ritz hotel, the newest, is opening its kitchens april 5 to students of haute cuisine
the cachet of the elegant right bank hotel is maintained in the decor of its new basement cooking school, where gleaming white-tiled spaces and hand-painted murals set the tone
the cordon bleu, long situated in cramped quarters in the classy champ de mars district under the eiffel tower, moved in january to the building on an anonymous corner of the 15th arrondissement in southern paris
the school where servants from affluent families long ago watched cooking demonstrations in an amphitheater now offers every high-tech amenity, including video screens
both schools offer all levels of instruction up to professional
despite the new home, tradition at the venerable cordon bleu remains intact. the top diploma at the cordon bleu is awarded to students who pass a nine-month session. the ritz school's top diploma follows a 12-week course
hardly a newcomer to fine food, the ritz has been known for its cuisine since auguste escoffier attracted international gastronomes early in the century. it decided to spread its know-how as part of an overall renovation plan started by mohammed al-fayed, the egyptian entrepreneur who bought the hotel nine years ago
we feel we're offering unique and superior instruction for a private cooking school,'' said gregory usher, an american who left the cordon bleu to take over the ritz school's administration. ``our chefs are tops.''
the courses are to be supervised by three of the ritz's own chefs, all winners of the top professional award, meilleur ouvrier de france. most daily courses will be handled by two chefs with credentials from prestigious french restaurants. one, andre guillut, perfected his english while working at restaurants like l'orangerie and ma cuisine in los angeles
the up-to-date equipment includes permanently cooled pastry marbles, the latest in ovens, freezers and mixers. the hotel's meat smoker will be used for ``charcuterie'' courses, and video outlets are available for taping recipes
pupils can browse in a reference library, taste wine with the ritz's sommelier, and the change and shower after the course in a special area
across the seine at cordon bleu, in the business since 1896, it's a whole new world
spanking clean in light greys and blues, today's big-scale school includes two demonstration rooms, four huge cooking and pastry rooms, and a beautiful winter garden
equipment includes convection ovens, pastry-rising ovens and huge dough-kneaders, plus special machines for a new course on vacuum-packing and cooking _ to be taught by patrick martin, the 1987 winner of the french national cuisine and pastry trophy
we're still emphasizing traditional french cuisine,'' said robin cahill, a cordon bleu graduate and its spokeswoman. ``but in our expanded facilities just about everything is new.''
the basics are still the main point,'' said chef martin, one of seven chefs. ``the students will still learn how to chop, knead, whip and do everything else by hand as well.''
the overwhelming majority of cordon bleu students are from abroad _ about 30 percent american and 20 percent japanese, said ms. cahill
while the ritz plans english translations in all courses, the cordon bleu still teaches its advanced courses in french
financing for the modernization comes from the pages group, headed by andre cointreau, which bought the school in 1981
intermediate students at the ritz may choose a one-to-six week course of practical sessions and demonstrations at cost in french francs of about $800 a week. the ritz's highest-level auguste escoffier course, a 12-week session, costs about $10,000
cordon bleu's main three 12-week courses comprise a cycle of ``basic'' through ``superior'' at a cost of about $4,200 each
to get the coveted cordon bleu grand diplome, pupils now spend nine months, reduced from 12, in intensive cooking and pastry courses preparing for the big exam, at a cost of $19,000
we're also offering new intensive four-day practical and demonstration sessions,'' ranging from charcuterie to regional cuisine and costing about $500, said ms. cahill
both schools conduct wine tasting courses
a visitor to paris who wants to compare the big-school ambience of the cordon bleu with the tonier ritz can attend demonstrations at either one for less than $35 each
rockwell international corp. and two former managers pleaded innocent monday to charges that they overbilled the air force by $450,000 on a sophisticated satellite navigational system
in a brief hearing, u.s. district judge consuelo marshall ordered the company and its former managers to file pretrial motions by april 4 and set a may 3 trial date, rockwell spokesman jeff charney said
he indicated the company plans to make pretrial motions but declined to elaborate
the company and the former managers _ donald carter, materials division director at the its seal beach plant, and robert zavodnick, manager of major subcontracts within the division _ were named in a 25-count federal indictment in january
the indictment alleged that the company and two men double-billed the government for work on the navstar global navigational system that uses radio signals from satellites to pinpoint locations on earth
as a result, the indictment claimed, rockwell received $450,000 in unlawful profits
the company has denied the allegations. ^an ap extra</head>
militant monks in tibet and restive armenians in the soviet union are among the minority nationalities in those countries now testing, sometimes with violence, the limits of their governments' professed policies of openness
moscow calls them ``hooligans.'' to beijing they are ``splittists.'' but to both countries they represent a threat to the reputation and unity of the state
thirty-one people died last week in rioting in the soviet city of sumgait in azerbaijan, where christian armenians are unhappy about being part of mostly moslem azerbaijan. in tibet, up to 23 have died in clashes between chinese police and tibetans in october and over the weekend
in both countries, the communist governments in the past have suppressed their minorities to unite vast tracts of land under the ruling ethnic group, the hans in china and the russians in the soviet union
josef v. stalin purged the ukraine in the 1930s, and mao tse-tung swiftly cracked down on unrest in tibet and moslem west china in the 1950s and 1960s
both countries, with china in the lead, have now declared greater tolerance for different views, exposing both to flashpoints of nationalist sentiment
china blames outside forces for its troubles, saying pro-independence supporters of tibet's exiled religious leader, the dalai lama, were responsible for the first outbreak of violence in the tibetan capital of lhasa last october
moscow is faced with a wider problem of ethnic disputes in armenia, religious identity in kazakhstan and political activism in the baltic republics of estonia and lithuania
foreign journalists in china have had slightly better access to the troubled areas than their moscow-based counterparts. china expelled 14 foreign journalists from lhasa last october, and has since given permission for only a few to return
but lhasa authorities, hungry for tourist spending to help china's poorest province, have not stopped group tours, and some reporters have joined excursion groups to tibet
the soviet union let a few correspondents go to vilnius, lithuania, on a foreign ministry-sponsored trip for a planned demonstration to mark the feb. 16 declaration of independence
but reporters there were followed constantly
no foreign journalist has been allowed lately into armenia or azerbaijan. telephone calls to yerevan sometimes went through, but nagorno-karabakh, the center of the armenian-azeri dispute, cannot be reached at all and sumgait only rarely
reflecting moscow's ``glasnost'' and beijing's similar policy of ``kaifang,'' the official media in both countries have carried limited reports of the disturbances
china's press has stressed that only a small number of tibetans have joined the disturbances, and has sent out a barrage of stories about tibetans criticizing the separatists and saying how much better life is under socialism
the government has stressed that it will continue to respect the local customs and help alleviate poverty in the regions where the nation's 67 million non-han minorities live
moscow, too, has linked the rioting to a small number of ``hooligans.'' soviet leader mikhail gorbachev, however, in a feb. 18 speech stressed the importance of working out a new policy on nationalities and said the cental committee would hold a special plenary session to discuss the matter
an army private who flew his small airplane into prohibited airspace over president reagan's santa barbara county ranch must spend 30 weekends in jail
ralph william myers, 33, of fort lewis, wash., convicted of lying to authorities about the reason he strayed into prohibited airspace on aug. 13, was sentenced monday by u.s. district judge manuel l. real
despite a probation department recommendation of probation, real sentenced myers to three years in jail for each of two counts of making false statements and then suspended all but 60 days of the incarceration. the judge also ordered myers to donate 1,000 hours to charitable service
myers' jail time will begin april 9 and is not to interfere with his military service. myers could have been sentenced to 10 years' imprisonment and a $500,000 fine
outside court, myers said he was made a scapegoat by the federal government because reports that there had been a near-miss caused ``hysteria.''
myers maintains his plane was no closer than 800 feet from the president's helicopter, marine one. reagan's marine pilot, lt. col. michael glynn, says myers' plane passed about 200 feet in front of his helicopter and 150 feet below it
myers' attorney, manuel araujo, said they will appeal the sentence
myers, who has been stripped of his pilot's license, originally told federal agents he strayed into the prohibited airspace while looking for a lost contact lens in the cabin. he later said he had lied about the lens because, ``i was trying to stay out of more trouble.''
myers was demoted from private first class to private for being absent without leave. he still has 18 months left in the army. 10.</note>
a group of men backing panama's new government seized control of the country's disputed consulate in london monday night by smashing through the glass door with a land rover, police reported
the british broadcasting corp. said the seizure took place because the consul in london, eduardo arango, refused to give up his post despite being fired by the new government
control of panama's embassy in washington is also in dispute following the ouster on feb. 26 of president eric arturo delvalle. he was removed from office after he tried to dismiss gen. manuel antonio noriega, the military leader and de facto ruler
the london consulate is about a mile east of the embassy. the bbc said arango was not in the consulate when the raid occurred
police said in a statement that six men _ two representatives of panamanian ambassador guillermo vega and four members of a british security firm _ smashed their way into the consulate
shortly after this, several people left the building, including three women believed to be secretaries, and a number of security staff. one glass-paneled front door was damaged and no one was injured as a result of the incident,'' the statement added
one of the staff members forced out of the consulate, tourism commissioner rolando domingo, 24, said: ``we were just working in there and then suddenly we heard a crash.''
he said the land rover broke through the glass doors and then a group of men burst into the building carrying large hammers. ``they threatened us with hammers and one tried to hit my face. they took my passport and documents. then they pushed me down the stairs and out of the building,'' domingo said
london police sealed off the area around the consulate in tudor street in the city, london's financial district
the united states and many other countries still consider delvalle the president of panama. he was removed from office by the national assembly, which is dominated by noriega supporters
the reagan administration has called for noriega's ouster since he was indicted in florida last month on drug trafficking charges
the bbc reported that arango was in panama at the time of delvalle's ouster and has said he helped smuggle delvalle from his residence to a hiding place in the central american country
the british domestic news agency press association said arango received a phone call at home from the consulate staff about the monday night raid
the agency quoted arango as saying he was prevented from entering the consulate after the attack and that one of the men occupying it had told him they were working for vega and carrying out orders from panama
british government officials said they were told last friday that arango was being fired as consul
arango said he had received letters from panama saying he was dismissed but had ignored them, press association said
as workmen repaired the doors, one of the british security guards who took part in the raid said:
it is an exaggeration to say we smashed in. we nudged the doors with the land rover. the police say they may prosecute us for mounting the pavement (sidewalk) but i don't think they can do anything else. we were authorized to enter the building but i cannot divulge any more.''
the four guards involved work for gb security, a private security company based in south london. they said they would be guarding the building overnight
a spokesman at the british foreign office, who in accordance with british practice declined to be named, said it was too early to say what action, if any, foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe might take over the incident
david r. bradley sr., chairman and chief executive officer of the st. joseph news-press &amp; gazette co., has died at age 70
bradley, who died sunday at a kansas city hospital, was the second generation of a communications family that has published the news-press and gazette for nearly 50 years
he was publisher of the st. joseph newspapers from 1956 to 1981, succeeding his father, henry d. bradley, as president of the company in 1972. the elder bradley died in 1973
bradley was known for keeping the newspapers on the leading edge of technology, switching to all-electronic production more than a decade ago. he also led the company into the tv market
the company's holdings include stations in savannah, ga.; jackson, miss.; hattiesburg, miss.; sioux falls, s.d., and wilmington, n.c., and cable tv systems in st. joseph, savannah and macon, mo
he was active in the associated press and served as a director of the news cooperative from 1970 to 1979. he also was first vice chairman of the ap, serving in that position from 1977-79
dave had a unique combination of common sense, a sharp business mind and a zest for life,'' said louis d. boccardi, president and general manager of the ap. ``you could count on him to help you get to the heart of any problem, but also to remind you that your problem was probably a little less earth-shaking than you thought it was. he was a treasured friend and a wise counsel.''
bradley was born in toledo, ohio, and graduated from the university of wisconsin in 1939
survivors include his wife, shirley wyeth bradley; two daughters; two sons and 11 grandchildren
funeral arrangements were incomplete sunday
wind, cold and snow moved thorugh the central rockies today, producing brisk wind gusts, thunderstorms, hail and snow squalls
the cold front moved into idaho and parts of utah and wyoming on sunday evening. at pocatello, idaho, wind gusted to 41 mph as visibility dropped to a quarter mile in snow squalls
thunderstorms broke out when the cold front passed through northern utah, producing small hail, frequent lightning and scattered power outages. wind gusted to 45 mph in the trenton and logan areas. the storm dumped up to a foot of snow in utah's mountains, and lesser amounts elsewhere in the state
snow and blowing snow was reported late sunday across central and southern wyoming. wind gusted to near 40 mph at rock springs and visibility at laramie dropped to a half mile. up to a foot of snow was expected in the southwest mountains of wyoming
eight to 16 inches of snow was expected in the mountains of colorado. high winds should cause blowing and drifting snow and poor visibility in the state's mountain passes
elsewhere, thunderstorms moved through parts of southeast virginia and eastern north carolina on sunday evening. nickel-size hail was reported at gatesville, n.c., near the virginia-north carolina line
santa ana winds were expected to develop across southern california today. a wind advisory was in effect for the northern mountains of southern california. by tonight, winds may gust faster than 50 mph in some canyon areas of the san bernardino valley
clear skies covered most of the nation this morning, but dense fog advisories were posted for parts of northern and central florida and southwest louisiana
temperatures ahead of the cold front were mild sunday, with a 72-degree reading at st. george, utah. the high for the nation sunday was 88 at yuma, ariz
temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. est ranged from 14 at yellowstone, wyo., to 71 at homestead air force base, fla
for today, rain or snow showers were forecast from northern arizona and the central rockies across the northern plains; and scattered rainshowers from northwest kansas to the upper mississippi valley. skies should be mostly sunny over the eastern third of the nation, except for a few snowshowers over northern new england
much of the nation should have highs in the 50s or 60s. highs should be in the 30s and 40s from the northern and central rockies across the northern half of the plains and the great lakes region into new england. temperatures should reach the 70s and low 80s from southern california across the desert southwest, and from the southern plains to the southern atlantic coast
