traders said the pound was strong throughout europe because of relatively high british interest rates
gold prices were lower in london and higher in zurich
the metal opened in london at a bid price of $437 a troy ounce, compared with late friday's $437.50. at midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $436
one bullion dealer said market participants in london were taking profits following friday's technical rally in new york
it is going to keep falling,'' he said. ``there is a lot of selling around.''
in zurich, the bid price was $434.25, up from $432 late friday
earlier, in hong kong, gold rose 54 cents to close at a bid $438.75
silver was quoted in london today at a bid price of $6.38 a troy ounce, down from friday's $6.41
prince charles thrilled spectators by shaking hands on both sidelines after beating an american polo squad assembled for the royal occasion
i can't believe it. i was so shocked,'' said anabelle mariaca, who shook hands with the prince of wales after the 90-minute match sunday at the palm beach polo and country club. ``i told him i was from bolivia, and he said, `i bet the weather is better there than here.' ''
the prince's windsor park team beat palm beach 6-4 on a soggy field doused by occasional rain. the prince, scheduled to fly home today via new york, scored a goal on a penalty shot, and teammate peter brant said charles saved five or six goals on defense
he played very well,'' brant said. ``he hadn't played in competition since the end of august, but he made some beautiful back shots.''
spectators included king constantine of greece and maj. ronald ferguson, father-in-law of prince andrew, charles' younger brother
charles' wife, princess diana, had other commitments, a buckingham palace spokesman said. andrew and his wife, sarah, finished a 10-day tour of southern california sunday and headed back to london
officials said the prince's visit with spectators afterward was unplanned but not unusual. to the fans, however, it was clearly a surprise
chris zeiser of west palm beach, who shook hands with charles, apologized to him for the weather
well, i'll have to come back again,'' replied the prince, who has visited the club twice before
about 8,500 people attended the match at the 6,200-seat stadium. both the sporting event and a luncheon for about 500 people beforehand benefitted friends of the masai mara, a conservation group for a wildlife habitat in kenya
the founders of the organization, geoffrey and jorie kent, were the prince's hosts and the first to greet the prince and king when they flew in saturday from pittsburgh, where they had attended a fund-raising dinner friday
charles, who has been outspoken recently about architecture, went from the airport to visit developer donald trump's 118-room mansion mar-a-lago in palm beach. charles spent two nights at the kents' ranch west of lake worth
charles was the honored guest at a wildlife demonstration conducted on the polo field by jim fowler of tv's ``wild kingdom,'' who presented a lion cub, aardvark, several birds and a 7-year-old cheetah
when fowler coaxed an eagle to fly to him by holding up scraps of food, the prince asked, ``is that off the luncheon menu?''
the eagle landed on the back of fowler's hand with a message in its claw. charles, who read it to the audience, said, ``all wildlife thanks those gathered here for your interest in wildlife.''
the prince joked, ``i didn't know this eagle could write, though clearly it does.''
cheetah handler cathryn hilker took charles' right hand, and together they petted the cat's face. the prince seemed reluctant, but the animal licked his hand
she loves men's hands because they have hair on them,'' ms. hilker explained
hundreds of roman catholics chanted ``we want religious freedom!'' after thousands crowded into a cathedral for a mass honoring a 13th-century czech princess who renounced royal wealth to serve god
the mass on sunday at st. vitus cathedral, in the castle complex where communist president gustav husak lives, drew about 8,000 people
it was one of the biggest religious services in the capital since the communist takeover in 1948 and an indication of the reviving strength of the nation's roman catholic church
dozens of plainclothes security officers were seen inside and outside the cathedral while mass was held to honor the princess who is to be canonized by the vatican later this year
police arrested 16 dissidents and religious activists under 48-hour detention orders on friday and saturday, apparently to prevent them from attending the mass. a dissident source said five people remained in detention sunday night, but four of them were expected to be freed today
augustin navratil, a roman catholic activist from moravia, was detained friday morning but there was no word he was free late sunday, the source said
navratil was the author of a 31-point church petition for more religious freedom that has gained more than 300,000 signatures, making it the largest such action in the soviet bloc since 1945
five other dissidents were briefly detained when they tried to visit a british diplomat friday, and two others also were briefly held that night
after the mass, about 1,000 people went from the cathedral to the nearby residence of cardinal frantisek tomasek. a few hundred chanted ``we want bishops,'' ``we want religious freedom'' and ``we want the pope.''
the chanting crowd appeared to reflect growing discontent among catholics at the lack of bishops in 10 of the country's 13 sees
the vatican has refused to accept government proposals to appoint as bishops members of the state-sponsored pacem in terris organization, a group of priests not recognized by the holy see
long live the holy father'' was another chant from the crowd outside tomasek's residence, which adjoins the castle where husak lives. the presidential flag was flying, indicating the 75-year-old president was home during the unusual demonstration
there is no official estimate of the number of believers in czechoslovakia, but vatican officials estimate about 60 percent of the 15.5 million citizens are catholic
soldiers turned back reporters and other motorists at a roadblock at the southern end of beersheva, about 10 miles north of the scene
a group of onlookers shouted insults at journalists gathered there and one man threw a rock at a tv crew. ``why don't you go photograph in the west bank. you are the cause of all of this,'' shouted one man
reporters at the checkpoint saw six or seven ambulances rushing to beersheva starting about 10:45 a.m. one army ambulance stopped and reporters could see the bodies of three arabs which a policeman at the scene identified as terrorists
