falling bond interest rates and unexpectedly high tuition increases have forced duquesne university to suspend a trendsetting tuition prepayment plan, according to school officials
the small roman catholic university announced three years ago that alumni could enroll their newborn children for $4,450 as full tuition payment for four years of education. the plan was expanded in 1986 to include non-alumni
the college takes the money and invests it, with the proceeds covering tuition for four years of college when the child is grown
the plan prompted about a dozen other private colleges to follow suit. six states also adopted plans that would enable parents to prepay a fixed amount of the child's college tuition, starting at birth
duquesne spokeswoman ann rago confirmed sunday that the university's board of trustees had voted wednesday to suspend the plan
when we began the program, it was a much different economic climate, but things have changed so we decided to suspend it,'' she said
the college will keep its commitment to 622 families already enrolled in the program, ms. rago said
when the plan was created, according to ms. rago, the university's rate of return on the bonds was 10.8 percent. it has since dropped to 8.52 percent, she said
tuition for 1988-89 recently was raised 8 percent, rather than the originally projected 6 percent
the university found it would be necessary to raise the 1987 tuition prepayment for a newborn to $8,630. that was calculated to cover tuition costs of $102,604 over four years, ending in the year 2005
for a 15-year-old, the one-time investment rose from $12,864 to $24,310
at this time, those numbers don't make the plan feasible,'' ms. rago said. ``the administration will re-examine it if the economic conditions change.'' 
hungarian intellectuals and a member of parliament have called on hungary to allow more ethnic hungarian refugees to emigrate from romania and appealed for international support in monitoring their rights
about 20 people spoke at the all-day forum sunday in a theater in budapest. more than 700 people attended the meeting, participants informed the associated press by telephone from the hungarian capital
the meeting sunday was the second one of the ``democratic forum'' since the group was formed on sept. 27 in southern hungary. the document issued at the september meeting called for ``genuinely effective reform'' to resolve hungary's economic and social problems
the meetings are unusual in communist hungary because authorities, although they have not officially recognized the forum, have not prevented them from taking place, and the results have been discussed in the official press
most of the speakers sunday focused on the ethnic hungarian minority in romania
hungary and romania are warsaw pact allies but have engaged in increasingly sharp rhetoric over the question of the ethnic hungarian minority in transylvania in recent months
transylvania was ruled by hungary before world war i, and both nations claim the area is the cradle of their national cultures and history
hungarian officials say increasing numbers of romania's nearly 2 million ethnic hungarians have sought refuge in hungary
geza szoecs, an ethnic hungarian poet from transylvania who now lives in switzerland, suggested that the hungarian government consider allowing a certain quota of ethnic hungarians from romania emigrate to hungary
he suggested the quota correlate to the number of hungarians who apply for asylum in the west each year, as well as the general decline of the population through the sinking birthrate
however, zoltan kiraly, a member of parliament, warned against establishing a refugee program that would help romanian communist leader nicolae ceausescu get rid of the hungarian minority
ethnic hungarians have said they are increasingly restricted in the use of their language and expression of their culture in romania, which denies the charges and accuses budapest of meddling in its affairs
kiraly told the gathering he and five other parliamentarians drafted a resolution calling on the government to set up a settlement fund for transylvanian hungarians who wish to stay in hungary
he said the draft resolution, which is to be put before parliament when it meets in spring session later this month, also calls on the government to seek the cooperation of the united nations and the international red cross and to mobilize international public opinion
kiraly, one of the most outspoken members of parliament, said many hungarians who enter hungary from romania go on to third countries because the hungarian authorities are not prepared to receive them
he said many of these ethnic hungarians, if given the chance, would opt to stay in hungary because of the cultural affinity. of aids</head>
single women are changing their attitudes about sexual relationships because of the threat of getting aids, according to a poll conducted for people magazine
the national telephone survey, conducted by market facts of new york, asked 500 women ages 18 to 49 about the impact of aids, the magazine reported in this week's issue
the survey found that the threat was on their minds even though the medical community has said very few aids cases have occurred outside of the known risk groups, which include homosexuals and intravenous drugs users, people said
the poll found that 75 percent said they were extremely or very concerned and 40 percent said their sex lives had been directly affected
of those who said their sex lives have changed, 78 percent said they've become more choosy about sex partners and three-fourths said they want to know a new partner's sexual history and insist that he use a condom, the poll said
acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer
it is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring
survivors and those who lost loved ones in a ferry disaster retraced the voyage of the herald free enterprise, casting wreaths and notes over the spot where it capsized a year before
daddy, miss you,'' said one of the more than 100 cards dropped into the water sunday, a cold, bleak day with a fine drizzle _ remarkably similar to the day the herald turned over and 193 of its passengers died
others joined in prayer sunday in this belgian port and across the north sea in the english port of dover to mark the worst peacetime disaster involving a british ship since the sinking of the titanic in 1912
about 270 set out from zeebrugge and stopped just outside the harbor wall where the ferry capsized march 6, 1987, when water rushed in through its open bow doors five minutes after it left port
for 20 minutes they cast flowers onto the choppy seas from the baltic ferry, which the herald's owners p and o pressed into service for the sad pilgrimage
some were led away to be comforted by red cross and social workers. others clung to their families. a few went off by themselves and stood looking into the murky waters
on the upper car deck, which was transformed into a makeshift chapel bedecked with flowers, prayers were said by three clergymen _ an anglican, a roman catholic and a major from the salvation army _ during a half-hour service
this service can mark a new beginning,'' said the rev. peter bowers, vicar of st. peter's and st. paul's church in dover. ``it does not mean we forget those who we have loved. ... in fact, it is from that memory that we build a new future.''
his words were echoed by the bishop of dover, the rt. rev. richard third, who told more than 600 bereaved at the anglican church of st. mary the virgin in dover that it was time to leave their grief behind
it is right to grieve. it is health-giving to express your sorrow _ but you can't go on doing it for a lifetime. there must come a moment when you surrender your grief, when you stop crying.''
at st. donaas roman catholic church across the road from zeebrugge port, the sunday service was turned into a memorial for the ferry victims
the rev. wim catry also offered prayers that the survivors and bereaved would be able to reconstruct their lives. he said in his sermon that a rose garden and plaque would be unveiled in may in front of the church to commemorate the dead
andrew parker, who turned his body into a human bridge so 20 passengers including his wife and daughter could walk across his back to safety, paid his own private tribute
he went out on a belgian tug to the spot where the herald capsized and with his 13-year-old daughter janice dropped 193 flowers into the water, one by one. his wife, eleanor, like several other britons who came here, remained onshore, unable at the last minute to relive their nightmares
said mrs. parker: ``i hate this day _ i just wish i could take it off the calendar.''
