u.n.-sponsored afghanistan peace talks resumed today with uncertainty persisting over whether pakistan is ready to sign an agreement with the soviet-backed kabul government which it does not recognize
resumption of talks came after unprecedented consultations between the pakistani government and opposition leaders attended by islamabad's chief negotiator, acting foreign minister zain noorani
sources close to the meetings held during the weekend in pakistan said most of 19 opposition parties urged the government not to stand in the way of the proposed pullout of the estimated 115,000 soviet troops helping kabul to fight moslem insurgents
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev has said a withdrawal could start in mid-may if a settlement is signed by next week
in an interview published today, pakistani president mohammad zia ul-haq said his country will not budge from its demand for an interim government in kabul as part of a settlement
the gulf news daily reported that zia was optimistic that the proposed peace accord on afghanistan will be signed on schedule
there is no question of the accord not going through. allowing it to be dropped is no option,'' he was quoted as saying
upon his return to geneva sunday night, noorani said the formation of a broad-based transitional government was as important as the troop withdrawl in bringing peace to the region
why should we not insist on an interim government,'' he said in response to a question from a reporter at the airport
last week noorani said pakistan would make up its mind after the islamabad consultations on whether to sign a settlement with the present kabul government of president najib, which pakistan does not recognize
he put up only a cryptic smile when asked again before today's session if islamabad was now prepared to sign
pakistan has insisted that any agreement on the withdrawal soviet troops should be linked to formation of an interim government that is acceptable to all sides in the 9-year-old war
the islamabad government says this is the only way to ensure the safe repatriation of 5 million afghan refugees from pakistan and iran
pakistan has been representing afghan rebels at the u.n.-sponsored talks, which began in 1982
the resistance movements, which say they represent 200,000 guerrillas, have rejected any power-sharing with afghanistan's president najib and have presented a plan of their own for an islamic government
the afghan government says its own policy of national reconciliation envisages a ``coalition government'' open to all political forces including the pakistan-based resistance movements
the soviet union, which sent its troops in december 1979 to help a faltering marxist government suppress a moslem insurrection, no longer demands a transitional government be formed before withdrawal
diego cordovez, the u.n. undersecretary general who has been mediating the afghan talks, said last week all major differences had been resolved in the first three days of the new negotiating round, which began last wednesday
the two sides agreed on a nine-month timetable for the withdrawal of soviet troops from afghanistan. cordovez said this agreement, following years of stalling on the timetable issue, represented a ``significant step'' toward a final political settlement
the sides also agreed that half of the soviet troops would leave in the first three-month phase, the so-called ``front-end loading'' which had been a major concern of the united states. conform; picks up 14th graf pvs; iran's foreign...</note>
iran and iraq shot missiles into each other's capitals today and both reported dozens of deaths as the ``war of the cities'' persisted between the two persian gulf war foes
iran's official islamic republic news agency said 12 civilians, including women and children, were killed and 30 wounded when an iraqi missile exploded in tehran today. it said a hospital clinic, several houses and 30 vehicles were destroyed in the blast
the missile was one of three iraq said its army shot into tehran early today in the latest round of the bruising offensive that has claimed hundreds of lives in both countries
irna said another 61 civilians were killed and 427 wounded sunday in iraqi air raids on 16 iranian cities and towns
the agency said schools and hospitals were hit in the wave of iraqi raids on the southern city of shiraz and dezful, arak khorramabad and other population centers in the west. eight other people were wounded in missile strikes on tehran on sunday, it said
it said iraqi artillery was shelling the northwestern border town of marivan, but made no mention of casualties or damage
baghdad communiques said iraqi fighter-bombers flew 118 combat missions against ``military and economic targets'' in 12 iranian cities sunday in retaliation for ``criminal attacks on iraqi civilian areas.''
irna reported that revolutionary guards fired four missiles into baghdad today
it said they were aimed at ``military centers.'' baghdad said the first two missiles crashed into residential sections of the capital, killing or wounding ``many civilians, including women and children.''
the agency said iraq retaliated by firing three long-range ``al hussein'' missiles, named after a 7th century shiite moslem saint, into tehran today
ina quoted a military communique as saying: ``iran's rulers must realize their weakness and stop fighting.''
the eight-day missile exchange has been the fiercest since the gulf war began in september 1980 and the first time that tehran has been hit by missiles
iraq says it has fired 41 projectiles into the iranian capital since the eye-for-an-eye missile duel began feb. 29, when iran sent two missiles crashing into baghdad
iran's foreign minister, ali akbar velayati, admitted saturday that ``more than 30'' missiles had hit tehran
the iranians have reported firing 22 missiles in that period, but the iraqis have only acknowledged 18 hits
iran has reported at least 106 civilians killed and more than 200 wounded in the iraqi missile blitz, with more than 100 killed and more than 500 wounded in air raids over the last week
iraq has reported heavy civilian casualties, but has given no numbers
