arab guerrillas in southern israel hijacked a passenger bus today and held it for three hours before israeli troops stormed it, killing three gunmen. three israeli civilians also were killed and eight were wounded, an army communique said
israel's state-run radio said the terrorists infiltrated from egypt and were armed with fragmentation grenades, assault rifles and a submachine gun
a man claiming to represent the palestine liberation organization's force 17 phoned a western news agency in jerusalem and claimed responsibility for the hijacking
israel radio said a plo spokesman in tunis told cbs news the group was not responsible for the attack. but a survivor from the bus said she heard the arab gunmen say they were from fatah, the plo faction headed by yasser arafat
a special anti-terrorist unit and border police stormed the bus, which was loaded with nuclear plant workers and hijacked near the aroer junction eight miles from the dimona nuclear facility
prime minister yitzhak shamir linked the attack to the rioting in the occupied west bank and gaza strip
these are the same people who incite violence in the (occupied) territories. we shall not tire from fighting them,'' said shamir
he noted today's attack was the second infiltration in two days. three palestinian guerrillas were killed by army soldiers on sunday after they tried to cross the lebanon border
israel radio and officials said the terrorists came across the lightly guarded border from egypt at night near ramat nafha and commandeered an israeli military automobile at about 7 a.m
the arab guerrillas drove the renault-4 towards the beersheva-dimona highway, throwing a hand grenade at an israeli semi-trailer but causing no injuries
the army and witnesses said a volvo bus with the nuclear workers was coming from the opposite direction, and the gunmen fired at the bus and threw grenades until it stopped
most of the passengers and the driver escaped but a man and nine women remained, the radio said
the last bus hijacking inside israel occurred on april 12, 1984, when four bomb-weilding palestinians hijacked an israeli bus near the mediterranean coastal city of ashdod. a soldier was killed on the bus when israeli troops stormed the vehicle and captured the hijackers
officials at soroka hospital in beersheva said eight women were admitted for treatment of gunshot wounds
police forced the bus to stop after the terrorists fired from the bus at passing people and cars. police closed the area, and army officers entered into negotiations with terrorists
the arab gunmen demanded to speak with representatives of the international red cross and also asked for a loudspeaker
maj. gen. yitzhak mordechai, commander of israel's southern region, decided to storm the bus rather than negotiate further after the gunmen opened fire
we made every effort to both relax them and to promise them that negotiations may bring results,'' mordechai told reporters at the scene
(but) they fired at us twice and afterwards they fired and killed one of the hostages and fired at women who were inside the bus,'' he said
in all, he said, the storming operation lasted about a minute
mordechai said the man was killed by arab gunmen during negotiations. he said shots fired by the terrorists when the bus was stormed appeared to have killed the women
the victims were not identified, apparently because of the sensitivity of their jobs
at the hospital, david, a curly-haired man in his late 20s, said he saw armed terrorists block the blue volvo bus, a special commuter vehicle carrying women workers from a plant in dimona
the terrorists blocked the bus and didn't give the driver a chance to turn around and get away,'' he said. ``the driver opened the door and many of the passengers scrambled out. about a half-dozen remained on the bus.''
david said the bus hijacking began about 7:30 a.m. and he watched the hijacking from another bus. he declined to give his last name
rafi hayon, a motorist traveling the beersheva-dimona highway, said the arab gunmen armed with soviet-made automatic rifles shot at his car when he refused to stop for them
i saw only two kalashnikovs in front of my eyes,'' he said in an interview broadcast by israel radio
it was the bloodiest attack by palestinian guerrillas since a hang-glider attack in late november in which a guerrilla landed in northern israel and shot to death six israeli soldiers and wounded eight
the dimona plant is at the center of a secret trial now going on in israel
mordechai vanunu, a former nuclear technician at dimona, revealed israel's atomic secrets to the sunday times of london in an expose published oct. 5, 1986. based on vanunu's information, the newspaper concluded israel possessed the world's sixth largest nuclear arsenal
in the sunday times story, vanunu detailed the route taken by 40 blue and white volvo buses he said transported workers to the nuclear plant each day
vanunu, 33, was tried on charges of treason and espionage for revealing israel's nuclear capability and the three-judge panel in the closed-door trial is currently deliberating its verdict
a 15-year-old boy described as despondent over school problems and upset about the outcome of a college basketball game blasted away with an assortment of rifles and handguns for five hours inside his home, officials said today
no one was injured in the incident, which ended when deputies talked the boy into surrendering early today, said monroe county sheriff's spokesman thomas ryan
the house is a shambles,'' ryan said this morning. ``he shot out the television, the stove, the walls and ceilings, windows, sliding glass doors, a water pipe which ruptured and squirted water everywhere, and even the electrical box in the basement.''
ryan said the boy, whose name was withheld because of his age, had picked up a gun and started shooting sunday night. his mother ran next door to call police
when deputies arrived at the house in the rural area southwest of rochester, they heard bullets whizzing by their heads and evacuated the house next door. deputies then set up a command post in a house down the road, from which negotiators talked to the youth by telephone, ryan said
before the boy surrendered early sunday morning he had fired at least 300 rounds of ammunition had been fired from a variety of weapons, ryan said. the boy's father had four or five rifles and shotguns and four handguns, ryan said
the boy had been suspended from high school last week for disciplinary problems,'' ryan said. ``whether this triggered him, we don't know. the only other thing he mentioned to hostage negotiators was that he was upset that syracuse lost to pittsburgh.''
pittsburgh edged syracuse university 85-84 to take the big east conference college basketball title sunday afternoon
the youth was taken to strong memorial hospital in rochester for a mental examination before being turned over to family court officials, said ryan
the supreme court said today it will try again to decide whether cities may be sued successfully when citizens' rights are violated due to alleged inadequate training of municipal employees
the justices said they will study the issue in an appeal by canton, ohio, officials
the city is seeking to kill a lawsuit by a woman who says police violated her rights by failing to provide her medical attention after she was arrested for speeding
the justices last year backed out of deciding the municipal-liability issue in a case from springfield, mass
by a 5-4 vote, the court declined for procedural reasons to decide whether springfield should be forced to pay damages in the death of a fleeing motorist killed by a policeman's bullet
the ruling left intact a $50,000 damage award the city was ordered to pay to the victim's family
the case acted on today involves geraldine harris, who was granted a retrial of her lawsuit by a lower court
canton officials said alleged inadequate training of police in summoning medical help should not be the basis for a lawsuit against the city
mrs. harris' lawsuit grows out of an april 26, 1978, incident in which she was stopped for speeding while driving her teen-age daughter to school
police said they put mrs. harris into a patrol wagon after the 52-year-old woman became upset and uncooperative. on arrival at the police station, the officers said she was lying on the floor of the vehicle
she repeatedly slumped to the floor during a stay of 30 to 40 minutes at the stationhouse
police officers did not call for medical help. they said they believed mrs. harris was merely excited and would calm down if left alone and permitted to see her family
when family members arrived, they had mrs. harris taken by ambulance to a hospital where she was diagnosed as suffering from stress reaction, anxiety and depression. the symptoms included immobility and difficulty in breathing. she was under psychiatric care for more than a year later
the harris family sued the city in federal court, and a jury awarded $200,000 against the city on grounds mrs. harris unreasonably was denied medical attention
the 6th u.s. circuit court of appeals threw out the verdict last july, saying it was unclear on what theory the damage award was based
the judge's instructions to the jury could have allowed it to decide erroneously that the city was at fault even if the failure to summon medical attention was not the result of a city policy, the appeals court said
this instruction allows a finding of municipal liability merely because (the city's) supervisory personnel did a bad act, with no need to find that the city was a bad actor through a city policy or custom. this was error,'' the appeals court said
canton officials asked the supreme court to throw out the lawsuit
city officials said the 6th circuit court ruling will allow the city to be found liable for misconduct at the retrial under an unreasonably broad theory
the city may be forced to pay damages if the jury decides that police were not trained adequately to summon medical help in such cases, city officials said
the appeals court ruling will impose ``the novel requirement upon cities that their police forces must provide paramedical officers or other trained medical specialists who exercise some type of professional judgment at the jail,'' city officials said
the supreme court recently has had trouble providing clear guidelines on the issue of inadequate police training as grounds for municipal liability in federal civil rights suits 
in a 7-1 ruling in 1985 the justices threw out a $1.5 million award against oklahoma city in the shooting death of a tavern patron by a police officer
only four justices agreed it was a mistake for the jury to be told it could infer from a single incident that the city was grossly negligent in its police training. three other justices voted to throw out the award for other reasons
the case is canton vs. harris, 86-1088
