u.s. navy helicopters dodged heavy machine-gun fire in the persian gulf and iran today claimed responsibility for the attack which came after the helicopters ignored a warning to stay clear of an ``iranian zone.''
the account carried by tehran's official islamic republic news agency evidently referred to the incident saturday night reported earlier by u.s. officials
they said american helicopters took ``evasive action'' when fired on from an oil platform and several small boats in the central gulf about midnight saturday
meanwhile, u.s. officials said there was no connection between the helicopter incident and the movement of six u.s. warships up the gulf today
the ships' appearance off dubai triggered speculation that the united states was planning to retaliate for the shooting saturday
all six, including a missile cruiser, three missile frigates, a combat stores ship and a chartered navy tanker, were part of ``routine movement, not connected with any other recent events in the gulf,'' said lt. col. john head, a spokesman for the u.s. central command
saturday's helicopter incident occurred as the aircraft were scouting ahead of the missile frigate simpson, returning up the gulf after a convoy escort mission
a u.s. statement said the helicopters took evasive action and did not return fire when the iranians shot at them
it did not say what kind of helicopters were involved or how many there were. nor did the statement mention any warning by the iranians before they started shooting
the platform was not identified by name or exact location, although the statement said it was not the rostam platform. rostam was shelled by u.s. destroyers last october in a retaliatory raid after an iranian silkworm missile hit a u.s. flagged kuwaiti tanker, the sea isle city, anchored off kuwait
the iranian account said: ``two u.s. helicopters attempting to approach an iranian zone in the persian gulf early sunday were forced to flee by the anti-aircraft fire of naval forces of the islamic republic of iran.''
it added: ``the navy anti-aircraft (unit) detected the two helicopters on its radar and warned them to stay out of the iranian zone. however, the iranian navy fired warning shots after the u.s. helicopters violated the iranian zone.''
shortly after midnight friday, u.s. officials said the missile frigate john a. moore fired at what were believed to be iranian speedboats seen on the radar screen before they disappeared
also sunday, thousands of iranians marched through central tehran to the soviet embassy, claiming moscow had supplied iraq with long-range missiles, iran's islamic republic news agency said in a report monitored in nicosia
irna said a number of students entered the embassy grounds by scaling a wall, but were thrown out by ``alert policemen.'' iran said it first learned about iraq's new missiles seven months ago and had warned the soviets that any use of the rockets would harm relations between tehran and moscow, irna said
in moscow, the soviet news agency tass said a mob besieged the embassy, pelted it with rocks and tried to set fires, threatening the lives of soviet diplomats and their families. similar ``hostile actions'' were directed sunday at the soviet consulate in isfahan, iran, tass said without elaborating
tass said the soviet leadership ``rejects any allegations about the soviet union's involvement in the missile attacks against tehran.''
in the so-called ``war of the cities,'' iran's official islamic republic news agency said 12 civilians, including women and children, were killed and 30 wounded when an iraqi missile exploded in tehran today. it said a clinic, several houses and 30 vehicles were destroyed in the blast. the missile was one of two iraq said its army lobbed into tehran early today
irna said another 61 civilians were killed and 427 wounded sunday in iraqi air raids on 16 iranian cities and towns
it reported that iranian revolutionary guards fired a missile at a ``military center'' in baghdad around midnight. the official iraqi news agency said the missile exploded in a residential area of the capital, killing and wounding ``a number of civilians, including women and children.''
a utah company that provides helicopters and crews for a third of the nation's civilian air ambulance services has been accused of violating federal aviation regulations, probably unintentionally, a newspaper reports
most of rocky mountain helicopter service's alleged violations involved paperwork and record-keeping deficiencies, the pittsburgh press reported sunday
the federal aviation administration findings stem from a two-month investigation of the company's safety procedures and regulation compliance, said wayne barlow, director of the faa's northwest mountain region, which covers rocky mountain's headquarters in provo, utah
the alleged violations are being reviewed and the final number could be fewer than the 120 now pending, barlow said
it looks like a case where a small company based in one location grew very rapidly to the point where it had aircraft and people operating in dozens of states and no real handle on how to manage them,'' he told the press
rocky mountain helicopter, the industry's largest vendor, supplies aircraft, pilots and mechanics to hospitals in 39 cities, including allegheny general hospital in pittsburgh
barlow said rocky mountain helicopters faces possible fines because the investigation uncovered a number of significant problems. however, he said, the faa believes rocky mountain is now operating in compliance with regulations and the agency had no plans to lift their license to fly
russ spray, the company's vice president of emergency medical services operations, said, ``we don't deny we made some mistakes, but we're fixing them as fast as they're being pointed out.''
the inspection was spawned by congressional pressure on the faa last year after a record medical helicopter accident rate in 1986, but the faa said it also wanted to become more acquainted with the medical helicopter industry
there are more than 235 medical helicopter programs operating at least 500 helicopters in 46 states
what we learn from rocky mountain will help us to manage the whole industry better,'' barlow said
the faa's 143-page report referred to such shortcomings as a lack of documented training in evacuating patients from the aircraft in emergencies, the press reported
other alleged violations ranged from a lack of training for the company's pilots to the failure of the director of operations and chief pilot to have the proper faa licenses for those positions, the newspaper said
on feb. 12, rocky mountain voluntarily grounded 62 of its helicopters until mechanics in each city could confirm all maintenance and accompanying paperwork were up-to-date and accurate
in most cases, this (grounding) just took long enough for a phone call to each city, but three aircraft were grounded for a day or so for repairs,'' spray said
on feb. 17, rocky mountain grounded 24 of its pilots because they did not have the proper paperwork to show they had received required training
within two days, all the pilots were flying legal again,'' spray said. visit</head>
a roman catholic bishops' conference gave the secret service information on an abortion rights group that planned peaceful demonstrations during pope john paul ii's trip to the united states, a newspaper reports
frances kissling, president of washington, d.c.-based catholics for a free choice, said she was surprised by the action
the information on the group was provided by the national conference of catholic bishops, sponsor of the papal visit, which is the religious arm of the civil u.s. catholic conference, the houston chronicle reported sunday
i think it is totally inappropriate for the u.s. catholic conference to be cooperating with government agencies in the collection of data that they know has no relevance to the physical safety of the pope,'' ms. kissling said
there has been within the church anincreasing attempt to silence and punish individuals who exercise their rights to disagree with the bishops on public policy,'' she added. ``i think that represents a kind of mccarthyism in the church.''
ms. kissling said there is no evidence the secret service conducted surveillance on her organization
the chronicle reported sunday it was unclear how or if the secret service, which was in charge of the pope's security during the sept. 10-19 trip, used the information about ms. kissling's group
richard doerflinger, assistant director of the bishops' office for pro-life activities, said his 1985 report about catholics for a free choice was sent to the secret service along with several membership letters and press releases on cfc letterhead that he had obtained
doerflinger said the secret service ``wanted to be sent any materials about groups conducting protests so they would know what to expect.''
the secret service released the material from its files in response to questions from the chronicle under the freedom of information act about monitoring of u.s. organizations in connection with the papal trip
the supreme court today cleared the way for a jury trial in former massachusetts gov. edward j. king's $3.6 million libel lawsuit against the boston globe
the justices, over one dissenting vote, left intact a massachusetts supreme judicial court ruling that a jury should hear king's contention that he was libeled by a nov. 8, 1981, column written by david farrell, who since has left the newspaper
the state court ruled that a jury might conclude that one allegation in the column had been published with ``actual malice'' _ a reckless disregard for the truth
justice william j. brennan in november blocked a libel trial, and the full supreme court later refused to set aside brennan's order
today's action set aside brennan's trial-blocking order. brennan voted to hear arguments in the case but four votes are needed to grant such review
king sued over various globe articles and editorial cartoons published in 1981
the state court threw out most of the ex-governor's claims in pretrial proceedings, but said a jury trial was needed regarding the farrell column. both the globe newspaper co. and farrell were named as defendants
in it, king was criticized for treating legislative and judicial figures as if they were his employees
that condescending attitude never was more evident than in october when king called a judge and demanded that he change a decision he rendered in a gang-rape case,'' the column said
in a much-publicized case, the judge had given a suspended prison sentence to five men who pleaded guilty to rape
king's lawsuit said no such conversation between king and the judge took place
state treasurer robert q. crane, a king political ally, said in pretrial testimony that he was farrell's source about king's telephone call to the judge
but the state's highest court noted that farrell was not told that crane had overheard the conversation, and that farrell did not investigate further
the court said a jury conceivably could conclude that farrell's failure to do so amounted to actual malice
public figures who sue for libel must prove that the allegedly libelous statement is false and was made with actual malice. private citizens have a less stringent burden, and must prove only that the statement is false and was made negligently
in a pretrial deposition, farrell said he had no reason to doubt crane's ``veracity and accuracy.''
in the appeal acted on today, globe lawyers said the massachusetts court ruling ``mutates actual malice into negligence, thus eviscerating'' the free-speech protections the supreme court has built into libel law since 1964
as long as writers are exposed to liability solely for the asserted inadequacies of their investigations, speech protected under the constitution will be chilled,'' the newspaper's lawyers said. ``stories for which reliable sources exist may be self-censored out of existence.''
but lawyers for king urged the court to reject the appeal and allow a jury trial on the libel allegation
farrell had obvious reasons to doubt the accuracy of crane's report,'' they said
the newspaper's appeal was supported in a ``friend-of-the-court'' brief submitted by the american newspaper publishers association, the american society of newspaper editors and other news organizations
the case is globe newspaper co. vs. king, 87-731
the supreme court today agreed to consider reinstating the death sentence of a florida man convicted of killing an 8-year-old girl in 1978
the court is expected to use the case to study death row inmates' right to raise new issues when they turn to the federal courts for help and to decide whether florida juries may be told their life-or-death recommendations are subject to the trial judge's approval
aubrey adams, who once worked as a corrections officer at the marion correctional institution in ocala, was convicted of the jan. 23, 1978, strangulation of trisa gail thornley near ocala
his conviction and death sentence have been upheld three times by the florida supreme court. the nation's highest court refused to review his case twice
in the second federal court appeal, adams in early 1986 challenged statements made to the jury by the judge in his state court sentencing trial
under florida law, a jury recommends life or death for convicted murderers in capital cases. the presiding judge is free to follow or disregard the recommendation
in adams' case, the judge told jurors about that aspect of the state's capital-sentencing law. ``the final decision as to what punishment shall be imposed rests solely upon the judge of this court,'' the jury was told
adams argued that such jury instructions run afoul of a 1985 supreme court decision in which the justices, ruling in a mississippi case, said a death sentence is invalid if a jury is misled about its role in determining whether the defendant actually will die
in the case, a mississippi prosecutor had told jurors they should not view themselves as determining life or death because their sentence would be reviewed automatically by an appeals court
the supreme court said such a statement misled the jury, and rendered the subsequent death sentence ``cruel and unusual punishment.''
a federal judge dismissed adams' 1986 appeal but the 11th u.s. circuit court of appeals last nov. 13 threw out his sentence
the appeals court said the judge's instructions to jurors violated the supreme court's 1985 decision, adding that adams was entitled to ``a new sentencing proceeding before an untainted jury.''
in the appeal acted on today, florida prosecutors noted that the florida supreme court previously had rejected an appeal in which adams mounted an identical challenge to the judge's instructions to jurors
they asked the justices to resolve the conflict between the state's highest court and the 11th circuit court
the state's appeal also contended that adams' challenge should not have been allowed because he did not raise it in his first federal court appeal
the case is dugger vs. adams, 87-121. tennessee case</head>
the supreme court today refused to free churches from having to comply with state financial-disclosure laws when waging public referendum campaigns
the court, citing the lack of a ``substantial federal question,'' turned away a challenge by 13 churches from jackson, tenn., to a law they contend violates their freedom of religion and freedom of speech
the tennessee law also affects other non-political organizations that decided to campaign for or against issues that appear on election ballots
the controversy arose during an august 1984 election held in jackson to determine whether establishments within the city would be allowed to sell liquor by the drink
the local option referendum was defeated by a vote of 6,514 to 6,474 _ a 40-vote margin
the 13 area churches, nine of them baptist-affiliated, took varying steps to make public their opposition to allowing on-premise liquor consumption in jackson
the churches spent a total of $5,150, mostly for advertising, in opposition to the referendum. but they failed to register as ``political campaign committees'' as required by the tennessee campaign financial disclosure act of 1980
the law defines such committees as any combination of two or more people ``making expenditures to support or oppose any candidate for public office or measure.'' it requires that the committees designate a political treasurer and file campaign-disclosure statements
the churches sued the state to challenge the law as applied to them
at trial, pastors for the churches testified that the referendum opposition resulted from moral, not political, concerns and that they considered their actions to be part of the churches' religious mission
the pastors also testified that their churches had not, and would not, get involved in partisan political campaigns as a matter of religious conviction
a state trial judge ruled against the churches, finding that all of them are ``political campaign committees'' as defined by the 1980 state law and that the law is constitutional
a state appeals court later overturned the state law as a violation of constitutional free-speech rights
the tennessee supreme court last may 26 ruled that the law does not violate free-speech rights when applied to either partisan elections featuring candidates or non-partisan referendum elections
the recent history of campaign financial abuses as well as the growth and possible dominance of special interest political action committees make the state's disclosure requirements necessary to allow the public to have some gauge by which to assess the sources, content and frequency of campaign publicity and activity,'' the state court ruled
its ruling did not discuss the churches' argument that the law violates their right to exercise freely their religious beliefs
in the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the 13 churches noted that the justices have ``never passed on the validity of disclosure requirements in referendum campaigns.''
the appeal questioned whether any state may justify ``prior registration and disclosure requirements to non-political organizations in general and churches in particular.''
tennessee attorney general w.j. michael cody urged the high court to reject the churches' appeal
the fact that this is a referendum election does not make the state's interest in providing any information to the voters as to how the election is financed any less compelling,'' cody said
the 13 churches who challenged the law are bemis pentecostal, calvary baptist, englewood baptist, first assembly of god, first baptist church of bemis, first baptist church of jackson, malesus baptist, north jackson baptist, northside assembly of god, poplar heights baptist, skyline church of christ, west jackson baptist and woodland baptist
the case is bemis pentecostal vs. tennessee, 87-317
sen. sam nunn, whose support is considered important in the south, says he has cast his absentee ballot for tennessee sen. albert gore jr. in tuesday's democratic presidential primary in georgia
nunn, d-ga., in a statement released sunday by aides as he was leaving for a week-long trip to the soviet union, said he voted for gore because ``his views come closest to my own views as to the steps our nation must take to meet our challenges at home and abroad.''
nunn had refused on friday during a news conference with georgia reporters to disclose how he voted, saying his position as chairman of the democratic leadership council precluded him from taking a public stand between gore and missouri rep. richard gephardt, both members of the dlc
but he said in his statement sunday that since that news conference he had eceived ``a number of inquiries from georgians asking me privately whom i had favored in the march 8 primary election.''
because i have responded frankly to these private inquiries, i feel that it is now more appropriate for me to state publicly what i have stated privately _ i voted for al gore,'' nunn said
the supreme court today let stand a ruling that the public has no right to attend hearings into the alleged tainting or bribing of a criminal trial jury while the trial is underway
the justices, without comment, refused to second-guess the validity of conducting such hearings in secret during the 1986 racketeering trial of louisiana gov. edwin w. edwards
a federal appeals court, in upholding the closed hearings, ruled that the public's constitutional right to attend criminal trials does not extend to ``the midtrial questioning of jurors.''
the appeals court also ruled that transcripts of the closed hearings may be withheld from public disclosure during the trial even if the jury is sequestered, and that the names of the jurors involved may be erased from the transcripts
after a 1985 trial ended in mistrial because a federal jury could not reach a unanimous verdict, then-gov. edwards and four co-defendants stood trial again in 1986 on charges of racketeering and bribery
all were acquitted after a two-month trial
on two occasions during the second trial, u.s. district judge marcel livaudais jr. received reports that the sequestered jury had been tainted
the first report suggested that one juror had told another that jury members in edwards' first trial were paid to vote for acquittal
the second report suggested one juror had told another of a possible bribery attempt by one defendant
in both instances, livaudais conducted proceedings in his chambers and determined that the people involved could continue serving as jurors
courtroom spectators, including news reporters, were given only vague accounts of why the hearings were held. the judge said he would release partial transcripts sometime after the trial was completed, but that those transcripts would not include juror names
three news organizations _ the times-picayune, gannett news service and capital city press _ and several of their reporters challenged the judge's use of closed hearings
the times-picayune is a new orleans newspaper. capital city press publishes the morning advocate and state-times newspapers in baton rouge
the challenge contended that livaudais should have given the reporters a chance to argue in favor of conducting open-court hearings and that he was required to tell why it was necessary to conduct the hearings in secret
the 5th u.s. circuit court of appeals last july 31 upheld the closed hearings
the appeals court noted that past supreme court rulings have established a public right of access to criminal trials but ruled that under that constitutional right ``no presumption of openness attaches to proceedings involving midtrial questioning of jurors.''
if the questioning of impaneled jurors were held in open court there is a substantial probability that what may have begun as a `tempest in a teapot' will end in a mistrial, a hung jury or a reversal on appeal,'' the 5th circuit court said
the news organizations then sought supreme court review
the case is times-picayune publishing vs. edwards, 87-872
communist rebels ambushed and killed six filipino sailors assigned to subic naval base 10 miles from the u.s.-run installation, the military said today. three civilians also died in the shootout
philippine officials today urged president corazon aquino to develop a unified negotiating strategy before talks on the future of american bases in the philippines
one of the country's best-known rebel priests fled to cebu city from mindanao island after he was wounded by comrades who learned he was planning to surrender, officials said today
the philippine constabulary said the philippine sailors were traveling to manila sunday when rebels opened fire on their land rover near the town of hermosa on the bataan peninsula
three civilians were killed in the cross fire during the 15-minute battle, the military said. there were no reports of rebel casualties
subic, 50 miles west of manila, is one of six installations technically under philippine command but effectively under u.s. control
communist rebels operate near both subic and clark air base, about 50 miles north of manila. in october last year, rebels killed three americans and a filipino of u.s. extraction in coordinated attacks outside clark
cabinet secretaries and members of congress' foreign affairs committee told reporters after a two-hour meeting today with mrs. aquino that they would continue talks to firm up the government position on u.s.-run bases
the united states and the philippines are expected to begin talks in the next few weeks on the future of the u.s.-run installations. under the current agreement, either government can unilaterally close the bases if it serves one-year's notice after sept. 16, 1991
mrs. aquino says she will honor the current bases treaty but has refused to say whether she will agree to extend the agreement. any extension beyond 1991 requires approval by two-thirds of the 23-member philippine senate, where opposition to the bases is strong
sen. leticia shahani said matters to be discussed in the review include the future of filipino employees at the bases and the possibility that nuclear weapons are being stored at the facilities
she said mrs. aquino is ``leaving us the liberty of taking a stand. on the other hand there is a need to coordinate the positions of the executive and the legislative.''
romeo capangpangan, spokesman of the department of social welfare, said the rebel priest, rev. frank navarro, sent word that he was recuperating in a cebu area hideout and wanted to surrender and be granted amnesty
navarro has been identified by the military as a new peoples army commander in eastern mindanao
capangpangan said navarro was apparently suffering from a bullet wound in the shoulder which he received in an ambush by his own followers last week in mindanao's surigao del sur province
welfare department official amelita costas told reporters that her office was willing to meet navarro at the place of his choice and take him to safety without any military escorts
the government amnesty program for communist and moslem rebels expired at the end of february. but defense secretary fidel ramos said rebels who wanted to surrender could receive amnesty on a case-by-case basis. white house</head>
the supreme court today refused to reinstate charges against 36 people arrested outside the white house while protesting reagan administration domestic and foreign policies
the court, without comment, left intact rulings that dismissed the charges on grounds government prosecutors acted vindictively
a demonstration for ``peace, jobs and justice'' occurred april 22, 1985. about 200 participants were arrested
they were charged with violating the terms of their u.s. park police march permit by sitting down on sidewalks outside the white house
most of those arrested agreed to pay a $50 fine for demonstrating without a permit rather than stand trial
but 36 demonstrators chose to stand trial. they were charged _ in addition to demonstrating without a permit _ with obstructing the sidewalks adjacent to the white house
each charge carries a maximum penalty of six months in prison and a $500 fine
u.s. district judge aubrey robinson ordered all charges against the 36 dismissed, ruling that prosecutors acted vindictively by bringing the second charge only for those who chose to stand trial
the u.s. circuit court of appeals upheld robinson's decision last year
the appeals court said there was ample evidence for robinson to conclude that prosecutors added the second charge to punish demonstrators for choosing to stand trial
a large group of defendants threatened to go to trial on what the government considered petty offenses,'' the appeals court said. ``the government had a strong incentive to try to keep clear of this courtroom morass. it wished to avoid the annoyance and expense of prosecuting these minor cases at a potentially drawn-out trial.''
prosecutors showed a `` disturbing willingness to toy with the defendants,'' the appeals court added
it said robinson was justified in throwing out both charges against the 36 demonstrators, not merely the second accusation that they obstructed the sidewalks
if in cases of vindictive prosecution the trial court judge may only dismiss the additional charge, the prosecutor wil have nothing to lose by acting vindictively,'' the appeals court said
the reagan administration said the lower court rulings could ``significantly hamper'' the government's handling off mass demonstrations in the nation's capital
the case is u.s. vs. meyer, 87-730
the supreme court today refused to revive a $3 million lawsuit by author william peter blatty against the new york times for the treatment his 1983 novel ``legion'' received on the newspaper's weekly best seller list
the justices, without comment, let stand a california supreme court ruling that dismissed blatty's lawsuit alleging intentional interference with prospective business advantage
blatty, author of ``the exorcist,'' contended that the times excluded ``legion'' from the weekly list for a period even though the newspaper knew the novel had sold enough copies to qualify
the california supreme court, by a 7-0 vote last dec. 29, said blatty could not pursue the lawsuit
four of the state court's justices based their ruling on the federal constitution's free-speech protections and the even greater protections for speech offered by the california constitution
they said such a lawsuit is barred unless a defendant has made a statement ``of and concerning'' the plaintiff
three of the state court's justices said blatty had failed to suggest that the newspaper intentionally misrepresented the results of its bookstore sales survey to hurt him financially
the case is blatty vs. new york times, 86-1803
the supreme court today cleared the way for a trial in what may become an important test case on the power of cities to control rents and otherwise protect mobile home residents
the court, without comment, rejected an appeal by santa barbara, calif., officials aimed at killing a lawsuit by the owners of a mobile home park who claim they unfairly are being deprived of their property's full value
a santa barbara ordinance adopted in 1984 requires mobile home park operators to offer their tenants leases of unlimited duration. it also permits a maximum yearly rent increase of 3 percent or three-fourths of the increase in the consumer price index, whichever is greater
the ordinance was challenged by william and jean hall, who own the los amigos mobile home estates in santa barbara
they said their property is being ``taken'' without the ``just compensation'' required by the constitution
the halls argued that granting mobile home owners a perpetual lease allows them to sell the lease at a windfall profit. the windfall is due to the new owners' anticipation of continued low land rent at below-market rates, the halls said
a federal judge threw out the suit, but the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals reinstated it in 1986
the appeals court noted that the halls said the price of mobile homes in the park shot up dramatically after the ordinance was enacted, suggesting the guaranteed low rents were worth a premium to buyers
reduced to its essentials,'' the appeals court said, the halls' claim ``is that the santa barbara ordinance has transferred a possessory interest in their land to each of their 71 tenants. this interest consists of the right to occupy the property in perpetuity while paying only a fraction of what it is worth in rent.''
the appeals court acknowledged that the ordinance allows mobile home owners to be removed if they don't pay the rent or if they misbehave. that may ease the economic impact, the appeals court said, but it does not alter the basic right of possession given the home owners
the ordinance ``changes the fundamental relationship between the parties, giving landlord and tenant complementary estates in the same land,'' the appeals court said
the appeals court said a trial is necessary to determine if the halls' allegations about a windfall are accurate
santa barbara county and other cities in california joined in asking the high court to review the case. the cities are berkeley, capitola, carson, cathedral city, fontana, hayward, los altos, los angeles, mountain view, oxnard, palm springs, rancho mirage, rialto, san buenaventura, san jose, san luis obispo, santa monica, vacaville, vallejo, west hollywood and westlake village
the justices on feb. 24 expanded the power of communities to impose rent controls by upholding a san jose, calif., ordinance that allows hardships to tenants to be considered when landlords seek rent increases
the ordinance had been atttacked as a ``robin hood'' law that steals from the rich to pay the poor
the case is santa barbara vs. hall, 87-220
jordan said today it welcomed the u.s. peace initiative but insisted that the plo participate in talks to quell violence in the israeli-occupied territories
information minister hani khasawneh said amman will ``be reporting to the u.s. administration as soon as we finish our consultations'' with other arab countries on the peace plan carried to the middle east last week by secretary of state george p. shultz
we always seek a united arab stand toward any peace process in the area,'' he said
he said there was no deadline for formulating a response to the u.s. initiative. shultz reportedly has asked jordan, syria, egypt and israel to report back by the middle of the month
the american plan calls for an international conference to launch bilateral talks between israel and a palestinian-jordanian delegation
the two sides would start in may to negotiate limited self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinians and in december would begin talks on a final settlement of the arab-israeli conflict
israel's coalition government is split along party lines over the american plan
the blueprint outlined by shultz proposed an international peace conference involving jordan, syria and palestinian representatives, but not the palestine liberation organization
both the united states and israel refuse to meet with the plo because they consider it a terrorist organization
the jordanian minister renewed jordan's call for an international peace conference under u.n. auspices and attended by all concerned parties in the conflict, including the plo and the soviet union
asked if jordan was optimistic, he said: ``we can't say so yet, but we hope we'll get fruitful results
we're interested in a peace settlement and that's why we welcome the u.s. movement,'' khasawneh said
the supreme court today refused to hear the appeal of a florida woman who says she was denied custody of her young child because she is a jehovah's witness
the justices, without comment, let stand state court rulings that bar rita mendez from exposing her daughter to any of her religious beliefs
the state courts also awarded primary residential custody of the girl to her father
in the appeal acted on today, mrs. mendez said her freedom-of-religion rights were violated by the custody determination
rita and ignacio mendez were divorced in miami in 1985, after a four-year marriage. their daughter, rebecca, was then 3
marital difficulties arose in 1983 over mrs. mendez's involvement with the jehovah's witnesses religion. her husband is a catholic who, according to court documents, felt his wife had ``betrayed him'' by joining the jehovah's witnesses
at a custody trial, mendez testfieid that it was not in rebecca's best interest to be raised as a jehovah's witness. of the 485 pages in the divorce proceedings transcript devoted to child custody, 249 pages contain references to the subject of religion
two psychologists and one psychiatrist testified that rebecca should live with her mother, whom they called the child's ``prime parent figure.''
but the experts said contact with her mother's jehovah's witness religion was not in rebecca's best interest because she needs ``to adapt herself to the mainstream of culture.''
they testified that a catholic upbringing ``would allow her to adapt to society and have the freedom that catholic children have in the society.''
judge phillip k. knight, in awarding primary custody of rebecca to her father, ruled that mrs. mendez should enjoy ``regular, frequent and liberal visitation, access and contact with the minor child.''
but he also barred mrs. mendez from exposing rebecca to ``any religious practices, attendances, teachings or events which are in any way inconsistent with the religious teachings and practices of the catholic religion.''
a state appeals court upheld the custody award, ruling that ``the record in this case does not support (mrs. mendez's) contention that the trial court made the father the primary residential parent ... solely because the mother is a practicing jehovah's witness.''
in a dissenting vote, one appeals court judge said granting the father primary custody amounted to ``an abuse of discretion.''
the child, exposed to the religious views of both parents for two years, showed no evidence of emotional or psychological harm,'' the judge said, adding that the custody proceedings showed ``the experts' personal biases against the mother's religion.''
their disdain for the mother's religion induced them to speculate as to the possibility of harm to the child in the future even though no evidence of harm existed,'' the dissenting judge said
lawyers for mrs. mendez told the justices, ``this court cannot eliminate religious bigotry in america but it can and should review this decision, which has deprived a parent of her child because of intolerance of her faith.''
the appeal added, ``the trial court's order places rita in the anomalous position of having a constitutionally protected right to speak to total strangers about her religion but not to her own child.''
the case is mendez vs. mendez, 87-1166
gunmen in a speeding car shot and killed a lebanese army officer in south lebanon today, a military communique reported
it identified the victim as 1st lt. talal kanso, 41, a shiite moslem, and said he was ambushed while driving to his headquarters in the southern market town of nabatiyeh at 9:00 a.m
the communique said kanso's driver fired at the assailants' car, killing one of them
the attackers escaped
the communique did not report any motive behind the killing
many lebanese army officers had been assassinated since 1984. most of the victims worked in the army's intelligence service
a co-worker and a relative of an american kidnapped in nicaragua last week by contra rebels say they have been told he is safe, but add that they don't trust the contras
richard boren, of elkin, was among 12 people abducted tuesday from the village of mancotal in northern nicaragua
the main thing that my family wants is for him to be released,'' said carol owens, boren's sister, who lives in carrboro
contras, who oppose nicaragua's leftist sandinista government, claim the group was ``detained,'' not kidnapped
boren, 30, is a long-term volunteer with witness for peace, a u.s.-based grass-roots ecumenical group that works in the war zones of nicaragua trying to change u.s. policy toward the country
he has been in nicaragua since november, assigned to travel from town to town along the honduran border recording witnesses' stories of contra attacks
dennis marker, director of the washington office of witness for peace, said contras kicked down the door of a house in which boren was staying and began shooting, wounding a 13-year-old girl in the leg
boren was taken prisoner at gunpoint while trying to bandage the girl's wound, marker said
six of the abductees have escaped since tuesday, he said, and one has told witness for peace specifics of the incident
the contras still have richard, and he obviously can't go until they let him go,'' marker said. ``i believe if they wanted to, they could release him immediately.''
we're not one bit happy that they're holding him, and we don't trust them, quite frankly,'' marker said
marker said a contra leader confirmed friday only that they had boren and that he was safe
ms. owen, who said she didn't learn of the abduction until thursday night, said state department officials told her saturday that her brother was all right
there were differences in culture and style in a television linkup between soviet and american students and scholars, but the students and 10 panelists agreed that the two countries are making progress in breaking down barriers
the two-hour forum saturday joined 350 undergraduates at tufts university's downtown campus with 200 moscow state university students
not accustomed to the american style of tv answers, the soviets often strayed from the questioning and read prepared speeches detailing minor points in soviet nuclear history
at one juncture, soviet moderator yevgeny p. velikhov said, ``it's a lecture. we have to teach the students something here.''
andrey kokoshin, deputy director of the institute for u.s.a. and canada, told a u.s. questioner the superpowers are moving past cold war tensions to begin ``to clear off layers of mutual fears.''
it seems to me what we are doing now in a first step to disarmament should create a new basis, a new faith to increase trust in each other,'' kokoshin said
the satellite-relayed ``space bridge'' forum was the first of three between tufts and moscow state on the nuclear arms race and cold war politics. the sessions are part of a course devised by tufts professor martin j. sherwin
the panel included two americans who worked on the top-secret manhattan project that developed the first atomic bomb in 1945, and a soviet researcher who helped build that country's first nuclear weapon in 1949
students and scientists frequently interrupted each other with applause, the loudest when sherwin praised soviet leader mikhail gorbachev's efforts to ease nuclear tensions
i think there's not a single person here who thinks he will be able to survive a nuclear bomb,'' said alexei milayev, a soviet physics student. ``we are gathered here in the final analysis to think about what must be done to prevent a nuclear war.''
velikhov, vice president for physics and mathematics for the soviet academy of sciences, noted the forum came 40 years after the u.n. committee on atomic energy abandoned its effort to ban nuclear weapons
today we are at the first stages of a non-nuclear world,'' he said. velikhov said the recent superpower arms reduction treaty signed in december ``is the first encouraging step. we believe, in a new international situation, we will succceed in resolving the question.''
mark anstendig, 21, a tufts junior history major from edgemont, n.y., said afterward the forum went a long way to promoting better understanding
i think there was good rapport on both sides,'' he said. ``it'll promote better feelings. i think it's a good microcosm of what could happen.''
the government announced plans today to amend the constitution to make it easier to extend direct federal rule in troubled state of punjab, where sikh militants have been waging a bloody campaign for independence
p. chidambaram, deputy home minister, told the governing lower house of parliament the amendments would only apply to punjab
he said the amendments would allow the government to extend direct federal rule for more than the one year presently allowed by the constitution
punjab's state government was dismissed in may 1987 for failing to curb sikh terrorism, and the state was placed under federal rule for six months. the duration was extended for another six months
on sunday the federal government went a step further and dissolved the state assembly, paving the way for fresh elections
chidambaram said articles of the constitution dealing with emergency rule will be amended to enable the government to impose a state of emergency on one state at a time
under the current rules, a state of emergency can be imposed on the whole country but not on individual states
at least 391 people have been killed in punjab this year in attacks blamed on sikh extremists. more than 1,000 people were killed last year
the minister, citing a government report on punjab, said the state assembly was dissolved because of the ``interference from members of the legislative assembly in the effective and efficient working of the police.''
there were numerous reports, he said, when legislators ``not only attempted to interfere, influence and prevent the police action but also threatening police officers of dire consequences if they failed to obey their commands,'' chidambaram said
he claimed the imposition of direct federal rule had brought about a ``distinct'' improvement in the situation in punjab
the formal bill proposing the amendments is likely to come at the end of the month. it is expected to pass easily since the congress party of prime minister rajiv gandhi has a majority in the lower house
the supreme court today left intact a $1.13 million jury award to an idaho boy paralyzed from the waist down after he was given a vaccination for three diseases
the court, without comment, rejected arguments by the vaccine manufacturer that such verdicts could force drug companies to abandon the production of essential vaccines
lederle laboratories, which makes the vaccine, said the case is a test of how far juries should be allowed to go in compensating people who suffer injuries after taking vaccines designed to protect them from life-threatening deiseases
at stake are billions of dollars because of the ``unprecedented explosion of vaccine liability litigation,'' said lawyers for lederle, a division of american cyanamid co
lederle manufactures tri-immunol, a vaccine to immunize children against diptheria, tetanus and pertussis. the company noted that the vaccine is licensed by the food and drug administration, and that only one other company markets a similar vaccine in the united states
kevin toner of burley, idaho, was given the vaccine in 1979 when he was three months old. he subsequently contracted a rare condition of the spine known as transverse myelitis, which permanently paralyzed him from the waist down
a federal jury found that lederle's vaccine caused the boy's paralysis, and decided that the drug company was negligent for failing to develop an alternative vaccine that would have been safer
lederle contended that the judge's instructions to the jury were indadequate because the jurors were not told that certain drugs are unavoidably unsafe and that such vaccines may be sold despite the risks
the company also said the verdict was impermissibly inconsistent with the jury's rejection of other claims against lederle
the company said the jury, in rejecting the other claims, decided that tri-immunol was not defective and that there are unavoidable risks in taking the vaccine
the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals last september upheld the jury award
in rejecting the company's argument on inconsistency, the appeals court said, ``it is not beyond peradventure that the jury thought that tri-immunol was fit for the purposes for which it was to be used but that lederle was negligent in failing to replace it with a better product.''
the appeals court added, ``were we charged with deciding whether jury verdicts are the most sensible way of allocating risks and costs regarding vaccines that have been proved beneficial, we might well design a different method.''
but it said the jury verdict did not violate idaho law, adding that any ``comprehensive reform'' in the area must be left to state legislatures
the appeals court opinion was written by anthony m. kennedy, who became a supreme court justice in february
the court's brief order today did not say that kennedy disqualified himself from considering the appeal. his participation under the circumstances would be highly unusual
the case is lederle laboratories vs. toner, 87-1151. minnesota case</head>
the supreme court today refused to allow an indian tribe to withhold from federal officials confidential records of a tribal court proceeding
the justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that gave the government custody of court records of the red lake band of chippewa indians in minnesota
the tribe in 1985 declared that records of proceedings before its court of indian offenses are confidential and not the federal government's property
the chippewas were concerned that if the documents were given to the interior department's bureau of indian affairs, the agency would be forced to surrender the material to a newspaper that sought the records under the freedom of information act (foia)
indian tribes are not covered by the foia and may not be forced directly to reveal confidential information to the news media
the 8th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled last august that the bureau of indian affairs is entitled to the material
the appeals court rejected arguments by the red lake band that only congress could grant the government access to the records, and ruled that the government has sovereignty over tribal courts despite the absence of specific congressional authorization
the considerable independence given tribes to govern themselves does not mean they have the power automatically to withhold information from the government, the appeals court said
the red lake band court of indian offenses was established in 1884 under authority granted to the tribe by federal officials
the 8th circuit court said that if the chippewa court had been created under a later federal statute, the indian reorganization act of 1934, the confidential records might be exempt from federal control
the case is red lake band vs. u.s., 87-950
the supreme court today refused to reinstate a pennsylvania law forcing state police officers to retire at age 60
the court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the state law violates federal restrictions against discrimination based on age
the 3rd u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled last june that pennsylvania violated the federal age discrimination in employment act
the appeals court said it is illegal to presume that officers over 60 are physically unfit for their work when officials have failed to adopt minimum fitness standards for all workers
until minimum standards are developed, implemented and enforced, the pennsylvania state police cannot justify its mandatory retirement law by relying on good health and physical conditioning as ... reasonably necessary to pennsylvania state police business,'' the appeals court said
the appeals court noted that new jersey, a neighboring state of pennsylvania, has a mandatory retirement age of 55 for state troopers that has been upheld in the courts
but the appeals court said, ``all members of the new jersey state police are subject to mandatory fitness requirements and are sanctioned for non-compliance.''
the federal law against age bias generally permits employers to force workers to retire before 70 only if it can be shown that being under 70 is a bona fide occupational qualification or if employers can prove it is highly impractical to test workers individually to assure they are still fit
the supreme court, in a pair of 1985 rulings that reinforced the employment rights of older workers, struck down efforts to force city firefighters to retire at age 55 and flight engineers at age 60
the 3rd circuit court cited those cases in invalidating pennsylvania's mandatory retirement age for state police officers
pennsylvania officials said the appeals court ruling places a heavy financial burden on the state
the state said it could be forced to pay $4 million in back pay and benefits to officers who have been forced to retire
officials also said that testing state police officers for fitness would be a costly process. they said it would cost some $2.4 million to determine whether the force's 4,000 members are healthy and fit
the state said its retirement-age policy is reasonable because of statistics that show a sharp decline in average fitness and health for older people
for example, the state said the decrease in aerobic capacity for an average group of men aged 26 and an average group of men age 58 is 57 percent. relative strength declines by about 35 percent between the ages of 29 and 50 and muscular endurance slips by 30 percent between ages 30 and 60, the officials said
pennsylvania's retirement law was challenged by the federal equal employment opportunity commission and otto j. binker, a lieutenant on the state police force who was near age 60 in 1983 when the suit was filed
the case is pennsylvania vs. equal employment opportunity commission, 87-958
a crowd of 200 eastern airlines passengers who had been bumped from new york-bound flights angrily confronted ticket agents, and one man was arrested for assaulting police officers, authorities said
several similar scuffles have occurred at miami international airport in recent months when eastern flights to the northeast were cancelled
the latest incident took place at the airport sunday when members of the crowd pressed against a ticket stand demanding to know if they could board the last flight to new york
one passenger went behind the stand and punched an eastern employee in the chest, said metro-dade police lt. robert otero
three officers struggled with the man, and one policeman fell to the ground after hitting his leg on a trash can, said otero
police arrested jack lemonik, 36, of new york city, on charges of simple battery, aggravated battery and resisting arrest with violence, said metro-dade police spokesman james wright
passengers shouted angrily at police during the struggle with lemonik, said curt arnel, 30, an attorney from merrick, n.y
eastern spokesman bob carson said 226 passengers were bumped from a 3:15 p.m. eastern flight to la guardia. some passengers were then bumped repeatedly from later flights
carson had no immediate explanation why so many people were bumped from one flight. one previous incident occurred when numerous passengers were bumped after a large jet was replaced by a small one
many of the bumped passengers were unable to board the last flight and were put up for the night in hotels, said eastern spokeswoman karen ceremsak
the widow of former cia director william j. casey testified today before the special federal grand jury that is investigating the iran-contra affair
sophia casey likely was questioned about what her husband might have told her before his death last year about the sale of u.s. arms to iran to obtain the release of american hostages and whether he mentioned anything about the diversion of proceeds to the contras
casey, who died of pneumonia on may 6, 1987, after suffering from brain cancer, was cia director when u.s. arm were sold to iran in 1985 and 1986
the agency provided logistical support to covert operations to help the contras. those operations were coordinated by former national security council aide lt. col. oliver l. north
north told congress that he was acting with casey's approval and that the former cia director recommended that he recruit retired air force maj. gen. richard v. secord to set up the private supply network because secord had experience in special operations
secord, who set up secret swiss bank accounts to funnel private donations to the contras, also helped broker the sale of u.s. arms to iran with his partner, albert hakim
north told congress last summer that casey saw the diversion as part of an effort to create a ``stand-alone'' or ``off-the-shelf'' enterprise that could engage in covert activities outside congressional review
mrs. casey's testimony comes as the grand jury appears to be preparing to return criminal indictments against the targets of the investigation, including north, secord, hakim and former national security adviser john m. poindexter
mrs. casey, who lives in roslyn harbor, n.y., last fall disputed a published account by journalist bob woodward that casey knew about the diversion to the contra rebels
in his book ``veil: the secret wars of the cia,'' woodward said that during an interview in the hospital casey acknowledged knowing about the diversion
in a sept. 28, 1987, interview, mrs. casey said her husband never told her of the diversion and expressed doubt that he knew about it
she termed ``absolute blasphemy'' woodward's account that casey had criticized president reagan as ``lazy and distracted.''
he's lying about that,'' mrs. casey told the associated press
she described her husband as ``a team player'' and a ``great patriot who would never do anything to harm his president.''
mrs. casey also expressed outrage at woodward's report that casey was ``struck by the overall passivity of the president.''
bill would never say that about the president,'' she said. ``bill loved reagan and they were very close. it's been very hurtful.'' case</head>
the supreme court today agreed to decide whether states may use anti-racketeering laws to close down adult bookstores
the court said it will review a pair of free-speech challenges to such an indiana law
under indiana's racketeer influenced and corrupt organizations law, patterned after the much-used federal rico act, law enforcement officials are authorized to seize any property used in a racketeering enterprise
the law was invoked in march 1984 against three fort wayne bookstores selling sexually explicit materials, each accused of at least two violations of the state's obscenity laws
law enforcement officials padlocked the stores and seized their nventories
a short time later, similar legal action was taken against three adult bookstores in indianapolis
the three fort wayne bookstores were allowed to reopen in april 1985 but only one, fort wayne books, remains in business. it filed the appeal acted on today
the three indianapolis bookstores also have gone out of business
later, two bookstores in howard county, ind., were prosecuted under the state law
an indiana appeals court ruled in 1985 that applying the state rico law to those whose only offenses are alleged obscenity law violations impermissibly hinders constitutionally protected freedom of speech
the appeals court said the padlocking of the bookstores represented an impermissible ``prior restraint'' of materials not yet ruled obscene
the indiana supreme court last year reversed the appeals court, ruling that applying the rico law in such a way is valid because the legislature did not pass it to promote censorship
the seizure order does not constitute a prior restraint or in any other manner impinge upon'' fort wayne books' free-speech rights, the state court said in a 3-2 ruling
in other action, the court:
_ agreed to consider reinstating the death sentence of a florida man convicted of killing an 8-year-old girl in 1978
the court is expected to use the case to study death row inmates' right to raise new issues when they turn to the federal courts for help and to decide whether florida juries may be told their life-or-death recommendations are subject to the trial judge's approval
_ left intact a $1.13 million jury award to an idaho boy paralyzed from the waist down after he was given a vaccination for three diseases
the court, without comment, rejected arguments by the vaccine manufacturer that such verdicts could force drug companies to abandon the production of essential vaccines
_ ruled unanimously that financially troubled farmers may not avoid foreclosure under federal bankruptcy law by promising to use their labor, experience and expertise in continuing to operate their farm
by an 8-0 vote, the court said a secured creditor's right to ``adequate protection'' under bankruptcy law cannot be satisfied by such a promise
_ refused to free churches from having to comply with state financial-disclosure laws when waging public referendum campaigns
the court, citing the lack of a ``substantial federal question,'' turned away a challenge by 13 churches from jackson, tenn., to a law they contend violates their freedom of religion and freedom of speech
_ let stand a ruling that the public has no right to attend hearings into the alleged tainting or bribing of a criminal trial jury while the trial is underway
the justices, without comment, refused to second-guess the validity of conducting such hearings in secret during the 1986 racketeering trial of louisiana gov. edwin w. edwards
_ cleared the way for a jury trial in former massachusetts gov. edward j. king's $3.6 million libel lawsuit against the boston globe
the justices, over one dissenting vote, left intact a massachusetts supreme judicial court ruling that a jury should hear king's contention that he was libeled by a nov. 8, 1981, column
_ cleared the way for a trial in what may become an important test case on the power of cities to control rents and otherwise protect mobile home residents
the court, without comment, rejected an appeal by santa barbara, calif., officials aimed at killing a lawsuit by owners of a mobile home park who claim they unfairly are being deprived of their property's full value
in seeking help from the nation's highest court in the adult bookstore case, lawyers for fort wayne books argued that ``neither interim nor permanent restraints of the type involved in this case may constitutionally be enforced prior to final judidical resolution'' unless the law guarantees speedy appellate review
the appeal noted that as yet no trial has been held to determine whether any of the materials seized from fort wayne books were obscene and therefore not constitutionally protected
the justices were told that ``a growing number of states are adopting similar rico laws, and there is a conflict among the states as to their constitutionality.''
the adult bookstore cases are fort wayne books vs. indiana, 87-470; and sappenfield vs. indiana, 87-614
fighting warm temperatures and wet snow, the leaders in the iditarod trail sled dog race were out of finger lake and on their way to rainy pass early today
thirteen teams left the finger lake checkpoint, 193 miles from the 1,158-mile race's starting line, in one hour late sunday. twenty-three other teams had arrived at the checkpoint
lavon barve of wasilla and jerry austin of st. michael pulled out at 7:39 p.m. they were followed by deedee jonrowe of bethel, 1987 champion susan butcher of manley, four-time champion rick swenson of two rivers and tim moerlein of kasilof
barve and swenson had declared their 24-hour layovers, then canceled the layover. all mushers are required to halt for one full 24 hour period during the race to rest themselves and their dogs
temperatures in the rainy pass area were in the high 20s early today, the national weather service reported. temperatures that hovered around 32 degrees on saturday took a toll on many of the sled dogs, which are accustomed to running in much colder weather
herbie nayokpuk was 18th into skwentna, a checkpoint 148 miles from anchorage, and notified officials he would take the race's mandatory 24-hour layover in skwentna
i've got to save some of my dogs,'' he said. ``i almost burned them up. i'll have to rest them a little bit.''
when the lead mushers reach puntilla lake in rainy pass, they will have covered 223 miles of the 1,158-mile race
fifty-two teams started the race early saturday. defending champion butcher finished last year's race in a record 11 days, two hours
the race is inspired by a 1925 dog sled relay that rushed diphtheria serum to nome during an outbreak of the disease. the top 20 mushers will split a purse of $150,000. the winner will get $30,000
u.s. mushers from outside alaska, and their positions: frank teasley of jackson, wyo., was 15th; terry adkins of mikado, mich., was 21st; robin jacobson of minnetonka, minn., was 27th; dan maceachen of snowmass village, colo., was 29th; john patten of grand marais, minn., was 35st; and stan ferguson of philadelphia was 41th. checks, halting traffic; canal operating normally; no pickup</note>
hundreds of irate retirees rallied in the streets today as local banks remained shuttered, and panama's ousted vice president urged his countrymen to take up arms against gen. manuel antonio noriega if the military leader didn't step down
meanwhile, a spokeswoman for the panama canal commission said ships were passing normally through the waterway despite reports that the nation's crisis was holding up passage of ships through the canal
about 300 retirees, chanting ``justice,'' were joined by scores of younger supporters who cut off traffic on the city's main avenida espana in front of the towering national bank of panama building
we little old people don't have that much strength, but we'll hold out here as long as we can,'' said violeta sanchez, 63, a retired secretary
at least 200 more retirees gathered in front of the treasury ministry to demonstrate
noriega's regime, under increasing pressure from the united states, tried to assure the country's 60,000 retirees over the weekend that they would be able to cash their pension checks for the first two weeks of march. but it did not say how or where, and the pensioners were indignant
rafael arosemena, president of the national bank, came out of the building to try to placate the retirees, and was surrounded by an antagonistic crowd. he told them they should go to another branch, but they refused to do so
later in the morning, the government radio station said the national bank would set up two payment booths in the afternoon to cash retirement checks
banks fearing a run because of political instability closed last week
the government blames the closures on lack of funds resulting from the freezing of panamanian government money deposited in five u.s. banks
panama's official currency is the u.s. dollar, and the government periodically receives shipments of tender from the u.s. banks where it keeps an estimated $50 million on deposit
a request for such a shipment last week was rejected because of legal action taken on behalf of eric arturo delvalle, who was ousted from the presidency on feb. 26
panama canal commission spokesman willie friar said the rumors that ship traffic through the canal was being disrupted began with unconfirmed reports that panamanian port authorities _ which have been independent from the canal commission since 1979 _ were accepting payment only in cash
she said other forms of payment were being accepted for port services such as bunkering _ taking on fuel or water
she also said the great majority of the three dozen vessels that make the passage on an average day do not use the port facilities
she said all 38 vessels scheduled to make the passage sunday did so, and that the 39 scheduled to pass through today were proceeding normally without delay
on sunday, roderick esquivel, panama's ousted vice president, said from hiding that if noriega does not relinquish power, panamanians should take up arms against him
in an interview with the associated press from a house where he was staying, esquivel warned sunday:
if peaceful means and the economic measures are not sufficient to achieve democracy, then i am the first to say that democracy must be obtained by fighting for it.''
esquivel was ousted from office in a military-orchestrated coup on feb. 26 along with delvalle, who also remains in hiding. the two men were removed from their posts a day after delvalle tried to fire noriega
many people think panama does not have much capacity for violence, but it does,'' he said
the education ministry postponed the start of public school classes until further notice. teachers were to have returned to school from vacation today for a week of preparation, with students beginning classes march 14. the ministry said in a statement the postponement was due to the climate of crisis
panama's 12 local banks have been shuttered since last tuesday. branches of international institutions closed their doors on friday
the national bank of panama said it could not supply its member banks with tender and instructed them on friday to remain closed until further notice
people have not been able to cash checks since feb. 29, and stores have stopped accepting checks and credit cards
the entire population is prepared to suffer economic hardship,'' esquivel said of mounting economic pressure from washington. ``and in a second phase, they are ready to sacrifice their lives.''
potential liability problems surrounding a tree house that extends two feet over public property have prompted city officials to give the structure the ax
it's accessible to the public, and there is the possibility it could entirely or partially fall on somebody passing by or damage property,'' said chief building inspector louis kidwell
the 8-by-6-foot tree house was built by teresa macdonald's father, a contractor, a few months ago as a christmas present for her sons, james, 6, and joey, 4
it features wall-to-wall carpeting, a shingled roof and sliding plexiglass windows and is a popular place for neighborhood children to play
if i didn't have school, i'd spend every single day up there,'' said james macdonald
my dad said, `whatever happened to the days of huckleberry finn and tom sawyer?''' said teresa macdonald
she said she understands the city's concern but added that few people use the sidewalk on their dead-end street
i've been up there on the windiest days and nothing has happened,'' she said. ``we'd have to have an earthquake or a nuclear war.''
the macdonalds have until march 21 to remove the tree house. if the city doesn't change its mind, they will build a foundation for it in their back yard and place it there
the supreme court, in an important victory for investors, today placed a heavy burden of proof on companies that are sued for denying they are holding merger negotiations after such preliminary talks are underway
by a 4-2 vote, the court said if companies withhold important information affecting stock prices, it must be presumed that investors who bought and sold the securities were relying on that information
an investor who buys or sells stock at the price set by the market does so in reliance on the integrity of that price,'' said justice harry a. blackmun for the court. ``because most publicly available information is reflected in market price, an investor's reliance on any public material misrepresentations, therefore, may be presumed.''
the absence of a five-vote majority in the case raises the possibility the issue could be reconsidered by the justices in another case with a different result. but, for now at least, today's decision is likely to have important repercussions on wall street
justice anthony m. kennedy, who joined the court last month, did not take part in considering the case. chief justice william h. rehnquist and justice antonin scalia disqualified themselves from participating without explanation
the court ordered further hearings in a dispute involving basic inc. of cleveland
the company merged with cebas inc., a subsidiary of combustion engineering based in connecticut, in december 1978
stockholders said basic executives falsely denied for 14 months prior to the merger that at least preliminary talks were underway between the two companies
as a result, many investors said they sold their stock at far less than its value
combustion engineering is a conglomerate that makes alumina or acid-based refractories _ non-metallic ceramic substances used as structural materials. both basic and combustion engineering were traded on the new york stock exchange
the stock of basic was selling at well under $20 a share when merger rumors began surfacing in late 1977. there was a dramatic increase in the volume of activity in the stock accompanied by a sharp run-up in price. the eventual merger price of the stock was $46 a share
company officials repeatedly said they could not account for the activity and denied merger negotiations were underway
the 6th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled in 1986 that public statements by basic management during the period leading up to the merger were misleading or untrue, even if the company's denials of negotiations might be correct technically
the supreme court today rejected the appellate court's reasoning that the company's denial of the preliminary talks by itself created grounds for the investors to win their suit
information about a company that is otherwise insignificant does not become important _ or material to the stock's value _ solely because the company denied existence of the development, blackmun said
materiality is something to be determined on the basis of the particular facts of each case,'' blackmun said. ``materiality depends on the significance the reasonable investor would place on the withheld or misrepresented information.''
using that standard, the court ordered further lower court hearings in the suit by investors in basic who said they lost money because facts were withheld from them
blackmun said the presumption at the new hearings must be that the investors would have relied on those facts, unless the management of basic can prove otherwise
where materially misleading statements have been disseminated into an impersonal, well-developed market for securities, the reliance of individual plaintiffs on the integrity of the market price may be presumed,'' blackmun said
he was joined by justices william j. brennan, thurgood marshall and john paul stevens
justice byron r. white, in an opinion joined by justice sandra day o'connor, said the ruling ``may have many adverse, unintended effects as it is applied and interpreted in the years to come.''
for example, white said many investors in basic who are now suing may have doubted the company's denials that preliminary merger talks were underway
such investors, the savviest of the savvy, will be able to recover under the court's opinion,'' white said
the case is basic inc. vs. levinson, 86-279. picks up 4th graf, `british news ...'</note>
british soldiers and police shot and killed three unarmed irish republican army members and foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe told the house of commons today a ``dreadful terrorist act has been averted.''
news reports said two men and a woman were killed sunday after they planted a car bomb and set it to go off tuesday during a military parade in this british colony
but howe denied the news reports and said no bomb had been planted
he said a second car linked to the guerrillas and parked in spanish territory near border with gibraltar, a british colony, contained three false passports and equipment, including an alarm clock, insulating tape, gloves and wire
there is no doubt whatever that as a result of yesterday's events a dreadful terrorist act has been averted,'' said howe, speaking to the house of commons in london
the three people killed were actively involved in the planning and attempted excecution of that act.'' he did not elaborate
british news reports said the two men and a woman were killed after authorities uncovered a plot to set off the car bomb. the reports quoted unidentified security sources
the reports said bomb-disposal experts defused 440 pounds of explosives in a spanish-registered car parked near gov. sir peter terry's official residence in gibraltar, on the southern tip of spain
british armed forces minister ian stewart said ``an intelligence tip-off'' led to information about the three members of the irish republican army, which is fighting a guerrilla war to drive the british out of northern ireland
ronald sindon, a spokesman for the governor, said local police coordinated the effort
the operation was under the control of the gibraltar police commissioner, and british forces acted in support of gibraltar police,'' he said
in an interview in london today on the british broadcasting corporation's radio 4 program, stewart said the gibraltar government of chief minister adolfo canepa asked britain for military assistance ``under the standard arrangements because of the involvement of suspected terrorists.''
stewart said the two men and a woman were unarmed when they were shot and killed by members of the british armed forces
asked whether gibraltar police participated in the shooting, sindon said: ``i am not in a position to comment on operational procedures.''
in madrid, spanish state security spokesman augustin valladolid said today spanish police had tipped off british authorities more than a month ago about the presence of the suspected ira members on spain's southern costa del sol
valladolid said british officials asked spanish police to keep the three under surveillance but not to intervene
in a statement released sunday in belfast, the ira said the three were attached to ``active service units'' of its general headquarters in belfast. it extended ``deepest sympathy to the families of the volunteers.''
independent television in britain today identified the three as mairead farrell, 31; don mccann, 30; and sean savage, 24. the report said they were driving to the airport when they were stopped by the police
it said miss farrell served part of a 14-year prison sentence in connection with a hotel bombing in belfast in 1976
efe, spain's national news agency, said the car carrying the three ira members was stopped by police on a road leading to the spanish border
british newspapers today quoted witnesses as saying plainclothes police officers jumped out of a vehicle and shot without warning at the three. they said one man and the woman fell on the spot and the other man had run 300 yards toward the town center before he was gunned down
the press association, the british domestic news agency, quoted officials as saying the purported bomb may have been timed to go off tuesday when soldiers of the royal anglian regiment are to take part in the changing of the guard ceremony
the regiment has just completed a tour in northern ireland
the guardian, a london newspaper, said today police were carrying out house-to-house searches in the spanish border town of la linea on sunday night for other members
the mainly roman catholic ira is fighting to unite northern ireland, a british province where protestants outnumber catholics 3-2, with the predominantly catholic republic of ireland in a socialist state. inserting 4 grafs after 2nd graf pvs, in washington; edits to tighten</note>
republican presidential contenders bob dole and jack kemp invoked president reagan's name today trying to stem a george bush tide on super tuesday, as the democrats focused on texas the day beore the most delegate-rich showdown in political history
in washington, a federal judge dismissed gop candidate pat robertson's $35 million libel suit against a former congressman who questioned his korean war record
gov. michael dukakis of massachusetts, the leader in polls of texas and florida democrats, met with senior citizens at a north miami beach condominium development
on sunday he campaigned in spanish as he appealed to hispanic voters in texas and then flew to georgia where he met with former president carter
robertson was in texas and told an audience in abilene, ``the frontier that beckons us today is the energy frontier.''
the former television evangelist got the endorsement of diane denman, vice chairman of the texas republican party, who said she knows all the candidates ``but without a doubt, i've got more confidence that it is pat robertson who will provide the unswerving commitment to the conservative beliefs that are needed to see america into the 1990s.''
dole told a news conference in atlanta that ``polls do demonstrate that i beat all the democrats. he (bush) doesn't beat any of them. ... we're trying to continue to reaganize the republican party, to let it grow.''
kemp, struggling to survive after finishing no better than third in any contest so far, told an audience at louisiana state university, ``i think the republican party wants a reagan republican progressive conservative to be nominated and frankly, george bush, bob dole and pat robertson don't qualify.''
we are in the race,'' insisted kemp, brushing aside questions of how well he had to do on tuesday to survive
while dukakis met with carter, sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee picked up backing from another influential georgian, sen. sam nunn. as the georgia senator left for a week-long trip to the soviet union, his office released a statement saying he had cast his absentee ballot for gore because ``his views come closest to my own views as to the steps our nation must take to meet our challenges at home and abroad.''
four of dukakis' rivals _ jesse jackson, gary hart, rep. richard gephardt of missouri and gore _ were in texas today, as was robertson. bush was ending his campaign day in his hometown of houston
texas, which votes with 19 other states on tuesday, offers a trove of 183 democratic delegates and 111 on the republican side
in washington, u.s. district judge joyce hens green signed a brief order dismissing robertson's libel suit ``with prejudice,'' which means that former rep. paul n. mccloskey jr., r-calif. is legally the victor in the dispute
robertson accepted the condition the judge imposed on friday in a one-sentence letter from his attorney douglas v. rigler that was delivered to the judge's chambers by messenger
under terms of the dismissal, robertson must pay court fees, printing costs and court reporters' fees, but not mccloskey's attorney's fees, which he has said total about $400,000
this is a confirmation of my integrity,'' mccloskey said today in a telephone interview from his home in san francisco. ``i don't like at the age of 60 to be called a pathological liar all over the united states. he is admitting that he is the one who is the liar.''
dole conceded sunday he was involved in ``a long, hard fight'' for the gop nomination and he had little cause for optimism about his prospects on tuesday when 17 states hold republican primaries and 20 hold democratic contests
there are 712 republican and 1,307 democratic delegates at stake, including the four to be selected from american samoa
southern and border states dominate the day and william brock, dole's campaign manager, said bush held a ``2-1 or a 3-1 lead in virtually every southern state.''
the vice president demonstrated his strength in the region on saturday when he overwhelmed his rivals in the south carolina primary and swept the state's 37 delegates
on the democratic side, dukakis looked strongest with leads in surveys in texas and florida, the two biggest super tuesday states, and a lock on his home state of massachusetts, which also votes on tuesday
it could be he'll come out of super tuesday the front-runner,'' said a gephardt aide of dukakis
but carter, during his meeting sunday evening with dukakis, predicted no clear winner on tuesday
jackson's support in the black community gives him the biggest southern base of any candidate. interviewed sunday on the abc program, ``this week with david brinkley,'' he said, ``i'm running strong in the south,'' but he refused to predict how many delegates he might win in the region
gore appeared on the same program and conceded he needs to win more than his home state of tennessee on tuesday. he predicted he would carry ``several other'' states, but refused to say which ones
robertson was interviewed on the nbc show ``meet the press'' and said that if he doesn't get 200 to 300 delegates on tuesday ``it will be difficult.''
the vast super tuesday landscape was too much for any candidate to cover in person. millions of dollars was being spent to reach voters through television and radio commercials, with many of the candidates trying to sell themselves by attacking their rivals
gephardt commercials accused dukakis of dirty tricks against other democratic contenders, while the massachusetts governor was running an ad showing an acrobat doing flips, a pointed reference to gephardt shifts on issues
dole continued to run commercials attacking bush for his role in the iran-contra affair, while the vice president was portraying the kansas senator as straddling on taxes. authors say</head> 4th graf pvs, ``excerpts from...''</note>
two noted sex experts who criticized health authorities for failing to stress the extent of the aids epidemic said today that their own estimates of the spread of aids were based on beliefs and estimates, not scientific evidence
we did not project our own database on to the general population,'' said robert kolodny, co-author with william masters and virginia johnson of ``crisis: heterosexual behavior in the age of aids.''
kolodny said at a press conference this morning that the authors' assertion that aids is ``now running rampant in the heterosexual community'' was an estimate based on analysis of existing studies that have appeared in scientific journals. it was not based on original research by the authors, he said
masters, asked for his justification of the claim, said, ``i simply believe it.''
the authors criticized health authorities for failing to stress the threat of aids to heterosexuals, and they have themselves been criticized by an aids expert for making recommendations that might alarm the public
but in their book masters, johnson and kolodny say that medical experts have played down their findings rather than present worst-case scenarios ``in the understandable wish to avoid mass panic.''
the book calls for widespread mandatory testing for acquired immune deficiency syndrome infection by pregnant women, couples seeking marriage licenses and hospital patients between ages 15 and 60
excerpts from the book are appearing in this week's issue of newsweek magazine. the authors run the masters and johnson institute in st. louis and wrote a best-seller, ``human sexual response.''
but some aids experts questioned their conclusions on the spread of the deadly disease
masters and johnson may have expertise in sexuality but they have no credentials to justify their recommendations concerning aids public health policy _ recommendations that will surely alarm the public,'' said mathilde krim, founding chairwoman of the american foundation for aids research
from everything we know today, such mandatory testing schemes will not help protect the public,'' she said saturday
masters and johnson's book suggests that to guard against infection, potential sexual partners undergo tests and remain monogamous
dr. beny j. primm, a member of president reagan's aids commission, said he agreed that recent optimistic reports about heterosexuals could ``lull people into a state of complacency.''
he said as a result many ``don't use condoms, still are promiscuous and still participate in group sex or other dangerous activities.''
the book disputed estimates that there are now about 1.5 million people infected with the virus in the united states
it is quite likely that there are now 3 million or more carriers of the aids virus in the united states, most of whom are otherwise healthy and unaware of their infected, contagious state,'' it said
experts generally are gravely underestimating the degree to which the aids virus has spread into the heterosexual community,'' it said
the authors said they based their findings on their own study of 800 sexually active heterosexual adults between the ages of 21 and 40 who met three criteria: no blood transfusions received since 1977; no use of illicit drugs by injection; no homosexual or bisexual contact since 1977
the study, however, did not appear to follow the usual scientific process and the authors conceded that their sample was not obtained by random sampling methods and did not closely match the general u.s. population
they said they found that among a subgroup of subjects who average more than 12 partners annually and generally failed to take precautions, 14 percent of the women had been infected with the aids virus and 12 percent of the men
the findings were an indication, the researchers said, that ''public health authorities have failed to impress the general public with the message that aids has broken out.''
the supreme court, in an important victory for investors, today placed a heavy burden of proof on companies that are sued for denying they are holding merger negotiations after such preliminary talks are underway
by a 4-2 vote, the court said if companies withhold important information affecting stock prices, it must be presumed that investors who bought and sold the securities were relying on that information
an investor who buys or sells stock at the price set by the market does so in reliance on the integrity of that price,'' said justice harry a. blackmun for the court. ``because most publicly available information is reflected in market price, an investor's reliance on any public material misrepresentations, therefore, may be presumed.''
the absence of a five-vote majority in the case raises the possibility the issue could be reconsidered by the justices in another case with a different result. but, for now at least, today's decision is likely to have important repercussions on wall street
justice anthony m. kennedy, who joined the court last month, did not take part in considering the case. chief justice william h. rehnquist and justice antonin scalia disqualified themselves from participating without explanation
the court ordered further hearings in a dispute involving basic inc. of cleveland
the company merged with cebas inc., a subsidiary of combustion engineering based in connecticut, in december 1978
stockholders said basic executives falsely denied for 14 months prior to the merger that at least preliminary talks were underway between the two companies
as a result, many investors said they sold their stock at far less than its value
combustion engineering is a conglomerate that makes alumina or acid-based refractories _ non-metallic ceramic substances used as structural materials. both basic and combustion engineering were traded on the new york stock exchange
the stock of basic was selling at well under $20 a share when merger rumors began surfacing in late 1977. there was a dramatic increase in the volume of activity in the stock accompanied by a sharp run-up in price. the eventual merger price of the stock was $46 a share
company officials repeatedly said they could not account for the activity and denied merger negotiations were underway
the 6th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled in 1986 that public statements by basic management during the period leading up to the merger were misleading or untrue, even if the company's denials of negotiations might be correct technically
the supreme court today rejected the appellate court's reasoning that the company's denial of the preliminary talks by itself created grounds for the investors to win their suit
information about a company that is otherwise insignificant does not become important _ or material to the stock's value _ solely because the company denied existence of the development, blackmun said
materiality is something to be determined on the basis of the particular facts of each case,'' blackmun said. ``materiality depends on the significance the reasonable investor would place on the withheld or misrepresented information.''
using that standard, the court ordered further lower court hearings in the suit by investors in basic who said they lost money because facts were withheld from them
blackmun said the presumption at the new hearings must be that the investors would have relied on those facts, unless the management of basic can prove otherwise
where materially misleading statements have been disseminated into an impersonal, well-developed market for securities, the reliance of individual plaintiffs on the integrity of the market price may be presumed,'' blackmun said
he was joined by justices william j. brennan, thurgood marshall and john paul stevens
justice byron r. white, in an opinion joined by justice sandra day o'connor, said the ruling ``may have many adverse, unintended effects as it is applied and interpreted in the years to come.''
for example, white said many investors in basic who are now suing may have doubted the company's denials that preliminary merger talks were underway
such investors, the savviest of the savvy, will be able to recover under the court's opinion,'' white said
the case is basic inc. vs. levinson, 86-279
people who hunt vampires, live in caves or slide down buildings in pink elephant costumes aren't crazy. they're just eccentric, and more creative than everybody else, says a researcher who spent three years studying them
dr. david weeks, principal clinical psychologist at the royal edinburgh hospital in scotland, interviewed 130 eccentrics and said he found only one insane person in the crowd
he has turned his findings into a book called ``eccentrics: the scientific investigation,'' to be published in may by stirling university press
it was the first scientific study of its kind in the world,'' weeks said in a telephone interview monday. his study exploded a few myths _ among them that britons are more eccentric than americans
britain has more of a reputation'' for eccentricity, said weeks, an american from garwood, n.j., who has lived in britain since 1975
but both the united states and britain seem to have more eccentrics than other countries, possibly because they have the strongest traditions of free speech, according to weeks
it's also a myth that british eccentrics are mainly aristocrats
they're mostly in the upper middle class _ professional people,'' the psychologist said, and they tend to be outspoken loners
weeks cites prince charles as an eccentric, given his interest in unconventional medicine, his habit of talking to plants, his solitary trips to meditate and his peevish outbursts against modern architecture
he'd probably be a lot more eccentric if he weren't royalty,'' the psychologist said. ``that probably restricts him.''
weeks reckons one person in 10,000 is an eccentric. they tend to be highly creative and have vivid imaginations and graphic dreams
they have lots of good ideas,'' weeks said. ``however, they can be inflexible. if they get a good idea, they stick with it.''
the eccentrics weeks met included a man who has lived in a cave for eight years
another eccentric scales office buildings in a pink elephant costume and has built a ``helimobile,'' a contraption with wheels, wings, flashing lights and an engine
it moves, but it doesn't fly,'' weeks said
then there was a teacher from long island, n.y., who set up a vampire investigation bureau, which is open at night. the teacher travels the world hunting the bloodthirsty creatures
and a scottish lady offered herself as a virgin sacrifice in a mock ritual atop a extinct volcano in the middle of edinburgh
only one turned out to be insane, weeks said. he thought he was a secret agent and demonstrated a throat-cutting technique on week' research assistant, kate ward, with a set of keys
weeks and ms. ward found eccentrics by word of mouth and publicity about their work. people who thought they qualified as eccentrics were given mental and personality tests
eccentrics tend to be happier than most people because they don't take themselves too seriously, weeks said. ``they just have this good sense of humor,'' he said
hundreds of students today shut down gallaudet university, the nation's only university for the deaf, out of anger over the selection of a president who is not hearing impaired
the school was closed early this morning after an estimated 600 students blocked campus entrances, said thomasina wilson, a spokeswoman for the school's security force
joining the students, who were supported by faculty members and alumni, was at least one high-ranking administrator, dean of student life frank r. turk, who told a reporter, ``i have never felt so defeated.''
at issue is the selection of elisabeth a. zinser, now vice chancellor of the university of north carolina at greensboro. gallaudet, chartered by congress in 1864 as the only liberal arts college for the deaf, has never had a deaf president
wilson said students blocked campus entrances with their cars about 6 a.m. james barnes, the school's vice president for business, closed the university a short time later
it's totally impossible for employees to get in,'' wilson said
the board said it would meet with the protesting students, but only if they allowed traffic on and off the campus. the students refused
besides a deaf president, the students were demanding the resignation of board chairman jane bassett spilman and a change in the make-up of the 20-member board to increase the number of deaf members from four to more than half
a city police officer, capt. m.j. johnson, said he expected no arrests as long as the demonstration remained peaceful
turk, walking with students outside the school, said the board was the problem
i've been on the gallaudet payroll for 35 years,'' said turk, who is deaf. ``i have never felt so defeated. i do not think i will ever experience a more frustrating feeling in my life. obviously, we need to overhaul our board of trustees completely. ... they must go _ now.''
after zinser's selection was announced late sunday night, students marched 60 blocks from the campus in northeast washington to the downtown hotel where the university's board was meeting, and back again
on the way back, the marchers passed the white house, then sat at the foot of the capitol grounds, where they were faced for half an hour by a line of 25 city police officers
earlier sunday, throngs of students, faculty and alumni had gathered at the school's gates and waved signs urging ``deaf president now.''
it's important for us,'' student sherri lambert said. ``a deaf president is a role model of all deaf people. he is a leader of the whole deaf community.''
students, faculty and alumni had been urging the appointment of one of the deaf candidates for several weeks. in picking zinser, the school's trustes bypassed two deaf candidates
the deaf candidates for the job were harvey j. corson, 44, superintendent of the louisiana school for the deaf in baton rouge and a gallaudet board member; and i. king jordan, 45, dean of gallaudet's college of arts and sciences. both are gallaudet graduates
the cause of a deaf president has had strong support in congress. republican presidential candidates robert dole and george bush have urged the board to name the school's first deaf president
in 124 years we didn't give them a chance,'' residence hall supervisor tina jo breindel wrote on note paper. ``like eating italian food in chinese restaurant _ strange.''
zinser, who has been vice chancellor at greensboro since 1983, said she plans to take the new job despite the protests. ``very soon i hope to have the opportunity to be a real person to them,'' she said
zinser said the most important step for her now is to develop skills to communicate with the deaf community. she does not know sign language, but is taking classes in it
spilman said zinser had been chosen ``because neither of the other two candidates had the breadth of her experience.''
the vote was 10-4 for zinser. of the four deaf board members, three voted against zinser; one could not vote because he was a candidate for the job
we are aware that it is inevitable that there will be a period where intense disappointment will take over,'' spilman said. ``we know that it will not be easily or quickly erased. we are convinced that, given a chance, both students and the deaf community at large will respond.''
zinser received her doctorate in educational psychology from the university of california, berkeley in 1972. she also has a bachelor's degree in nursing from stanford university and a master's degree in management from the massachusetts institute of technology
the previous president, jerry c. lee, left in january to become a vice president of bassett furniture co., run by the board chairman's family
gallaudet has an enrollment of 2,200 university students, 400 high school students and 200 elementary school students. nearly all the undergraduates are deaf
school spokesman kelly voyet said life at gallaudet is similar to that at other colleges except for the ways in which people communicate
students are ``taught in the total communication method, which is signed english and voice,'' said voyet, ``so that no matter what method the student uses to communicate, it's available to him. a lot of students in their schools learned how to lip read as well as sign.''
the students use tty machines, which have typewriters with screens, to talk on the telephone; strobe lilghts replace fire alarms
otherwise, its basically the same'' as other universities,'' voyet said. ``you just don't hear a lot of voices. other than signing, there's nothing different. they live in dorms, play sports, have homecoming. it's a university with the normal university things. the communication method is a little different in some respect, but that's it.''
election campaigning is causing some beer lovers in kenya to run short of their favorite brew as politicians try to woo voters with free rounds, an official of kenya breweries limited said monday
the result, according to bar and restaurant owners across the country, is that they aren't getting enough beer to satisfy customer demand
many politicians vying for parliamentary seats and civic posts in the march 21 election have been buying beer for would-be supporters
peter burugu, transport and sales director for the privately-owned kenya breweries, said the company saturday released 500,000 crates of beer for distribution throughout the country. each crate holds 24 bottles
normally this is enough but it proved inadequate during this period of the year and the 1988 political campaigns,'' he said
a bank had to tell the fire department to ignore its earlier message about ignoring fire alarms when fire broke out during a test that used smoke to check for leaks
we had to call ... and say this is the real thing,'' bob brown, a spokesman for commercial national bank, said sunday
the bank had told the fire department earlier to ignore alarms set off by the smoke pumped into pipes sunday morning to look for leaks
the fire was out in less than 30 minutes
an avalanche hit a small village in this eastern province near the iranian border, killing 19 people and injuring eight others, the anatolia news agency said monday
the dispatch said eight homes were buried under the avalanche in ikiyaka village in the township of yuksekova on sunday. a 7-month-old baby was among the victims
anatolia said governor arif akbulut and a health team flew to the village by a helicopter on monday as roads were cut off because of heavy snow in the area
two blacks described by police as ``trained terrorists'' were killed, and six policemen were slightly injured in a shootout at a house in queenstown, police said monday
police, acting on a tip, surrounded a house in the southern city on friday afternoon and ordered the inhabitants to leave. when the occupants refused, police threw ``stun grenades'' into the house, police said in a statement
a stun grenade contains no shrapnel and is considered non-lethal
a shootout ensued, and two black men inside the house were killed. the six officers suffered minor injuries, the statement said
police did not say how they knew the men were ``trained terrorists.''
also monday, police said they expelled seven police reservists because they were members of the extreme right-wing afrikaner resistance movement
the paramilitary group seeks a whites-only homeland within south africa and has been taking an increasingly confrontational stance recently against the white-led government
several thousand members marched on government buildings on feb. 27 to present a petition calling for an all-white state
the government said last week it would dismiss policemen holding membership in the organization. the seven reservists, from northern transvaal province, were the first policemen expelled under the government's new policy
a two-headed shrimp a fisherman found in his bait bucket appears to be the first such specimen on record, experts say
we're dealing with a first occurrence here, i guess, to the best of our knowledge,'' said neal baxter, chief of the national marine fisheries service ecology division in galveston
the shrimp has been sent to the smithsonian institution in washington
howard fraley, 37 and his wife, c.j., were fishing near galveston last may when fraley dipped into his bait bucket and came out with the oddity
i said: `why, this thing's got two heads!''' he said
the couple photographed the shrimp, then took it home and put it in their freezer
mrs. fraley mentioned it to baxter, who told austin b. williams, a curator of invertebrates at the smithsonian's national museum of natural history
it was as curious to me as it was to the folks who found it,'' williams said
williams dissected the shrimp and said both heads appeared normal in many ways. he has searched scientific literature to the late 1800s, but has found no mention of a similar case
fraley feels lucky to have found the creature
i was excited,'' he said. ``and to think i nearly tore the head off.''
corruption is so rampant in the soviet republic of turkmenia that a powerful underworld has developed, complete with hit men, protection rackets, police payoffs and powerful mob chieftains, pravda said monday
the communist party newspaper even noted that the funeral of an underworld crime boss drew 400 mourners
pravda said many police officers not only looked the other way at crime in the central asian republic, but masterminded some of the schemes. it said 12 are now are on trial for extortion
they extorted money mostly from those who wouldn't appeal to the police, like a certain gavrush sarkisya, a former shop foreman, who confessed to the police later that he owed the criminals ($150,000),'' pravda said. ``and they threatened him with a firing squad should he fail to pay up.''
other central asian republics also have been blasted by the soviet media for large-scale corruption. in recent months, the media have exposed millions of dollars in graft in uzbekistan, turkmenia's neighbor to the north
on jan. 20, the weekly literaturnaya gazeta disclosed that the head of an agricultural complex in uzbekistan built his own mob empire, complete with his own courts and an underground prison constructed by 1,000 workers
the expose was striking in its recitation of abuses
pravda's account on turkmenia, while not as dramatic, was the strongest criticism yet of the soviet union's southernmost republic, which has 3.27 million people, mostly moslems
official media criticism of turkmenia usually has centered around moslem customs judged by the central government to be abhorent, such as reports of young women being killed for insufficient marriage dowries
the republic suffers a difficult situation, created over years of bureaucratic rule,'' pravda said. referring to the swelling bureacracy, it added: ``every sixth person in the republic is a hack official
many highly placed police officials, and policemen of lesser ranks, were involved in all kinds of crimes and often acted as their skilled masterminds,'' the newspaper reported
pravda said the crackdown in the region began with the recent appointment of alexander f. udalov as the republic's police chief. pravda said he was threatened shortly after taking office by ilyas a. sarkiev, one of those now on trial
just leave me alone. quit this case. several hundred thousand rubles will go your way,'' sarkiev was quoted as telling udalov. ``also keep in mind. i know the city your daughter lives in. i have nothing to lose, you know. you won't be able to get all my people.''
the newspaper said that sarkiev was arrested three days after making the threat
pravda also described a threat against a. allaverdov, the manager of a footwear shop in ashkabad. he reported that when he had a falling out with sarkiev, violence began
allaverdov told authorities his new car was stolen and found burned the next morning in the center of the city. the windows of his apartment were shot out, he said, and he received a threat that his son would be kidnapped
pravda said the recent crackdown has routed several ``criminals'' from official posts in turkmenia, but it noted that a recent funeral illustrated continuing problems
a well-known underworld figure died in a traffic accident. four hundred criminals came to his funeral from different cities, which goes to show the atmosphere in ashkhabad quite well,'' pravda said
seven passengers were killed and 24 were critically injured when a bus overturned on a winding mountain road in zimbabwe's eastern highlands, police said monday
the bus was apparently trying to overtake another vehicle near the village of chimanimani, near the mozambique border, when it ran off the road and flipped over, police said
the bus was carrying about 70 people when it crashed sunday morning. police said they had no further details
the supreme court ruled unanimously today that financially troubled farmers may not avoid foreclosure under federal bankruptcy law by promising to use their labor, experience and expertise in continuing to operate their farm
by an 8-0 vote, the court said a secured creditor's right to ``adequate protection'' under bankruptcy law cannot be satisified by such a promise
the ruling is a key setback for many farmers who suffered financial difficulty in the early 1980s. one such couple was james and mary ahlers, grain and livestock farmers who farm about 840 acres of land in nobles county, minn
the ahlers have outstanding loans with two minnesota banks, norwest bank worthington and the federal land bank of st. paul
today's decision, overturning a ruling by the 8th u.s. circuit court of appeals, is a victory for the two banks
between 1965 and 1982 the ahlers obtained four loans from the federal land bank of st. paul, securing each of the loans with a separate parcel of land they owned
between 1982 and 1984 they obtained additional loans from norwest bank worthington, securing them with a second mortgage on the land used to secure the federal land bank loans and a first mortgage on their farm's machinery, equipment, crops and livestock
the ahlers defaulted on the loans _ over $500,000 to the federal land bank and about $450,000 to norwest. just after norwest went to court in an attempt to take control of the ahlers' assets, the couple filed for reorganization under federal bankruptcy law
that move automatically froze norwest's collection efforts in a state court
the two banks, claiming they were undersecured creditors, sought the bankruptcy judge's help in seizing control of the ahlers' assets. the banks said the ahlers could not protect their secured interest in the outstanding loans
the bankruptcy judge and a federal trial judge cleared the way for foreclosure on the ahlers' farm but the 8th circuit court reversed those rulings in 1986
the appeals court ruled that the banks' right to adequate protection could be satisified by the ahlers' promise to continue to work their farm with the experience and expertise they bring to the job
the banks then successfully sought supreme court review, joined by the reagan administration in urging a reversal of the appeals court ruling
writing for the court today, justice byron r. white said the appeals court ruling wrongly carved out an exception to the ``absolute priority rule'' of bankruptcy law
that rule bars people who file for bankruptcy from getting anything out of a reorganization plan unless all creditors are paid off in full
we find no support in the (bankruptcy) code or our previous decisions for the court of appeals' application of the absolute rule in this case,'' white said. ``we conclude that the rule applies here, and (the ahlers') promise of future labor warrants no exception to its operation.''
justice anthony m. kennedy did not participate in the decision
the case is norwest bank worthington vs. ahler, 86-958
guilt drove a man to turn himself in and confess after more than two years on the run since he bludgeoned and strangled his sister in a dispute over money, police say
i think the police are looking for me,'' officials quoted henry zalewski as saying when he walked into a police station saturday evening
zalewski, 54, was charged sunday with second-degree murder in the killing of his sister, genevieve zalewski, 62, in the apartment they shared on sept. 30, 1985
he did it in a fit of anger ... and because of a financial situation he was in,'' said detective joseph stabile
zalewski also was charged with attempted murder for the beating of a neighbor, alice turel, now 50, on the same day
detectives said that during his confession zalewski said he turned himself in because the guilt was driving him toward suicide
stabile said that at the time of the slaying zalewski was penniless and in debt to a loanshark for $8,400
on the morning of the slaying, zalewski made his sister breakfast. while she was in the kitchen, he struck her on the head with a piece of pipe, dragged her into a bedroom and strangled her with rope, stabile said
while fleeing he encountered turel and beat her over the head with a pair of pliers before kicking her down a flight of stairs, stabile said. turel needed 67 stitches in the head
he disappeared after the attack but police watched the apartment for three months because a hit list of neighbors was discovered inside, officer hugh barry said
zalewski said he took $40 from the house and began wandering up and down the east coast. he got a social security number under a phony name and alternated between getting welfare and temporary work
stabile said zalewski started drinking a quart of vodka a day to try to dull the memory of killing his sister
three weeks ago, he phoned st. stanislaus church to find out where his sister was buried
a homemade bomb exploded near the saudi arabian airline office here monday and blew off the finger of a man, police said
aaron abraham, deputy superintendent of police, told reporters that a man saw a bag on the sidewalk in front of the building housing the saudian arabian airline office
as mohamed fauzir baharuddin, 33, opened the bag, the bomb exploded, blowing off a finger and injuring him on the face, neck and chest, abraham said
a police bomb disposal unit searched the area but found no other bomb
police said they didn't know the motive for the bombing or who was responsible for it. they said an investigation was under way. ireland</head>
mayor raymond l. flynn says he may skip boston's st. patrick's day parade because he and his wife have been invited to dublin by irish prime minister charles haughey
missing the parade in south boston would mean flynn would not face jeers similar to those he faced at a recent hearing on his plan to desegregate housing projects in that neighborhood
flynn was invited to dublin to help celebrate that city's millenium
police said flynn's integration proposal has made him a target of increasing death threats
we've gotten threats periodically since he came into office, but they've increased over the past few weeks,'' said sgt. detective edward wallace. ``we're treating it as a serious matter.''
flynn's wife, cathy, said she was preparing to go to church sunday when police told her someone had threatened to bomb the house. wallace said a search failed to turn up any explosive device
i took a position that i believe in and i'm going to see that it's implemented,'' the mayor said saturday about his housing plan. ``i can't just worry about the political consequences of everything i do. people in southie have more respect for somebody who takes a position rather than someone who ducks and hides behind someone else.''
city councilor james kelly, of south boston, said he believed flynn was skipping the parade to avoid potential embarrassment
i think the mayor feels he would not be that well-received,'' said kelly, a vocal flynn critic. ``obviously that would not be good for his image. after all, this is his neighborhood.''
u.s. officials are monitoring polish and east german cooperation with efforts to close down an arms trading office affiliated with the abu nidal terrorist group
according to a cia report, abu nidal kept an apartment in warsaw and his associates ran a trade operation from an office tower there after he was forced to leave iraq in 1983
last summer, u.s. diplomats began pressuring the polish government privately, and in august the poles promised to close the operation, s.a.s.-international commerce and investments, and order its staff to leave the country. a similar operation was closed in east germany
the front offices have been shut down in poland and east germany,'' a state department official said. ``they have told us and we believe that they have been shut down.''
this doesn't necessarily mean that these governments have ended all their contacts with abu nidal's associates for good. we'd like to think so. it is something that remains to be seen,'' said the source, who like others interviewed over the past week spoke on condition of anonymity
polish officials insisted that the government ``had no idea'' what s.a.s. was
but u.s. officials say polish security agencies must have known that abu nidal had overall control over s.a.s., and that the organization was selling soviet-bloc arms in the middle east
there are factions in these governments, and top political leaders and places like the foreign ministries might not have known what was going on,'' one u.s. government terrorism expert said
abu nidal, nom de guerre of palestinian-born sabri al-banna, is now believed to live in tunis, according to soviet-bloc and administration sources
abu nidal's group is blamed for numerous terrorist incidents, including attacks in the rome and vienna airports on dec. 27, 1985, in which 18 people were killed
the head of s.a.s., samir hasan najmeddin, was forced to leave poland on jan. 14, several days after the departure of his top deputy, according to polish officials
the poles delayed the expulsions for nearly a month past a promised december deadline, upsetting some u.s. counterterrorism officials who pushed for release of an unclassified version of the cia report
u.s. diplomats dealing with europe, meanwhile, sought to keep the affair under wraps, administration sources said
some details of the report were published in the new york times, however, angering polish leader wojciech jaruzelski, who complained about the leak during a january meeting in warsaw with deputy secretary of state john c. whitehead, the no. 2 official in the department, sources said. whitehead expressed ``regret'' about the disclosure, the sources said
the cia report, which was discussed by administration officials but not shown to the ap, said najmeddin settled in warsaw in 1973 at no. 3 bagno st., apt. 24, and founded s.a.s. 10 years later to sell arms and other goods abroad, mainly in the middle east. s.a.s. maintained offices on the 25th floor of the intraco building in warsaw
poland earned badly needed foreign currency from the enterprise, and abu nidal's group kept most of the profit as well as weapons
s.a.s. was the most important link in a chain of legitimate business enterprises affiliated with abu nidal in europe, the u.s. report said
the east germans allowed an abu nidal affiliate called zibado consultant and international commerce to keep an office on friedrichstrasse in east berlin in 1983-86, but now have closed it, and bulgarian officials also have curtailed their ties with terrorist organizations, according to a senior administration source
polish government spokesman jerzy urban announced the closure of the s.a.s. office in january and said authorities did not know whether abu nidal had ever been in poland
i am saying this cautiously, because the authorities cannot exclude'' that abu nidal entered the country under another name, urban told reporters
according to the cia, abu nidal presided over at least four meetings in warsaw, two in december 1983, again in september 1984 and most recently in june 1987
in poland, s.a.s. dealt with the etat cenzin co. and paid its representative, andrzej marchewska, $600 a month to facilitate visas for palestinian operatives and obtain customs clearances for shipments of pistols, rifles and hand-held anti-tank and anti-aircraft weapons
the cia report said many of these weapons went to terrorists linked to abu nidal
in the summer of 1984, the report said, s.a.s sold libya 4,000 soviet-designed kalashnikov assault rifles made in east germany for about $500,000
the next year, s.a.s. was agent for the sale of rifles and pistols in the middle east
in 1986, the report said, the company obtained 115 british enfield anti-riot weapons, keeping 15 and giving 100 to east german authorities
additionally, the report said, s.a.s. sponsored scholarships for palestinians to study in poland, and some of them were recruited into abu nidal's terrorist organization. accidental</head>
the death of a 12-year-old boy whose nude body was found in his family's portable dishwasher has been ruled accidental, authorities said monday
brown county coroner genie williams has not officially ruled on a cause of death, but cmdr. david zasada said initial indications are that michael conard ``very probably died of a lack of oxygen prior to the hot water'' beginning to circulate in the machine a week ago
the boy, who was 4-foot-10 and weighed about 90 pounds, apparently used the soap dispenser inside the door to pull the door shut, zasada said. there is no release mechanism inside the machine, he said
the boy took off his clothes and watch before climbing in machine, apparently to see how it worked, zasada said
suicide was ruled out because there was no note and friends, family and teachers indicated the boy was well-adjusted and happy, zasada said
the first california condor egg produced by a captive breeding pair is fertile, and a chick should emerge from the shell in less than two months, san diego wild animal park officials said today
fertility of the egg, laid last thursday, was confirmed this morning when condor keepers briefly held it up to a high intensity lamp and detected a preliminary stage of development, park spokesman tom hanscom said
the egg was returned to an incubator, where it will be kept until the expected hatching between april 28 and may 3
all of the 27 living california condors are in captivity, 14 at the wild animal park and 13 at the los angeles zoo. of the 27, 13 were hatched in captivity as part of an effort to build a breeding flock to save the rare birds from extinction
meanwhile, the parents of the condor egg were said to be doing well. keepers removed the egg from its nest at the park's ``condorminium'' to stimulate more breeding activity by the pair, and that's what's happening
that's real positive,'' hanscom said. ``that would lead us to hope for the production of a second egg, which could come as early as 30 days after the first egg.''
the parents are doing fine, the egg is doing fine, the keepers are doing fine,'' hanscom added
h. ross perot, the self-made texas billionaire businessman and philanthropist, will be the speaker at this year's associated press annual meeting luncheon, ap chairman william j. keating announced monday
keating, chief executive of the detroit newspaper agency, said the luncheon will be held at the hilton hawaiian village hotel in honolulu april 25, immediately following the news cooperative's annual meeting of newspaper members
perot, whose achievements include organizing the rescue of two of his employees from an iranian jail in 1979, is an outspoken champion of american entrepreneurial spirit, public causes and family values. electronic data systems corp., which he founded in 1962 with $1,000 of his own money, grew into a multibillion-dollar company and was acquired by general motors corp. in 1984
the ap meeting is held on the first day of the american newspaper publishers association annual convention, scheduled this year for april 25-27 in honolulu
mozambique rebels said monday they killed 43 mozambican and 13 zimbabwean soldiers when they captured the town of sena in central zambezia province
a lisbon-based spokesman for the mozambican national resistance said one zimbabwean and two mozambican army battalions were chased off during the attack sunday
the spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, claimed the rebels also seized large quantities of military supplies. there was no independent confirmation of the claims
the rebels have been fighting since 1977 to topple the marxist mozambican government. troops from neighboring zimbabwe, tanzania and malawi fight alongside the mozambican army against the guerrillas
a palestinian convicted of trying to plant a bomb on an israeli airliner lost his bid to appeal his 45-year sentence monday after a judge declared the prison term was ``not a day too long.''
nezar hindawi was jailed in october 1986 for duping his pregnant fiancee into carrying a bomb aboard an el al jumbo jet at london's heathrow airport the previous april. israeli guards found the bomb before it reached the plane
allegations that the jordan-born palestinian was in league with the syrian embassy in london led britain to sever diplomatic ties with damascus. hindawi claimed the israelis framed him
hindawi's sentence was ``not a day too long'' for ``as foul and as horrible a crime as can possibly be imagined,'' ruled lord chief justice geoffrey lane, presiding over the three-judge appeals court
hindawi's attorney, michael massih, argued that hindawi's actions had not caused loss of life. but lane said, ``it is no thanks to him that he did not succeed in destroying 36o to 37o lives in an effort to promote one side of a political dispute by terrorism.''
pleading for hindawi to be permitted to appeal his sentence, massih argued that it was harsh compared with the 35-year sentence imposed on patrick magee, convicted of planting an irish republican army bomb in a hotel where prime minister margaret thatcher was staying. that bomb killed five people
lane pointed out that unlike magee, hindawi could get one-third off for good conduct and serve only 30 years
hindawi, 33, was not in court
here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken monday by the supreme court

adult bookstores

the court agreed to decide whether states may use anti-racketeering laws to close down adult bookstores
the justices said they will review a pair of free-speech challenges to such an indiana law
the cases are fort wayne books vs. indiana, 87-470; and sappenfield vs. indiana, 87-614

death penalty

the court agreed to consider reinstating the death sentence of a florida man convicted of killing an 8-year-old girl in 1978
the court is expected to use the case to study death row inmates' right to raise new issues when they turn to the federal courts for help and to decide whether florida juries may be told their life-or-death recommendations are subject to the trial judge's approval
the case is dugger vs. adams, 87-121

vaccine

the court left intact a $1.13 million jury award to an idaho boy paralyzed from the waist down after he was given a vaccination for three diseases
the court, without comment, rejected arguments by the vaccine manufacturer that such verdicts could force drug companies to abandon the production of essential vaccines
the case is lederle laboratories vs. toner, 87-1151

farm bankruptcy

the court ruled unanimously that financially troubled farmers may not avoid foreclosure under federal bankruptcy law by promising to use their labor, experience and expertise in continuing to operate their farm
by an 8-0 vote, the court said a secured creditor's right to ``adequate protection'' under bankruptcy law cannot be satisfied by such a promise
the case is norwest bank worthington vs. ahler, 86-958

churches

the court refused to free churches from having to comply with state financial-disclosure laws when waging public referendum campaigns
the court, citing the lack of a ``substantial federal question,'' turned away a challenge by 13 churches from jackson, tenn., to a law they contend violates their freedom of religion and freedom of speech
the case is bemis pentacostal vs. tennessee, 87-317

secret hearings

the court let stand a ruling that the public has no right to attend hearings into the alleged tainting or bribing of a criminal trial jury while the trial is underway
the justices, without comment, refused to second-guess the validity of conducting such hearings in secret during the 1986 racketeering trial of louisiana gov. edwin w. edwards
the case is times-picayune publishing vs. edwards, 87-872

globe libel

the court cleared the way for a jury trial in former massachusetts gov. edward j. king's $3.6 million libel lawsuit against the boston globe
the justices, over one dissenting vote, left intact a massachusetts supreme judicial court ruling that a jury should hear king's contention that he was libeled by a nov. 8, 1981, column
the case is globe newspaper co. vs. king, 87-731

mobile homes

the court cleared the way for a trial in what may become an important test case on the power of cities to control rents and otherwise protect mobile home residents
the court, without comment, rejected an appeal by santa barbara, calif., officials aimed at killing a lawsuit by owners of a mobile home park who claim they unfairly are being deprived of their property's full value
the case is santa barbara vs. hall, 87-220

jehovah's witness

the court refused to hear the appeal of a florida woman who says she was denied custody of her young child because she is a jehovah's witness
the justices, without comment, let stand state court rulings that bar rita mendez from exposing her daughter to any of her religious beliefs
the case is mendez vs. mendez, 87-1166

cities

the court said it will try again to decide whether cities may be sued successfully when citizens' rights are violated due to alleged inadequate training of municipal employees
the justices said they will study the issue in an appeal by canton, ohio officials
the case is canton vs. harris, 86-1088
members of this city's influential construction unions threw rocks and eggs and shouted pro-union slogans today outside the annual convention of the associated builders and contractors, officials said
police in helmets were called in to keep traffic flowing outside moscone center, where about 2,000 demonstrators from the building trade councils of three san francisco bay area counties stood five-deep blocking buses carrying convention guests and their families, officers reported
the association will seek a court injunction against the demonstrators, said terry maenza, spokesman for the association
we have met this morning with unruly and irresponsible behavior that has jeopardized the safety of our members and their families,'' said mike perkins, national president of associated builders and contractors
the association is a fast-growing organization of 19,000 employers who hire mostly non-union workers
although 2,000 association members were expected at the meeting, only 400 had arrived when it opened
union members claim the contractors' organization is seeking to break union control of construction projects
about 10,000 workers are employed on construction sites throughout the city, said tom thompson, director of one of the union contractor's associations. graf pvs: on friday ...; deletes outdated 11th graf pvs: department of ...; retransmits a0628 to fix category code to a</note>
arizona's top police officer testified today at gov. evan mecham's impeachment trial that he was ``surprised and shocked'' when the governor told him not to cooperate in an investigation of an alleged death threat
department of public safety director ralph milstead told the senate today that mecham told him last nov. 15 the alleged threat ``was a family spat.''
impeachment charges against the 63-year-old mecham, first-term republican, included a charge that he tried to thwart an investigation of the alleged threat
milstead quoted mecham as saying, ``the attorney general is out to hang me and i'm not going to help him in any way ... don't tell the attorney general anything.''
he said, `never, don't give them any help,''' milstead said. ``this whole situation surprised and shocked me... i just cannot cover up, even if the governor is the one telling me to do that.''
the senate decided earlier this morning not to grant immunity to the man accused of making the threat, former state official lee watkins
attorney general bob corbin told lawmakers that granting immunity to watkins, former head of state prison construction, could wind up protecting him from prosecution for alleged crimes ``you have no way of knowing about today.''
senators were considering whether to grant ``use immunity'' to watkins to force him to say whether he threatened the life of donna carlson last november, which would have meant his testimony could not be used against him in criminal court
on friday, watkins invoked the fifth amendment right against self-incrimination in refusing to testify before the senate. watkins said today that if the state grand jury probe were over he would have no problem with testifying
these are the people (the attorney general's office) that are out to get the governor,'' watkins said. ``anybody that gets in the middle is going to get hurt.''
shortly after the senate's voice vote, watkins admitted he hadn't expected to get immunity
a grant of immunity should be made only if the testimony sought is central to the case, if lawmakers think watkins will tell the truth and if the immunity will not compromise a criminal investigation, corbin said
a state grand jury investigation of watkins is continuing, corbin said
mecham's defense lawyer, jerris leonard, accused prosecutors of trying to harm watkins' reputation in testimony last week and of ``splattering the mud broadly enough so that it splatters on the respondent (mecham).''
department of public safety director ralph milstead also was scheduled to take the stand today. mecham is accused of ordering milstead not to cooperate with corbin's investigation of the alleged threat
mecham was impeached nov. 5 by the house, which also accused him of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
watkins has been investigated by the state grand jury in connection with the alleged threat but has not been charged. attorneys said last week the inquiry was continuing
last friday, peggy griffith, head of the governor's office of women's services, testified that watkins told her nov. 12 that ms. carlson, a former special gubernatorial assistant who was about to testify before the grand jury on the $350,000 loan, was a ``bad girl.'' she told the trial that if ms. carlson kept talking ``she is going to take a long boat ride.''
watkins has denied making a threat, and prosecutor william french asked him friday if he had taken six lie-dectector tests in an effort to prove he hadn't made the threat. watkins refused to answer the question
mrs. griffith also testified that when she described the alleged threat to max hawkins, then watkins' boss, he shrugged it off as ``just a bunch of hot air.''
mecham, in testimony before a house impeachment committee in january, acknowledged that he may have told milstead not to cooperate with the attorney general's probe. however, mecham also contended he was not fully informed about the seriousness of the situation before his conversation with milstead
mecham, the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in six decades, did not attend the first five days of testimony last week
a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required to convict mecham and remove him from office. mecham also faces a may 17 recall election and a march 22 criminal trial in connection with the $350,000 campaign loan
canadian prime minister brian mulroney will make an official visit to washington and meet with president reagan on april 27, the white house said monday
it will be the fifth meeting between the two leaders, and mulroney's third visit to washington
the supreme court today agreed to study the appeal of a convicted chicago murderer sentenced to 50 to 100 years in prison for his crime
the justices said they will use warren lee harris' case to give federal courts some further guidance in how to handle the appeals of defendants convicted in state courts
harris was convicted of the july 19, 1977, murder in chicago of earnest howard
after his conviction was upheld by the illinois courts on direct appeal, harris filed a so-called habeas corpus appeal in state courts. in it, he contended for the first time that he was denied adequate legal help at his trial
state courts ruled that harris could not raise that issue because he had failed to raise it on direct appeal, but it then rejected the merits of harris' ineffective-assistance argument
harris then sought help from the federal courts, in a habeas corpus petition raising the same issue
a federal trial judge ruled that harris' procedural default, which usually would preclude federal court review of his claim, had been waived by the state courts
but the 7th u.s. circuit court of appeals last june 12 ruled that the procedural default blocks federal court review of the ineffective-assistance argument
the case is harris vs. reed, 87-5677
six u.s. navy ships assembled in the southern persian gulf on monday, prompting rumors of retaliation for an iranian attack on american helicopters, but the navy called the ship movements routine
iran said monday its anti-aircraft batteries fired on two helicopters over the weekend, forcing them to withdraw, because the choppers ignored a warning to stay clear of an ``iranian zone'' in the gulf. the united states issued a similar account earlier
rumors of navy action spread through shipping circles in the gulf, where iran and iraq have been at war since september 1980, when six u.s. vessels were spotted off dubai. they included a chartered tanker and combat stores ship
the navy denied the rumors. ``we wouldn't be planning an attack with a supply ship,'' lt. cmdr. mark van dyke said. ``these movements were scheduled long before the helicopter incident.''
tehran's official islamic republic news agency said the helicopters were ``forced to flee'' by anti-aircraft fire at about midnight saturday
u.s. officials had said american helicopters took ``evasive action'' after machine guns were fired from an oil platform and several small boats during a scouting mission ahead of the u.s. missile frigate simpson. they did not say how many choppers were involved
neither report gave the location of the oil platform or named it, but the american versian said it was not the rostam platform, which four u.s. destroyers shelled oct. 19
rostam has been reported under repair since the raid, described by u.s. officials as a ``measured response'' to an attack in which an iranian silkworm missile damaged a u.s.-flagged kuwaiti tanker anchored at kuwait's main oil terminal
at the time, the u.s. officials said more severe reprisals could be expected if iran attacked other american ships or aircraft
since last july, u.s. warships have protected kuwaiti tankers sailing under the american flag. eleven of the sheikdom's tankers have been given u.s. registration
the rostam precedent combined with the sighting of the six ships to encourage the rumors of u.s. plans for retaliation
navy officers said two of the ships, the guided missile frigates copeland and gary, were learning the ropes as new members of the gulf-based fleet, the middle east force
they were escorting the 18,000-ton stores ship san jose and the 39,000-ton oiler l.h. gianella, both on resupply missions, van dyke said
he said it was ``just coincidental'' that the four ships were spotted near the missile cruiser wainwright and missile frigate john a. moore, which have been in the gulf for weeks and were on ``routine escort duty'' off dubai
in the navy's gulf operation, which has been cut from 17 to 16 ships, the copeland and gary are expected to replace sister frigates mcclusky and reuben james, the next vessels slated to depart under navy policy that limits duty tours to six months, port-to-port
iran's account of the helicopter incident said: ``two u.s. helicopters attempting to approach an iranian zone in the persian gulf early sunday were forced to flee by the anti-aircraft fire of naval forces of the islamic republic of iran
the navy anti-aircraft detected the two helicopters on its radar and warned them to stay out of the iranian zone. however, the iranian navy fired warning shots after the u.s. helicopters violated the iranian zone.''
nothing was said in the u.s. version about a warning before the shooting started
it was the second time in a month that iran claimed to have driven off american helicopters with anti-aircraft fire. u.s. officials denied the first iranian report, of a similar incident feb. 12 at sirri island in the south central gulf
iran uses some oil platforms and small islands in the gulf as bases for armed speedboats that attack commercial shipping
there have been no such attacks since feb. 11, and no iraqi air raids on iran's own oil shipping since feb. 12 _ one of the longest lulls in the ``tanker war'' since it began in february 1984
iran and iraq have been attacking each other's capitals and other cities since feb. 29, in a new round of the ``war of the cities'' that has cost thousands of lives during the 7{-year-old war. pvs, any user.</note>
the reagan administration said today it has protested poor maintenance of some panama canal facilities, but said the problem was not linked to the recent political turmoil there
there are some facilities that are maintained by panama that we have protested in a sense of not being adequately maintained,'' said white house spokesman marlin fitzwater
he said the complaint was registered ``sometime previously'' and was not intended to justify an abrogation of the panama canal treaty
meanwhile, a newspaper reported that political appointees installed by the panamanian government are mismanaging operations of the canal that have been turned over by the united states
any user of those facilities will tell you there are difficulties now that simply did not exist 10 years ago,'' an unidentified panamanian economist told the new york times
among the facilities suffering from mismanagement are ports, marine bunkering installations, a railroad, a bridge and air traffic control, according to the times, which interviewed canal employees and shipping experts
this government has put a political aspect to an equation that has no room for politics,'' said a panamanian engineer who has worked at the canal for more than a decade. ``as soon as you start to mix panamanian politics with the running of the canal, that is the end of things.''
the country's political situation has been particularly troubled in recent weeks. gen. manuel antonio noriega, the military leader who is panama's de facto leader, engineered the ouster of president eric arturo delvalle after delvalle tried to fire him
the united states still recognizes delvalle, who is in hiding, as panama's rightful president and has brought economic pressure to bear to oust noriega. noriega is also under indictment in the united states for alleged drug trafficking
panama is scheduled to take control of the waterway in the year 2000, according to the 1977 treaties. but some of the 7,000 canal employees, 83 percent of whom are panamanians, fear that domestic political interference could hinder their ability to run the canal professionally, the times said
as the year 2000 approaches, it is going to be necessary for laws to keep this organization a bit apart from the normal government structure, so there is no interference by other ministries or the implantation of political but unskilled people in the upper echelons,'' said dennis p. mcauliffe, an american and chief administrator of the canal
a panamanian civil engineer told the newspaper that derailments on the railroad have increased because of lack of maintenance and that rail yards ``are in a state of disrepair.''
shipping lines complain that lights and gangways don't work and that fenders along docks are not maintained
the panama defense forces have taken some of the best office buildings for their own use as warehouses or as prisons, the times reported, forcing some canal operations to move elsewhere
president reagan lashed out today at congressional opponents to contra aid, accusing them of a lack of courage in the battle against communism in central america
in a speech to the veterans of foreign wars convention, reagan talked about the votes last week in congress that left the rebels battling the leftist government of nicragua without u.s. funding
the 216-208 vote defeated a democratic plan to provide $30.8 million in food, clothing and medical aid to the rebels. the vote was scheduled by the democratic leadership so the house could not vote on an aid plan favored by the republicans
courage hasn't exactly been the watchword of some opponents of contra aid,'' reagan said. ``... last week, aid opponents tried to pass the buck of responsibility for abandoning in the field the young men and women of the democratic resistance, and that ploy failed as it should have.''
administration officials have expressed the hope congress could come up with an alternative plan to keep the rebels alive as a fighting force
after reagan's speech, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater acknowledged that a ``real problem'' exists for the administration because a new contra aid package might not be considered for some time
it's just a matter of time,'' he said. ``we will produce a package,'' he vowed at another point
in his speech, reagan recalled that nicaraguan president daniel ortega dismissed cardinal obando y bravo as the mediator in peace talks with the rebels
you know where ortega stands. isn't it time for congress to have the courage to show where it stands?'' reagan asked rhetorically
now it's time for congress to show that it knows you can't have real peace negotiations when one side has helicopter gunships and the other has bandages,'' he said
reagan said the defeat of the contras would mean a ``grave strategic defeat for the united states.''
the communists in central america understand this, the soviets understand this _ it's time that congress understood it, too,'' reagan said, adding, ``a soviet base on the american mainland is a pistol pointed at the heart of the americas.''
reagan contended that the ``real issue'' before the congress is not the contras, ``it is communisim in central america.''
the president, who was warmly greeted by the audience of older veterans, told them of his recent trip to brussels, belgium, where he met with nato leaders. he asked their support for the ratification of the recently signed u.s.-soviet treaty banning medium-range nuclear missles from europe
reagan also called on congress to reject further cuts in the nation's defense budget and allow for a strong alliance defense
this is not the time to drop our guard,'' reagan said. ``it's just this simple. if we put americans in harm's way, we owe them the best weapons money can buy.''
we'll need to keep up our strength if we're to succeed, and that's why the congress must not further reduce the defense budget,'' reagan said
offering a report on the brussels meeting in his saturday radio address, reagan declared that ``arms reduction is not enough'' in dealing with the soviets and demanded they abandon the ``offensive strategy'' displayed against the western alliance on the european continent
reagan said there was a ``lesson learned'' at the meeting, which was the first full-scale summit for the leaders of the north atlantic treaty organization in six years
one must always negotiate with the soviets from a position of strength,'' reagan said
following the nato summit, a white house advance team traveled to moscow to scout out possible sites for the fourth meeting between reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev, planned for late may or early june
in his radio speech, reagan pointed out that while the allies praised the new u.s.-soviet agreement to remove all medium-range nuclear missiles from europe, they reaffirmed the need to remain united and keep their guard up
that's why continued modernization of nato forces _ nuclear and conventional _ is essential,'' reagan said
the u.s. government is seeking the dismissal of a lawsuit that would end federal aid to religious schools abroad, primarily jewish schools in israel, a prosecutor said monday
bernard bell, an assistant u.s. attorney in new york's southern district, said he filed papers in federal court friday arguing that the case ought to be dropped because the american civil liberties union does not have ``standing,'' a legal term which means the right to bring the lawsuit
but c. edwin baker, a staff attorney the aclu in new york, said the civil liberties group maintains that it can pursue the lawsuit because the aclu represents american taxpayers whose money is used for the schools. the aclu has until march 24 to respond
the lawsuit stemmed from reports last december that sen. daniel k. inouye, d-hawaii, had persuaded his colleagues to allocate $8 million to build schools in france for north african jews
the program provoked a firestorm of criticism, prompting inouye to ask congress to rescind the money. lawmakers agreed to inouye's wish
after president reagan signed the bill killing the $8 million program last month, the aclu amended its complaint to cover jewish and catholic schools that receive money under the american schools and hospitals abroad program, which is administered by the agency for international development
baker said lawyers learned about the program in the course of their research into the inouye-supported item
the lawsuit, filed in u.s. district court in new york, claims that providing money to ``pervasively sectarian schools'' or for construction of sectarian schools is a violation of the constitution's first amendment calling for separation of church and state. the aclu asks the court to block further spending on the schools
under the schools and hospitals program _ a favorite in congress _ grants are awarded to a non-profit american organization that sponsors an institution overseas. the program is designed to promote american educational methods abroad and train foreigners in medicine and promote american educational values
aid, which has regulations governing the program, awards the grants on a competitive basis. congress is notified before the money is spent
the budget figures indicate how fond congress is of the program. in fiscal year 1988, aid asked for $10 million; congress increased the budget to $40 million. the previous fiscal year the program received $35 million
the aclu is not challenging grants given to hospitals or non-sectarian schools abroad, baker said. but the group wants to end support for schools that have as a stated goal the teaching of principles and doctrines of roman catholicism and orthodox judaism
aid documents for the four years ending in 1986 show that institutions in lebanon were given the most money, a total of $24.8 million. the lion's share _ $24 million _ went to the american university of beirut
institutions in israel snagged the second largest amount of money, a total of $20.2 million. project hope, which operates schools worldwide, received $14.3 million
all of the religious schools named in the lawsuit are in israel
among the institutions which teach judaism and have received money since fiscal 1983 are: the american college of belz, jerusalem, $500,000; beth rivka comprehensive school, kfar chabad, $750,000; beth yaacov avat, ashdod, $100,000; boys town, jerusalem, $1.2 million; emunah women of america community college, jerusalem, $650,000; gan yavne youth village, gan yavne, $150,000; machaniam high school, kiryat gat, $400,000; ohr somayach school, jerusalem, $2 million' sha'alvim teachers' college, d.n. agalon, $400,000
the lawsuit does not name any catholic schools for which it wants to eliminate money. twentieth century fox studios.; picks up 8th graf pvs: ``edward adler ...; subs 12th graf pvs, ``the median ..., to conform rhoden reference</note>
script writers struck movie and television producers today and the union predicted viewers of talk shows, game shows and daytime soaps would quickly notice a difference in programming
hundreds of writers grabbed ``the writers guild strikes'' placards depicting a quill and lightning bolt as mid-morning picket lines snaked in front of twentieth century fox studios
the writers guild of america rejected a final offer presented sunday by the alliance of motion picture and television producers and called a walkout for 9,000 of its 9,600 members. the 600 wga news writers are exempt from this action
the strike began here and in new york city at 9 a.m. pst today. the contract expired at midnight feb. 29
marty waldman, a wga spokesman in new york, said there would be no picketing in the east today
the longer the strike goes on, the more reruns the public will see,'' said brian walton, wga west executive director and chief negotiator. ``it's a very tight ratings race and unfortunately for the networks it will impact them.''
picket captain stanley ralph ross said selection of fox's west los angeles studio ``was fairly arbitrary,'' adding its size and location had a lot to do with it
we usually pick a major studio, and there's parking around here,'' ross said
grandview u.s.a.'' writer ken hixon, who marched with his 2-year old son, sam, said writers were much more unified for this strike than in their last walkout in 1985
there was nearly a civil war last time between screen writers and television writers. but this time there's real solidarity,'' hixon said
viewers will begin seeing the effects on those programs relying on scripts on a daily basis. talk shows, game shows and the soaps will see a difference right away,'' said guild spokeswoman cheryl rhoden
the strike slows down the production process and if prolonged, ``it finally comes to a halt,'' she said. a three-month strike delayed the fall television season three years ago
walton said the network that would be hardest hit would be first-place nbc, whose ``the tonight show starring johnny carson,'' ``saturday night live'' and ``late night with david letterman,'' would be affected immediately
edward adler, president of wga east, said nine soap operas on the east coast and five in california also would be affected immediately, as would prime time miniseries, television movies and features in development or in production
but herb steinberg, a spokesman for the alliance, which represents 200 producers and studios, said a strike was anticipated and scripts have been stockpiled
shows like carson's show will go into reruns. but we will continue business,'' he said
producers had sought to scale back residual payments for some one-hour shows syndicated in the united states and said they couldn't pay writers more for reruns in foreign markets
the median annual income for writers is $40,000 a year, but about half of the guild's members are unemployed at any given time, said rhoden. the writers sought the first change in 17 years in how they are compensated when programs are aired in foreign markets. they now receive a single lump sum that varies depending on what is negotiated between the writer and producer
the writers also demanded more artistic control on the final product
we had all kinds of creative guarantees in there short of giving them total control,'' steinberg said. ``the director is the captain of that creative team. we couldn't bargain away rights that belonged to other guilds and unions.''
the producers had offered a $50 million package over a three-year period, including improvements in pension and health plans, steinberg said
in union ballots last week in los angeles and new york, 96 percent approved a walkout if no agreement was reached
the last script writers strike was in 1985 and lasted two weeks. since the wga won its first contract in 1947, script writers conducted strikes five times, more than any other entertainment industry union
separately, the screen actors guild and american federation of television and radio artists bargained through the weekend with makers of tv and radio commercials over daily pay rates and rerun payments for 100,000 actors
members of those unions approved a strike by a 93 percent margin in recent votes, said sag spokesman mark locher
president reagan's spokesman said today the administration welcomes ``the support and advice'' of 30 senators who argued in a letter to secretary of state george shultz that israel should be willing to give up control of occupied land in return for middle east peace
we are in the midst of an ongoing processs. the views of these senators are helpful to us and probably instructive to other parties in the region,'' marlin fitzwater told reporters
the 23 democrats and seven republicans, including several strong supporters of the jewish state, also expressed support for shultz's plan to bring israel, jordan, syria and palestinian arabs to a peace conference by may 1 in an effort to stop violence in israeli-occupied territory that has claimed some 80 arab lives in three months
the senators noted that israel has in the past supported the idea of ``land for peace'' by returning the sinai peninsula to egypt. but they cited a statement by israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir that ``this expression of territory for peace is not accepted by me.''
we hope that the prime minister's statement did not indicate that israel is abandoning a policy that offers the best hope for long-term peace,'' the letter said
the administration welcomes the support and advice from this group. they are senators of considerable stature and interest and involvment in middle east affairs,'' the spokesman said
at the state department, spokesman charles e. redman said shultz would respond to the letter. he declined to address the matter further, except to say that the administration prefers ``to maintain a certain discreet distance'' in the mideast peace process
but redman, in a comment that seemed to be directed at shamir, said the state department hopes for an ``early response'' from mideast governments to the u.s. plan to set up negotiations on palestinian self-rule by may 1
we believe all the parties understand and appreciate the reason that we've asked for these kind of responses,'' redman told reporters
shamir on sunday blocked a decision by the israeli cabinet. he said he would permit a vote on the american initiative after he returns from talks here next week with reagan and shultz
israeli foreign minister shimon peres had demanded a cabinet decision before shamir went to washington
at the white house, fitzwater said shultz was to brief reagan later today on his middle east trips and he noted that shamir is to visit with the president on march 16
at the moment, we proceed on a pace that's fairly well structured and has been laid out by secretary shultz and his shuttle diplomacy of the last several days,'' fitzwater said
the spokesman said the administration was involved in a process ``that involves a blend of some new ideas and new beliefs,'' but he refused to comment further, saying, ``in the middle east, it's more important not to say anything that prohibits the process or acts as a stoppage than to say anything that might stimulate activity.''
shultz, upon returning saturday from the middle east, expressed no criticism of shamir's position, saying the prime minister and israeli foreign minister shimon peres agreed that israel's annexation of territory could be a topic for negotiations. peres and his labor party have openly endorsed shultz's proposals, while shamir and his likud party have not
strong supporters of israel signing the letter included senators alan cranston, d-calif.; edward m. kennedy, d-mass.; daniel patrick moynihan, d-n.y.; howard m. metzenbaum, d-ohio; frank r. lautenberg, d-n.j.; carl levin, d-mich., and rudy boschwitz, r-minn
others whose names were on the letter included senators daniel inouye, d-hawaii; lowell p. weicker jr., r-conn.; george j. mitchell, d-maine; brock adams, d-wash.; thomas a. daschle, d-s.d.; j. bennett johnston, d-la.; donald w. riegle jr., d-mich.; tom harkin, d-iowa; warren b. rudman, r-n.h.; bob kasten, r-wis.; j. james exon, d-neb.; patrick j. leahy, d-vt.; john kerry, d-mass.; mitch mcconnell, r-ky; william s. cohen, r-maine; alan k. simpson, r-wyo.; christopher j. dodd, d-conn.; dennis deconcini, d-ariz.; kent conrad, d-n.d.; john glenn, d-ohio; timothy e. wirth, d-colo.; wendell h. ford, d-ky., and bob graham, d-fla. expressing concern about violence in tibet.</note>
the reagan administration expressed deep concern today about violence in tibet as chinese foreign minister wu xueqian opened talks with secretary of state george p. shultz
we remain deeply concerned about the state of human rights in tibet and the recurring incidents of violence,'' said charles e. redman, the state department spokesman. ``we urge all concerned to exercise restraint in order to avoid further bloodshed.''
at the same time, redman said tibet is considered an integral part of china. ``nothing has changed on that,'' he said
redman said he expected shultz would take up the situation with wu during their talks
the state department and congress have accused china of harsh measures in putting down unrest in tibet
reports that reached beijing on sunday said thousands of rioting tibetans had set bonfires in lhasa's streets and several people were killed during more than 12 hours of clashes with police. the protesters were demanding tibet's independence from china
police fired bullets and tear gas at protesters saturday and three to nine people were killed, according to the unconfirmed reports from western sources in lhasa
the administration, meanwhile, is dangling high-technology sales as an inducement for china to give firm assurances it will halt delivery of silkworm missiles to iran
the tradeoff _ and at least chinese neutrality in a u.s. drive to impose an international arms embargo against iran _ looms as the potential highlight of the talks wu opened today
it is his first visit in four years, and the agenda is substantial. for instance, shultz will solicit china's support for his proposal for arab-israeli peace talks
shultz is trying to structure a peace conference in which the united states, the soviet union, china, britain and france would serve as sponsors, but without the power to impose terms of a settlement
that calls for some delicate diplomacy. shultz is walking a tightrope between jordan and israel on the subject
king hussein refuses to negotiate unless he has big power support. but israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir refuses to allow china or the soviets, who usually support arab positions, to take an active role
wu arrived sunday, had dinner with shultz and sees him and defense secretary frank c. carlucci separately today. on tuesday, the chinese foreign minister calls on president reagan at the white house and meets with shultz again
the shipping war in the persian gulf is uppermost in u.s. minds
china may be iran's largest arms supplier. sales last year were worth an estimated $1 billion
the most dangerous of the weapons are silkworm missiles _ short-range rockets that even in unskilled hands can wreak havoc on merchant ships. iran has used them effectively
despite u.s. appeals, china persisted in delivering installments of the silkworms to iran last year _ and denied what carlucci and other u.s. officials said it was doing
frustrated, the united states retaliated in october by suspending a decade-old process of liberalizing the types of high technology american companies could sell to china
since then, china has said it has stopped selling silkworms to iran. a u.s. official, speaking friday on condition of anonymity, said ``our information is that they've been living up to that.''
still, before resuming liberalization of the high-technology trade, ``we want to be sure we're in sync with the chinese on what we're talking about,'' the official said. ``we want to be sure that this responsiveness will continue.''
on an arms embargo, meanwhile, shultz would like a commitment from wu that china would not veto a resolution in the u.n. security council to impose a worldwide arms embargo against iran
the sanctions would enforce a cease-fire resolution adopted last july that iraq accepted but iran scorned
state department experts believe china would at least remain neutral if the soviet union agreed not to veto the resolution. the united states has been after moscow since july for support, but is not sure it has it yet
commerce secretary william verity will lead a u.s. delegation to the soviet union in april for a conference on trade and economic cooperation, the commerce department said monday
the meeting, of the joint u.s.-u.s.s.r commercial commission, is being held as a follow-up to the december summit meeting between president reagan and soviet leader mikhail gorbachev
the two leaders, in a joint statement at the end of the summit in washington, instructed the commission to develop proposals to expand the two nations' trade and economic ties
it will be the 10th meeting of the commission, which last met december 1986 in washington
while in moscow, during the week of april 11, verity will meet with gorbachev and address the u.s.-u.s.s.r. trade and economic council, an organization of u.s. companies and soviet firms
verity will be accompanied by representatives of the agriculture, treasury and state departments, the national security council and the office of the u.s. trade representative
a 77-year-old farmer on monday pleaded innocent by reason of mental deficiency to charges he fatally shot his ailing wife
oscar carlson entered pleas of innocent and innocent by reason of mental deficiency to charges of first- and second-degree murder in douglas county district court
carlson is charged with the shooting death last week of his wife of 47 years. he reportedly told authorities he shot the 71-year-old woman to end her suffering from alzheimer's disease
michael dolan, an attorney for carlson, said he asked the court to reduce carlson's $100,000 bail, and allow the man to post his home and five acres as assurance against flight. douglas county judge donald gray took the matter under advisement
meanwhile, carlson remained at the douglas county jail, dolan said
the reagan administration is considering economic and trade sanctions against panama, including withholding monthly payments for the panama canal, but has not made any decisions yet, a white house spokesman said today
spokesman marlin fitzwater said meetings will be held later this week to discuss options on how the united states can apply pressure to force the ouster of panama's military strongman, manuel antonio noriega
on march 15, the united states is due to pay $6.5 million to the panama canal commission, a monthly payment toward the $75 million to $80 million the united states makes each year under the panama canal treaty
one of the options under consideration, fitzwater said, is to put the money into an escrow account instead of paying it to panama
earlier in the day, sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., said the united states was right to put economic pressure on noriega's government, which d'amato predicted would fall within 10 days
we are grinding him down to a halt, and we should,'' d'amato said on nbc-tv's ``today'' show
i think we could have moved much faster,'' added d'amato, who is sponsoring a senate resolution calling for a total trade embargo against panama
we begin to see the incredible effects that we do have economically,'' the new york republican said
panama's 12 local banks have been closed since tuesday; branches of international institutions closed their doors friday
the administration last week backed legal efforts to freeze panamanian government deposits in u.s. banks, and authorities in panama were prevented from drawing on those accounts to keep the nation supplied with u.s. dollars, the official currency of panama
calling the panamanian strongman a terrorist and ``petty tyrant,'' d'amato asked:
if we can't take noriega on with the power that we have in the area economically, militarily, ... how are we going to deal with the drug lords of mexico and colombia and bolivia and when are we really going to take on that war?''
this is an opportunity and time for us to strike a blow for democracy and to go after one of the drug lords in this hemisphere,'' he said
questioned as to when he thinks noriega will be forced from power, d'amato replied, ``i would say within 10 days.''
appearing with d'amato, juan b. sosa, the ambassador of panama's deposed president, eric arturo delvalle, agreed with that prediction
israeli soldiers shot and wounded at least 12 palestinians on monday, and the army said arab rioters hurled a grenade for the first time since violence began in the occupied territories three months ago
defense minister yitzhak rabin defended the behavior of soldiers in the occupied west bank and gaza strip. he told parliament it was the first time in israel's 40-year history ``in which face-to-face, close, they see the ... hate of the rioters.''
strikes and job boycotts extended to the administration of the territories. palestinian employees of the gaza tax department were summoned to military headquarters monday after 38 of the 40 workers said they were resigning
inside israel, palestinian guerrillas captured a commuter bus near beersheba and soldiers stormed the vehicle. three israelis and three guerrillas were killed
according to the army spokesman's office, soldiers shot and wounded seven palestinians at idna after attackers threw a grenade at troopers who raided the west bank village to arrest ``rioters and inciters of rioting.'' the arab-run palestine press service put the number of wounded at eight
it was the first use of a grenade since arab riots began dec. 8
the first army report of arab gunfire in a demonstration occurred sunday in the askar refugee camp near nablus. no soldiers were injured
israeli surveillance and restrictions make it difficult for arabs to get firearms, and the palestine liberation organization has ordered protesters to avoid using guns
international sympathy has been created by images of well-armed soldiers shooting and beating youths armed only with rocks and homemade gasoline bombs in what arabs call ``the uprising.'' according to u.n. figures, 83 palestinians have been killed
at al-ittihad hospital in nablus, dr. hamdallah kazlak said two palestinians were treated for gunshot wounds suffered in clashes with troops at the nearby balata refugee camp
he said 20-25 others from balata and the askar camp were treated for injuries caused by clubs, rubber bullets or tear gas, including a 4-year-old girl hit in the head by a rubber bullet
a 33-year-old arab from askar, salah eddin abdul-raouf, was dead on arrival at the hospital and kazlak said his relatives attributed the death to tear gas. he said the cause of death was unclear, however, and noted the man suffered from heart disease
army officials said they were investigating reports of the protests
hospital officials in the gaza strip said soldiers shot and wounded three arabs during protests on the anniversary of israel's withdrawal from the strip soon after invading it in 1956. israel captured gaza from egypt, and the west bank from jordan, in the 1967 middle east war
army spokesmen said soldiers opened fire when rubber bullets and tear gas did not disperse ``a violent demonstration in the shati camp,'' wounding three palestinians
the hospital officials, speaking anonymously, said more than 100 people were treated for beatings and injuries caused by tear gas and rubber bullets, most suffered at shati
military authorities summoned employees of the gaza tax department to discuss a sunday letter signed by 38 of the 40 workers saying they were resigning in response to a call by underground palestinian leaders
a senior official said the israelis explained the financial difficulties workers would face if they quit and ``the general situation in terms of public services that will be damaged.'' he said the workers had not yet resigned officially
israeli officials claim arab government workers in the territories have been threatened by palestinian nationalists and islamic militants
the united states has been embarassed in space research since the challenger disaster, and risks forfeiting its edge in high technology and other fields unless it expands space-based scientific missions, a nasa official and researchers told a congressional hearing monday
further delays in projects already backed up three years plus a lack of funding for new space experiments will allow the soviet union, japan and european nations to cement the lead they have taken over the united states since the challenger explosion, said lennard a. fisk, associate administrator of the national aeronautics and space administration
a lead that we had was allowed to erode and now we have to ask ourselves where we are going,'' said fisk, who outlined the science-related portion of nasa's proposed fiscal 1989 budget to the senate subcommittee on science, technology and space
fisk said 20 major science-related payloads are scheduled to be carried into space in the next four years, half of them aboard space shuttles and half on expendable rockets
the projects include probes to venus and jupiter and the launching of an x-ray telescope, space telescope and gamma ray observatory designed to work in tandem to study a number of phenomena, including a supernova that occurred last year
the new x-ray telescope, the advanced x-ray astrophysics facility, should also help researchers determine what the universe looked like up to 20 billion years ago and produce dramatic improvements in pharmaceuticals and computer chips, said dr. harvey tananbaum of the harvard-smithsonian center for astrophysics
resumption of the shuttle program and approval of nasa's science-related budget is vital to getting the 20 projects launched by 1993 and to prove to commercial businesses which pay to have satellites and experiments carried into space that the unites states will re-establish itself as a dominant force in space, fisk said
he also urged researchers to develop new space-based experiments and technology so that nasa can begin planning missions past 1993, when it is scheduled to complete current projects
we have a hiatus in space science launches today because of the challenger tragedy,'' fisk said. ``let us not create another hiatus in the mid-1990s by failing to start major flight projects now.''
sen. john kerry, d-mass., a subcommittee member who presided over the hearing, said a revitalized space program also was vital to massachusetts businesses and universities, which received 846 contracts totaling $413 million in 1987 and have to date in 1988 been awarded 710 contracts totaling $388 million
fisk and the academicians told the subcommittee that nasa should not be pressured to curtail manned missions with civilian researchers because of the january 1986 challenger explosion that killed seven astronauts, including new hampshire teacher christa mcauliffe
david l. akin, associate director of the massachusetts institute of technology space systems laboratory, said that while computers and robots can greatly contribute to space research, their advancement should not be used to support calls for an end to manned space flights
exploration is one of the last jobs which should be turned over to robots, as the curiosity for thirst and knowledge underlying the urge to explore is one of the finest attributes of being human,'' akin said. ``let us instead spend our efforts getting humans out of mine shafts and off high steel construction sites. robots should totally replace man in the worst of jobs, not the best.''
the dalai lama, god-king of tibetans, held a prayer service monday in northern india to mourn weekend violence in lhasa, capital of tibet
in new delhi, hundreds of tibetan refugees chanted ``we shall overcome'' in a demonstration solidarity with people in tibet. police prevented the crowd from marching on the chinese embassy
a statement from the dalai lama's new delhi office said the trouble in lhasa ``is yet another indication of the depth of tibetan people's resentment and opposition to chinese rule.''
hundreds of tibetans attended the service in dharmsala, the dalai lama's exile headquarters in northern himachal pradesh state, the statement said. it declared that the tibetan issue ``cannot be solved by use of force'' and called on china ``to seriously negotiate for a solution.''
in a statement from dharmsala, the dalai lama urged the chinese to ``work toward a settlement which will benefit both the tibetan and the chinese peoples.'' he asked that tibetans ``in the meantime ... refrain from violence in spite of repressive measures that the chinese may take.''
official reports in china said one policeman was killed and 28 were injured in the lhasa clash saturday. unconfirmed reports from western sources put the toll at three to nine dead, including a buddhist monk and two chinese policemen
the dalai lama fled to india with about 100,000 of his followers in 1959, after an abortive tibetan uprising. china, which claims tibet has been an integral part of it for centuries, moved troops into the remote mountain region in 1950
saturday's violence was the first in lhasa since oct. 1, when 2,000 tibetans led by buddhist monks set fire to a police station facing the jokhang temple. police opened fire and at least 14 people were reported killed
many tibetans resent the government in beijing because of oppression of tibetan religion and customs and destruction of temples during the 1966-76 radical cultural revolution
although china has tried to redress past wrongs, friction remains between tibetans and chinese who continue to hold many senior posts in lhasa
the tibetan government has refused nearly all requests by foreign journalists to visit lhasa and has restricted tourism since the disturbances last october
a prisoner handcuffed to a hospital bed broke the bed rail monday and overpowered his police guard, then took the officer's gun and held two people hostage before giving up about six hours later
the prisoner freed the hostages, both hospital engineers, but continued to hold police off while threatening to shoot himself or fire into potentially explosive tanks of acetylene and oxygen in a subbasement of north general hospital in harlem
he was rational but very upset,'' said detective frank gallagher, the chief negotiator. ``he had fits of depression and at one point put the gun to his head and at another point to his mouth.''
the prisoner, identified as yusuf harris, 27, freed himself around 4:25 a.m. in his seventh-floor room at the hospital, where he had been taken for treatment of exposure after being arrested on kidnap charges early saturday, officials said
authorities were investigating how he broke his bed rail without alerting the guard, officer timothy austin, in a hallway outside, said chief of patrol john p. mccabe said
after getting austin's gun, the barefoot harris, wearing only a hospital gown and dragging a wedge-shaped section of aluminum-pipe bed rail from his wrist, made his way to the second floor, where he got the drop on a security guard, according to patients who saw the incident
harris allegedly took the guard's wallet, with $7, then forced him to break open a window leading onto a setback
around this time harris fired austin's .38-caliber service revolver, chief robert johnston said, but it was not known whether the discharge was accidental or harris had tried to hit someone. no one was shot
harris made his way to the subbasement, where he burned his buttocks while clambering over a boiler, said johnston
he took his hostages, ray cadmus, 50, of nesconset, and kemail bajramoski, 35, of manhattan, at the engineers' office, said police. one of the captives freed harris from the bed rail by chiseling the handcuff chain
cadmus was freed at 7:20 a.m. after police sent in some coffee and doughnuts, said johnston. bajramoski was let go about an hour later when gallagher agreed to stay with harris in place of the hostage
he said he wanted to blow himself up but he didn't want to go alone,'' said gallagher
later, the officer saw the prisoner turn the gun on himself
he said to me, `you want to see me do it? i'll do it right now,''' gallagher related
gallagher quoted harris as saying he had tried to escape because he feared going back into the criminal justice system
the prisoner was calmed by talking on the telephone to his father and sister and to an assistant district attorney, steven nuzzi, who were brought to the hospital
finally, he threw the gun out ``and walked out and took my hand,'' said gallagher
still barefoot, but with a red plaid shirt and a sheet over his gown, harris was brought out at 10:45 a.m
mccabe said he would be charged with robbery, reckless endangerment and weapon possession
austin, 28, who was treated for cuts and bruises, had arrested harris originally early saturday after harris allegedly used a starter's pistol to force a cabbie to drive him from the bronx to manhattan
harris fled the cab and jumped into the east river when the driver got the attention of police in eastern harlem, authorities said. harbor police fished him out and austin arrested him on charges of kidnap, menacing and gun and marijuana possession, police said
he had been taken to the hospital for treatment and observation. proceedings</head>
a palestinian convicted in a terrorist attack on an israeli jetliner lost out monday in his bid to block the canadian government's attempt to deport him
federal court justice james jerome dismissed an application from mahmoud mohammad issa's lawyers, who argued that the scheduled march 15 deportation hearing would violate canada's charter of rights and freedoms
the attorneys said that mohammad, 45, will not get a fair hearing because immigration minister benoit bouchard has already told parliament that ``the government will not rest before he (mohammad) is out of the country.''
the judge said bouchard's comments could have been more temperate. but he said the process ``also involves a sense of fairness to canada'' and is necessary to assess ``who should come in and who should not.''
lorne waldman, one of mohammad's lawyers, said he was filing an immediate appeal of the decision and a request for a stay in deportation proceedings until the appeal is heard
in 1970, a greek court convicted mohammad of manslaughter for his part in a 1968 attack on an el al airliner at athens airport that left one israeli passenger dead. he served three months of his 17-year sentence and was released in a hostage exchange
he came to canada with his wife and three children a year ago and established a comfortable suburban life in brantford, ontario
when reporters discovered his presence in the country in january, mohammad acknowledged having lied about his criminal record to gain entry to canada. but he said he renounced terrorism and avowed to live here peacefully
some left-wing groups and newspaper columnists have been sympathetic to his case
however, his claim to have renounced palestinian terrorism long ago has been challenged by the israeli airline pilots association, which claims mohammad was involved in a 1986 plot to attack a jewish settlement in morocco
in addition, the montreal newspaper, le devoir, has reported the existence of an autobiographical book about mohammad which depicts him as an active terrorist in 1975
mohammad has denied both allegations
mohammad tried to leave canada quietly last month through a secret royal canadian mounted police operation. the plan called for him to fly to london's heathrow airport and change planes for algiers, possibly continuing on to morocco
authorities have not clarified exactly what went wrong. mohammad flew to london but was put on a plane back to toronto
an heiress who was awarded $6 million from a church she said exploited her won the bible speaks' 65-acre headquarters monday with a $3.23 million bid at an auction in u.s. bankruptcy court
it was the second time that elizabeth dovydenas, 35, of lenox, had outbid others for the church's now-abandoned property, which includes 23 buildings. judge james f. queenan jr. had rejected her november bid of $1.8 million as too low
i'd be happy either way,'' said mrs. dovydenas' husband, jonas, after learning the couple's bid was the highest of the four sealed bids at the court hearing
the money mrs. dovydenas bid for the estate will go toward repaying the $6.6 million claim she won in federal bankruptcy court last april against the bible speaks
she had sued the church for donations she made as a parishioner from 1982 to 1986, contending that she was lied to and that her unquestioning trust was exploited by church founder and leader rev. carl h. stevens jr
queenan agreed in his ruling, calling the case ``an astonishing saga of clerical deceit, avarice and subjugation on the part of the church's founder.''
the ruling was upheld in january in u.s. district court in springfield, but the church's lawyers have announced they intend to file an appeal
the dispute landed in federal bankrupcy court after the church obtained chapter 11 protection, arguing that mrs. dovydenas' case could forced it into insolvency
the claim by mrs. dovydenas, an heir to the dayton hudson department store fortune, is by far the largest of the 250 creditors who are owed a total of $7 million by the church
her lawyer, gordon walker, said he doubted she will ever receive all the money she won, although another piece of church property in maine recently sold for $1.1 million and a florida condominium and a mission ship are also up for sale by a court-appointed trustee
i hope we even get $4 million,'' the attorney said. ``the question is, where did all that money go? we're going to look into that question.''
the bible speaks had claimed 1,200 members worldwide until the ministry disbanded last summer, saying it would never operate under the control of a court-appointed trustee. the trustee, david ferrari, had been apppointed by the bankrutpcy court to manage the estate until mrs. dovydenas' claim could be paid
most of the church's 20 pastors followed stevens to baltimore, although a few remained behind to set up another church in lenox
the church's lenox estate had been valued at $6 million, but investors said town zoning restrictions made it difficult to develop the land
dovydenas said monday he and his wife planned to sell some of the church property to developers and turn some of it into a school and a community center for the wealthy town, the summer home of the boston symphony orchestra
