a federal judge on monday dismissed gop presidential candidate pat robertson's $35 million libel suit against a former congressman, who said the court's action unmasked robertson ``as the fraud he is.''
robertson, complaining he could not campaign and pursue the suit at the same time, had asked for the dismissal. he called monday's action ``a real victory.''
u.s. district judge joyce hens green formally ended the suit against former rep. paul n. mccloskey jr., r-calif., who had questioned robertson's korean war record, after robertson agreed to pay court costs
green signed a brief order dismissing the case ``with prejudice,'' which means that mccloskey is legally the victor in the dispute
this is a confirmation of my integrity,'' mccloskey said in a telephone interview from his home in san francisco. ``i don't like at the age of 60 to be called a pathological liar all over the united states. he is admitting that he is the one who is the liar.''
robertson accepted the court-costs condition in a one-sentence letter from his attorney, douglas v. rigler, that was delivered to the judge's chambers by messenger
mccloskey said, ``the court's service was to unmask this man as the fraud he is.''
but robertson, in a campaign appearance in wichita falls, texas, said the judge ``gave me what i consider a real victory.''
she denied him any court costs _ any damages, i should say. he asked for $400,000. and i have the privilege of suing him once the primary is over,'' he said
however, in an opinion issued last week, green quoted _ and underlined _ a passage from a 1985 federal appeals court opinion that stated: ``dismissal of an action with prejudice is a complete adjudication of the issues presented by the pleadings and is a bar to further action between the parties.''
mccloskey's attorney george lehner said he understood that this citation means his client cannot be sued again over any statements he makes about robertson's war record
it's an absolute dead letter,'' lehner said. ``i assume he can bring suit if pete says something else, but not about this whole korean business.''
under terms of the dismissal, robertson must pay court fees, printing costs and court reporters' fees, but not mccloskey's attorney's fees, estimated at $400,000
the judge gave mccloskey's lawyers 20 days to file an itemized list of court costs to be assessed against robertson. those costs could range between $5,000 and $20,000, depending on conflicting estimates given by lawyers for both sides
if robertson had rejected green's dismissal, he would have had to go to court on tuesday to begin the trial, which was expected to last about three weeks
the judge gave me an impossible dilemma,'' robertson said on sunday, ``the choice of either defending my honor on tuesday or being president and running for president.''
the suit stems from mccloskey's allegation that robertson used the political influence of his late father, sen. a. willis robertson, d-va., to avoid combat in the korean war
the former television evangelist filed the lawsuit in 1986. several former marines later came forward to support mccloskey's allegation
mccloskey said monday he is setting up a legal defense fund hoping to raise money to pay for the attorneys' fees. founder, of aim.</note>
dennis banks, a former leader of the american indian movement, was sentenced today to five years' probation for illegally possessing dynamite
banks, 50, of south dakota's pine ridge indian reservation, pleaded guilty to the charge in exchange for dismissal of all other charges remaining against him and three other defendants in the 12-year-old case
trial had been scheduled to begin here next month, following years of legal sparring that included numerous appeals to the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals and the u.s. supreme court
banks, his wife kamook, russ james redner and kenneth moses loud hawk, all american indians, were charged with possessing eight guns with obliterated serial numbers and 350 pounds of unregistered dynamite
the weapons and explosives allegedly were found when oregon state police stopped a motor home and a station wagon near ontario, just west of the oregon-idaho border, on nov. 14, 1975
kamook banks, redner and loud hawk were arrested at the scene. authorities said banks and another man, leonard peltier, escaped on foot. prosecutors said banks' fingerprints were found in the motor home, which was owned by actor marlon brando
peltier later was convicted in the june 1975 gunshot slayings of two fbi agents on the pine ridge reservation. he is serving two life sentences in a federal prison at leavenworth, kan
a gun belonging to one of the slain fbi agents was found in the vehicles that were stopped in oregon, authorities said. they said the vehicles were en route from the puget sound area of washington to the pine ridge reservation
banks was a leader of the american indian movement, formed in the 1960s to support indian rights. in 1973, he and other aim members staged a 10-week siege at wounded knee, s.d., to protest treatment of indians in the united states
the new president of gallaudet university said monday she empathizes with students and faculty at the all-deaf university who are protesting her appointment because she hears
i do feel very deeply a sense of compassion and empathy,'' elizabeth zinser said monday in a telephone interview. ``i know it's hurting them because they very much wanted their seventh president to be deaf
but i think that what the students are expressing in general is their deep concern and care for the university. i hope that they and i ... as soon things quiet down can begin to focus on the work of gallaudet university.''
hundreds of students shut down gallaudet, the nation's only university for the deaf, out of anger monday over the selection of a president who is not hearing-impaired
zinser said she would probably begin her new job this summer. meanwhile, she will begin an intensive program to learn sign language and hopes to volunteer with agencies that work with the deaf, she said
zinser, vice chancellor of academic affairs at the university of north carolina at greensboro since 1983, was named gallaudet president sunday by the school's board of trustees
zinser said she was concerned about the student protests but not about what impact it might have on her presidency
i think it would be inhuman on my part not to be concerned,'' she said. ``but my concern is for the pain that i know some individuals are feeling. i do, however, believe that the board has made its decision.''
the university belongs to a large and varied constitutency of which the president is a symbol,'' she said. ``i am not, perhaps to some, the best symbol
i know that i cannot fully understand the experience of deafness without being deaf. ... but i will become as knowledgable and as understanding and as empathetic as anyone can who's a hearing person.''
zinser holds a doctorate in educational psychology from the university of california at berkeley. before coming to north carolina in 1983, she was a professor, dean of the school of nursing and senior academic officer at the university of north dakota at grand forks. ^with am-iran-iraq, bjt</head>
the soviet ambassador to the united nations on monday urged iran and iraq to stop bombarding each other's capitals and said the escalating ``war of the cities'' was a major development in the war
we think that the war between cities adds some new dimension to the protracted military conflict between the two neighboring countries,'' soviet ambassador aleksander belonogov said
belonogov made his statements in an unusual news conference outside the u.n. security council, which later met behind closed doors on the iran-iraq conflict
last july, the security council demanded an immediate cease-fire in the 7{-year-old war. the united states is now pushing for an arms embargo against iran for rebuffing the resolution, but the soviets have balked at an embargo
belonogov said he met monday with secretary-general javier perez de cuellar and with the president of the security council this month, yugoslav ambassador dragoslav pejic, and urged them ``in the most energetic terms'' to try to persuade iran and iraq to stop the missile attacks
it is difficult to say what political and psychological consequences the war of the cities may result in,'' belonogov said
the position of my country is clear. we are for the soonest possible political resolution of the conflict between iran and iraq and for the speediest possible implementation of the'' cease-fire resolution
belonogov was also asked whether his country believes iran now accepts the cease-fire resolution, as it seemed to claim in an ambiguous unsigned note to the council last week
we don't think that it would be right just to disregard the new developments in the situation,'' he said, refusing to elaborate
the unsigned note from iran claimed that a feb. 28 letter from its foreign minister constituted acceptance of the resolution. the letter, however, did not say that iran endorsed the resolution
british ambassador sir crispin tickell on monday called the letter ``an undated, unsigned scrap of paper.''
where does that leave us?'' he said. ``it does not constitute a clear acceptance.''
state department spokesman charles redman said in washington monday that the united states doesn't accept the unsigned note either and will keep pushing for an arms embargo on iran
each of the five permanent members of the security council _ the soviet union, china, france, britain and the united states _ has the power to veto an embargo resolution
the soviets are close allies of iraq but have also been trying to improve relations with neighboring iran. both iran and iraq are believed to be using soviet-made missiles in the ``war of the cities.''
belonogov denied that what he called ``the defensive weapons now used against tehran and other cities'' are soviet-made
hundreds of experts from around the globe gather in antebellum charleston this week to seek ways to make the world's cities better places to live
the 4th international conference on making cities liveable, which opens wednesday, is being held in the united states for the first time
the quality of life in our cities has become increasingly a national concern,'' mayor joseph p. riley jr. said monday
riley said charleston boasts many ``important national, if not international, examples of the liveability of cities,'' from its preservation efforts to its innovative programs of low-income housing to the acclaimed spoleto arts festival
but we have so much to learn,'' he said
it's a conference for people who are concerned about the quality of life in the city'' but isn't a professional conference, said suzanne lennard, one of the organizers and a founder of the center for urban well-being
it brings together many different kinds of people. it brings together city planners and architects, city council presidents and mayors and citizens who are simply concerned about making their cities more liveable,'' she said
more than 300 people are expected to attend and more than 100 people are scheduled to speak. among the topics of discussion will be the design of public spaces, festivals, the role of markets in the city and a number of case studies
the center for urban well-being, based in southhampton, n.y., is a partnership that conducts research, publishes and works with cities on urban issues
the first three international conferences were held in venice. ``we wanted to bring it to america to make it more accessible for americans,'' mrs. lennard said
one of the topics of discussion will be public art _ sculptures and other art in public places such as parks
sculptor bonifatius stirnberg, who has crafted numerous, whimsical, human-sized sculptures for parks and fountains throughout europe, will talk about his craft
usually crafted of bronze, his works are often designed for a particular town and tell something about its history or folklore. they include a sculpture of carnival characters on a barge that's part of a fountain and a long bronze sea serpent whose tail serves as a park bench
stirnberg, of aachen, west germany, said through an interpreter, ``the goal of my work is to make sculpture that is loved by the people _ that people can move and touch.''
in contrast, riley said, ``in america we see so much public art that is not of a human scale.''
riley said ``the power of a meeting like this is in the learning, teaching and sharing. it has the potential of improving the quality of life in cities all over america and beyond.''
a 15-year-old girl who was acting out a scene from the movie ``stand by me'' was struck and killed when she misjudged the speed of an oncoming train and stepped into its path, authorities said monday
the accident sunday in suburban fairport occurred behind the american national can co., said fairport police chief joseph d. picciotti
kimberly anne strassner and three friends were singing the movie's title song and recreating the scenes in which four boys artfully dodge trains, picciotti said
they actually heard the engineer (whistle) and felt the rumble of the track,'' said picciotti, who interviewed one of the friends monday. ``the victim for some unknown reason challenged the train and lost.''
the 105-car conrail train was heading east when the conductor spotted the youths and blew a caution whistle, monroe county sheriff's deputies said
miss strassner and her girlfriend were standing between two sets of tracks as the train approached. at the last moment, she leaped into the train's path and was struck and thrown 50 feet, picciotti said
miss strassner's mother, patricia sampson, said ``stand by me'' was her daughter's favorite movie
she watched it over and over again. and she had a crush on the actor. she bought the video and she went to any friend who had a vcr and watched it,'' her mother said
no order is too tall for richlee shoes, which specializes in elevator shoes
it even sells elevator bedroom slippers
if you're going to be taller at the office and the company picnic, why wouldn't you want to be taller at home? won't the neighbors notice if you run out to get the paper that you're shorter?'' said bob martin, who operates the company with his sister and three brothers
ninety styles, priced $40 to $120, are displayed in 100,000 square feet of warehouse space just south of frederick. it sells direct and through mail order
we don't feel we've even scratched the surface'' of the number of men who want to appear taller, said martin. ``depending on the style, our shoes can make a man two inches taller. i've had people call me up ... they say `the difference in my height has made a difference in my social life.'''
elevator shoes have come a long way from the days when the company's celebrity spokesman, mickey rooney, sported oxfords with chunky heels that didn't hide their purpose. today's elevator shoes look like normal shoes but have a built-up insole
martin said he even has one regular customer who stands 6-foot-5
i asked him why,'' he said. ``he said he was a basketball player in college and all his friends were 6-feet-7 or 8.''
a self-cleaning bathtub and salt dyed red so that people can know how much they use. sunglasses with pockets and a life-preserver for horses
those are inventions by kids involved in a program called invent america, which seeks to boost the level of creativity and innovation in this country
at dommerich elementary school in this orlando suburb, fifth-graders are brainstorming their way to new ideas to resolve problems, such as locating a dog at night or taking out the garbage
the invent america class is taught by gil rowe one day a week to each of five classes of gifted students in different grades. he came from ocoee elementary school, which won four of invent america's nine state awards, the most of any school in the country
we've just kind of forgotten to teach the children the old american ingenuity,'' says rowe, 44. the program was started by the privately funded u.s. patent model foundation in washington
besides opening up the innovative process, rowe says, the program enhances students' self-esteem. one ocoee second-grader who was emotionally and mentally disturbed and had no friends invented a device that earned him his classmates' admiration
suddenly he became a famous inventor. he just became a totally different individual,'' rowe said
the problem of finding a dog at night was addressed by 11-year-old seth swanson, who plans to develop a dog collar with a light attached before the class ends with a school fair in april
ten-year-old robbie cadle hates carrying the garbage cans out so much that he concentrated all his efforts on that one issue
his solution? motorized garbage cans that can be driven from the house to the street, and back. aids</head>
the sex experts dr. william masters and virginia johnson said monday they could not provide scientific evidence to support their widely publicized claim that aids is ``running rampant'' among heterosexuals
when masters was asked at a contentious news conference how he could justify such a claim, he said, ``i simply believe this.'' johnson, asked the same question, said ``i'm not sure we chose the word `rampant' ourselves.''
on page seven of their new book, they write: ``the aids virus is now running rampant in the heterosexual community.''
the book, ``crisis: heterosexual behavior in the age of aids,'' was made available to reporters monday morning. the first reports of its contents appeared in connection with an excerpt from the book published in this week's newsweek magazine
we don't see an explosion into the heterosexual community,'' said dr. peter fischinger, aids coordinator for the public health service. ``this does not mean we can be complacent about it.'' he noted that nationwide screening of blood donors has found that only about one in 40,000 has the potential of being infected with the aids virus
the public health service has been working very hard to try to get the best sense of prevalence of hiv infection in the united states,'' fischinger said. hiv, or human immunodeficiency virus, is the virus that causes aids
dr. stephen joseph, new york city's health commissioner, said of the masters and johnson study, ``all in all, i think it's greatly overblown.'' he criticized them for not submitting their data to a scientific journal where it could be reviewed in detail by other researchers, and he said their data did not support the sweeping claims they made
i think everyone would agree there is a serious danger in heterosexual transmission,'' he said. but ``contrary to what they say, i think the public health service people have been saying that for a long time.''
masters and johnson and dr. robert kolodny, their co-author and a director of the masters &amp; johnson institute in st. louis, studied 800 men and women in atlanta, st. louis, new york and los angeles
the study, the centerpiece of their book, included only people who said they did not use illicit intravenous drugs and said they had had no homosexual or bisexual contact and no blood transfusions since 1977
masters, johnson and kolodny chose four hundred men and women who said they had had at least six sexual partners each year for the preceding five years, and another 400 who said they had been monogamous
the researchers found that 5 percent of the sexually active men and 7 percent of the sexually active women had antibodies to the aids virus, meaning they had been exposed to it
the researchers said, however, that these findings could not be used to project how many people in the united states might be infected with the aids virus. ``this is not meant to be _ it was not constructed as _ a broad representative sample of the population,'' said kolodny
kolodny said the claim that aids is rampant among heterosexuals comes from studies by other researchers. but other studies have diverged widely on the question of how rapidly aids is entering the non-drug-using heterosexual community
in october, for example, dr. thomas quinn of johns hopkins university in baltimore studied men and women visiting a sexually transmitted-diseases clinic in baltimore and found that one-third of the men infected with the aids virus and almost half of the women got the infection through heterosexual contact
that was one of the highest reported rates of spread among heterosexuals. at the same scientific meeting, however, researchers from new york city and the u.s. centers for disease control reported that only one in 205 men coming to a sexually transmitted-diseases clinic in new york city was infected with aids in the absence of drug use, homosexuality or other high-risk behavior
vice president george bush, anticipating a super tuesday windfall of republican convention delegates, is targeting illinois, the biggest state in bob dole's midwest base, as the battleground that could end the kansas senator's hope of a comeback in the gop race
i don't know what dole does if he doesn't win illinois,'' said bush campaign manager lee atwater
i can't wait to hear their new theory if they lose illinois,'' he said. ``everyone comes up with a theory on how they can still win it.''
a dole campaign source agreed the kansas senator must win illinois and said they would spend about $500,000 on television advertising, their largest budget for any state
rich bond, bush's deputy campaign manager, refused to cite a specific figure for the campaign's advertising budget but said they would spent ``whatever it takes.''
traveling with bush in missouri on monday, atwater said he expected the vice president to win 12 or 13 of the 17 gop events on tuesday
asked he was hoping for a clean sweep, bush said, ``you always wish for that, but i certainly would never predict that. it's too much for anyone to expect.''
while bush aides speculate about a possible super tuesday sweep that could net the vice president up to 600 gop convention delegates, the dole camp talks about surviving the south and getting back to the midwest, where the kansas senator has whipped bush in iowa, minnesota and south dakota
dole is undefeated in the midwest and illinois is in the midwest,'' said dole campaign aide larry mccarthy
the key is how well we do in the midwestern tier of states, starting with illinois,'' said richard wirthlin, dole's pollster
but bond disputed the dole homeground advantage in illinois
the votes aren't in bob dole's backyard,'' he said. ``the votes are in chicago and the collar counties (the chicago suburbs) and it's hardly a typical farm state.''
with 82 gop delegates at stake, the illinois primary is march 15, one week after super tuesday
dole has already started his television campaign in illinois with a biographical ad that emphasizes his humble upbringing, war service, and leadership role in congress
dole turned ronald reagan's vision into an action plan for america,'' said the ad, which concluded with the narrator saying, ``bob dole is a strong man _ with a record of solving tough problems.''
dole has a strong organization in the state, headed by illinois house minority leader lee daniels and augmented by former gov. richard ogilvie
backing bush was gov. james thompson, as well as 93 of the state's 102 republican county chairmen
while the dole campaign cited illinois as the staging ground for a comeback, bush aides called the state important but not essential
if for some reason george bush can't win illinois, i still suspect he's going to be the nominee of the republican party,'' said atwater
the bush campaign aide cited the key role the state has played in past presidential nomination races
in my mind, ronald reagan was going to be the nominee when we won illinois in 1980,'' he said. ``in my mind when mondale won illinois in 1984, he was going to be the nominee.''
atwater and bond contended that the election calendar also is a problem for dole
they cited the fact that among the key states that follow illinois are connecticut, where bush has a big advantage, and new york, where the vice president is the only candidate to have delegate slates filed in every congressional district
we get 45 delegates just for showing up,'' said bond
even winning a state or two,'' added bond, ``i don't see how he (dole) gets the upper hand. ... can he win a state or two? sure. can he stop bush? i don't think so.''
tunisian foreign minister mahmoud mestiri will visit washington later this month to discuss the u.s. mideast peace initiative as well as bilateral issues, the state department announced monday
mestiri will meet with secretary of state george p. shultz and other officials, as well as with congressional representatives, on march 28 and 29, the announcement said
president reagan renewed his call monday for weapons for the rebels fighting nicaragua's leftist government, but house speaker jim wright gave the request an icy reception
in a speech to a veterans of foreign wars convention, reagan said his congressional opponents on the issue of aid to the contra rebels lack courage to fight communism, and said efforts to renew ``humanitarian'' aid for the rebels are insufficient
now it's time for congress to show that it knows you can't have real peace negotiations when one side has helicopter gunships and the other has bandages,'' reagan told the group
reagan's spokesman, marlin fitzwater, said later that the administration still hopes wright will come up with a new contra aid proposal and that the white house will be encouraging efforts in the senate to write an aid bill
fitzwater acknowledged that ``time is a problem. ... we don't know how long (the contras) can last.'' u.s. aid to the rebels ended a week ago
but on capitol hill, where the house last week narrowly defeated an effort to send food and clothing to the contras, wright said it is time to turn to other issues
there is a weariness with the contra issue'' among house members, said wright, d-texas. he added that he plans to begin mapping out a program of other legislation to bring to the floor, including issues like welfare reform and a health-care bill
wright also signaled that a group of senators trying to revive some kind of contra aid bill could run into procedural roadblocks, reminding reporters obliquely that the house traditionally reserves the right to originate any legislation to appropriate money
i'm not looking for problems'' with a senate-originated bill, he said, but added: ``those who draft the legislation ought to be mindful of that.''
wright said last week's defeat of the democratic $30.8 million contra aid package means that the united states is left with little more than moral suasion as a tool to influence central american peace efforts
it just throws it into the hands of the central americans entirely, and sort of withdraws the united states for the moment from having any direct influence,'' he said
wright said he has sent telegrams to both sides in the conflict, urging them to pursue a cease-fire agreement when they meet this week for the first time without a mediator and inside nicaragua
he said he urged the sandinista side to permit a role for nicaraguan cardinal miguel obando y bravo, whom nicaraguan president daniel ortega has rejected as a mediator after several fruitless sessions. and he asked the rebels to go forward with the talks, noting that they had been granted the high-level direct talks they have been seeking
in his speech, reagan said the defeat of the contras would mean a ``grave strategic defeat for the united states.''
the communists in central america understand this, the soviets understand this _ it's time that congress understood it too,'' reagan said. ``a soviet base on the american mainland is a pistol pointed at the heart of the americas.''
reagan contended that the ``real issue'' before the congress is not the contras, ``it is communism in central america.''
referring to last week's 216-to-208 vote, reagan said: ``courage hasn't exactly been the watchword of some opponents of contra aid. ... last week, aid opponents tried to pass the buck of responsibility for abandoning in the field the young men and women of the democratic resistance, and that ploy failed as it should have.''
the supreme court said monday it will decide whether a criminal defendant's right to a jury selected from a cross-section of the community is violated when prosecutors disqualify potential jurors because they are black
the court will review the case of frank d. teague, sentenced to 30 years in prison for the armed robbery of a chicago supermarket and for the attempted murder of police officers shot at after the robbery
the justices in 1986 ruled in a case called batson vs. kentucky that prosecutors never may disqualify potential jurors based on their race. the court said such tactics violate equal-protection rights
but a subsequent decision strictly limited the retroactive effect of the batson ruling
the court said the batson decision does not apply to convicted criminals who, like teague, had exhausted direct appeals in state courts prior to april 30, 1986, when batson was announced
if the justices were to rule that the prosecutorial tactics used at teague's trial violated his sixth amendment right to cross-sectional jury selection, he would be entitled to a new trial even though the batson ruling came too late to help him
presumably, such a ruling would affect other prison inmates' convictions as well
the 7th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled last may that past supreme court decisions make clear that ``the fair cross-section requirement of the sixth amendment does not apply to the jury itself'' but only to the pool of potential jurors from which juries are chosen
lawyers for teague, who is black, contend that his fair-trial rights were violated when prosecutors used all 10 of their so-called peremptory challenges to exclude blacks from the jury
the court's decision is not expected until sometime in 1989
the american society of composers, authors and publishers announced monday that it will produce a memorial tribute to composer frederick loewe in a broadway theater on march 28
confirmed to perform and-or speak are julie andrews, richard harris, louis jordan, robert goulet, agnes de mille, kitty carlisle hart and herman levin, who produced loewe's most famous musical, ``my fair lady.''
ken sunshine of ascap said the theater will be announced later. the tribute will be free and open to the public
loewe and lyricist alan jay lerner also wrote the songs for ``brigadoon,'' ``paint your wagon,'' ``camelot'' and the movie ``gigi.'' loewe died feb. 15; he was 86. illinois</head>
presidential candidates sent out their last wave of commercials in super tuesday states on monday, and republican bob dole was already appealing to tv viewers in the next battleground
dole was running ads in 11 states, including illinois, which holds its primary next tuesday
in illinois, the kansas senator started running a spot called ``strong man'' that stresses the poverty and war wounds dole overcame in rising to his present post of senate gop leader. the ad says dole ``turned ronald reagan's vision into an action plan for america. tax cuts, aid for the contras, fighting wasteful spending.''
dole was running a mix of ads _ including an attack on vice president george bush's iran-contra role _ in illinois, alabama, maryland, gorgia, louisiana, washington, oklahoma, north carolina, missouri, arkansas and florida
bush was expected to trounce dole in the super tuesday arena and planned ``the heaviest media buy we'll place anywhere in this campaign'' in illinois, according to aide rich bond
bush has been endorsed by illinois gov. jim thompson and most of the state's county republican chairmen
sen. albert gore jr, d-tenn., was running a mix of seven tv spots in 13 southern and border states. four of the ads were head-on criticism of rival democrats while the other three stressed populist, anti-establishment themes
gore planned to split his time between illinois and south carolina until the saturday primary in south carolina, and then return to illinois until next tuesday's primary there
rep. richard gephardt, d-mo., has been endorsed by powerful rep. dan rostenkowski of chicago and expects to spend parts of thursday and friday in illinois. spokeswoman lisa cutter said gephardt was not advertising in illinois as of monday
the congressman was running a mix of five television spots in eight super tuesday states: texas, oklahoma, louisiana, arkansas, alabama, mississippi, florida and georgia. among them were endorsements by rep. claude pepper, d-fla., and marvin leath, d-texas, his famous trade ad about the $48,000 k-car, and two attacks on michael dukakis
two democratic native sons, jesse jackson and sen. paul simon, planned no television advertising in their home state of illinois
we're planning to run a barnstorming campaign around the state'' counting on news coverage, said simon press secretary terry michael
simon skipped super tuesday, saying he couldn't afford it and it would be inconclusive. jackson ran a modest, upbeat tv campaign to augment a full schedule of personal appearances
the united states would welcome participation by north korean athletes in the seoul olympics, a senior u.s. diplomat said monday
the olympics would be better off if north korea chooses to participate,'' said assistant secretary of state edward derwinski. ``but time is running out.''
he added that ``we have nothing but a positive attitude'' toward participation by pyongyang
derwinski said the united states will have ``some additional naval units'' in the region at the time of the september olympic games. speaking at the u.s. information agency's foreign press center, he said the additional naval presence was ``a very timely, practical coincidence.''
other u.s. officials have said the additional presence will probably consist of one or two aircraft carriers
derwinski warned that any attempt by the north koreans to disrupt the games ``would make them a total pariah.'' north korea is one of only a handful of countries, including cuba, which is boycotting the games
derwinski indicated that the united states would ask visiting chinese foreign minister wu xueqian to use his country's leverage with north korea to prevent any disruption of the olympics
this is the logical, diplomatic way to proceed'' with the pyongyang government, he said. ``we have no leverage with them, and any suggestion on our part would be counterproductive.''
americans took out $5.42 billion more in installment debt than they paid off in january, the biggest monthly increase in four months and the second strong month in a row, the government said monday
the federal reserve said consumer credit grew at a seasonally adjusted rate of 10.6 percent in january, following an increase of $3.98 billion in december, which translated to an annual rate of 7.9 percent
growth in both months was greater than the 5.9 percent rate for all of 1987, which represents a considerable slowdown compared with recent years. the rate was 10.5 percent in 1986
the relatively strong january report is both a reflection of job growth _ unemployment hit a nine-year low of 5.7 percent in february _ and a sign that the rebound in consumer confidence after the october stock market crash is continuing, according to david cross, an economist with the futures group, a washington consulting firm
what we're seeing right now ... is a sort of soft landing for consumer spending,'' said cross, whose firm is predicting growth between 6.5 percent and 7 percent this year. ``we're not really looking for a recession to occur, if anything just a bit of slowness in the first half of the year.''
the january increase was the biggest advance since debt rose by $6.43 billion in september. the gains in both months were strongly influenced by an upturn in car sales
auto loans rose by $1.54 billion in january, an annual rate of 7.1 percent, and followed a stronger gain of 10.7 percent in december
credit card and revolving loans grew by $2.0 billion in january, a 16.5 percent annual rate, following an increase of 19.3 percent a month earlier
the debt category which includes bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate grew by $1.73 billion, an 11.6 percent growth rate, following a decline of 3.5 percent in december
loans for mobile homes increased $142 million after falling $122 million in december
the various changes left total consumer debt at $617.5 billion in january
rescuers using trained dogs found the body of a cross-country skier buried in an avalanche in mount rainer national park, a park spokesman said monday
pamela benton lee, 28, of olympia, was buried sunday afternoon in the plummer peak area, 5,000 to 6,000 feet in elevation, spokesman dave uberuaga said
her companion, sean mehan of olympia, told rangers he probed unsuccessfully in the snow for about an hour before skiing out and notifying park rangers, uberuaga said
mehan, with two rangers and two climbers, tried to get to the site late sunday, but had to turn back because of darkness and avalanche hazard, uberuaga said
on monday, a team of 11 park staff, 10 members of the area mountain-rescue council and three dog units began probing the avalanche, uberuaga said. an initial shoulder-to-shoulder sweep of the avalanche failed to fine ms. lee, he said
a dog that sensed a ``hot spot'' found the body buried near the base of the avalanche, uberuaga said. rescuers used probes to pinpoint the body and dig it out. ms. lee had been missing about 20 hours
the avalanche, about 60 feet wide and 120 feet long, ranged in depth from 2 feet to 10 feet, uberuaga said
a high avalanche hazard was posted all day sunday, after paradise received 10 inches of snow saturday, bringing the total there to 130 inches. avalanche hazard was still considered high on monday
the soviet union has bought an additional 300,000 metric tons of u.s. corn for delivery this year under a long-term supply agreement between the two countries, the agriculture department said monday
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. the 300,000 tons of corn would be about 11.8 million bushels
corn prices recently have been averaging about $1.85 per bushel at the farm level, meaning that the sale could have a farm value of around $22 million
the corn is part of the grain the soviet union is committed to buy during the fifth and final year of the agreement, which calls for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of u.s. grain. the pact expires sept. 30
according to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. the soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain equivalent
with the latest purchases, the soviets now have bought 3.17 million tons of corn, plus almost 6.9 million tons of wheat; 813,300 tons of soybeans, and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal
rep. richard gephardt emphasized his support for an oil-import fee on monday, one day before four oil-producing states vote on super tuesday, then went to the alamo to call himself the democratic candidate for economic independence
we're standing today in front of the alamo, a place where there was a fight for independence,'' gephardt said. ``this election in 1988 is a fight again for the independence of america, the fight for us to regain control of our economic destiny.''
gephardt spoke to about 400 supporters and tourists in this city, generally considered a stronghold for massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, after speaking at a struggling dallas plant that makes equipment for the oil industry
dukakis was at the alamo sunday. many of the democrats here are hispanic, and dukakis spoke to them in fluent spanish
but rep. albert bustamante, d-texas, supporting gephardt, told the rally on monday that no one suffers more from the oil industry's downturn than south texas hispanics
if you want somebody who speaks spanish, i do a little of that and i can interpret for dick,'' bustamante said, noting that gephardt has begun studying spanish. san antonio mayor henry cisneros has stayed neutral, although his wife has endorsed dukakis
gephardt recalled he trained for the missouri air national guard at lackland air force base near here. he then attacked dukakis for wanting to cut the defense budget
he's going to leave us in jeopardy and vulnerable,'' gephardt said
he continued to criticize his foes for opposing an oil-import fee
anyone like al gore or michael dukakis who tells you that they're for making america energy independent is simply trying to deceive you in a shameful way,'' gephardt said after touring dresser industries, a dallas plant that gephardt said shows the need for long-term domestic energy policy because of its nearly 50 percent cutbacks in operation
gephardt has concentrated on gore and dukakis in his texas swing. polls indicate he and gore are battling for third behind dukakis and civil rights leader jesse jackson. but gephardt said his chances for winning texas were good. africa</head>
a security council draft resolution circulated monday calls for mandatory economic sanctions, including an oil embargo, against south africa to force the government to abolish apartheid within a year
the draft resolution, to be discussed when the council meets tuesday, expresses outrage at the banning of anti-apartheid activities and concern for the ``worsening of the human suffering resulting from the apartheid system'' of racial segregation
the resolution says south africa's intransigence ``compels the international community to impose, as a first step, selective mandatory sanctions.''
under south africa's system of apartheid, the 26 million blacks have no voice in national affairs and the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate schools and districts
the resolution, circulated after three days of debate, calls for a halt to export and sale of oil to south africa; an end to further investment and loans; a ban on imports of iron and steel; a halt of all trade promotion and support for trade; prohibition of sale of kruggerands and all coins minted in south africa; and cessation of all forms of military, policy or intelligence cooperation, especially the sale of computer equipment
south african u.n. ambassador leslie manley told the security council on thursday, ``we will not bow to your threats or demands and we reject your accusations with contempt and invite you to do your damnedest.''
the resolution calls for all u.n. members to back the sanctions and report progress to the secretary-general. it establishes a security council committee to monitor implementation
security council resolutions can be vetoed by any one of its permanent members _ the united states, great britain, china, france and the soviet union. the council and the u.n. general assembly have condemned south africa in the past, but the united states and other countries have opposed sanctions
the resolution says the sanctions would remain in force for one year, after which the council again will meet to determine if south africa has abolished apartheid
the proposed measures also require south africa to lift the ban on anti-apartheid political activities, release all political prisoners, allow the free and safe return of exiles and commence dialogue with leaders of the majority black population
the draft resolution was submitted by algeria, argentina, nepal, senegal, yugoslavia and zambia
the supreme court on monday set the stage for an important ruling on sex discrimination, agreeing to study a case in which ``unconscious stereotyping'' allegedly played a key role in denying a woman an accounting firm partnership
the justices said they will review a ruling that places a heavy burden on employers to disprove sex bias
arguments in the case will be heard in the fall during the court's next term and a decision is not likely to be announced until 1989
price waterhouse, one of the nation's largest accounting firms, is accused of discriminating unlawfully against ann hopkins. she quit the firm's office here after she was denied promotion to partnership, a move that would have made her a part owner
ms. hopkins joined the firm in 1978 and was nominated for partnership in 1982, the only woman among 88 candidates for partnership that year
she had been very successful in getting business for the company, winning government contracts worth an estimated $34 million to $44 million
of the 88 candidates, 47 were invited to become partners; 21 were rejected outright; and 20 including ms. hopkins were placed on hold
the following year she was told she would not become a partner, and she resigned in 1984 to set up her own consulting firm
both her critics and supporters at price waterhouse said she sometimes was overly aggressive, too harsh, impatient with her staff and very demanding
one critic suggested she needed to take a ``course at charm school.''
a partner in the firm who urged her promotion told her she would stand a better chance of becoming a partner if she would ``walk more femininely, talk more femininely, dress more femininely, wear make-up, have her hair styled and wear jewelry.''
others said her use of profanity was a black mark against her
ms. hopkins then sued price waterhouse, accusing the company of violating title vii of the 1964 civil rights act prohibiting on-the-job sex disscrimination. she said that sex stereotyping, unconscious or otherwise, barred her from being named partner
the supreme court ruled in 1984, in the case of a woman denied partnership in a law firm, that professional partnerships are covered by the 1964 law
a federal judge ruled price waterhouse must prove ``by clear and convincing evidence'' it would not have made her a partner regardless of whether sexual stereotyping played a part in its decision
price waterhouse said it was unable to provide such proof
the u.s. circuit court of appeals here last august said there is ``competent evidence that ... the partnership selection process at price waterhouse was impermissibly infected by stereotypical attitudes toward female candidates.''
the appeals court said even if there is evidence that ms. hopkins' personality played a part in her denial of partnership, price waterhouse is unable to prove ``impermissible bias was not the determinative factor.''
the appeals court ordered further hearings to determine what back pay and other remedies the company must provide
the case is price waterhouse vs. hopkins, 87-1167
president zia ul-haq of pakistan was quoted monday as saying he's certain of signing an afghan peace accord soon, even though his representative continued to press for an interim government to oversee withdrawal of soviet troops
pakistan's chief representative in the peace talks, acting foreign minister zain noorani, said islamabad was still hoping for soviet cooperation, even though his country wants an interim government to replace the present moscow-backed regime
it is in their interest, too, to see that there is peace and calm after they leave,'' said noorani after talks resumed monday morning following a weekend recess
however, zia was quoted as telling the gulf news, a united arab emirates newspaper, that ``there is no question of the accord not going through.'' ``allowing it to be dropped is no option,'' he said
the talks adjourned so pakistani government and opposition leaders could discuss whether they're ready to sign an accord with the soviet-backed afghan government of president najib
pakistan represents afghan rebels in the talks and does not recognize the kabul government
noorani declined to say what pakistan had decided over the weekend
no afternoon session was scheduled following the morning meetings conducted separately by u.n. mediator diego cordovez with the afghan and pakistani delegations. asked whether there was any progress, afghan foreign minister abdul wakil said only, ``ask mr. cordovez.''
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev has named march 15 as the deadline for signing a settlement if the pullout of 115,000 soviet troops is to begin in mid-may, before a u.s.-soviet summit
agreement was reached thursday on a withdrawal over nine months in which half of the troops would leave within 90 days
a spokesman for the largest group in the seven-party afghan rebel alliance said monday that progress was being made in setting up an islamic government with headquarters possibly in afghanistan. professor abdul kadir kariab, in charge of political affairs of the fundamentalist hezb-i-islami party, said a u.s-educated engineer, ahmed shah, had already been unanimously elected head of state
kariab also told reporters in geneva that the alliance was already in contact with pakistan, iran and other countries regarding possible recognition of the future government
the alliance claims to represent 200,000 rebels and to control 80 percent of the afghan territory
kariab also repeated charges raised by the chairman of his party, gulbaddin hekmatyar, that the united states and the soviet union had struck a ``secret deal'' to prevent formation of such a government. he said a ``jewish lobby'' was part of such ``conspiracy'' because it feared islamic fundamentalism
he said that if pakistan were pressed to sign ``a settlement in the present shape, (it) will be historic treason to the afghan people.'' protester</head> 3rd graf, `jim condon...' subs last graf with additional quote on incident.</note>
a south african diplomat was cited for assault monday after his car struck a protester and a police officer outside a radio station where he had been interviewed, police said
south african vice consul duke kent brown was arrested about a quarter-mile away after allegedly fleeing the scene, police chief john race said
brown was charged with simple assault, released on his own recognizance and ordered to appear in court in april. the charge carries up to a year in prison and a fine of $1,000, race said
brown left the burlington area following his release, police said, and he failed to make three other scheduled appearances with the media
jim condon, news director at radio station wjoy-wqcr and a witness, said the protester who was struck suffered minor bruises
race identified the injured officer as todd shepard, said he had suffered leg bruises and was being examined at a hospital
it was unclear whether brown would be covered by diplomatic immunity. race said police had called the u.s. state department for guidance
a spokesman in the south african embassy in washington, third secretary heyn van rooyen, said brown is connected with the consulate in new york
there are different degrees of diplomatic immunity,'' said van rooyen, adding he was not sure what would apply to brown
condon said about 30 members of the vermont committee on southern africa had gathered outside the station to protest brown's participation in a talk show
he said brown left the station under police escort and made his way to a car in a parking lot. brown got in and a few protesters sat on the hood, condon said
police were in the process of removing protesters from the hood when brown ``hit the accelerator,'' condon said. target</head>
metropolitan area residents exceeded the goals set by the better air campaign in reducing traffic volume and wood smoke on high pollution days and met the oxygenated fuel program's goals, officials announced monday
gov. roy romer and denver mayor federico pena reported the results of the 90-day better air campaign and the two-month oxygenated fuels program at a news conference
the people of this area are to be congratulated,'' romer said. ``by reducing their driving between november and january and by restricting wood burning on high-pollution days, they have reduced carbon monoxide pollution in the metro area by up to 17 percent.''
the campaign's purpose was to reduce traffic volume and wood-smoke pollution on days when temperature inversions caused denver's carbon-monoxide levels to soar
the project achieved a 9 percent reduction in traffic on high-pollution days, equivalent to three million miles daily, and a 10 percent reduction in carbon monoxide vehicle emissions, said anne grady, spokeswoman for the colorado department of health's air pollution control division. she said the program's goal was an 8 percent traffic reduction and a 9 percent reduction in carbon monoxide
carbon monoxide emissions from wood-burning fell 7 percent on high-pollution days during the most recent better air campaign, said grady, and the goal was a 6 percent reduction
pena said the 7 percent carbon monoxide reduction attributable to observance of wood-burning bans was more than double last year's results
the better air campaign ran from early november until the end of january. in its previous three years, it ran for just 60 days
the oxygenated fuels program, which was launched for the first time in january and lasted two months, required all service stations along the 130-mile corridor along the front range between colorado springs and fort collins to sell only oxygenated fuels, or fuels containing at least 1.5 percent oxygen
the program's purpose was to provide a gasoline that would burn cleaner in car engines and thus contribute less carbon monoxide pollution, officials said. motorists were offered the choice of an ether-gasoline blend, or gasohol, which contains ethyl alcohol
grady said the oxy fuels program was right on target in its goal of reducing ambient carbon-monoxide levels by 8 percent to 10 percent. the reduction was in the 8 percent to 9.5 percent range, she said
a medical student whose nickname and appearance were similar to another student's may have been tortured and murdered by mistake by killers hired to hit his classmate, investigators said
both students were cuban-americans from florida, both were studying medicine at the universidad central del este in the dominican republic, but they did not know each other
the body of ignacio pereda, 26, of miami, dumped near a sugar cane field two days after he was kidnapped, had been beaten so badly that only a birthmark on the back of one hand permitted his identification, the miami herald reported monday, quoting the victim's family
his abduction came just three weeks before he was scheduled to graduate from the caribbean medical school on feb. 12
police, stumped for a motive, began looking into an earlier incident involving another cuban-american student at the university
shortly before the killing, student jorge sotolongo had a run-in with a jealous husband, who fired his gun but hit no one, the herald reported
the two young men resembled each other and pereda, from miami, was known by a nickname similar to sotolongo _ bobolongo
we believe the murder could have been a mistake,'' said first lt. jose antonio torres of san pedro de macoris, a town about 40 miles east of the capital of santo domingo, where the body was found
sotolongo has returned to his home in st. petersburg
i don't think he is in any danger, he is here with me,'' sotolongo's father told the herald. ``he is sorry for the other boy. he doesn't know if they killed him by mistake or if they wanted to kill him.''
pereda's murder devastated his parents, who have no other children, and friends
he didn't smoke, or drink or fool around. he was very educated, an old-fashioned person,'' said his classmate and girlfriend, virginia garcia. ``no drugs, no alcohol, no women. there are very few men like him nowadays.''
one aunt, aida rodriguez, said she wants to go to the dominican republic
we want answers,'' she said
