this is the logical, diplomatic way to proceed'' with the pyongyang government, he said. ``we have no leverage with them, and any suggestion on our part would be counterproductive.''
the first california condor egg produced by captive breeding is fertile and contains the makings of a chick, san diego wild animal park officials said monday
you can't actually see an embryo yet, but what you can see is the beginnings of circulatory development, which appears as a dark dime-sized dot toward the top of the yolk,'' park spokesman tom hanscom said
the egg was laid thursday, the product of a male condor known as ac-4 and a female condor called un-1. it was removed immediately from its nest in the park's ``condorminium'' and placed in an incubator
keepers peeked inside the egg by holding it up to a high-intensity lamp in a process known as ``candling.'' the egg then was returned to its incubator, where it will be kept until the hatching expected between april 28 and may 3, hanscom said
now, we incubate the egg according to the parameters that have worked so well in the past and hope ... we can hatch a healthy condor chick,'' he said
all 27 living california condors are in captivity. fourteen are kept at the wild animal park and 13 at the los angeles zoo
thirteen of the 27 birds were hatched in captivity in an effort to build a breeding flock to save the rare birds from extinction. each of those eggs were taken from nests in the wild
the breeding program has been conducted at the san diego zoo and its affiliate, the wild animal park, since 1983 in cooperation with state and federal wildlife officials
the last known wild condor was captured in april 1987 by government biologists after it was determined the carrion-eating birds' existence was threatened by lead poisoning in their food supply and human encroachment upon their central california habitat
our success or failure has pivoted on the captive production of a fertile egg and that's what we've got,'' hanscom said of the 4-day-old egg
meanwhile, the parents of the egg were said to be doing well. keepers removed the shell from its nest soon after it was laid to stimulate more breeding activity by the pair, which hanscom said has begun
that's real positive,'' he said. ``that would lead us to hope for the production of a second egg, which could come as early as 30 days after the first egg
the parents are doing fine, the egg is doing fine and the keepers are doing fine.''
more than 1 million serious crimes were reported in florida last year, a record number blamed in part on the spread of ``crack'' cocaine and other drugs, authorities announced monday
the number of reported homicides, rapes, robberies, assaults, burglaries, larcenies and motor vehicle thefts rose 6.3 percent to go over the 1 million mark for the first time, to 1,021,283, said robert dempsey, commissioner of the florida department of law enforcement
as you know, the crime rate is driven to a large extent by the drug problem. there is no question about that,'' dempsey said
he urged gov. bob martinez and the legislature to consider increasing spending for criminal justice. presently, he said, 6 percent of an $18.5 billion budget is devoted to the criminal justice system, which includes law enforcement and the courts, he said
it's intolerable. we need to do something about addressing credibility in the criminal justice area,'' dempsey said. ``we need to address the career criminals, the jail situation and some of the weaknesses in the so-called criminal justice system, which as many of you know is no system at all.''
dempsey also said citizens need to start a grassroots campaign to help prevent violence and property thefts. increases in property crime, particularly in some of the more rural counties, can be directly attributed to the increase of the powerful crack form of cocaine, the commissioner said
anybody who tells you the drug problem is leveling off is in fairyland. they don't know what's happening,'' he said
the florida figures released monday were preliminary. a complete report was expected to be issued later this year
the commissioner said florida continues to lead other states in crime rates, or the number of crimes reported per 100,000 population. he compared florida's 1987 figures with figures reported by other states in 1986
we have the highest crime rate in the nation,'' said dempsey
department spokesman john joyce said florida's per-capita crime rate, which increased by 2.9 percent in 1987, has been significantly higher in past years than the figures reported by other states. since florida is one of the first to release its figures, new data was unavailable in other states
in 1986, florida had 8,238 serious crimes reported per 100,000 population, compared with 7,408 in texas, 7,322 in arizona, 7,081 in oregon, 7,032 in colorado, 6,880 in washington, 6,763 in california, 6,626 in new mexico, 6,491.5 in michigan and 6,290 in nevada
the district of columbia actually had the highest of all with 8,339 per 100,000 population
in florida, the total arrests for cocaine last year were up 32.8 percent over 1986, while property crimes increased 6.7 percent over 1986. the number of motor vehicle thefts rose by 16.4 percent, and aggravated assaults showed a 3.1 percent increase
the number of reported murders and rapes was slightly down. homicides declined from 1,371 to 1,368 and rapes declined from 6,153 to 6,017
more police officers were assaulted and killed in 1987 than the previous year, 10 compared with six. assaults on police officers rose from 7,289 in 1986 to 7,833 in 1987
dempsey acknowledged that the overall crime increase was not as high as had been reported in recent years. from 1985 to 1986, his department reported a 7.9 percent increase. the increase was 11.4 percent from 1984 to 1985
it's true the rate of increase is dropping but it is still an increase,'' dempsey said
u.s. sen. howard metzenbaum opened his bid for a third, six-year term on monday, describing himself as a fighter and warning backers to brace for negative ads and gutter politics from opponents
this battle that i'm about to embark upon today will be the toughest battle that i've ever experienced in my lifetime. i cannot tell you all the details of all the stuff, and nonsense, and sleaze that they're pouring into ohio,'' metzenbaum, d-ohio, told an airport rally
i'm asking ohioans to judge this campaign not on nasty, negative ads nor gutter politics. you'll see plenty of both thrown our way, and it's already started,'' said metzenbaum, who is being challenged by cleveland mayor george voinovich, a republican, in the nov. 8 election
there are some powerful forces who want to see me out of the senate. for them no price is too high, no tactic is too low,'' metzenbaum said
the rally, which drew a crowd of about 100 that included officeholders and union members, was one of four as metzenbaum barnstormed the state in a plane piloted by u.s. sen. john glenn, d-ohio, his campaign chairman. other stops were in cincinnati, dayton and cleveland. 1 graf after 8th graf previous, `the other...' with conditions on release.</note>
a 31-month pretrial detention ended monday for a defendant in the wells fargo robbery case after a judge approved arrangements for his $1 million bond
juan segarra palmer was released after u.s. district judge peter dorsey signed the papers. segarra palmer and another wells fargo defendant, filiberto ojeda rios, had been held without bond longer than any other defendants in federal judicial history
segarra palmer's father, enrique segarra, testified before a u.s. magistrate earlier monday that his son would be disgraced ``personally and politically'' if he failed to appear for trial on charges in the 1983 robbery of $7 million from a wells fargo depot in west hartford
he is a person of great character,'' enrique segarra said. ``if he said he will be here, he will be here.''
i'm happy, but i have to say the real issue is not my freedom,'' harvard-educated segarra palmer, 38, said as he walked out of court. ``the real issue is the freedom of puerto rico and preventive detention.''
segarra palmer, who was arrested in august 1985 in puerto rico, was held without bond until last month, when u.s. district judge t. emmet clarie set bond at $1 million
clarie has, however, refused to do the same for ojeda rios, saying the defendant could flee to avoid prosecution
segarra palmer's bond is secured partly by $500,000 in property owned by 11 people in the town of naranjito, puerto rico, the hometown of his wife, luz berrios berrios, another wells fargo defendant who has been free on bond for some time
the other $500,000 is unsecured, but his parents and three siblings signed agreements to pay the money should segarra palmer not appear for trial
under terms of his bond, segarra palmer cannot leave hartford, must be home by 10 p.m. each night and agreed that the government has the right to try him in absentia should he flee. the government also plans to require him to wear an electronic bracelet to monitor his movements, but none of the devices are available in hartford, said his attorney, leonard weinglass
sixteen people are awaiting trial in the wells fargo robbery, which the government contends was masterminded by los matcheros, a radical, sometimes violent group advocating puerto rican independence
victor gerena of hartford, the wells fargo guard authorities allege carried out the robbery, hasn't been captured. prosecutors say they think he is in cuba
pretrial hearings in the case began 14 months ago and are expected to last several more months
an eastern airlines passenger was free on bond monday after allegedly battling police and ticket agents when he and 200 irate passengers were bumped off new york-bound flights
it was the latest of several incidents in recent months that have plagued eastern in the wake of canceled flights and bumpings
the confrontation sunday began when 226 passengers were bumped from a 3:15 p.m. flight to la guardia, said eastern spokesman bob carson. some were later bumped repeatedly from other flights, and were demanding to get on the final flight of the night about 9:30 p.m
the angry passengers pushed up against the ticket counter when the flight was called, and jack lemonik, 26, of great neck, n.y, allegedly went behind the counter, said metro-dade police lt. robert otero
lemonik allegedly punched one ticket agent in the chest and pushed another with his rucksack before police moved in
three officers grabbed lemonik, otero said. one hit his leg on a trash can and fell to the ground, and was later treated for a knee injury, otero said
passengers shouted angrily at police as they struggled with lemonik, said curt arnel, 30, of merrick, n.y
lemonik was charged with two counts of simple battery, aggravated battery and resisting arrest with violence, said metro-dade police spokeswoman lizette williams. he was released on $5,500 bond monday, police said
passengers who could not be booked back to new york on sunday were put up in hotels and were to be put on flights monday, said eastern spokeswoman karen ceremsak. the pack</head>
republican presidential rivals searched monday for a way to stop george bush from a clean sweep on super tuesday, while democrats scoured the south for the votes that could propel one of them out of the tightly bunched pack on the biggest primary day in u.s. history
vice president bush said a sweep of the 17 gop primaries was ``too much for anyone to expect.'' but he was leading polls in virtually every super tuesday state except missouri, where sen. bob dole of kansas had a narrow edge
even dole conceded in oklahoma city ``it's fair to say george bush has a good margin,'' but said the race is tight in oklahoma, missouri and north carolina
earlier, the kansas senator said in birmingham, ala., ``my philosophy in the south ought to sell like hotcakes, but so far it isn't happening. bush is getting a lot of ruboff from ronald reagan.''
dole claimed polls show ``that i beat all the democrats. (bush) doesn't beat any of them .... we ought to nominate a winner instead of a loser.''
gov. michael dukakis of massachusetts, hoping to emerge from the super tuesday contests in his home state and 20 others with a delegate lead, campaigned at a retirees' condominium development in north miami beach and picked up the backing of annie ackerman, 74, a onetime chicago ward organizer now known for her prowess in turning retirees out to vote. she called him ``a person of integrity who gets things done'' and ``a mensch,'' using the yiddish word for good man
asked if super tuesday was a flop in bringing moderate and conservative democrats back to the party's fold, the governor replied, ``it's not been a flop for mike dukakis.''
four of his rivals _ jesse jackson, richard gephardt, albert gore jr. and gary hart _ were in texas monday
jackson, hoping the allegiance of black voters throughout the south will give him his finest hour in two runs for the presidency, visited an aids clinic in dallas and journeyed to brownsville, texas, where he pledged to fight efforts to make english the official language of the united states
we are a great nation. we can speak more than one language,'' said jackson
gephardt, the missouri congressman who has staked his campaign on a tough stance against countries with unfair trade practices, made a pitch in dallas for an oil import fee and campaigned in san antonio in front of a landmark
we're standing today in front of the alamo, a place where there was a fight for independence,'' gephardt said. ``this election in 1988 is a fight again for the independence of america, the fight for us to regain control of our economic destiny.''
in dallas, outside a plant that has cut its production of oil field equipment nearly in half, gephardt said, ``anyone like al gore or michael dukakis who tells you that they're for making america energy-independent without being for an oil import fee is simply trying to deceive you in a shameful way.''
something's happening out there,'' gore said, insisting the undecided vote was breaking his way. he said the democrats would have a two-man race after tuesday, and he would be one of the two
gore got a boost from sen. sam nunn of georgia, who left word after he departed on a trip to the soviet union that he had cast an absentee ballot for the tennessee senator
pat robertson raised again his claim that there are soviet missiles in cuba, telling a satellite radio audience in 18 states, ``i don't think the missiles ever got taken out in '62. and i am somewhat convinced that more missiles have been introduced.''
a federal judge in washington dismissed robertson's $35 million libel suit against former rep. pete mccloskey, who questioned his korean war record. the judge said mccloskey was the prevailing party in the acrimonious lawsuit. robertson agreed to pay court costs but not mccloskey's legal fees
super tuesday, the biggest primary day in history, saw gop voters go the primary polls in 17 states and democrats choose candidates in 20 states. there are 712 republican and 1,307 democratic delegates at stake
dukakis was hoping for a strong harvest of delegates from texas, florida and maryland, as well as massachusetts, rhode island and washington state
bush, talking with reporters on air force ii en route to columbia, mo., was asked about the possibility of a sweep. ``you always wish for that, but i certainly would never predict that. it's took much for anyone to expect,'' he replied
bush, who clobbered dole, robertson and jack kemp in south carolina's primary on saturday, admitted he was tired
it's been a difficult effort leading up to super tuesday,'' he said, adding that on tuesday itself ``we've got a pretty relaxing day _ except for the tension factor.''
pat robertson renewed his contention that there are soviet missiles in cuba on monday and also said the federal reserve board was unconstitutional
earlier, in wichita falls, texas, the republican presidential candidate said he was satisfied with a federal judge's dismissal of his libel suit against a former congressman who had questioned robertson's war record
in texas, the biggest super tuesday prize with 111 gop delegates, robertson talked about military needs and about his contentions concerning missiles
in new england, they thought it was a gaffe when i said there were missiles in cuba, but those cubans (in florida) don't believe it's a gaffe. they believe there's russian missiles in cuba,'' he said
later, in a call-in show on shreveport's kflo radio, he said, ``everybody in the miami area _ almost without exception _ certainly 95 percent of those cuban-americans know in their hearts that there are missiles in cuba. i don't think the missiles ever got taken out in '62. and i am somewhat convinced that more missiles have been introduced.''
to support his contention, he said cuban leader fidel has denied the missiles are there and has criticized robertson for saying they are
on other subjects raised on the call-in show, robertson said:
_``there has been filed, by a united states senator from montana, a suit in the federal court alleging that the federal reserve board is unconstitutional. i think it's true.''
_the supreme court needs people like (justices) antonin scalia, william rehnquist (and defeated nominee) robert bork, people like that, who honor the constitution as it was written.''
_``not one of the trading partners of america truly is dealing fairly with us. they're either restricting imports into their country on the one hand, or they are subsidizing unfairly exports from their country to us.''
_``i believe, in my heart, and from some indication from some people who i've talked to, that there are american servicemen still in laos. they aren't in vietnam, they're in laos. ... i believe we could put a throttle-hold around some of those southeast asian nations, to make them insist those missing-in-action people come out of there.''
_raising the possibility of an alternative to the united nations, ``i think if we had an alternate organization of free nations, democratic nations, who did not commit terrorism and did not torture and abuse their own citizens, we could have the power of the world. and we could exclude from that agency the soviet union, the east bloc countries and these other dictators that are practicing slavery and what have you against their people.''
in washington, a u.s. district court judge dismissed robertson's $35 million suit against former rep. paul n. mccloskey jr., who had accused robertson of ducking combat duty during the korean war
the judge gave me what i consider a real victory,'' robertson said during a news conference at wichita falls' municipal airport
however, mccloskey said, ``this is a confirmation of my integrity.'' robertson, in asking that the suit be dropped, ``is admitting that he is the one who is the liar,'' mccloskey said. ``the court's service was to unmask this man as the fraud he is.''
robertson had said he had to ask that the suit be dismissed since he couldn't pursue the presidency and go through the trial that was to start on tuesday
mikhail s. gorbachev has told factory workers not to be discouraged by slow improvements in their standard of living and to have faith in his overhaul of the economy
he visited the enormous first state ball bearing plant in moscow, his first meeting with rank-and-file workers since a sweeping law took effect jan. 1 giving factories more financial independence from central ministries
gorbachev said he was particularly sensitive to complaints about poor housing and food and said they were top priorities for improvement
the 57-year-old soviet leader visited the factory friday but media did not report on the trip until monday. why the reports were delayed was not clear
of course we have a sufficient number of problems,'' gorbachev told the workers. ``part of them are left from the past, others were born today, in the course of restructuring, in the process of realizing economic reforms. that's natural. but i have the impression that you haven't panicked, and i would say are optimistically looking to the future and confidently going forward.''
gorbachev has visited factories several times since becoming communist party general secretary three years ago, highlighting the importance he attaches to workers' roles in reviving the sluggish soviet economy
the ball bearing plant employs 20,000 factory and office workers. gorbachev said he wanted to get a first-hand look at how the government's new economic reforms are being implemented
for politics, the most important thing is to know the mood of the people, to feel the pulse of life,'' gorbachev said in remarks carried by the official news agency tass
he explained to the workers why some of his economic policies may be hard to swallow, because they mean harder work and in some cases less pay. salaries, he said, must be adjusted according to the productivity and quality of labor
how can you pay someone a full ruble if he hasn't earned it? what will he buy with this money?'' he said
he said the reason desired goods have not been available in stores is that workers were guaranteed salaries whether or not they did their jobs properly
under the new law, managers at factories responsible for 60 percent of the country's industrial output can bargain with suppliers and wholesale customers for some products. enterprises are free to keep some of their profits, but those that are unsuccessful are liable to be declared bankrupt. the factories set workers' salaries according to the quality of their work
gorbachev critcized plant managers who try to find an easy way out of improving output by buying foreign equipment
obviously you must buy some things, but only that which is absolutely necessary, and you should rely on your own domestic machine-building, on the achievements of our engineering.''
he assured the workers socialism will not be threatened by the country's growing private enterprises, known as cooperatives
it's understood that we need industrious and honest initiative, but not of the kind of some cooperatives which exploit a deficit and engage in outright money-grabbing,'' gorbachev said
limited private enterprise has been allowed to supplement state-run enterprises since may 1987. prices of the goods and services produced by cooperatives are generally much higher, but gorbachev told the workers the government plans to get its fair share of profits, through a progressive tax
routine strip searches of children awaiting deportation are unconstitutional, a federal judge ruled monday, saying immigration agents must first have a reasonable suspicion that drugs or weapons have been hidden
u.s. district judge robert kelleher rejected an immigration and naturalization service argument that the body-cavity searches are needed because adults will use children as couriers if agents cannot search them
children confined by the ins are not charged with any criminal offense, let alone an offense that might indicate a propensity to conceal weapons or contraband on their persons,'' kelleher ruled
in 1987, of 84,000 aliens searched, there were 20 discoveries of contraband or weapons, only four of which were related to juveniles, kelleher noted
his ruling came in a class-action suit filed in 1985 by a coalition of immigrants' rights groups that challenged what they described as routine strip-searches of children upon admission to ins detention facilities and following all visits with anyone other than attorneys
children are particularly susceptible to trauma from strip searches, kelleher said. he rejected an argument by assistant u.s. attorney ian fan that children from central america have no expectation of privacy when arrested here
many carry the expectation of liberty, opportunity and a better life, the embodiment of which is our constitution,'' kelleher wrote
only children are affected by the ruling. john hagar, an american civil liberties union lawyer involved in the suit, said the ruling covers all nine states in the ins' western region
