washington (ap) _ the justice department's nazi-hunting unit has identified 9,800 people as former concentration camp guards and said monday it will have them placed on the immigration watch list of individuals to be barred from the united states
the office of special investigations compiled the names with the assistance of a sophisticated new computer database
names of suspected criminals and nazi persecutors are systematically checked against immigration records to determine if they are in the united states
the names of individuals not found to be in this country are included in the watch list to prevent them from entering
osi has listed thousands of such people in the past few years. but the 9,800 now to be placed on the watch list of the u.s. immigration and naturalization service ``for serving as concentration and death camp guards is probably the greatest number'' to be added at one time, said the office's chief, neal sher
the watch list includes people who are prohibited from entering the united states under a federal law barring individuals who assisted or otherwise participated in nazi-sponsored persecution
the provision, known as the holtzman amendment, was invoked when austrian president kurt waldheim was placed on the watch list last year following a decision by attorney general edwin meese iii
the justice department cited evidence that waldheim had participated in activities amounting to persecution of jews and others in greece and yugoslavia in world war ii when he was a german army intelligence officer
the immigration watch list contains some 40,000 names. in addition to those participating in nazi-directed persecution, the list contains the names of criminals, known terrorists, communists or people who have been deported from the united states
duke austin, an ins spokesman, said names submitted by the office of special investigations are routinely added to the watch list
the reagan administration renewed its request on monday for an ``early response'' from israel to a u.s. middle east peace initiative
it also said it welcomed the ``the support and advice'' of 30 senators who contend israel should be willing to give up control of occupied land in return for middle east peace
at the state department, spokesman charles redman said the administration is looking for a reply to secretary of state george p. shultz's plan to set up negotiations on palestinian self-rule by may 1
redman's comment appeared to be directed to israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir, who is due in washington next week for meetings with president reagan and shultz
we believe all the parties understand and appreciate the reason that we've asked for these kind of responses,'' redman said
shultz just returned from a middle east trip during which he promoted a plan to bring israel, jordan, syria and palestinian arabs to a peace conference by may 1. one goal is to stop violence in the israeli-occupied gaza strip and west bank regions that has claimed some 80 arab lives in three months
shultz briefed regan on monday on his travels
on sunday, shamir blocked a decision by the israeli cabinet on the u.s. initiative. he said he would permit a vote after he returns from his talks in washington, but israeli foreign minister shimon peres had demanded a cabinet decision before shamir departed
redman avoided a direct reaction to shamir's move, but he went on to call for an ``early response'' from israel and the three arab governments _ jordan, egypt and syria _ to whom shultz submitted his plan
shultz said during his middle east travels last week that he hoped for a reply within about 10 days. he said he believed in deadlines as a way of accelerating action
at the white house, spokesman marlin fitzwater was asked about the letter from the 23 democrats and seven republicans, a group that included several strong supporters of the jewish state
the senators noted that israel has in the past supported the idea of ``land for peace'' by returning the sinai peninsula to egypt. but they cited a statement by shamir that ``this expression of territory for peace is not accepted by me.''
we hope that the prime minister's statement did not indicate that israel is abandoning a policy that offers the best hope for long-term peace,'' said the letter, dated march 3
the administration welcomes the support and advice from this group. they are senators of considerable stature and interest and involvment in middle east affairs,'' fitzwater told reporters
we are in the midst of an ongoing processs. the views of these senators are helpful to us and probably instructive to other parties in the region,'' he added
the spokesman said the administration was involved in a process ``that involves a blend of some new ideas and new beliefs,'' but he refused to comment further
at the state department, redman said shultz would respond to the letter. he declined to address the matter further, except to say the administration prefers ``to maintain a certain discreet distance'' in the mideast peace process
when he returned saturday from the middle east, shultz expressed no criticism of shamir's position. he said the prime minister and peres agreed that israel's annexation of territory could be a topic for negotiations
peres and his labor party have openly endorsed shultz's proposals, while shamir and his likud party have not
strong supporters of israel signing the letter included senators alan cranston, d-calif.; edward m. kennedy, d-mass.; daniel patrick moynihan, d-n.y.; howard m. metzenbaum, d-ohio; frank r. lautenberg, d-n.j.; carl levin, d-mich.; and rudy boschwitz, r-minn
others whose names were on the letter included senators daniel inouye, d-hawaii; lowell p. weicker jr., r-conn.; george j. mitchell, d-maine; brock adams, d-wash.; thomas a. daschle, d-s.d.; j. bennett johnston, d-la.; donald w. riegle jr., d-mich.; tom harkin, d-iowa; warren b. rudman, r-n.h.; bob kasten, r-wis.; j. james exon, d-neb.; patrick j. leahy, d-vt.; john kerry, d-mass.; mitch mcconnell, r-ky; william s. cohen, r-maine; alan k. simpson, r-wyo.; christopher j. dodd, d-conn.; dennis deconcini, d-ariz.; kent conrad, d-n.d.; john glenn, d-ohio; timothy e. wirth, d-colo.; wendell h. ford, d-ky., and bob graham, d-fla
sen. albert gore jr. said monday that two leaders would emerge from the democratic presidential field after super tuesday balloting and he would be one of them
something's happening out there,'' gore said, wrapping up his texas campaign with an airport appearance in houston, his fifth visit to the city in the past three weeks
the undecided vote is still large but it is breaking our way. we are getting reports from all over the super tuesday area and all indicate exactly the same thing. our campaign has the momentum.''
