the air force's top officer says he never dreamed the reagan administration's military build-up would be derailed so quickly, but he intends to maintain readiness even as his service shrinks
gen. larry d. welch also said monday the air force couldn't afford to develop the new midgetman nuclear missile favored by many congressional leaders; said he would press for salary bonuses for pilots and make it easier for young pilots to stay in the cockpit; and would shut down at least three air force bases if congress let him
the four-star general added the public shouldn't be too concerned by press reports of delays in flight testing the new ``stealth'' bomber, and said he intends to repair strained relations with congress with a new openness about the onset of contracting problems
welch was interviewed by the associated press on the eve of congressional hearings on the air force's fiscal 1989 budget. that budget blueprint, designed to comply with a deficit-reduction plan, cuts air force spending authority by $10 billion compared with what the service wanted and eliminates more than 23,000 active-duty job slots
the 53-year-old welch said it already was clear when he took over the air force in july 1986 that military spending was going to be slashed
but we thought at the worst, we would level (off),'' welch added. ``we never expected a real decline. we were certainly not expecting that from 1985 through 1989, there would be a 13 percent overall decline in real buying power.''
the only way to cope with such cuts, welch continued, is to reduce the size of the force. otherwise, too little money is spread too thinly to maintain combat readiness, he said
to keep a ready force, we'll have to have a somewhat smaller force,'' the general said. ``and we will be deferring some things, delaying some things.''
among the programs taking a large cut is the midgetman missile, a one-warhead nuclear missile that would be deployed on a truck-like launcher to make it more survivable. the air force would like to kill the program outright, but requested enough money to keep research going until a new administration makes a final decision
welch said he knew that congressional democrats favored the project. but the midgetman is so expensive it makes more sense to develop a mobile rail launcher for the existing 10-warhead mx missile, he said
deploying the midgetman would cost $36 billion ``and the only place we can find to take another $36 billion is out of conventional forces,'' welch said
that's too high of a pricetag ``for an incremental contribution to deterrence,'' he added
asked what would happen if congress refused money for both the midgetman or a rail-mobile mx, welch replied: ``i think that would be absolutely irresponsible.''
turning to other topics, welch said:
_air force relations with congress are strained because of a perception the service tried to cover up problems with the b-1b bomber. that is ``an absolutely false charge,'' welch said, because in truth the air force itself ``was badly surprised by the lag in the development'' of b-1b radar-jamming gear
nonetheless, ``we are (now) going to great pains to keep the congress thoroughly informed on anything that looks like a problem.''
_there's no reason for concern at this point about a delay in flight testing the radar-evading stealth, or b-2, bomber. sources have said the first flight test was pushed back four months to august because of technical problems
i think we've been very realistic about (the b-2),'' welch said. ``unlike some other programs, we didn't say five years in advance that we're going to fly that airplane on the 23rd of may. we knew better
_the air force is asking for money to pay its pilots a salary bonus because re-enlistment rates have fallen to unacceptable levels. retention rates are running about 48 percent compared with the target 60 percent, and for the first time in years, the air force expects to end fiscal 1989 with an overall shortage of pilots _ 22,312 on duty compared with 22,556 needed
_the air force also will try to keep its pilots happy by changing promotion policies to make it clear to young lieutenants and captains they should concentrate on flying, and not worry about finding staff jobs to make them more promotable
_and if he had his druthers, he would try to save money by closing unneeded bases. welch declined to identify his candidates, but said three bases could probably be closed quickly
federal testing of the nation's pork supply is being stepped up immediately as part of a crackdown on illegally high traces of a suspected cancer-causing drug used widely by hog producers, the agriculture department said monday
officials said the department's food safety and inspection service will initiate random sampling of hog carcasses in 100 of the nation's largest swine slaughter plants for laboratory tests to determine levels of sulfamethazine
usda officials on feb. 4 had announced their goal was ``to eliminate violative levels of the drug sulfamethazine'' in hogs marketed in the united states
two hog carcasses will be tested at each plant during the initial phase of the program. if one or both hogs are found to contain drug traces at or above the permitted level of 0.1 part per million, the plant will be subjected to more intensive testing
hog carcasses found to be within the drug's permitted level will be released for consumption. those with higher residues will be condemned
a new ``sulfa-on-site'' (sos) procedure for making quick screening tests in the plants without sending samples to laboratories for more detailed, time-consuming tests also is being incorporated into the program, said lester m. crawford, fsis administrator
sulfamethazine is used in swine to treat or prevent a number of diseases and also is used in subtherapeutic dosages in feed to promote faster growth and to improve weight gains. illegally high traces of the drug have been a problem in an average of about 5 percent of the hogs going to slaughter
a study by the food and drug administration's national center for toxicological research in arkansas tentatively determined that sulfamethazine causes tumors in the thyroid glands of mice, crawford said last month when the new regulatory effort was announced. lithuanian-american</head>
the state department has confirmed that the soviet union is not allowing lithuanian-american povilas peciulaitis to emigrate despite a statement last december that he would be free to leave, rep. edward feighan said monday
feighan, d-ohio, urged secretary of state george p. shultz to quickly intervene and requested a meeting with soviet ambassador yuri dubinin. he also sent a letter to soviet leader mikhail gorbachev asking that the matter be resolved quickly
they have the audacity to tell us now that it was a mistake,'' feighan said of the soviets. ``if the soviets think i'm going to stand by and meekly accept this broken promise, they had better think again.''
peciulaitis, 64, was born in lithuania, but his parents were naturalized american citizens
feighan said he fears for peciulaitis' personal safety, adding that verbal attacks against the man have recently appeared in newspapers and on television in lithuania
if the soviets can renege on a promise, we can't be sure that they won't try to harm mr. peciulaitis,'' feighan said
peciulaitis, who was exiled to siberia for 22 years, is being sponsored by his brother, who lives in suburban cleveland
a sharp cold front brought a renewal of winter weather whistling across the central rockies and the western plains on monday
a winter storm warning was posted through the night into tuesday for the mountains of southern colorado. snowfall totals of 8 to 16 inches were possible, along with gusty wind causing considerable blowing and drifting, the national weather service said
advisories for snow and blowing snow were posted into the night the southeastern colorado plains and adjacent foothills and for the san luis valley
a mixture of rain, sleet and snow extended from north dakota to western nebraska and temperatures were in the 20s and 30s
an advisory for snow and blowing snow was issued for western south dakota, where wind accompanying the snow gusted to 59 mph at the rapid city airport
strong southerly wind ahead of the cold front drove temperatures up into the 70s across much of texas, and into the 60s as far north as eastern kansas and southern missouri
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 22 degrees at laramie, wyo., to 82 at fort myers, fla. the low for the day was 3 degrees above zero at yellowstone national park in wyoming
for tuesday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from northern texas and the central gulf coast into the middle mississippi valley and the lower ohio valley, with showers in southern sections of the upper great lakes. snow was forecast in the upper mississippi valley and northern sections of the upper great lakes. widely scattered showers were forecast from northwestern texas across much of kansas and eastern colorado
highs in the 30s and 40s were predicted across a wide area from northwestern texas and western oklahoma, much of the rocky mountain region, the northern plains, the upper mississippi valley across to new england; above 60 from oregon to california and from the rio grande valley of texas to the southern and mid-atlantic coast; in the 70s from central california to southern arizona, from south-central texas to tennessee and alabama, and from west virginia to northern florida; in the 80s in southern florida and the lower rio grande valley of texas; and in the 50s elsewhere
it's too soon to consider bailing out the federal insurance fund for savings institutions or merging it with the healthier funds for commercial banks and credit unions, the nation's top regulator of s&amp;ls said monday
i think that's vastly premature,'' said m. danny wall, chairman of the federal home loan bank board
wall, speaking to the national association of federal credit unions, said the federal savings and loan insurance corp., which backs s&amp;l deposits up to $100,000, has about $20 billion to work with over the next three years
president reagan in august signed legislation recapitalizing fslic, which was technically insolvent and unable to deal with failed s&amp;ls. the legislation provides $10.8 billion over three years from the sale of bonds, to be paid off by a special assessment on profitable institutions
wall said it's too soon to determine whether that will be enough to handle the industry's problems, particularly in the southwest where s&amp;ls have been hard hit by the faltering energy industry and the consequent moribund real estate market
there's no way of knowing what the (regional) economies will be or will have been in three years. ... (a rebound) could occur in texas. it could occur in other areas of the country. it could blow all of our problems completely out of the water in a positive way,'' wall said
his comments came less than a week after two thrift industry lobby groups began discussing the future of the insurance fund
a committee of the u.s. league of savings institutions, the largest s&amp;l trade association, discussed a plan that would require billions of taxpayer dollars to bail out the ailing thrift industry
according to mark clark, a vice president of the league, the committee talked about a number of possible scenarios, including one that envisioned the issue of government notes to s&amp;ls. the notes would be traded for bad loans owned by s&amp;ls and would be guaranteed by the u.s. treasury
clark said the committee meeting was simply a ``brain-storming session'' and the plan ``is by no stretch of the imagination a proposal.''
the u.s. league discussion, as well as a proposal to merge insurance funds, are particularly controversial because the thrift industry, seeking a smaller burden on healthy s&amp;ls, argued for a smaller recapitalization of fslic
the national council of savings institutions, another trade association, is proposing, as a contingency plan, a merger of fslic with the federal deposit insurance fund, which had $18.3 billion at the end of 1987
the plan is unpopular with banks, which pay a premium for deposit insurance that is less than half the premium paid by savings institutions. a merger with the national credit union share insurance fund, which has about $1.3 billion, is equally unpopular with that industry
john t. morgan, chairman of the council, said last week that fslic likely won't have enough money to take care of all insolvent s&amp;ls. wall talked of resolving the cases of 50 insolvent s&amp;ls this year in addition to about 100 cases in texas. losses for the industry as a whole are expected to surpass $4 billion for 1987
morgan argues that there's a limit to how much more healthy s&amp;ls can contribute and that congress will not want to earmark tax money without first tapping into the other insurance funds
rep. gerald kleckza, d-wis., has introduced legislation that would merge the three insurance funds, as well as the federal agencies that regulate the three segments of the financial system. the council, however, would keep the regulatory agencies separate
wall said he saw little prospect, at least in the near term, that congress would approve a merger of the funds or of the regulatory apparatus and he argued that they were better left apart
the supreme court on monday postponed until later in the year a ruling in a multibillion-dollar battle over so-called ``gray market'' goods, the growing business that allows consumers to purchase costly imports at steep discounts
the justices announced they again will hear arguments in the case in april with a decision expected by july
the case will be re-argued with justice anthony m. kennedy, who joined the court last month, taking part in the deliberations. kennedy's participation in the case will give the court six members, a quorum, to consider the underlying dispute
kennedy did not take part as the court ruled, 5-3, on monday that the court of international trade does not have exclusive authority over the dispute. the majority said that a federal judge properly considered the case
the three justices who dissented did so on a procedural issue. they said the federal courts lacked jurisdiction, a decision that would in effect disqualify them from considering the merits of the case
the dispute is over interpretation of the federal tariff act of 1930. the u.s. customs service says the law allows gray market goods into the country without approval from trademark owners
two leading discount distributors, k mart corp. and 47th street photo inc. of new york city, also are defending the customs service regulations
typically, the discount companies buy trademarked products in the united states more cheaply than do the owners of the u.s. trademarks
some 60 major companies that own trademarks banded together to form the coalition to preserve the integrity of american trademarks and challenge the customs service regulations
a federal judge upheld the customs service regulations. but the u.s. circuit court of appeals here ruled last year that the rules are invalid under the 1930 tariff act
the statute prohibits unauthorized imports of ``any merchandise of foreign manufacture if such merchandise ... bears a trademark owned by a citizen of, or by a corporation or association created or organized within, the united states.''
the customs service says the law protects only american companies that purchase trademarks from independent foreign manufacturers and does not protect american subsidiaries, affiliates or parent companies of foreign manufacturers
justice william j. brennan wrote monday's opinion upholding the authority of the federal courts to rule in the dispute. he was joined by justices byron r. white, thurgood marshall, harry a. blackmun and john paul stevens
dissenting on the jurisdictional issue were chief justice william h. rehnquist and justices antonin scalia and sandra day o'connor
a television expose showing city workers goofing off has added fuel to a campaign to recall mayor federico pena, the mayor's opponents said monday
a top public works official and two street workers lost their jobs and pena suspended four others following the kusa-tv report last week about city street crews
the mayor, who announced the action over the weekend, said he will continue his investigation of the allegations and within the next week expects to discipline several mid-level supervisors in the public works department, the city's largest agency with 1,770 employees
meanwhile, marge doty, chairwoman of the metropolitan action committee, which is pushing the pena recall, said the revelations have ``added impetus to our movement, absolutely.''
the campaign has half the petition signatures needed to force an election to replace pena, who was re-elected to a second three-year term last year. ms. doty said she has not counted how many signatures have been gathered on the 1,200 petitions being circulated
a kusa reporter and cameraman, using an unmarked car, followed six city street crews around for several days to see what they accomplished. only two crews were shown working without excessive breaks. in one case, a pothole repair crew did no work at all during an eight-hour period, spending the time visiting several food stores and loafing near parks
lee ramirez, deputy manager of the public works department, resigned following the reports, and pena then fired two workers and suspended four others
pena told a news conference that ramirez was ``a hard-working and dedicated employee'' who had ``the fortitude ... to tender his resignation in the best interest of the city. and i agree with that conclusion.''
steve newman, executive director of the colorado chapter of the american federation of state, county and municipal employees, said two of the disciplined public works employees are innocent and their punishments would be appealed
he also blamed the department's problems, which include a $1 million budget deficit, on poor management, nepotism, cronyism and missing equipment
i will be meeting with the mayor this week, probably on thursday, and i will have a long list of documented problems and incidents we've brought to their attention,'' he said. ``hopefully, this time he'll deal with it.''
the movement to recall pena began after citizens complained of unplowed, impassable streets following a christmas weekend snowstorm
the metropolitan action committee has until mid-april to collect 40,000 petition signatures
gov. roy romer and three other democratic leaders on saturday announced their opposition to the recall drive
properly filling potholes'' is an issue worth debating, but not serious enough to merit a recall election, the governor said
sen. tim wirth, d-colo., said pena ``is the person who has finally broken loose the airport and has made the convention center come closer to being a reality. those are the issues it seems to me that we ought to be talking about.''
denver is close to reaching agreement to build a new, $4 billion airport in neighboring adams county to replace stapleton international airport, and it will begin construction soon on a $115 million convention center
the opening talks on a new long-term grain agreement between the united states and the soviet union will get under way here on march 19 instead of in vienna, austria, on march 11 as previously announced, a senior trade official said monday
deputy u.s. trade representative alan f. holmer said in a one-paragraph statement issued by the agriculture department that the change was ``due to scheduling conflicts'' but did not elaborate
the current five-year pact will expire on sept. 30. it calls for annual purchases of grain from the united states
officials announced on march 4 that the negotiations on a new agreement would begin march 11 in vienna
fifty-two members of the senate are urging south african president p.w. botha to release a prominent south african journalist jailed without charges for the last 14 months
in a letter made public monday, the senators asked botha to work for the immediate release of zwalakhe sisulu, 38, an award-winning journalist and editor of the the new nation, a newspaper sponsored by the catholic church. sisulu was a nieman fellow at harvard university during the 1984-85 academic year
the letter was made public by sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., who hailed sisulu as ``the best that journalism has to offer'' and a reporter and editor who is ``passionate in his commitment to non-violence and to building a truly non-racial society in south africa.''
his arrest and incarceration were unconscionable,'' kennedy said. ``his continued detention _ without bail, without charges and without trial _ is indefensible.''
the letter said that sisulu's imprisonment ``strengthens the cause of those who pursue a racial agenda and who seek a violent solution to south africa's problems.''
the government monday presented 25 photogravures seized from a now-imprisoned drug dealer to the national museum of american art
the work by photographer edward sheriff curtis, part of the artist's 20-volume work on north american indians, was turned over to museum director charles c. eldredge by attorney general edwin meese iii
the photographs printed from specially etched plates in a process yielding great sensitivity of tone were among the items confiscated from ronald francis perry of san francisco under a federal law allowing the federal government to seize the assets of drug traffickers
the photogravures were forfeited to the government after san francisco police investigating perry discovered two pounds of cocaine, a $30,000 art collection and $14,500 hidden in a secret panel in a closet and took the case to the drug enforcement administration
perry pleaded guilty to drug and tax charges in 1987 and is serving a sentence in federal prison in allenwood, pa
the government is selling perry's home and the remainder of his property, which includes 75 cases of fine wine, eight rare persian carpets, several handguns, a porsche and a mercedes. said they...</note>
communist guerrillas ambushed a vehicle near subic bay, killing three civilians and six filipino sailors assigned to the u.s.-run naval base, the military said monday
the sailors, and three civilians who had hitched a ride, were traveling from subic to manila on sunday when rebels of the new people's army fired on their land-rover near hermosa, on the bataan peninsula 40 miles west of the capital, the philippine constabulary reported
there were no reports of rebel casualties in the 15-minute battle
subic, about 50 miles west of manila, is one of six military facilities operated by the united states under an executive agreement that expires in 1991
communist rebels operate near both subic bay and clark air base, 50 miles north of manila. last october, guerrillas killed three americans and a filipino in coordinated attacks outside clark
in a related development monday, two philippine constabulary troopers held hostage by communist rebels for more than a month said they killed nine guerrillas in an escape the day before
noel de leon and roberto nabua said they were captured feb. 3 at a rebel checkpoint outside san francisco, a town near catanauan, 110 miles southeast of manila in quezon province. they spoke to filipino reporters in catanauan
they said they were tied up for 32 days and were moved from place to place. de leon and nabua also said a foreigner they did not identify took videotape pictures of them
on sunday, the two said, they loosened their bindings and grabbed the m-16 rifles of their two guards, who were cooking a meal in a house at buenavista, about 10 miles north of catanauan. they said they killed both guards and seven other rebels
in another report monday, officials said one of the best-known rebel priests had fled southern mindanao island after being shot by comrades who learned he was planning to surrender
romeo capangpangan, spokesman in cebu city for the social welfare department, said the rev. frank navarro was reported shot in the shoulder last week by his own followers in mindanao's surigao del sur province
he said navarro had sent word that he was recuperating at a hideout in the area and wanted to surrender in return for amnesty. cebu city is 360 miles southeast of manila
the government amnesty program for communist and moslem rebels expired feb. 29, but defense secretary fidel ramos said rebels still could receive amnesty on a case-by-case basis
according to the military, navarro is a new people's army leader in eastern mindanao. the army issued two reports last year that he had been killed. from iraq. no pickup.</note>
iraq and iran fired missiles into each other's largest cities monday and sent aircraft to bomb towns in the second week of a long-range duel that has killed hundreds of civilians
the official iraqi news agency said iraq fired three missiles into tehran, a city of 6 million
iran's islamic republic news agency said revolutionary guards fired five missiles at ``military centers'' in baghdad in retaliation for ``these inhuman acts,'' and hit the northern city of mosul with a missile for the first time
both sides reported their border towns pounded by sustained artillery fire and air raids that killed scores of people
it was the eighth day of missile exchanges between the persian gulf neighbors, which have been at war since september 1980
iraq confirmed that two missiles fell on residential sections of baghdad, whose population is 5 million, killing or wounding ``many civilians, including women and children.''
it said a missile hit a residential district of mosul, killing or wounding civilians and damaging several houses, shops and cars. mosul also was reported bombed
irna, the iranian agency, said 30 civilians were killed and more than 100 wounded in tehran, most of them women and children. it said one missile demolished a clinic, a school and several homes
iraq says it has fired 41 missiles into the iranian capital since the exchanges began feb. 29. the iranians have reported firing 23 missiles on baghdad in that period, but the have acknowledged only 18 hits
in baghdad, labor minister baker mahmoud rasoul said iran began the latest round in the ``war of the cities to pave the way for its new (ground) offensive.''
vice president taha muhieddin maarouf, also addressing the gathering of arab labor ministers, said ``our armed forces are fully ready to rout any iranian offensive.''
they apparently referred to threats saturday by hashemi rafsanjani, speaker of the iranian parliament, to answer the iraqi missile barrage with action along the 730-mile border war front
asian diplomats in baghdad said khalid mahmoud, an emissary of pakistan's foreign ministry, delivered a letter from president mohammad zia ul-haq for president saddam hussein of iraq as part of a diplomatic effort to stop the aerial war. its contents were not disclosed
the missile exchange is the fiercest of the war. it is the first time surface-to-surface missiles have hit tehran, which is 290 miles from the iraqi border. iran periodically has launched missiles at baghdad, which is only 80 miles from the frontier
iran has reported at least 122 civilians killed and more than 300 wounded by missiles, and more than 100 killed and 500 wounded in air raids during the past week. iraq has reported heavy civilian casualties, but not exact figures
on monday, iran's news agency said 61 civilians were killed and 427 wounded by iraqi air raids on shiraz in the south and dezful, khorramabad, arak and a dozen other cities in the west
iraq said its planes attacked the cities of hamadan, arak and kermanshah in western iran
tehran radio confirmed a raid on arak, but there was no immediate word on casualties or damage. it said iranian warplanes raided basra, the southern iraqi port near the border, and as-sadiq and mosul in the southwest
according to the iraqi news agency, ``many civilians'' were killed or wounded in the raids
the iranians said their artillery hammered military and economic targets in amarah, qurna and aziz, north of basra, through the night and morning. they said iraqi gunners shelled marivan in northwest iran, killing one person and wounding several
rep. jack kemp said monday he would press on with his republican presidential campaign regardless of the outcome of the super tuesday contests
kemp told a news conference at the state capitol that his disappointing showing in the race so far had not caused him to consider dropping out
i'm running for ideas, for a cause, to keep the reagan revolution alive,'' he said
he said he did not know how he would do on super tuesday, but thought the race would remain open. and he said he planned to press his campaign in next week's illinois primary
kemp said he saw himself as ``a bridge candidate,'' whom followers of vice president george bush, kansas sen. bob dole and former television evangelist pat robertson all could turn to if the race is not wrapped up by the time of the republican national convention
i think ultimately that the republican party is going to want a conservative to follow ronald reagan,'' he said
he repeated his assertion that he is not interested in the vice presidential nomination
i don't expect it. i don't think it will be offered. i don't want it. and besides, i'm a quarterback and not a lineman,'' said the former professional football player
kemp conceded that the oil and agriculture industries had not shared fully in the economic successes of the reagan administration. but he said he did not favor an oil import fee, calling that ``a quick fix.'' he said lower interest rates would help the energy industry more in the long run
he also advocated repealing the windfall profits tax and called for further deregulation of natural gas
in a speech to the oklahoma legislature prior to the news conference, kemp drew applause when he denounced panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega and called for continued support of the contras in nicaragua
he said it would be ``a big mistake'' for the united states to accept a communist base in nicaragua. he said that would pose a threat to the panama canal and nicaragua's neighbors and ``ultimately to mexico.''
a court convicted 16 people in belgium's biggest child sex case monday, including the former head of the u.n. children's fund for belgium
they were given prison terms of up to 10 years, but some lesser terms were suspended. two defendants were acquitted
most were arrested soon after the case came to light early last year and spent several months in jail before the trial. the trial revealed the existence of belgian and international child sex rings
several adults who lent their children to adults for sex were among the defendants. the husband of one of the two mothers acquitted is to be tried later
jean-claude weber, a 40-year-old film producer now jailed in france on similar charges, got the longest sentence, 10 years
philippe carpentier, 46, got nine years. he heads an association whose public purpose was to help pedophiles overcome their compulsion but actually supplied them with children
michel felu, 47, a member of the unicef belgian staff who used the children's fund offices and equipment to make pornographic pictures for use in special international magazines, was sentenced to eight years
jozef verbeeck, 63, former head of unicef-belgium, was given a two-year suspended sentence. one mother got three years suspended and another a 30-month suspended sentence
unicef was awarded symbolic damages of one franc for the harm it suffered. ...'' to update with comment on shultz talks with wu.</note>
secretary of state george p. shultz met monday with chinese foreign minister wu xueqian and said the united states is prepared to increase high technology exports to china
during toasts following their state department luncheon, the two leaders hailed the progress in bilateral relations and made almost no reference to issues which divide them
chief among them is china's reported sales of military weaponry to iran in defiance of u.s. efforts at the united nations to win support for a worldwide arms embargo against iran. the administration has been seeking assurances from china that it will not veto an embargo resolution
the reagan administration has generally refrained from public condemnations of the chinese sales, and shultz on monday alluded only to press reports in both countries of u.s.-chinese ``differences'' on the persian gulf war
administration officials have indicated a willingness to increase high technology exports to china in exchange for a chinese commitment to halt delivery of weapons to iran
although shultz made no direct link between the two issues, he indicated u.s. interest in increasing sales of sophisticated technology to china
over the last five years, the united states has significantly liberalized its controls over technology exports to china, and we are prepared to do more to ensure u.s. exporters remain competitive in the china market,'' he said
last october, the united states retaliated against china for selling silkworm anti-ship missiles to iran by suspending the process under which china had been given increasing access to u.s. products with advanced technology
since then, china has said it has stopped selling silkworms to iran. a u.s. official, speaking friday on condition of anonymity, said ``our information is that they've been living up to that.''
still, before resuming liberalization of the high technology trade, ``we want to be sure we're in sync with the chinese on what we're talking about.'' the official said. ``we believe the chinese position has been responsive to our concerns, but we want to be sure that this responsiveness will continue.''
although no details of their private talks were disclosed, shultz also was expected to discuss with wu the u.s. proposal for direct arab-israeli peace talks
u.s. officials, who asked not to be identified, said shultz's talks with wu were cordial and covered a range of international issues
they said discussions later in the week will focus on human rights and the persian gulf situation
shultz is trying to structure a peace conference in which the united states, the soviet union, china, britain and france would serve as sponsors _ but without the power to impose the terms of a settlement
shultz made no reference in his remarks to recent anti-chinese rioting in tibet. state department spokesman charles redman said between three and nine people are believed to have been killed, and he expressed deep concern over the human rights situation in tibet
he also reiterated the u.s. view that tibet is an integral part of china
shultz, discussing shared interests of the two countries, said both have opposed the soviet occupation of afghanistan and the vietnamese military intervention in cambodia
the united states is convinced that a secure china is in the interest not only of china but of the u.s. and the states of the east asian region,'' shultz said
wu, in turn, said there is great potential for continued development of u.s.-chinese relations, ``yet there are also obstacles and difficulties
therefore, our two sides have no reason to rest content with the present status,'' he said
wu also met with defense secretary frank c. carlucci on monday. he will meet with president reagan on tuesday
the soviet union on monday sought an urgent security council meeting to demand an end to the iran-iraq ``war of the cities,'' and the united states insisted anew on an arms embargo against iran
soviet ambassador alexander m. belonogov told reporters he expected a meeting of the 15-member council by wednesday. he said the soviets will introduce a resolution demanding an end to the devastating missile bombardment of both capitals
moscow, however, has been reluctant to push for a punitive arms embargo against iran for delay in complying with a cease-fire as demanded by the council last july 20. the soviets have been improving relations with tehran
belonogov said his government favors more time for diplomacy before imposing a weapons ban against iran or iraq
in washington, state department spokesman charles redman on monday urged the council to act quickly on an arms embargo resolution
iran meanwhile demanded that the council condemn iraq for starting the deadly war of the cities now in its second week
both sides claim the strikes on tehran and baghdad are defensive and retaliatory. both are believed to be using soviet-made missiles in the missile attacks, the most intense in the 7{-year-old war
as the council met behind closed doors to discuss the missile strikes, iran's attempt to stave off an embargo with an ambiguous note to the council appeared to have failed
the ``undated, unsigned scrap of paper'' does not ``constitute a clear acceptance'' of security council resolution 598, british ambassador sir crispin tickell said monday. ``if they accept, they should say so _ loudly, clearly and unequivocally.''
redman said the united states sees nothing new in the ``non-paper'' and ``very much doubts that anyone else does either.''
he told reporters that in pursuing the arms embargo, ``we are continuing active consultations with other council members to achieve consensus on this resolution, which we are convinced would help bring the gulf war to an end.'' the unsigned note handed by iran's u.n. envoy to the security council president last week claims a feb. 28 letter from iranian foreign minister ali albar velayati constituted acceptance of the council's cease-fire resolution
the letter, however, did not say iran endorsed the resolution
we also note that several iranian spokesmen have issued statements over the past few days disavowing the non-paper released in new york,'' redman noted
the agreement of all five permanent council members _ the united states, the soviet union, china, britain and france _ is needed to pass an arms embargo resolution. each has a veto. washington has said the stumbling block is the soviet union
redman said secretary of state george shultz would probably raise the issue in talks with foreign minister wu xueqian of china this week
the soviets are close allies of iraq but have also been trying to improve relations with neighboring iran
crowds in tehran, angered at being the target of soviet-made missiles, tried to storm the soviet embassy over the weekend. belonogov denied that ``the defensive weapons now used against tehran and other cities'' are soviet-made
he also urged iran and iraq to stop the attacks and described the escalation in the war of the cities as a major development in the gulf conflict
we consider this as just not another espisode in the war ... we think that the war between cities adds some new dimension to the protracted military conflict between the two neighboring countries,'' he said
belonogov said he met monday with secretary-general javier perez de cuellar and with the president of the security council this month, yugoslav ambassador dragoslav pejic, and urged them ``in the most energetic terms'' to try to persuade iran and iraq to stop the missile attacks
the position of my country is clear. we are for the soonest possible political resolution of the war conflict between iran and iraq and for the speediest possible implementation of the security council resolution 598.'' and last name of sen. mikulski in 11th graf.</note>
a group of u.s. representatives sent a scathing letter to president p.w. botha to express ``outrage and dismay'' over the slaying of a black activist
seven u.s. senators signed a similar letter to piet koornhof, south africa's ambassador to the united states, that also protested the jan. 24 slaying of godfry sicelo dhlomo, 18
dhlomo, an anti-apartheid activist, was killed four days after police questioned him about his appearance in foreign television documentaries, including a cbs documentary, ``children of apartheid.''
we the undersigned members of the u.s. congress are writing to express our outrage and dismay at the assassination of godfrey sicelo dhlomo,'' said the letter, signed by 31 house members and obtained by the associated press on monday
he is one of more than two dozen anti-apartheid activists killed in mysterious circumstances since 1980,'' it said. ``none of these killings have been solved by the police, lending allegations of official involvement greater credibility
physical evidence attests to the fact that mr. dhlomo was beaten and tortured, and it is common knowledge that intimidation and threats are everyday tools of the south african security police
a south africa in flames will be the inevitable result of your government's failure to reform security police tactics and work toward a democratic society. we strongly urge a prompt and thorough investigation into mr. dhlomo's death and other apartheid-related crimes.''
some of the house members who signed the feb. 11 letter will participate in hearings on south africa beginning march 15. the letter to botha was initiated by cardiss collins, d-ill
police arrested dhlomo during a raid on the johannesburg offices of a civil rights organization on jan. 20 and questioned him about his statements in several foreign news films
after his body was found near his parents' home in soweto, several anti-apartheid groups said they suspected police involvement. the police have denied involvement and have offered a $2,500 reward for the arrest of the killer or killers
the letter signed by the senate members, written by sen. barbara a. mikulski, d-md., said: ``we have a very strong interest in sicelo and require your government to allow an independent body to investigate the circumstances under which he was murdered.''
the house letter addressed botha as prime minister, a post he has not held since 1984 when he became president under a new constitution
britain began a 25-day military exercise monday to test its ability to protect the falkland islands from invasion, the defense ministry reported. argentina said its forces would be on ``defensive alert.''
at this stage, it's very much a paper exercise,'' a ministry spokesman said. ``the exercise will start with intelligence reports that an enemy is raising the threat level. they will play out a scenario.''
an infantry batallion of 600-1,000 soldiers based in britain will fly to the south atlantic archipelago march 17-18, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity
argentina claims the islands off its coast, which it calls the malvinas, and invaded them in april 1982. britain sent a naval task force and won a 74-day war that killed 712 argentines and 258 britons
britain says the exercise, called fire focus, is purely defensive. one of its functions will be to test a new $690 million airport built since the war
ian stewart, the armed forces minister, said criticism of the exercise from argentina and other latin american nations resulted from misunderstanding of its size
i do not see how something which is purely a defensive exercise can be seen as provocative,'' he said
we have to defend the falklands. we had a very unfortunate experience six years ago. we not only have a right to have a defensive garrison in the falklands, we have a responsibility to do so.''
the exercise, scheduled to end march 31, is the largest since the war and the first with reinforcements flown from britain. military units could not be airlifted in 1982 because the airport was inadequate, and the naval force took weeks to reach the islands
argentina says the islands are part of its inheritance from spanish colonial rule and claims britain stole them in 1833
britain has refused to discuss sovereignty, declaring that the 1,900 falkland islanders prefer to remain british, but stewart said: ``in other respects we would like to have more normal relations with argentina.''
navy chief jose toribio merino said monday the nation's military commanders will select in june or july the candidate for a yes-or-no presidential vote later this year
it was the first time a time frame has been set for the nomination of the presidential candidate. no date has been set for the election
president augusto pinochet, the general who has ruled chile since the 1973 coup that ousted the elected government of marxist president salvador allende, has given every indication he will seek the nomination
as the powerful army commander, the 72-year-old pinochet will be among the four military chieftains selecting the candidate for an eight-year term
merino spoke with reporters after a meeting of the law-making, four-member junta that he heads
he said the presidential election ``has to take place during the second half'' of this year
according to the 1980 constitution drafted by the armed forces, chile's president for the 1989-97 term will be chosen in a yes-or-no plebiscite on a single candidate
the candidate will be named by the commanders of the army, navy, air force and national police
if the military-picked candidate is rejected by the voters, an open presidential election must be called in 1990 with pinochet remaining in power until then, according to the constitution. gephardt likely to be biggest loser</note>
democrats richard gephardt and albert gore jr. are in a battle of their own in tuesday's southern primaries, competing for the same voters and harboring hopes of knocking each other out of the presidential race
with jesse jackson poised to collect the south's considerable black vote, and michael dukakis scoring with southern liberals, gephardt and gore are both vying for what's left: the moderate and conservative, blue-collar and middle-income white voters
acknowledging dukakis may do very well tuesday, each would like to emerge as the white alternative to the massachusetts governor. and each would like to move on to the next round of contests without the other, trying to draw a bead on dukakis
both gore and gephardt have scaled back southern expectations as their initial strategies have not been fulfilled
gephardt concentrated on the early iowa contest, hoping it would propel him. but his victory there hasn't provided momentum in the south. gore played on regional appeal, but that hasn't been enough in a field fractured by so many candidates
the result: each needs to beat the other to continue
there are two gs in this race and only one g is going north,'' said one source close to gore's campaign, insisting on anonymity
gephardt's tough foreign trade-retaliation message and the powerful television commercials that helped him in south dakota and iowa have been overwhelmed by the enormity of campaigning in the 20 states of super tuesday
he has spent about $1.2 million on television _ and has been outspent three-to-one by both gore and dukakis
gore has been pummeling gephardt in tough negative television commercials that the gephardt campaign acknowledges has been effective against their candidate. gore has branded gephardt a ``phony flip-flopper.''
dukakis also has slammed gephardt with television ads that depict him as a flip-flopper on issues
we have been pinned down in a very tough negative crossfire between dukakis and gore,'' said gephardt polltaker ed reilly. ``they have gone to any areas we have strengths, especially gore, and just beat the ... out of us. that's effective ... but i think the net effect is going to be to drive (voter) turnout down, very very low.''
gore has run ads attacking dukakis and jackson, too, but the main focus of the television attack has been on gephardt
ideally for the gore campaign, we would like to _ and we expect to _ narrow the field by eliminating dick gephardt, thereby creating a situation where senator gore can focus clearly on michael dukakis and jesse jackson,'' said gore spokesman arlie schardt
an abc news poll of the south released monday night said that ``the biggest loser on super tuesday will probably be richard gephardt, who is leading only in his home state of missouri and could drop below the 15 percent threshold for delegates'' in 12 of 16 states polled
both gore and gephardt are focusing on the delegate count coming out of super tuesday rather than the number of states won. neither predicts an outright win in the biggest states of florida and texas, but they hope to collect a big share of delegates there
gore forces believe if they can push gephardt into a fourth-place finish in delegates, and hold him to winning little more than his home state of missouri, he will be staggered and unable to continue. gephardt forces scoff at that notion
they're not going to knock us out,'' said reilly. ``no way ... it's absurd.''
but both gephardt and gore face the prospect of leaving the south impoverished and facing, in dukakis if he wins florida and texas, a candidate who has demonstrated national appeal
gore took out a $1 million line of credit to saturate southern television. gephardt faced a financial squeeze going into the south that limited his ability to run the ads that proved effective elsewhere, including his vow that unless south korea opened its markets he'd put so many taxes on their products a hyundai automobile would cost $48,000
noting that ad, dukakis spokesman leslie dach said: ``the hyundai may very well run out of gas on tuesday night.'' protest at capitol and corrects spelling of student leader jerry covell</note>
gallaudet university students vowed monday to keep their campus closed indefinitely after the school's board of trustees reaffirmed its selection of a hearing presdent to head the nation's only liberal arts university for the deaf
we're going to keep the school closed,'' said student leader jerry covell. ``we will stop when we get a deaf president.''
covell and around 1,800 of the school's 2,200 students protested at the capitol after board of trustees chairman jane basset spilman told the students the board would not reconsider its decision to hire elizabeth ann zinser as gallaudet's next president
the selection of zinser, an administrator at the university of north carolina at greensboro, was the product of a ``careful, reasoned'' search process, spilman said
a lawful, proper and final decision was made,'' she said
as spilman made her announcement in the school's field house, students listening there spilled out into the street and began a one-mile walk to the capitol
spilman and several other board members listened for about 30 minutes to complaints from the 100 or so students, then left without speaking to reporters
gallaudet, the nation's only liberal arts college for the deaf, was created by an act of congress in 1864, and relies on federal funding for most of its operating budget. in fiscal year 1988, gallaudet received $62 million from congress
we're trying to put some pressure on congress, to get them to put some pressure on our board,'' said covell, a 23-year-old frederick, md., resident. ``after this, we'll march to the white house.''
monday's protest capped a week of demonstrations in which students tried to convince the board of trustees to hire a deaf person as the school's seventh president
after spilman announced sunday that zinser had won out over two deaf finalists, students walked to the hotel where the board was meeting, then continued their protest at the capitol. monday, students gathered before dawn and blocked all entrances to the campus, forcing officials to cancel classes for the day
a committee of 10 students, two faculty members and two staff members told the trustees that they wanted zinser replaced with a deaf president, the resignation of spilman, and assurances that deaf people would constitute a majority of the school's 20-member board within three years
the student group and the trustees met for around three hours on the northeast washington campus before spilman announced that the decision made the day before would stand
i do not think i will ever experience a more frustrating feeling in my life,'' said frank r. turk, the school's dean of student life, who is deaf. ``i have been on the gallaudet payroll for 35 years, and i have never felt so defeated.''
spilman said zinser was selected because she is a ``top caliber academician'' who also has the administrative and fund-raising skills the school was looking for
deaf students claim that only a deaf person can truly understand their educational needs
zinser said she understood the students' frustration
i feel considerable empathy and compassion for the students,'' zinser said by telephone from her greensboro office. ``i hope to speak with them soon, but given the intensity of this situation, it's only right for me to maintain some distance.''
students had expressed outrage that zinser does not speak sign language, but the incoming president vowed to accelerate immediately her study of the language
i have a facility for learning it, and now that i have been hired, i plan to have an intensive training program.''
spilman said that zinser was selected bu a 10-4 margin, with the three deaf members and one hearing member of the trustees' selection committee voting for one of the two deaf candidates
philip w. bravin, a deaf trustee who headed the search committee, said he and the committee's other deaf members lobbied to no avail for a deaf president
your expressions outline exactly what we put on the table,'' bravin, an ibm executive, told the students who remained on campus after spilman's announcement. ``we did the best we could do.''
bravin asserted that the two other finalists for the post _ i. king jordan, gallaudet's dean of the college of arts and sciences, and harvey j. corson, superintendent of the louisiana school for the deaf, in baton rouge, la. _ both were qualified to be gallaudet's next president
no candidate has the perfect criteria, and they both were qualified. i think the committee's decision speaks for itself.''
jury selection began monday in a trial of a taiwanese gangster accused of killing a chinese-american journalist openly critical of the taiwanese government
tung kuei-sen has pleaded innocent in the 1984 shooting of henry liu at the writer's daly city home
the plea puzzled his attorney, since the 35-year-old tung testified two years ago in a new york drug trial that he and a fellow member of taiwan's largest criminal syndicate, the united bamboo gang, gunned down liu on government orders relayed by gang chief chen chi-li
i suspect he just wants to tell the jury and everyone else his story,'' said defense attorney douglas gray. ``he thought he was doing his government's bidding ... and he was left twisting slowly, slowly in the wind.''
prosecutor robert bishop said he expects the trial before san mateo county superior court judge margaret kemp to last two weeks and he will call up to 18 witnesses. gray said he was unsure how he would present his case
tung faces one count of murder and one special allegation that he used a gun in the oct. 15, 1984, slaying. if convicted, he could face 27 years to life in prison
tung was convicted of heroin smuggling after a federal trial in new york in 1986 and was sentenced to 20 years in prison
liu, a long-term critic of the taiwanese government, was a columnist for a chinese-language newspaper in san francisco and had just published a book that attacked the island nation's ruling party when he was killed
the u.s. congress and the state department condemned liu's murder and house hearings were held to look into the murky circumstances surrounding it
chen has blamed the killing on taiwan's former chief of military intelligence, vice admiral wang shi-ling, who said he only directed that liu be taught ``a lesson.''
both chen and wang are serving life sentences in taiwan after being convicted in the killing in a taiwanese military court. two intelligence officials who served under wang are serving lesser terms
wu tun, 35, the second gunman, is serving a life term for the killing in a taiwan prison
a 300-pound bear that mauled a 2-year-old boy in a shopping mall was under quarantine monday, as federal investigators began a probe into the animal's keepers, authorities said
kevin e. kuhn of galion was listed in fair condition at children's hospital with deep cuts to his scalp and face that required more than 100 stitches, officials said
he was attacked saturday while posing with the himalayan bear, named fluffy, after a children's performance at a shopping mall in mansfield, about 60 miles north of columbus
the bear was held at an undisclosed location, said joe evans, director of environmental health services for the richland county health department. the bear's owners had not sought return of the animal, and evans indicated the county would resist any efforts to return the bear
we will fight that, if necessary,'' he said. ``we have had some contact with the owners and indicated our intent ... to take over custody of the animal until we can find a more permanent disposition.''
the county might seek to destroy the animal, but that has not been determined, he said
u.s. department of agriculture investigators arrived in mansfield on monday to look into the attack, police capt. john arcudi said. owners of exotic animals must register with the agriculture department
at this time, i don't know what criminal charges could be filed,'' arcudi said. ``it's more civil than criminal.''
fluffy is one of four bears featured in the ``goldilocks and her bears'' shopping-center attraction. a bear named fluffy in the same troupe clawed a jacksonville, fla., 4-year-old during a show last month, police said
that child required at least six stiches, police said, and the bear was quarantined five days before being released to its owner, walter naghtin sr., 54, of tampa, fla
it was unclear whether the same bear was involved in both attacks, authorities said
in the jacksonville case, naghtin and his son, walter naghtin jr., were charged for allowing wild animals to perform without a permit, police said. they pleaded guilty and were fined and sentenced to six months' probation
permits were obtained for the mansfield performance, police said
efforts to reach the naghtins monday were unsuccessful. ruth naghtin of northbrook, ill., who identified herself as the mother of the elder naghtin, said she did not know where they were. convictions</head> earlier movie.</note>
the man whose attempted murder conviction led to the book and television movie ``deadly intentions'' was sentenced to 15 years in prison monday on federal marijuana and weapons charges
the sentence was handed down after a prosecutor alleged that the defendant, former doctor patrick henry, planned to use blood serum containing the aids virus in a revenge scheme and planned to kill a former federal prosecutor
u.s. district judge emmett cox imposed the sentence and ordered henry sent to a prison where he could receive psychiatric treatment
in an appeal for mercy, henry, 40, said he ``got discouraged'' in prison after his 1979 conviction and ``picked up some bad attitudes.'' while in prison, henry wrote ``the outlaw's bible,'' under the pen name e.x. boozhie. prosecutors said the book instructs readers on how to avoid arrest
henry served 6{ years of a 15-year sentence in an arizona prison for the attempted murder of his first wife, christine. he moved to mobile in an attempt to regain his medical license
judge, i don't know if you believe a man can change,'' henry said. ``i'm going to do my best.''
his current wife, nancy, turned to authorities when she discovered an ammunition box concealed in their home that contained an assortment of materials, including manuals on explosives and false identities
henry was convicted jan. 21 of possessing a pistol after being convicted of a felony, and scheming to distribute marijuana to prisoners in arizona where he had served time
u.s. attorney jeff sessions told the judge monday that henry planned to use the pistol and a bomb to ``blow up the u.s. attorney's office'' in tucson. neither the pistol nor the bomb were introduced as evidence in the trial
sessions said the ammunition box also contained two vials of blood serum containing the aids virus. he said the virus was confirmed by testing at the department of defense laboratory in washington
fbi spokesman gene eason said authorities could only surmise how henry planned to use the aids virus. he said the serum apparently was collected while henry worked at a mobile doctor's office while attempting to recover his professional license as a dermatologist
my view is simply this, the evidence indicates very strongly this defendant would like to pose a danger to the witnesses in this trial and the trial 10 years ago,'' sessions said
defense attorney jim byrd told the judge the government had pursued henry because of a ``spiteful, neurotic suicidal wife'' who lied during his trial
pat's life has been dissected by the fbi and agents of the u.s. government,'' byrd said. he said henry had a constitutional right to possess books on bombs, marijuana growing, scorpions, and identity manuals
there was never any threat of blowing up the u.s. attorney's office or any other target,'' byrd said. ``pat is an electronics hobbyist. none of these materials pertained to a detonating device.''
byrd said sessions' version of the case was ``fantasies of a suspicious mind.''
sessions argued that henry planned to return to arizona and kill former u.s. attorney randy stevens, who co-wrote the book ``deadly intentions.''
the movie starred michael biehn as a promising young physician who terrorized his wife after his violent, schizophrenic personality emerged. he was arrested for plotting to kill his wife after she divorced him
a photograph of stevens also was in henry's ammo box, sessions said
an army private who was piloting an airplane that came close to president reagan's helicopter last year over southern california was ordered to spend 30 weekends in jail monday for making false statements about the incident
ralph william myers, 33, of fort lewis, wash., was convicted of lying to authorities about the reason he strayed into prohibited airspace in his rented plane aug. 13, 1987, at the same time the president was heading to his hilltop ranch north of santa barbara
despite a probation department recommendation of probation, u.s. district judge manuel l. real sentenced myers to three years in jail for each of two counts of making false statements. real then suspended all but 60 days of the jail time
in addition to the suspended sentence and five years' probation, the judge ordered myers to donate 1,000 hours to charitable service
myers' jail time will begin april 9 and is not to interfere with his military service, the judge said. the maximum sentence myers could have received was 10 years in jail and a $500,000 fine
myers told the judge he ``cannot justify or condone statements i made last august. i apologize to the government agencies involved.''
outside the courtroom, myers said he was a scapegoat for federal government mishandling of his aircraft. ``i haven't gotten a fair trial since day one because of the hysteria surrounding the near miss of marine one,'' he said. ``there was not a near miss.''
according to the president's marine pilot, lt. col. michael glynn, myers' plane came passed about 200 feet in front of the helicopter and 150 feet below it. myers maintains his plane was no closer than 800 to 1,000 feet from marine one
his attorney, manuel araujo, said they will appeal the sentence
myers was demoted a private's pay grade for being awol. he still has 18 months left to serve in the u.s. army
myers, and a passenger, oregon businessman harlan lee jones, were arrested at john wayne airport in orange county. marine helicopters, which had been escorting the president's marine one, chased the piper cherokee to the airport, but authorities said myers seemed unaware that he was being followed
myers told secret service and federal aviation administration agents he was looking for a lost contact lens in the airplane's cabin when he strayed into the prohibited airspace. he also claimed he was unaware the airspace was restricted
a day later, he admitted he had lied about the lens
myers, who had been absent without leave from the army since aug. 3, 1987, said he lied because he was confused about the entire situation. ``i was trying to stay out of more trouble,'' he explained in court documents
the breast of chicken was cooked to perfection and the trappings in the state department's elegant eighth-floor dining room reflected painstaking effort
all seemed in order monday when secretary of state george p. shultz hosted a luncheon for chinese foreign minister wu xueqian except for one apparent gaffe in protocol _ the silverware was from taiwan
