the chop sticks were from taiwan
raymond and michele l'esperance took three of their quintuplet babies home from the hospital monday, saying they were eager to begin family life with the in-vitro infants
raymond jr., danielle and erica l'esperance and their parents rode away from william beaumont hospital in a white limousine decorated with silver balloons as a crowd of doctors, nurses, hospital administrators and reporters watched
the babies, born jan. 11, were the first quintuplets born in the united states after being conceived through in-vitro fertilization, which involves fertilizing ovum in the laboratory and implanting the embryos in the womb
the other two babies, veronica and alexandria, who were placed on respirators at birth, remain in the hospital. they are off the respirators now and are expected to be released in a few weeks, said dr. daniel batton, director of newborn medicine at beaumont
they still require special attention and monitoring,'' batton said. ``but we expect those problems will resolve in the next couple of weeks, and we don't anticipate any problems.''
looking ahead to the task of raising five babies at one time, the couple said they are ready to take the infants to their new house in clarkston and let them join their three other children as a family
we are pleased and overjoyed to have three of our babies going home,'' said l'esperance, a corrections officer with the macomb county sheriff's department
we can't wait to have the other two home. we'll just start getting down to being a family.''
the babies that left the hospital have gained about 3 pounds each in the eight weeks since their birth. raymond left beaumont weighing 4 pounds, 9 ounces; danielle weighed 6 pounds, 6 ounces; and erica weighed 5 pounds, 14 ounces, said pamela wells, nursing director in the in-vitro fertilization program at beaumont. transmissions</head> continues to forbid publishing of yellow pages, but not white pages directories.</note>
a federal judge on monday cleared the way for the regional bell telephone companies to offer certain new computerized information services, including voice storage and electronic mail
but u.s. district judge harold greene, in a 66-page decision, refused to retreat from an earlier decision in which he said phone companies could transmit information but could not generate or manipulate the content of the information
it is the court's expectation that this easing of the information services restriction will avoid anticompetitive effects, and that it will at the same time bring this nation closer to the enjoyment of the full benefits of the information age,'' greene said in his decision
though greene's decision lifts the legal barrier to the bell companies' offering of the new services, the companies still would need state and federal regulatory approval before they could integrate them into their networks
industry experts and bell company officials say the computer software for these services has been developed and could be offered to consumers in some parts of the country within one to two years
voice storage and retrieval services would allow consumers to rely on the phone network for storing and retrieving messages, functions now performed by telephone answering machines. electronic mail, a service now available in many private phone systems, allows the computer-to-computer transfer of messages
in addition, greene said the bell companies can perform certain computerized ``gateway'' services such as data transmission, billing management and services that enable different computers to ``speak'' to each other
bellsouth and bell atlantic said the decision was an important step toward making a wide range of information services available to american consumers. but both said the judge did not go far enough, and bell atlantic said it will appeal the decision
we view this as a start, but only a start. we still are not allowed to provide content for information services,'' a bellsouth statement said
bell atlantic chairman thomas e. bolger said the company is ``particularly concerned'' that greene is continuing to forbid the bell companies from electronic publishing of yellow page phone directories. greene's september ruling allowed electronic white pages, but bolger said the court's restrictions do not allow ``a sufficiently flexible and comprehensive'' electronic service for white pages directory
he also said greene's decision to continue to forbid the bell companies from getting into the content side of information services will delay the delivery of more sophisticated services _ like home banking and shopping _ to most american consumers
joel gross, a telephone analyst with donaldson, lufkin &amp; jenrette, said the decision was a ``major breakthrough'' for the regional phone companies. he said that in the long term, ``it will be a tremendous boon to the industry,'' though in the short-term will have little effect on the companies' earninings
services like this, since they are software-based, should be high-profit services and voice storage and retrieval will create new (traffic) volumes for the phone networks,'' he said
gene kimmelman, a spokesman for the consumer federation of america, said the decision means regulation of the industry will become more important ``to prevent the bell companies from overpricing local phone service to finance these new services.''
greene, who oversees the antitrust decree that broke up the american telephone &amp; telegraph co. four years ago, has been reluctant to allow at&amp;t's offspring, the bell companies, to compete in areas where their control of the local phone networks would put them at an advantage over competitors
last september, he refused to lift prohibitions on the baby bells that prevent them from making phone equipment or offering long-distance services. in considering the restrictions on information services, however, he opened the door slightly. monday's ruling details the information-services options now open to the bell companies. pledged</note>
jesse jackson said monday he's going into the super tuesday elections as an underdog, but thinks he'll do very well nonetheless
i don't have a crystal ball,'' he said when asked how many delegates he might pick up in the day's balloting
jackson pointed to the ``high-tech, well-financed operation'' of democratic presidential rival michael dukakis
he has money; i have the message and the grass-roots approach. it will be interesting to see how these concepts play out,'' he said
jackson made the comments in an interviw aboard his campaign plane flying from an airport rally in laredo to a rally at the university of houston
as he campaigned on the eve of super tuesday, jackson said texas has shaped up to a fight between himself and dukakis. he also contended his message has become part of the political mainstream
when one takes a serious look at my positions, they are very central to the broad-based american point of view,'' he said
earlier, jackson visited an aids clinic in dallas and told a rally in brownsville: ``i'll be your friend in washington.''
jackson pledged to fight against proposals to make english the official language of the united states
we are a great nation. we can speak more than one language. ... two-thirds of the hemisphere speaks spanish. we should grow and speak more languages, have broader culture,'' he said
jackson donned a sombrero and the popular latin-style shirt called a guayaberra as he addressed the mixed-race outdoor gathering where several people waved red united farm worker flags
