after jackson's visit, she said, the state health director called a meeting to find out why the sanitary laws were not being enforced in the field
you need a friend in the white house,'' jackson said. ``i'm your friend in brownsville. i'll be your friend in washington.''
jackson was accompanied by former new mexico gov. toney anaya, who addressed the gathering in spanish, texas agriculture commissioner jim hightower, prominent feminist leader sissy farenthold and tennessee politician john j. hooker
one man in the crowd, carlos martinez, said he was supporting jackson because jackson cares about the mexican-american problems and the poor people. martinez said the once-bustling port of brownsville ``is dead'' and that he had been laid off a few years back from both marathon and pyramid oil companies
we're just about forgotten about down here and the economy is really bad. we're looking for a change,'' he said
