earlier he visited with dying men in an aids clinic in dallas
several onlookers said that jackson and democratic rival michael dukakis will likely split the democratic vote in this area. dukakis, who speaks fluent spanish, has been pushing hard for the hispanic vote and visited neighboring harlingen a week ago
but county commissioner candidate gilberto villarreal, a jackson supporter, said, ``speaking spanish or marrying a hispanic does not give you the heart of a hispanic.'' he said that while dukakis has done ``tremendous work in massachusetts,'' jackson has the heart of a hispanic. ``he came up from the grass roots. he has not forgotten what it is to be poor,'' he said. with later testimony. picks up 13th graf, `milstead, the...'. should stand for ams.</note>
arizona's top police official testified at gov. evan mecham's impeachment trial monday that he realized almost immediately mecham had committed a crime in ordering the official to not cooperate in an investigation of an alleged death threat
i was in shock over what he was saying, taken aback, speechless,'' said col. ralph milstead, director of the state department of public safety
milstead quoted mecham as angrily telling him: ``i don't want you to help the attorney general hang me. don't tell him anything.''
milstead said he had phoned the governor nov. 15 to discuss a report that lee watkins, then a mecham administration official, had threatened to send a former mecham aide on ``a long boat ride'' if she didn't stop testifying before a grand jury investigating mecham campaign finances
watkins has denied threatening the aide, donna carlson. and milstead has said he cooperated with the attorney general's office
milstead, whose testimony is crucial to the obstruction of justice charge against the governor, blurted out his statement regarding a crime during cross-examination by mecham's attorney, fred craft
craft asked why milstead, in his report on the incident, quoted the governor's words but not milstead's own part of the conversation
because i'm not committing a crime,'' said milstead. ``... i'm not obstructing justice.''
when did you conclude that the governor's words constituted a crime?'' asked craft
as i'm hearing them and reflecting on them,'' said milstead, adding it took him ``about two seconds'' after hanging up the phone
craft asked milstead why he did not write down his conclusion that a crime had been committed
i didn't think it was necessary,'' said milstead. ``anyone with a legal background could read it and see this was an obstruction of an investigation.''
craft kept milstead on cross-examination for most of the day and said he would continue quizzing him tuesday. senate democratic minority leader alan stephens told reporters the senators were growing restless and had requested that craft be asked to conclude
it's difficult for us to listen to what many of us consider repetitious quetions,'' he said. ``if that's what they do in a court of law, i'm glad i'm not a lawyer.''
at one point, craft asked if milstead was surprised that his staff didn't tell him the governor had assigned a member of his cabinet, max hawkins, to investigate the death threat allegation
no, it didn't surprise me,'' said milstead. ``max hawkins is not a law enforcement officer. he's not competent to investigate it. lee watkins works for him, and max hawkins wouldn't be taken seriously anywhere on earth that i know of.''
hawkins, former head of the department of administration, was fired last week by acting gov. rose mofford, who said he had publicly attacked government officials
milstead, the trial's seventh witness, took the stand at the start of the second week of testimony. mecham, the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in six decades, has not attended the proceedings yet
mecham, 63, a first-term republican, is accused in the impeachment proceedings of obstructing the attorney general's investigation of the alleged death threat through his orders to milstead
mecham, in testimony before a house impeachment committee in january, acknowledged that he may have told milstead not to cooperate with the investigation. however, mecham contended he was not fully informed about the seriousness of the situation before his conversation with milstead
the governor also is accused in 23 articles of impeachment of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 in a state fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
mecham also faces a recall election may 17 and a criminal trial march 22 on felony charges accusing him of concealing the $350,000 loan
milstead described a tense, angry, fearful mecham trying to minimize the alleged threat
he said this was a family spat and there's nothing to it,'' milstead testified
milstead said he had called the governor as a courtesy to tell him he was taking the matter to the attorney general and was surprised by mecham's anger
his reaction was, `well, if you want my permission to talk to the attorney general, you can't have it. the answer is no.'''
at one point, milstead said he was ``kind of pleading'' and told mecham: ``we always cooperate with the attorney general.''
he said, `never. don't give them any help.'''
earlier in the day, attorney general robert corbin advised the senate not to grant immunity to watkins, who invoked fifth amendment protection against self-incrimination friday and refused to testify
corbin confirmed that watkins is the target of a grand jury investigation and said it would be inappropriate to immunize him from possible future prosecution
impeachment trial prosecutor william french said: ``we would be against giving the likes of mr. watkins a bath for all the sins he has committed
the senators were unanimous in their rejection of immunity
a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required to convict mecham. the senators then could take another vote and bar him from holding state office again
jury selection began monday in the wedtech corp. racketeering case involving rep. mario biaggi, with 48 candidates being excused and 58 others asked to return
last week, 94 potential jurors were excused for hardship reasons, leaving 106 who had filled out a 63-item questionnaire about their feelings and who they might know involved in the case
on monday, u.s. district court judge constance baker motley excused 48 candidates based upon their answers while 58 were asked to return tuesday, either to be requestioned or to appear for the first time
the jurors will have to decide the fate of biaggi, his eldest son, former bronx borough president stanley simon and four co-defendants, who are accused of turning the wedtech corp. into a ``vehicle for making illegal payments to public officials.''
the seven are charged with participating in a racketeering enterprise that allegedly looted millions of dollars in stock and cash from wedtech, a bronx defense contractor now in bankruptcy proceedings
all are charged with racketeering and conspiracy, each carrying a maximum 20-year penalty upon conviction. biaggi also is accused of extortion, bribe-receiving, wire fraud, perjury and filing false tax returns, and the other defendants also face various other charges
wedtech was a small, bronx machine shop that grew into a multimillion- dollar-a-year defense contractor. it rose through a small business administration program that allowed minority-owned firms to obtain government contracts without competitive bidding
a number of federal, state and local inquiries are looking into allegations of bribery, influence peddling and other wrongdoing
asked about one of his responses to the questionnaire, a potential juror, joseph c. siragusi, told mrs. motley he had problems with the concept of programs set up especially to help minorities and women
when mrs. motley further explained the concept to him, siragusi said: ``under that circumstance, i wouldn't consider it unfair.''
when there were no objections from defense and government attorneys, mrs. motley ruled there was no reason to excuse siragusi. he will be reinterviewed tuesday
raymond joseph sullivan, another jury candidate from the bronx, was asked if he had stated on the questionnaire that he opposed programs helping minorities
sure did,'' sullivan said. ``i have four children. i wouldn't want to see them denied a job.''
sullivan was asked to return when court resumes at 9:30 a.m. tuesday
cardinal miguel obando y bravo and the secretary-general of the organization of american states agreed to be witnesses at talks between the government and contra rebels, a presidential communique said monday
the agreement by joao baena soares, the oas official, and obando y bravo, roman catholic archbishop of managua, appeared to ease the way for truce negotiations starting wednesday in sapoa, on the border with costa rica about 90 miles from managua
president daniel ortega last week said the cardinal was no longer needed as a mediator in talks with the u.s.-backed rebels. obando y bravo had served as a go-between since last november at government request
the contras insisted the cardinal be a witness, and the talks had appeared to be in jeopardy
ortega sent letters this week to obando y bravo and baena soares asking them to serve as witnesses, the government's voice of nicaragua radio said monday
no one answered the telephone at the headquarters of the washington-based oas
contra leader adolfo calero earlier monday accused the government of ``preparing a unilateral show'' rather than planning for the talks
in a telephone interview from miami, calero complained that the leftist sandinistas had not responded to a contra demand that obando y bravo be present ``as witness, moderator and guarantor of the talks.''
ortega said last week that the three days of talks would be headed by his brother, humberto ortega, the defense minister and one of nine members on the ruling national directorate. acceding to a contra demand, he said the talks would be held in nicaragua and suggested the sapoa site
the contras accepted and named calero to head their delegation, but said the cardinal must attend
calero said the contras received no word from the government about security arrangements or the agenda
the government says the talks should center on laying down arms as outlined in the regional peace plan signed last august by the presidents of nicaragua, el salvador, guatemala, costa rica and honduras
the rebels want a proposal outlined by the cardinal last month to be included
his agenda called for the government to grant total amnesty to political prisoners, review a mandatory military draft law, allow full press freedom and renew a dialogue with its internal opposition. in return, contras were to accept a 30-day cease-fire
we haven't received any response to our position of last thursday ... which included these items,'' calero said
we said clearly then that we accept the high-level meeting to discuss the cardinal's agenda and that we had agreed with the preliminary details of the meeting, but we haven't had a response from the sandinista government,'' he said. inadequate''</head> cost was $7.735 million, but annuities may pay more over time. inserts 2 grafs after 18th graf pvs bgng: the government, to add justice department comment. picks up 19th graf pvs bgng: judy resnick's ...</note>
an attorney experienced at representing the families of deceased astronauts said the settlement negotiated by the government for four challenger families was ``woefully inadequate.''
ronald d. krist, a houston attorney who represented astronauts' survivors from the apollo fire in 1967 as well as three families from the 1986 space shuttle disaster, said the four challenger families should have received more money and would have if they had had formal legal representation
the families, according to documents released monday, are dividing the proceeds from annuities and lump sums that cost a total of $7.735 million. payments from the annuities will be extended over years and may amount to much more than the actual cost. the settlement was negotiated for the families by the department of justice. morton thiokol inc., manufacturer of the rocket blamed for the challenger accident, paid 60 percent of the settlement and the u.s. government paid the rest
if they're happy, i'm happy for them,'' krist said of the four families that settled without filing lawsuits. ``but i would never have put my stamp of approval for a settlement at the level that they received
they would have netted more money if they had been adequately represented,'' krist added
challenger exploded on jan. 28, 1986, just 73 seconds after it was launched from the kennedy space center in florida. seven astronauts, including new hampshire school teacher christa mcauliffe, died in the accident
mcauliffe's husband, along with the wives of challenger commander dick scobee, mission specialist ellison onizuka and engineer bruce jarvis all settled through the justice department negotiations
however, the widow of mission specialist ron mcnair, the father of jarvis, and the mother of mission specialist judy resnik all hired krist to file separate suits only against thiokol. the suits were settled out of court, but krist said he was under court order to not discuss how much was paid
but he was blunt about the government-negotiated settlement
that settlement is woefully inadequate,'' he said. ``i'm suggesting that if i was representing them, i would not have allowed any of them to settle for the amount they received of less than $2 million a piece (per family).''
however, betty grissom, whose husband gus died in an apollo spacecraft fire in 1967, said, ``it sounds like they did ok.''
mrs. grissom said she received only $350,000, and she had to sue on her own for that. the government, she said, ``didn't care'' and never attempted to help her or the widows of two other astronauts who died in the apollo fire
i never heard from the justice department,'' she said. ``i thought we got an injustice done to us. i feel like we got taken. they act like they care now, but they didn't back then
it kinda hurts,'' she added. ``it stings that ... we never got treated like that. it hurts when i think that they're getting that much money.''
michael d. oldak, a washington lawyer and ex-husband of astronaut judith a. resnik, said the documents confirm for him that resnik family was treated unfairly by the government in settlement negotiations
resnik's father, marvin, and her estate were initially involved in settlement negotiations with the government, said oldak, who represented the resniks
he said the government made two offers, but neither were accepted. oldak said that because resnik was single and childless, and because the government's compensation formula was weighted heavily toward surviving spouses and children, the offer to resnik's survivors was ``a quarter to a half of what they were offering the other families.''
the government has declined to contribute anything to any of the families outside the four it negotiated settlements with
justice spokeswoman amy brown said the government had made settlement offers to attorneys for the resniks, smiths and mcnairs based on the same formula used for the other families. these were rejected, she said
after the rejections, the families either negotiated directly with morton thiokol, or filed suits or claims against the company or the government. miss brown said the government would not negotiate further with the three non-settling families because it would not enter a settlement separate from one with morton thiokol or which exceeded the guidelines used in the other settlements
judy resnik's father and her estate recently settled privately with morton thiokol for a sum that marvin resnik said it was between $2 million and $3.5 million
oldak declined to confirm the amount, but he said, ``in hindsight, it was a good decision not to be part of the (government-negotiated) settlement.''
one lawsuit, filed by jane smith, widow of challenger pilot michael smith, remains to be settled. mrs. smith did not participate in the government-negotiated settlement and a court ruled she could not sue the government. but she is suing thiokol
mrs. smith declined to come to the telephone when her houston home was called on monday
the judicial misconduct hearing of a former vermont supreme court justice began with a delay monday as attorneys for a key figure in the case argued she should not have to testify
attorneys for former chittenden county assistant judge jane wheel told the judicial conduct board that her criminal case would be damaged if she testified in the separate case of her friend and former co-worker, justice william hill
hill was one of three supreme court justices accused of allowing their personal relationships with wheel to interfere with their judicial duties
the charges filed in january 1987 by the state judicial conduct board named hill, thomas hayes and ernest gibson iii. hill has retired since the charges were filed. hayes has died and the charges against gibson were dropped and he remains on the court
the scandal threw the state's highest court into turmoil. the justices refused gov. madeleine kunin's request that they step aside, but they did disqualify themselves from all cases involving people connected with the case
the complaint alleged that the three used their clout to help wheel, whether it was in minor matters, like writing memos endorsing suggestions she made, or major matters, like advising her while she was under criminal investigation by the state attorney general's office for allegedly padding her paycheck
wheel was convicted on three counts of false swearing during a jury trial last month. she was accused of lying during an inquest into allegations that she submitted false pay vouchers
wheel appeared in court briefly monday. but she left after she and her attorneys were given one day to submit memoranda on why she shouldn't have to testify
hill's attorney, michael marks, had said he and his client welcomed the misconduct hearing, calling it hill's opportunity to defend himself publicly
but most of the first day's testimony centered on wheel and her activities as an assistant judge
in hill's written responses to the board's original charges, he said his relationship with wheel was strictly professional and did not go beyond ``the amicable relationship expected of judges who work together.''
but the state on monday attempted to depict a much closer relationship between the two
court reporter joan giard described a gathering she attended at the holiday inn in waterbury. wheel arrived with hill on one arm and hayes on the other
she danced with justice hill that evening,'' giard said. ``i remember looking over.''
marks objected to much of the testimony about wheel and her criminal case, but was overruled by harvey otterman, the chairman of the three-member hearing panel
the retirement of hill, 60, from the high court leaves few options for punishment if he is found guilty of judicial misconduct. he could be reprimanded or perhaps restricted from serving on the court under a law that allows retired justices to sit on certain cases
don't let them tell you this is a television campaign,'' massachusetts gov. michael s. dukakis said monday as he raced through a final day of pre-super tuesday campaigning
still, dukakis packed 21 television interviews into his final day of stumping before tuesday's primaries and caucuses in 20 states _ including 14 southern and border states
he campaigned in person monday in miami and the tampa area, then traveled to an evening rally in the raleigh-durham area of north carolina before a scheduled flight back to boston
if we can emerge from super tuesday with the lead in terms of delegates, we'll be on our way to the nomination,'' he said
dukakis kicked off the day of campaigning in miami, perhaps his most solid base of support in the south
at a senior citizens rally, dukakis picked up the valued endorsement of 74-year-old annie ackerman, who has a reputation in miami for being able to get out the vote
you have come out to listen to the man who will be the next president of the united states,'' ackerman said. she spoke of dukakis' immigrant roots, something he had in common with many of those at the rally
my mother would have said he's a mensch,'' she said, referring to the yiddish word for good man. ``he's a person of integrity who gets things done.''
ackerman, a former ward organizer for the late chicago mayor richard daley, met with several of the presidential candidates but decided on dukakis after a straw poll of the residents of her condominium complex
dukakis traveled from miami to plant city to attend a strawberry festival and also marched in a parade with florida attorney general robert butterworth at his side on monday
he planned to vote in his hometown of brookline, mass., tuesday morning, spend the day at his statehouse office and then fly to chicago to begin campaigning for the illinois primary
throughout his southern campaign swing, nearly all of dukakis' stops have come in areas where he is expected to win. the strategy seems to be to reinforce areas of strength rather than seek new support
there are only so many hours in a day _ you can't go everywhere,'' the massachusetts governor has repeatedly said
asked whether the super tuesday primaries were a flop in attracting moderate and conservative democrats, dukakis said, ``it's not been a flop for mike dukakis. i don't understand what the labels mean.''
dukakis has not talked much about his opponents. he has continued to criticize missouri rep. richard gephardt, seen by many as his principal rival, but such comments have only come with prompting from reporters
he said he is worried that the negative campaigning between him and gephardt is hurting the chances for the democratic party in november. in response to a barb from gephardt criticizing the dukakis attacks, he said, ``no, i don't think i've impugned his integrity.''
meanwhile, in boston, 20 protesters were arrested outside dukakis' statehouse office on trespassing charges as they staged a sit-in to demand an immediate increase in welfare benefits
most of the protesters went limp when told to leave the building, so police had to lift them into nearby elevators
while he's out stumping, our kids are starving,'' one protester shouted
stanlake samkange, an author and politician who fought for independence for zimbabwe, died in harare of heart and lung ailments after a long illness, his widow said monday. he was 65
tommie-marie samkange said her husband died sunday
samkange was the first black college graduate in the province of mashonaland in 1947 when zimbabwe was the white-ruled british colony of rhodesia. he received a bachelor's degree with honors in history
as a black nationalist, he held top posts in the next three decades in several political parties including joshua nkomo's zimbabwe african people's union and bishop abel muzorewa's united african national council
samkange retired from politics in 1979, the year when a british-sponsored accord provided for independence for zimbabwe and rule by the black majority
robert mugabe's zimbabwe african national union won the march 1980 elections and mugabe became prime minister. mugabe and nkomo had led rebel armies in guerrilla warfare against white domination
samkange also worked as a free-lance journalist and wrote three books on politics in africa. he received a master of science degree from syracuse university in new york
after retiring he opened a publishing house
his wife said burial will be saturday at the family farm at msengezi near harare and a memorial service will be held friday in harare
a jobless streetsweeper who set himself afire near prime minister margaret thatcher's residence was buried monday at a service attended by relatives, friends and about 100 unemployed britons
derek bainbridge, 41, burned to death in his car parked 40 yards from mrs. thatcher's downing street residence on feb. 16
he had been unemployed for 18 months and left a suicide note saying, ``too young to retire, too old to live.''
his family invited unemployed people to attend the funeral in bainbridge's hometown of worksop in central england 180 miles from london
steven brown said he came to the burial with other jobless people ``because i can understand what derek bainbridge went through. people can't understand how you feel having to pay for rent, gas and electricity when you don't have a job.''
the rev. brian hunt, who presided at the service, said prayers for the unemployed and ``for those who are going through depression, frustration and anger.''
britain's unemployment has doubled from 1.3 million in 1979, when mrs. thatcher won her first of three terms in office, to 2.6 million in december. the government has said that was a seasonably adjusted 9.4 percent of the work force. called off, picking up 4th graf pvs, `when police...'.</note>
a woman told authorities monday that she threw her housemate's missing 7-month-old daughter into the delaware river, but police said they didn't know whether to believe the retarded woman
divers aided by tracking dogs searched the chilly river for the blue-eyed infant, who disappeared sunday from a row house near trenton state prison. at dusk monday, the search was suspended indefinitely
the 30-year-old woman was in police custody monday but had not been charged, said police sgt. robert orlowski
when police first questioned her sunday, the woman said a man had knocked her down, kidnapped the toddler and driven off, orlowski said. then she said the man tossed the baby into the river. after further questioning, she said the baby fell off her lap into the river, orlowski said
she admitted this morning that she threw the baby in the river yesterday,'' orlowski said
they don't know really whether to believe her or not because of her diminished mental capacity. she has the capacity of a 4- or 5-year-old. her story has changed so many times since she reported it, they really don't know what to believe,'' orlowski said
the detective who has been with her all day yesterday and today feels pretty certain this is what happened,'' orlowski said
according to police, the woman asked the baby's mother, rebecca mcguinn, for permission to play with the baby sunday morning
ms. mcguinn gave her approval, but said the woman had to remain in the living room. however, the woman apparently took the child from the house while the mother was asleep, orlowski said
vice president george bush said monday ``the person that clearly wins super tuesday is going to be the nominee of the party'' as he coasted on polls that gave him a big lead in most of the 17 gop contests
bush stopped short of forecasting a sweep on tuesday
you always wish for that but i certainly would never predict that. it's too much for anyone to expect,'' he said earlier in the day
at his last public appearance of the day, in rogers, ark., the vice president said he was ``optimistic but not overconfident.''
asked what he'd do if he didn't win super tuesday, he replied: ``i'll have to do what i did when i got kicked in iowa _ get up off the canvas, go out and fight hard.'' after his third-place finish in iowa, bush went on to a solid win in the new hampshire primary eight days later
in a two-hour stop at tulsa international airport, he told a rally that super tuesday constitutes ``the most historic political event in modern political history.''
it's critical,'' he said. ``the person that clearly wins super tuesday is going to be the nominee of the party and i think the next president.''
bush, introduced by gov. henry bellmon at the rally, later toured the american airlines maintenance and engineering facility at the airport and took a moment to turn a wrench on an engine
bush appeared tired at a 15-minute news conference following a brisk walking tour of the sprawling facility
the vice president dismissed the possibility of a brokered convention
we're talking about victory and he's talking about brokering something,'' he said. ``i don't see it happening. i think there are so many events that i think the republican nominee will be determined before the convention.''
bush was asked about negative ads that he called ``comparative'' spots criticizing dole's record in the senate
when attacked, you'll see some retaliation,'' bush said. ``but when you look at the totality and how it all came about, i think people understand that a person has a right to, in a laser-like fashion, go after them. i think actually the factual back-up of those ads is pretty irrefutable.''
bush, a former oilman, said he feels ``compatible with the base of this state.'' but he said he cannot support a tax on imported oil as a means of shoring up the ailing domestic energy business
i was in the oil business, and i remember what it was like to have government controls, allocations of markets and regulation. and who hated it the worst? the oil industry,'' bush said
that also has an artificial, inflationary built-in premise to it. everybody's costs go up. it's like any other tax. and i'm opposed to raising taxes. the industry is split on the oil import fee. i don't happen to be in favor of it. i think what i propose, including a tax credit for exploration ... is the way to go.''
the federal government insisted monday that west germany had had no serious disagreements with its nato allies about disarmament at an alliance summit last week
attempts ... to fabricate disagreements on basic questions between the federal republic and its allies ... find a basis neither in the proceedings nor in the results of the summit,'' said a communique
it said chancellor helmut kohl determined at the north atlantic treaty organization summit in brussels, belgium, that the alliance will ``concentrate on working out a comprehensive (disarmament) concept.''
kohl assumed from the talks that ``work within the alliance will proceed smoothly, and be finished at the latest within a year,'' said the statement read to reporters by government spokesman friedhelm ost
it also said there should not be attempts to ``artifically create pressures'' on nato to make a quick decision on the modernization of short-range nuclear weapons
that remark appeared to be aimed at prime minister margaret thatcher of britain, who told the summit that the alliance would soon have to think seriously about modernizing its aging short-range nuclear weapons
kohl had resisted demands at the summit for a stronger nato position on the modernization of short-range nuclear weapons, which have a range of up to 300 miles
kohl wants nato to postpone the scheduled modernization of those weapons and to begin negotiations with the soviet-led warsaw pact alliance on reducing short-range nuclear arsenals
monday's statement repeated kohl's position that he does not favor total removal of nuclear weapons from europe, but wants a reduction and parity in conventional and nuclear arms by both nato and the warsaw pact
bonn officials have said west germany would be the main battleground in a european war because it borders east germany and czechoslovakia
prosecutors monday sought a one-month delay in gov. evan mecham's criminal trial for allegedly concealing a $350,000 campaign loan, while defense lawyers said the charges should be dismissed
maricopa county superior court judge michael ryan said he would rule on the delay motion, which was opposed by the defense, wednesday or thursday. he did not say when he would rule on a series of defense motions brought monday
delays in pretrial procedures sought by the defense have left too little time for prosecutors to prepare, said assistant attorney general barnett lotstein. he sought to change the trial starting date from march 22 to april 21
the governor's political agenda has no place in this courtroom,'' lotstein told ryan. ``he wants a speedy trial. we want a trial after the rules have been complied with.''
defense attorney michael scott argued against a delay in the trial, adding, ``we want to resolve this matter and put it behind us.''
in an indictment handed up jan. 8, the governor was charged with six felony counts of fraud, perjury and filing false documents in his failure to disclose a $350,000 campaign loan. his brother and 1986 campaign manager, willard mecham, faces three similar counts
mecham's senate impeachment trial went into its second week monday, and he also faces a may 17 recall election
defense attorneys filed a series of motions monday seeking:
_ dismissal or a new determination of the charges' validity, on several grounds including a claim that people who had a definite stance on the mecham recall movement were unfairly excluded from the grand jury
the motion said the indictments should be dismissed ``because both those who favored the recall and those who opposed the recall were blanketly excluded from the grand jury without any regard'' to their ability to make a fair decision
_ dismissal of the charges on grounds the mechams were victims of selective prosecution
the motion claimed that other public figures, including state lawmakers such as former house majority leader burton barr and current house minority leader art hamilton, were not prosecuted when it was found that they had omitted items from their financial disclosure statements
not only was governor mecham not given a written opportunity to file an amended return, his protestations of oversight and avowals of no criminal intent fell upon deaf ears,'' the motion said. ``why? because the political turmoil surrounding his nine months in office threatened to destroy the power and influence the republican party had spent more than 20 years nurturing and cultivating.''
_ a change of venue because of massive pretrial publicity, and separate questioning of prospective jurors in an effort to see that they are not biased
_ separate trials for evan and willard mecham, who now are scheduled to be tried together
ryan also took under advisement a defense motion to dismiss two of the counts against willard mecham and four of the counts against the governor. the defense claimed the grand jury did not have jurisdiction to bring those charges
a homeless man who gained national recognition for his refusal to abandon his makeshift camp on state-owned land was found dead in his hut monday by his children, police said. bill britt was 52
britt's badly decomposed body was found by his son and daughter in his hut about 30 feet from the fence surrounding the evergreen cemetery in boston's brighton district, spokesman scott gillis said
britt, born britton william boughner in the affluent neighborhood near the state-owned land, had lived at the reservoir near boston college since 1969
in his case, he felt that this was where he wanted to live, this was his estate,'' said clyde raymond, a friend of britt's. ``he died free, so to speak. he had his own drummer and he stuck with it.''
britt, who was known as the ``hermit of chestnut hill,'' had been dead for several months and his body, dressed in multiple layers of clothing, was almost reduced to skeletal, gillis said
an autopsy was performed on britt in an attempt to determine the cause of death, but results weren't expected until tuesday, gillis said
in 1985, officials started trying to move britt from the metropolitan district commission land in the chestnut hill district on the boston-brookline border
britt, who was legally blind, lived on money he earned redeeming can and bottle deposits. he refused welfare and several attempts to relocate him to public or subsidized housing
in may, britt's plastic and wood wigwam was destroyed in a fire while he was in new york city to appear on the ``late night with david letterman'' television show. he rebuilt it, despite deteriorating health. doctors said britt, who was nearly toothless, had ulcers and needed a corneal transplant
a judge monday refused to dismiss an indictment or delay the murder trial of a former state trooper accused of killing a fellow officer in her patrol car
circuit judge j.c. norton rejected the defense motions as jury selection opened in the trial of joseph cecil duncan, 33, who is charged with shooting elizabeth cobb, 31, three times in the head at close range
miss cobb's body was found oct. 12 in her patrol car near a rural dallas county church. the fbi has said miss cobb was the first female state trooper in the nation to be slain on duty. duncan attended her funeral and was charged in the case later
authorities say duncan was the beneficiary of a $250,000 insurance policy on the victim's life. duncan has pleaded innocent and says he and miss cobb planned to marry
jury selection was expedited monday when the judge declined to grant a defense motion to question potential jurors individually rather than have members of the jury pool answer general questions put to all
the defense had argued that the state destroyed evidence that might have been significant to the defense. the evidence in question was the bullets from a .22-caliber pistol found in a black trans-am
at one point after miss cobb disappeared on patrol, officers issued a bulletin for a black trans am that reportedly had been chased by miss cobb's patrol car in dallas county
defense attorney henry pitts said a texas drifter named charlie shoemaker is being held on drug charges in okaloosa county, fla., and is the man who was driving the black trans-am
but assistant attorney general william wasden said monday that prosecution witnesses will show shoemaker is not involved in the shooting
the leftist sandinista government withheld nearly $20,000 belonging to the u.s. embassy and its employees when they turned in their money in a currency exchange, an embassy source said monday
the source, who spoke on condition he not be further identified, said the embassy turned 208 million old cordobas in to the government in exchange for new ones in accordance with last month's economic measures
the total, which included private money and embassy funds, was worth about $20,800
the government last month created a new cordoba worth 1,000 times more than the old one and pegged it at 10 to the u.s. dollar
the government set an exchange limit of 10 million in cordobas per person or institution, or the equivalent of $1,000. the u.s. embassy was given $1,000, and the rest was withheld
according to the new law, the remainder should be put in a bank account, where it is converted to the new currency but frozen. an embassy spokesman said monday the embassy had no information whether that occurred
a central bank spokeswoman said she had no information on the u.s. embassy account, but confirmed that the money should have been put in an account
the embassy source said the sandinistas asked for proof that the cordobas turned over by the americans were obtained legally in nicaragua. exchange houses issue receipts for dollars turned into cordobas. the government did not require such receipts from individuals changing their currency
i don't know if we have receipts for everybody,'' the embassy source said. ``i know i always throw mine out.''
embassy spokesman lou falino said: ``we have no comment.''
developer peter kalikow took ownership of the new york post from rupert murdoch on monday, calling it a historic moment and pledging to make the money-losing tabloid ``a winner financially and editorially.''
the papers transferring ownership were signed monday afternoon, according to post spokesman howard rubenstein. last month, after marathon bargaining, the post's 10 unions agreed to concessions required by the new owner, and the last of the unions officially ratified the concessions sunday
the rescue of the post is nothing less than an historic moment,'' kalikow said in a statement, thanking the unions and employees ``for their heroic efforts.''
union leaders will sign formal papers tuesday and meet with kalikow on thursday to ``get to know each other,'' said george mcdonald, president of the allied printing trades council, which represents eight of the 10 unions
we're delighted, really delighted, glad it's all over,'' mcdonald said
kalikow bought the nation's oldest continuously published daily newspaper for $37.6 million from murdoch, who sold the paper to comply with federal communications commission regulations barring ownership of two media outlets in the same city. murdoch owns wnyw-tv in new york
the sale was contingent upon the union concessions, which totaled $22 million and eliminated 130 jobs
murdoch, who was in london on monday, has said he was losing $100,000 a day with the post and had lost $150 million in the 12 years he owned it
kalikow said he intended to stop the post's losses and added: ``i am committed to expanding its readership base through millions of dollars in promotion, adding features to the paper, greatly expanding its investigative reporting and strengthening its advertising revenues to make the paper profitable on a long-term basis.''
the paper will be a winner financially and editorially,'' he said
an israeli businessman with reported links to israeli politicians and army officers went on trial monday accused of being a spy for the soviet union, his lawyer said
shabtai kalmanovich, 46, who emigrated to israel from the soviet union in 1971, denied the charges, according to defense attorney amnon zichroni
he said the tel aviv district court hearing the case barred him from further comment. the trial is being held behind closed doors and zichroni said it is expected to last about seven months
kalmanovich has been in custody since his arrest dec. 23
israel television has described kalmanovich as an international businessman with interests in africa who ``employed hundreds of people throughout the world, among them former israeli (cabinet) ministers and reserve officers.''
the jan. 10 report said, ``among his friends were members of the knesset (parliament), high-ranking politicians and senior army reserve officers.'' it did not give any names
kalmanovich was born in lithuania and after his arrival in israel he served in the army and then worked briefly as an aide to former israeli legislator shmuel flatto-sharon
the television report said kalmanovich had connections with people involved in east-west spy swaps in the 1970s. it said that in august 1977, kalmanovich traveled to east germany and met with wolfgang vogel, an east german lawyer who mediated such exchanges
in april 1978, kalmanovich helped bring about the release of an israeli prisoner from a jail in mozambique, according to the television account. it said that in the same month, east germany released an american student and the united states freed robert g. thompson who had been convicted of passing secrets to the soviets. with children,' on fox network sted syndicated; subs 11th graf, `milstead played...', to delete reference to `trouble in mind' being only other non-transvestite role.</note>
harris glenn milstead, known to moviegoers as divine, the campy, 300-pound transvestite star of such films as ``pink flamingos'' and ``hairspray,'' died in his sleep in a hotel room, the coroner's office said monday. he was 42
los angeles county coroner spokesman steve stewart said investigators went to the regency plaza hotel on hollywood boulevard, where milstead was a guest when he died during the night. ``the cause of death is under investigation,'' stewart said
milstead apparently died of asphyxiation, said spokesman john west of pmk public relations
he was finally getting respect within the industry,'' said milstead's manager, bernard jay. ``he was getting the legitimate screen and television offers that showed the industry had finally accepted him as the very good character actor he always knew he was.''
milstead got a medical checkup last friday and was declared in excellent health, other than his weight, ``which has been a constant problem throughout his life,'' said jay
west said milstead, star of the latest john waters-directed movie ``hairspray,'' was in los angeles to appear in an episode of the fox network television series ``married ... with children.''
milstead was to have appeared in that role dressed as a man, but he was best known to movie fans as the bizarre female impersonating star of such cult classic films as ``pink flamingos,'' ``lust in the dust,'' ``polyester'' and ``female trouble.''
the divine character was garishly made up and outrageously chesty, as well as loud, raucous and foul-mouthed. milstead's appearance made the first waters films a favorite for after-midnight showings at arty cinema houses
but with each film, both milstead and waters found a wider audience, and ``hairspray'' has enjoyed a good following as well as flattering reviews, coming in no. 16 this weekend in the box office with $577,258 at 79 theaters for a $7,307 per screen average
in the film, set in the early 1960s, he plays the mother of a chubby teen-age girl who becomes a teen television dance star and pioneer integrationist. dressed as a man, he also plays a segregationist television station manager
in another non-transvestite role, milstead played a sydney greenstreet-type character in the 1985 film ``trouble in mind.''
milstead said in a 1985 interview that he grew up fat and taunted by classmates in lutherville, a suburb of baltimore. the only son of a businessman and his wife, milstead told an interviewer he had a fantasy life revolving around female movie stars and dreams of becoming a celebrity
one of his few friends from high school was waters, whose obsession with trashy movies nearly matched milstead's fantasies of celebrity. waters began casting his friend in bizarre roles
in the 1972 ``pink flamingos,'' divine was introduced as ``the filthiest person alive.''
the character is a real person,'' milstead once said of divine. ``sometimes she's just too bold, but she has socially redeeming qualities, no matter what she does. she's her own person and a lot of people like that
the camp element is something out of the ordinary, this big man playing a sexy woman.''
besides film roles, milstead also used the divine persona in a nightclub act
he is survived by his mother and father, frances and harris milstead, who now live in florida, west said. don't</note>
kansas sen. bob dole, on a last-ditch campaign swing through missouri monday, all but conceded super tuesday to vice president george bush _ but said he wasn't giving up the fight for the republican presidential nomination
we know that we won't be the front-runner after super tuesday, but it's not over after super tuesday,'' he told a crowd of about 80 supporters during a brief rally at the springfield regional airport. ``we're going to win in november.''
earlier, in oklahoma city, he said bush appears strong in the south but ``there may be some surprises'' and republicans should nominate someone who will win the general election
we don't want to lose the white house by nominating the wrong person,'' dole said
the senator from kansas said his race against bush for republican votes in the big round of balloting tuesday was tight in oklahoma, missouri and north carolina
we're moving very quick in georgia. washington state looks pretty good,'' dole said at a news conference at will rogers world airport. ``there are some opportunities in rhode island and massachusetts
the other states? no, i think it's fair to say george bush has a good margin. but again, there may be some surprises
the final analysis is what happens in november,'' dole said. ``electability's going to be a big, big factor. we don't want to lose the white house by nominating the wrong person.''
dole displayed a copy of monday's birmingham (ala.) post-herald, which published a survey saying that while bush is the strongest candidate among gop primary voters, dole is stronger among voters of all parties
i attract a lot of democrats and independents,'' dole said in commenting on the newspaper's poll, which surveyed 1,131 voters in 14 southern states. ``i don't think i scare anybody off. i think i attract a lot of people.''
the senator took a verbal shot at bush when asked whether the super tuesday series of primaries and caucuses, with gop events in 17 states and democratic events in 20 states and american samoa, was too big
i think what the democrats did was try to design a system where they would in effect select the democratic nominee. i'm not sure that's going to work,'' he said
but what could happen is that they might select the weakest republican, so they might get a consolation prize that way.''
on the gop side, he said that ``this is a race between bob dole and george bush.''
i would invite friends and supporters of (new york rep.) jack kemp and pat robertson to take a look at our candidacy and maybe join us tuesday night at polling places around the state,'' dole said
dole was joined at the news conference by oklahoma republican sen. don nickles and several gop members of the state legislature who are backing dole. nickles said dole is the best-qualified candidate to deal with the energy and agriculture industries vital to oklahoma, and predicted a victory on tuesday
you've been to this state many times and have been warmly received. i hope and expect you'll be warmly received on tuesday night as well,'' nickles said
dole, saying kansas football teams don't have much success in oklahoma, said: ``it's about time you give kansas a break, and give america a break by voting for bob dole tomorrow.''
a federal appeals court monday halted work on the navy's plans to relocate the aircraft carrier nimitz to everett, wash., a project that has been opposed by environmental groups
in a 3-0 decision, the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals ordered the navy to stop preliminary work on the $272 million project until an appeals board reviews a state permit, chiefly on the issue of how to dispose of contaminated sediment from harbor dredging
the washington shorelines hearing board began a final week of hearings monday on water quality and development permits for the project. a decision is scheduled in may or june. four votes are needed on the six-member board to reject the state permit
we fully expect that when the project receives full review ... there will be significant modifications,'' said victor sher, a lawyer for six environmental groups that oppose the dredging
the ruling means ``the navy must comply with state environmental laws, just like everybody else,'' he said
also opposing the project is the tulalip indian tribe, whose fishing grounds include everett bay
lt. cmdr. joe march, a spokesman for the home-port project, said he would study the ruling to see what options the navy has
the navy plans to relocate the nimitz and 12 support ships in everett harbor on puget sound, hoping to have the first ships arrive in 1992
the principal dispute is over the navy's plan to dredge about 3.4 million cubic yards of sediment from the harbor and dispose of it in port gardner bay near crab beds at depths of 310 to 430 feet. about a third of the sediment is contaminated with heavy metals and organic compounds, the court said
the navy plans to ``cap'' the contaminated dredging with a lawyer of clean sediment. but the court said the technique is experimental and has been criticized by the u.s. fish and wildlife service, which said the method had failed both times it had been tested at comparable depths. northern... pickup 5th graf pvs: the two men... subs 10th graf `he said' with 3 to include quote on threatening movements and reference to fourth person; pick up 11th: gasoline pumps at...</note>
british soldiers shot three ira members dead and britain said monday the killings averted a ``dreadful terrorist act'' in its fortress colony on the southern coast of spain
foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe said in london the soldiers opened fire sunday after the unarmed ira guerrillas parked a white renault-5 with spanish license plates near the convent, the official residence of the governor. he said the soldiers acted on a tip from spanish police
police said they were searching gibraltar and adjacent spanish territory for a car believed connected with a bomb attack the irish republican army allegedly planned at the governor's residence during the ceremonial changing of the guard, which hundreds of spectators attend
members of the royal anglian regiment, just transferred from duty in northern ireland, were scheduled to participate in the ceremony tuesday. the ira is fighting a guerrilla war to drive the british from northern ireland
in belfast, northern ireland, gangs of youths charged into the streets monday afternoon, throwing firebombs at buses, vans and trucks in violence that continued into the evening, police reported
bus service in roman catholic areas was halted after several buses were set afire
a police spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with british practice, said he did not know if the attacks were a reaction to the reports from gibraltar
the two men and a woman were shot by men described by witnesses as wearing jeans and speaking with british accents
the british soldiers were believed to be members of the special air services, or sas, an elite undercover unit that has been involved in previous actions against the ira
sgt. george field of the 220-man gibraltar police force said officers were looking for a ford automobile but did not believe it contained explosives
the independent spanish news agency europa press quoted police in madrid, however, as saying the car might contain explosives intended for an attack tuesday
howe acknowledged in his remarks to parliament that the three ira members were on foot and unarmed when they were killed sunday afternoon while heading for the spanish frontier
he said they were challenged and ``made movements which led security personnel to believe their lives were in danger.''
there is no doubt whatever that as a result of yesterday's events a dreadful terrorist act has been averted,'' howe said. ``the three people killed were actively involved in the planning and attempted execution of that act.''
the foreign secretary also said a fourth ira guerilla ``recently crossed into gibraltar and is thought to have carried out a reconnaissance for an act of terrorism.''
gasoline pumps at the shell service station where two were shot down bore several bullet holes police had marked with blue arrows. about 100 hundred yards up the avenue, where the third fell, white marks on a large tree indicated more bullet holes
howe said the soldiers found keys to a second car on the body of one of the men. that car, a red ford fiesta registered in spain, was found parked in la linea de la concepcion on the spanish side of the gate separating this 2.25-square-mile limestone rock from the spanish mainland
in the ford, police found three false passports, an alarm clock, insulating tape, gloves, wire and a set of keys to the third car, which police are searching for, howe said
he said reports that the renault contained several hundred pounds of explosives were unfounded
europa press said spanish police speculated that the ira members left the renault near the convent to make sure there would be space for the third car, which they planned to park on tuesday rigged as a as a car bomb
the ira identified the dead as mairead farrell, 31, who served 10 years in prison for bombing a belfast hotel; daniel mccann, 30, and sean savage, 24, all of west belfast. the men had been arrested on charges of possessing explosives
sir peter terry, the governor and commander-in-chief of british forces in the colony, issued a statement praising the 30,000 residents and said the people of gibraltar showed ``their determination to stand alongside all british people in their fight against international terrorism.''
augustin valladolid, spokesman for spanish state security, said in madrid that spanish police spotted the three ira members on the southern costa del sol more than a month ago and told british authorities, who requested surveillance but no intervention
el pais, spain's leading daily, said they left spain a week ago, probably for britain, ``but planned to return to malaga and did.'' it quoted spanish police as saying they followed the trio ``right up to the gate'' of gibraltar
in parliament, howe expressed gratitude to spanish authorities, ``without whose invaluable assistance the outcome might have been very different.''
gibraltar is a sore point in relations between britain and spain, which claims sovereignty over the rock it ceded in 1713 after losing the war of spanish succession. to update with comment from ms. desillers, picking up 12th graf pvs, `she said through...'.</note>
bank accounts containing what's left of the fortune donated to save liver-transplant patient ronnie desillers were frozen monday after a judge was told the dead boy's mother had spent some of the charity money on jewelry, clothes and furniture, a state attorney said
dade circuit judge francis christie appointed a curator to manage the estate in accordance with a petition filed by state attorney general robert butterworth and state attorney janet reno of miami
ronnie's mother, maria desillers, has spent more than half of the money donated to her 7-year-old son, who died last year while awaiting a fourth transplant, the petition said
among the donors was president reagan, who like many others was touched by news reports of the theft of funds raised by ronnie's classmates. he gave $1,000
when ronnie died at children's hospital of pittsburgh last april 29, an account in his name had accumulated $509,913, the petition said. the account balance on feb. 17 was $239,288, said fred kerstein, assistant state attorney and chief of the economic criminal division
as recently as jan. 19, 1988, $25,000 had been withdrawn from the fund, ``thereby further depleting the assets of the estate,'' the petition said
based upon an examination of bank records, at least $47,000 appears to have been expended by maria desillers on jewelry, clothing, furniture, housing expenses, an automobile and automobile expenses, these funds having been assets of this estate,'' it said. there was no further breakdown of the expenditures in the petition
asked about the allegations in the petition, ms. desillers said: ``why do they not say that money went to charity? why do they not say that some of that money was assigned to me personally? ... how come they don't say how much of that money went to kids?''
she said she had already planned to use the money that was frozen to help two ailing children who are awaiting transplants, one from miami and the other from costa rica, and would go to probate court to straighten out the dispute
there are two children that have less than six months to live, and that's what i want to do with the money,'' she said
ms. desillers is being sued by children's hospital for failing to pay $261,189 of ronnie's $424,302 bill
in refusing to pay the balance, ms. desillers charged the hospital with giving poor care to her son and threatened to file a malpractice suit
ms. desillers and her lawyer, harold robbins, said last month they would refuse to pay a $1,000 state fine for allegedly violating florida charity laws
she said through robbins that she had never asked the public to donate money and she was not legally a charity. she also said she was entitled to the money as ronnie's sole heir
after ronnie's death, ms. desillers created the foundation to assist other children in need of organ transplants
she returned to the limelight when it was learned that the formerly unemployed public relations agent was living in a luxury apartment building and driving a bmw equipped with a telephone
she denied squandering any of the donations, explaining that the car was second-hand, the car telephone was a gift and the apartment doubled as her office
the petition filed by butterworth and ms. reno asked that ronnie's estate be frozen ``to prevent additional assets of the estate ... from being wasted and to protect persons interested in the estate, including creditors.''
immediate and irreparable injury will result to assets of the estate ... if maria desillers is permitted to withdraw the funds,'' the petition said
attorney karen geivers was appointed estate curator, kerstein said
the first inmates arrive tuesday at camp sauble for 90-day terms of hard labor and military-style discipline that officials hope will keep the young offenders out of the prison system
it is michigan's first experiment with a probationary program that has caught on in other states. the so-called ``boot camp,'' one of about 15 such programs in seven states, is a last stop for young, first-time felons who otherwise would have been sent to prison for at least a year
a lot of the people put into the corrections system have never been held accountable for anything in their lives, and as a result, have never had any pride,'' deputy warden stanley adams said. ``here, we hope they'll leave with a sense of accomplishment because they'll be held accountable for everything they do.''
everything'' includes how their hair is trimmed to how their beds are made and how their uniforms are buttoned
the first dozen of an eventual 156 probationers are expected by the end of the week at camp sauble, a former state corrections department minimum-security work camp tucked away in manistee national forest in northeast michigan. inmates must be between the ages of 17 and 25 and never have been in the prison system before
the inmates will rise at 5 a.m. each day and prepare for an inspection of bunks and uniforms. after breakfast, they will fall in for an exercise period before heading out for about seven hours of unpaid work in and around mason county
before dinner, there will be more physical training and calisthenics, and after dinner inmates will attend academic or substance-abuse treatment programs. one hour will be allowed nightly to write letters or watch television news before lights go out at 10 p.m
military protocol will be enforced strictly. inmates will be required to stand at attention when in the presence of an instructor and will receive demerits for violations
if an inmate commits a serious crime, such as the assault of a staff member or fellow inmate, or if he receives three misconduct charges, he will be returned to the judge who sentenced him, likely resulting in a prison sentence
if a candidate passes the program successfully, he will be freed on probation
some say the program is an effective way to jolt first-time offenders into straightening out. others claim it is a ploy by politicians who want their constituents to believe they're tough on crime
one such critic is jerry miller, executive director of national alternatives to incarceration
the people in these programs are usually from families where yelling and screaming and putting down are day-to-day occurrences, so a program like this isn't going to scare them,'' said miller, whose non-profit organization, based in alexandria, va., studies programs that keep offenders out of prison. rage</head> graf: `the guerrillas ... aroer junction.' picks up 22nd graf pvs, `the arab ...</note>
three palestinian guerrillas seized a commuter bus monday and held nuclear plant workers hostage, killing three israeli civilians and wounding nine before police shot the hijackers to death, officials said
the palestine liberation organization claimed responsibility, saying in a statement released in nicosia, cyprus, that the hijacking was part of ``escalating military action'' against israel
the statement said the guerrillas launched the attack from within israel, and did not infiltrate from a neighboring country
israeli army officials said the guerrillas infiltrated from egypt and held 10 women and one man hostage for about three hours. the bus was seized as it shuttled workers of the top-secret dimona nuclear plant
in the occupied territories, at least 12 arabs were shot monday during clashes with israeli troops, and the army said palestinian protesters hurled a grenade at troops, wounding one soldier slightly in the west bank village of idna
also, more than 20 arab tax collectors in the gaza strip submitted mass resignations after underground leaflets called for palestinians to quit working for israel's military administration. an army official says the resignations are not final
israeli analysts said escalating violence could harden the position of prime minister yitzhak shamir and the right-wing likud bloc, which has not accepted the peace initiatives of u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz
defense minister yitzhak rabin told israel's knesset, or parliament, that monday's bus victims ``were killed for mothing else but for their being jewish, residents of israel.''
in an anonymous telephone call to a western news agency in israel, a man said the hijacking was the work of plo's force 17, a palestinian commando group linked to plo chairman yasser arafat
if the commandos did come from egypt, it would mark the eighth infiltration into israel from egypt, jordan or lebanon since late november
shamir said the infiltrations and the three months of violence in the occupied west bank and gaza strip were part of a plo strategy
these are the same people who incite violence in the (occupied) territories. we shall not tire from fighting them,'' shamir said on israel radio
in washington, state department spokesman charles redman condemned the hijacking and noted ``with sadness that at a time when the majority ... are looking for a peaceful solution of the arab-israeli conflict, terrorists emerge to attack the innocents.''
foreign minister shimon peres, a leader of israel's doves, said the hijacking was an indication of why israel refused to deal with arafat
this shows exactly why the plo is a disaster for both arabs and jews,'' peres said
lt. gen. dan shomron, the armed forces chief of staff, said the guerrillas crossed the lightly guarded border from egypt, and he criticized egyptian authorities for not doing more to stop such infiltrations
army officials said the terrorists were armed with fragmentation grenades, two soviet kalashnikov assault rifles and a swedish-made karl gustav submachine gun
the arab gunmen first seized a small military vehicle at about 7 a.m. near the nafha prison, a few miles from the sinai desert border with egypt
the guerrillas, riding in the captured vehicle, went on a rampage along the highway, shooting at passing cars and trucks and wounding one israeli man in the leg, police officials said
police chased the car and shot out a tire, forcing the guerrillas to abandon the vehicle, police said
the guerrillas then seized the red-and-white bus carrying workers to the dimona nuclear plant, during which the bus' driver and all but 11 passengers escaped. police later stopped the vehicle by barricading the road near the aroer junction
the arab trio was headed toward beersheva, away from the nuclear facility, when they seized the bus, indicating the facility was not the target of the guerrillas
the guerrillas gave israeli authorities one hour to produce an international red cross official and free jailed palestinians
they presented an ultimatum. if their demand were not met within half an hour, including the release of detainees and palestinian terrorists, they will (kill) the hostages,'' said maj. gen. yitzhak mordechai, the army's southern commander
moments later, mordechai said, the guerrilla leader fatally shot in the chest victor ran, 39, the father of three children
when they fired and executed one of the hostages and fired at the women who were in the bus, despite our promises that we will not harm them ... we stormed the bus and killed the three terrorists,'' mordechai said on israel radio
he said the assault by anti-terror police lasted about one minute
rina shiratzky, 31, the mother of two, and miriam ben yair, 46, the mother of four, were fatally wounded when israeli soldiers stormed the bus
mordechai said an investigation showed the shots were fired by the arab guerrillas
cardinal jozef glemp, leader of poland's roman catholic church, said monday he has been invited to visit moscow in early june for ceremonies marking the 1,000th anniversary of russian christendom
no polish primate has ever visited the soviet union
glemp said he received the invitation last month to attend observances organized by the russian orthodox church
there have been no talks yet,'' glemp told reporters at warsaw's okecie airport after returning from a weeklong visit to rome, where he met with polish-born pope john paul ii. ``i only got a formal invitation. i want to go, obviously.''
church sources have said a visit by glemp to the soviet union could help pave the way for a future visit there by the pope
in january, john paul said he would visit the soviet union only if he could meet with roman catholics around the country
glemp has let it be known he would like to visit the soviet union, especially former polish territories in the soviet lithuanian republic that has a large polish minority and where the catholic faith is quite strong
asked whether he planned to visit other places than moscow, glemp said he ``might change from an official church representative into a tourist for a few hours ... with pleasure because there are many things to see there.''
the soviet invitation reflects a turnaround since mikhail s. gorbachev came to power three years ago
the soviets previously attacked the polish church for inspiring opposition activities, but more recently have made overtures to polish catholics
almost 90 percent of poland's population is catholic. apartment</head>
an unemployed handyman waived his right to a jury monday and his trial began on charges of killing seven women and leaving their bodies to rot in and near his apartment
harrison ``marty'' graham's decision came as common pleas judge robert latrone prepared to begin jury selection. graham then entered pleas of innocent to seven counts each of murder, voluntary manslaughter and abuse of a corpse
the judge, after determining graham, 28, understood the charges, ordered the lawyers to begin presenting their cases. both sides waived opening statements
assistant district attorney roger king moved for admission of all testimony and documents from a monthlong pretrial suppression hearing, including a confession graham made to police, admitting strangling the seven women during sex. latrone granted the request
during the pretrial hearing, defense attorney joel moldovsky, contending his client is mentally incompetent, sought unsuccessfully to suppress the confession
moldovsky argued the confession was made in violation of graham's constitutional rights and after graham allegedly was beaten by police during 17 hours of interrogation
graham surrendered to police at his mother's urging aug. 16 after a weeklong manhunt that started when he was evicted from his apartment because of a putrid stench
a police search uncovered the rotting bodies in graham's bedroom and leg and foot bones on the roof of his apartment house
in the confession, graham told police the bodies began piling up in his bedroom and he began having problems with maggots. he also told of his difficulty sleeping during the day because of birds on the roof outside his apartment, picking at human remains
moldovsky has indicated that graham's defense will be insanity
the first witness called by the prosecution, acting medical examiner robert catherman, said all seven deaths were homicides but said it was impossible in most cases to determine the cause of death because of decomposition
soldiers in tanks and jeeps patrolled the main streets and poorer areas of the capital monday to block further protests against the rising cost of living
president joaquin balaguer summoned his advisers to discuss ways of controlling inflation, a major factor in recent unrest in this caribbean island nation of more than 6.5 million people
protesters burned tires early monday during a 24-hour strike in five low-income sectors of santo domingo
three days of clashes last week between protesters and soldiers left one person dead and many businesses damaged. more than 300 people were arrested
the previous week, three people were killed and eight injured in protests in eight of the country's 26 provinces
support seemed to be dwindling for a general strike called for wednesday to demand lower prices for basic commodities, wage increases for public and private workers and better public services
we are willing to talk and hold sincere discussions with the authorities to solve the conflict as long as they manifest their sincere willingness to satisfy our demands,'' said spokeswoman virtudes alvarez of the national conference of popular organizations
the group called for the general strike and organized earlier strikes in the last few weeks that shut down many parts of the capital
labor groups opposed the strike, but promised to support it if it takes place. they want either a later strike or talks among the government, unions and business community to try to solve the economic problems
the main opposition party, the dominican revolutionary party, is also against the strike, although left-wing political parties support it
balaguer said sunday he would meet with his agricultural advisers, merchants and business people to develop a plan to implement price controls
shortages of many goods, including milk, have become prevalent
a private economist estimated the february inflation rate at about 5 percent and predicted a 50 to 60 percent rate for 1988 if that continued
private sources have estimated inflation in 1987 at around 30 percent, although the government's central bank maintains it was closer to 16 percent
the author of a petition on religious freedom in communist czechoslovakia that was signed by about 300,000 people has been arrested and charged with slander, an emigre source said monday
the london-based emigre publishing firm palach press said augustin navratil was accused of committing ``slander of a state organ and of a public organization.'' conviction is punishiable by up to one year in prison
the exact targets of the purported slander were not spelled out
navratil, a roman catholic activist from a village in moravia, was one of 16 people detained over the weekend in advance of a catholic pilgrimage in prague sunday
dissident sources in prague said navratil was detained friday morning. other activists were held for 48 hours and released late sunday or early monday, the sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity
palach press said it was not clear if stanislav devaty, a spokesman for the charter 77 human rights movement, was rearrested after his 48-hour detention expired
in czechoslovakia, authorities may hold people for 48 hours without formal charges
dissident sources said devaty was detained late friday night after attending a dinner with british diplomats in an embassy secretary's apartment
five other dissident activists invited to the dinner were detained before they could get in, and that action drew a strong protest from the british foreign office
navratil's petition calls for separation of church and state and for bishops to fill czechoslovakia's 10 empty roman catholic sees
cardinal frantisek tomasek gave unprecedented support to the petition in a letter of jan. 4
palach press also reported that in a separate development, 12 people were briefly detained saturday in prague as they left the home of a granddaughter of thomas g. masaryk, president of czechoslovakia's pre-world war ii democracy
it said the group had planned a graveside ceremony on sunday honoring masaryk in the village of lany, about 30 miles west of prague
