the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell .50 to 149.93. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was down .87 at 292.87
on friday the dow jones industrial average slipped 5.63 to 2,057.86, reducing its gain for the week to 34.65 points
declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 4 on the nyse, with 670 up, 812 down and 480 unchanged. big board volume totaled 201.41 million shares, against 203.31 million in the previous session. with stock price; picks up 7th graf pvs, firestone stock.</note>
italian tire manufacturer pirelli today launched a $1.86 billion offer for firestone tire and rubber co., complicating firestone's plan to sell 75 percent of its tire-making division to bridgestone of japan
pirelli, in an advertisement in the wall street journal, offered $58 a share cash for all 32 million firestone common shares outstanding
pirelli said in a statement today its offer was conditioned on acquiring at least two-thirds of firestone's shares, on the agreement beween firestone and bridgestone not being signed and on the removal of firestone's anti-takeover defenses
we won't have anything more to say until the board has had an opportunity to make a review. i would expect that would begin immediately,'' firestone spokesman robert troyer told the akron beacon journal on sunday in a telephone interview from chicago, home of firestone's corporate headquarters
an acquisition of firestone would substantially increase pirelli's current 1.5 percent share of the u.s. tire market, the world's largest. it would also give the italian company its first manufacturing facilities in the united states
wall street analysts had speculated on thursday that pirelli would make an offer for firestone
firestone's stock leaped $11.37{ a share in early trading today to $61 a share, above pirelli's $58-a-share offer, indicating that speculators expected an even higher offer to emerge
firestone stock closed at $49.62{ friday, up $5.50 for the week in heavy trading. nearly 4.2 million shares of firestone's common stock changed hands last week, compared with about 850,000 in an average week
it was not immediately clear what effect an investment or takeover attempt by pirelli would have on the pending proposed joint venture between firestone and bridgestone corp. firestone's board and ultimately shareholders will have to decide which offer to accept
pirelli could block the bridgestone deal if it was able to purchase a sufficient number of firestone shares
pirelli said today that if it was successful in its bid for firestone, it would spin off parts of the company to the french group michelin
michelin would pay about $650 million to acquire firestone's brazilian holdings as well as master care inc., firestone's u.s. service company, pirelli said
michelin would also have an option to buy 50 percent of firestone's synthetic rubber and diversified product holdings in the united states for about $150 million
on feb. 16, bridgestone and firestone said they intended to form a new akron-based tire business, to be called firestone tire co., that would own firestone's worldwide tire manufacturing operation. bridgestone would own 75 percent of the joint venture
firestone chairman john j. nevin has said the company wants to distribute to shareholders ``a very substantial portion'' of about $1 billion in cash that would be generated by the joint venture
firestone has been considered an attractive target for both foreign-based companies because of their interest in gaining u.s. market share
troyer said bridgestone officials were notified upon learning of possible action by pirelli on sunday
at the time the $1.5 billion bridgestone deal was announced, firestone's board approved an anti-takeover measure that took effect tuesday
that measure would raise the cost of a takeover by creating a special class of preferred stock in the event an individual or group acquired 20 percent or more, or made a tender offer for 20 percent or more, of firestone's stock without approval of the board
in a letter to shareholders released last week, nevin said the anti-takeover plan was not intended to prevent a fair offer for the shares of the company and should not deter anyone from acquiring the company if the buyer gives shareholders full value and negotiates in good faith
pirelli, headquartered in milan, had sales of $3.65 billion last year
the supreme court today agreed to hear a reagan administration appeal aimed at allowing the government to take a bigger tax bite out of some corporate mergers
the court said it will review a ruling stemming from the acquisition of a small west virginia company by a corporation traded on the new york stock exchange
the smaller company, basin surveys inc., was owned by donald e. clark of buckhannon, w.va. it provides services to the petroleum industry
clark sold the business in 1979 to n.l. industries of new york, which produces petroleum equipment, chemicals and metals
n.l. industries gave clark 300,000 shares of its stock and $3.25 million to acquire basin surveys
at issue in the case was whether the cash payment, commonly called ``boot,'' should be taxed as a capital gain or considered a dividend and taxed as ordinary income. generally, the capital gain tax rate is lower
the tax reform bill enacted in 1986 eliminated the different tax rates for capital gains and ordinary income
but the administration said the different treatment will still apply to some corporate shareholders
also, in urging the court to consider the government appeal, justice department lawyers said congress sometime in the future might restore for all taxpayers the different treatment of ordinary income and capital gains
the 4th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled in favor of clark last september, sparing him from paying $972,505 in taxes
the appeals court said, ``we regard the boot as a cash payment by n.l. in return for clark's relinquishment of a portion of his interest in the newly reorganized corporation. because clark surrendered more than 20 percent of his interest in n.l., he is entitled to capital gain treatment.''
the appeals court arrived at the 20 percent figure by noting that n.l. industries offere clark two choices in the merger: he could receive either 425,000 shares of n.l. stock or 300,000 shares plus $3.25 million in cash
the appeals court said clark, by choosing the latter option, in effect gave up more than 20 percent of his interest in n.l. industries in return for the cash
the appeals court said that under federal law a shareholder who relinquishes more than 20 percent of his corporate control and is less than a 50 percent shareholder after the transaction is entitled to have cash proceeds from the transaction treated as capital gains
justice department lawyers said the ruling is in conflict with decisions by other federal appeals courts. they said the supreme court should eliminate the confusion
the case is commissioner of internal revenue vs. clark, 87-1168
manufacturers hanover corp., wounded from possibly uncollectable third world loans, is seeking to sell its profitable consumer finance unit to raise capital, the wall street journal reported monday
quoting banking sources it did not identify, the newspaper said the nation's sixth-largest banking concern is asking between $500 million and $600 million for huntingdon valley, pa.-based manufacturers hanover consumer services inc., which has about $3 billion in assets
the banking company has been forced to take austerity measures because of a $1.14 billion loss last year, due mainly to a $1.7 billion addition to reserves that reflected the questionable collectability of some third world loans, a problem afflicting many american banks
john meyers, a manufacturers hanover spokesman in new york, said he could not comment on the journal report. but he said the bank has consistently stated it would rebuild capital partly via property sales and expense cuts
we've said all along there is a host of assets we can realize gains on,'' meyers said. ``it is part of our game plan to get shareholder equity replenished.''
banking industry analysts have said manufacturers hanover's consumer finance business is considered highly prized and profitable within the company, so a sale would reflect on the seriousness of the bank's capital needs
on the other hand, the consumer finance unit is a stand-alone operation, so it could be sold much more easily that other company property
