livestock and meat futures closed mostly higher on friday
production in the u.s. paper industry appears poised for a third consecutive record-breaking year as demand remains strong for all major grades of paper and paperboard, an industry trade association said monday
the american paper institute, a trade association for american pulp, paper and paperboard companies, said production is running at a rate of 75 million tons a year, or about 3 percent above its pace at the same point last year
production for all of 1987 amounted to a record 74.4 million tons, up from 70.9 million tons in 1986, and is expected to rise by about 2 percent in 1988, according to figures supplied by the trade association
the group's forecast was released as it began its national conference
the institute's president, red cavaney, said the forecast for 1988 presumes avoiding a recession, a pro-growth trade policy, a fairly low interest rate climate and no major tax increases
last year was also a record in terms of the dollar value of paper and paperboard sales, the group said. it said it expects final figures for 1987 will show sales of about $87 billion, or 16 percent more than the previous high of $74.8 billion set in 1986
the paper industry derived its strength in 1987 from heightened demand in the various markets its serves, the institute said
demand for white papers, for instance, reflected trends such as increased use of office copy and computer printout papers and of envelopes
strength in direct-mail advertising helped fuel robust growth in commercial printing, stimulating printing paper demand, the paper institute said
paperboard production set a record last year as packaged goods production surged, triggering increased demand for paper used for shipping containers, folding cartons and fiber cans, the institute said
newspapers and the high quality color-printed advertising pieces that retailers and businesses use to reach their customers performed strongly in 1987, the group said, pushing newsprint production to a new high last year
exports of market pulp and paper products reached a high in 1987 as a decline in the dollar made them more competitive with prices charged overseas, the institute said
while sales surged in 1987, so did the profits of paper companies that had already begun aggressive cost-containment programs, the institute said
it said after-tax profits in the u.s. paper industry rose 56 percent in the first three quarters of 1987, reaching a decade high of 5.7 percent of sales
businesses that lose money from the sale of stock aren't entitled to special tax breaks no matter why the stock was purchased, the supreme court decided today
the court, voting 8-0, ruled against an arkansas conglomerate that sought to claim as an ordinary-loss deduction for federal tax purposes a $10 million loss from the sale of stock in a texas bank it once controlled
arkansas best corp. of fort smith in 1969 had acquired more than 65 percent of the stock of national bank of commerce, the fourth largest bank in dallas
congress passed a law in 1970 that prohibited conglomerates that owned a bank from expanding their non-bank business through new acquisitions in other industries
arkansas best, which owns trucking, furniture manufacturing, data processing and other businesses, decided to divest itself of the bank stock. the 1970 law gave it 10 years to sell the bank stock
because of public awareness that arkansas best was under legal obligation to divest itself, disposing of the bank stock without taking a big loss was difficult
at the same time, the bank's finances were deteriorating. arkansas best therefore acquired additional stock in the bank in an attempt to keep it solvent
the conglomerate began selling off the bank stock in 1975, and sought to claim the losses as ordinary losses rather than capital losses _ a tax advantage
the internal revenue service ruled that the losses suffered by arkansas best were capital losses. the irs rejected arkansas best's arguments that the stock was not bought for typical investment purposes but for business purposes _ and therefore its sale should yield ordinary losses
the 8th u.s. circuit court of appeals agreed with the irs but other federal appeals courts had reached conflicting conclusions
writing for the high court today, justice thurgood marshall said motivation behind the stock purchase is irrelevant ``to the question whether the asset is property held by a taxpayer ... and is thus within (federal tax law's) general definition of capital asset.''
because the capital stock held by (arkansas best) falls within the broad definition of the term `capital asset' in (the tax code) and is outside the classes of property excluded from capital-asset status, the loss arising from the sale of the stock is a capital loss,'' marshall said
justice anthony m. kennedy did not participate in the decision
the case is arkansas best vs. commissioner of internal revenue, 86-751
bond prices and interest rates stabilized in quiet early trading today following friday's sell-off
the market seems to be on dead center right now,'' said marshall b. front, an economist at stein roe &amp; farnham, a chicago investment and mutual-fund management firm. ``there doesn't seem to be any news affecting the market.''
by midday, the treasury's 30-year bond was up about 1-32 point while its yield, which moves inversely to its price, slipped to 8.46 percent from 8.47 percent late friday
the bellwether issue had plunged about two points, or $20 per $1,000 in face amount, on friday, after the government reported unexpectedly high february employment levels, raising doubts about forecasts of an economic slowdown later this year
the government said the economy created half a million jobs last month, dropping the civilian unemployment rate to 5.7 percent, its lowest since 1979. the january rate had been 5.8 percent
front said the market was currently involved in a ``tug of war'' of sorts on the outlook for interest rates
the bulls point to lower commodity prices _ the price of gold continues to fall, oil prices continue to slip _ and other signs of weakness in economic activity,'' he said. ``the bears look at the employment numbers ... which were shockingly good and say ... the economy is likely to accelerate
i think a lot of people are going back to their drawing boards.''
interest rates have fallen sharply since fears of recession surfaced after the stock market crash five months ago. but bondholders worry that with some signs of economic growth, the federal reserve may want to tighten its credit policies, thus pushing interest rates higher, to prevent inflation from heating up
in the secondary market for treasury bonds today, prices of short-term governments were unchanged, intermediate maturities rose 1-32 point and 20-year issues were off 1-32 point, according to figures provided by telerate inc
the movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the price of a bond with a $1,000 face value
the merrill lynch daily treasury index, which measures price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with maturities of a year or longer, fell 0.01 to 113.3. the shearson lehman daily treasury bond index, which makes a similar measurement, lost 0.04 to 1,183.34
in corporate trading, industrials and utilities were unchanged in light trading, according to the investment firm of salomon brothers inc
moody's investment grade corporate bond index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, was off 0.06 to 284.36
yields on three-month treasury bills were up 2 basis points to 5.72 percent. a basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. six-month bills -fell 1 basis point to 5.94 percent and one-year bills were unchanged at 6.27 percent
the federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, traded at 6 9-16 percent, up from 6{ percent late friday
leading foodmaker h.j. heinz co. reported a 22 percent surge in third-quarter earnings monday, attributing the improvement to higher sales volume, acquisitions and the beneficial effects of a cheaper dollar
the company said earnings for the three months ended jan. 27 totaled $91 million or 69 cents a share, compared with $74.7 million or 55 cents a share in the year-earlier period. sales totaled $1.25 billion vs. $1.08 billion, a 15 percent rise
we are encouraged by the earnings record achieved to date through our existing business base as well as the superior market opportunities offered by our strategic world-wide acquisitions,'' said chairman anthony j.f. o'reilly. ``we are optimistic that we will again achieve fiscal year results consisted with our historical trends.''
the pittsburgh-based company embarked on a series of acquisitions last year, notably in the pet-food business, in which it bought mavar and california home brands, two american concerns. heinz also recently acquired orlando s.a., an important spanish food company
the dollar's depreciation also helped heinz because its u.s.-produced foods became more competitive overseas. at the same time, profits from goods produced and sold by heinz's foreign operations rose when converted into dollars
for the nine-months ended jan. 27, heinz said it earned $284.3 million or $2.14 a share, a 16.3 percent gain over the $244.4 million or $1.78 a share in the year-earlier period. sales rose 13 percent from $3.3 billion to $3.8 billion
