share prices fell monday on the london stock exchange as the british pound rose in foreign-exchange markets, making british exports more expensive
at the close, the financial times-stock exchange 100-share index was down 16.3 points, or 0.88 percent, at 1818.2
a moderate 404.8 million shares were traded, down from 579.7 million on friday which had been the most active session since dec. 18
dealers said banks and other financial stocks were among the worst affected. companies heavily involved in exports to continental europe also lost ground
steel production fell to 1.971 million tons in the week ended march 5, a decrease of 1.5 percent from the previous week's 2.002 million tons, the american iron and steel institute reported monday
the industry's production amounted to 91.8 percent of capacity during the week, compared with 93.2 percent in the previous week
estimated figures for the year to date showed production at 17.769 million net tons, an increase of 38.4 percent from the 12.837 million net tons in the previous year. the steel operations of usx corp., the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down by a strike during the first month of 1987
production so far this year used 89.1 percent of capacity, compared with 64.9 percent a year earlier
net tonnage by district for the week ended march 5: northeast coast, 284,000; pittsburgh, 194,000; youngstown, 122,000; lake erie, 167,000; detroit, 172,000; chicago, 518,000; midwest, 197,000; southern, 221,000; and western, 97,000
grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly higher monday on the chicago board of trade, while soybean futures were mixed
expectations of new export business supported prices, analysts said
they said friday's massive sell-off of soybean futures swept a good deal of speculative interest from the soybean market, leaving it listless and quiet
at the close, wheat was } cent to 2 cents higher with the contract for delivery in march at $3.04 a bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 2} cents higher with march at $2.00} a bushel; oats were \ cent to 4 cents higher with march at $1.90} a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 2{ cents higher with march at $6.14 a bushel
the number of oil and gas rigs working in the united states decreased by five this week to total 978, baker hughes inc. announced
the total reflects the number of rigs actively exploring for oil as of last friday, not the number of rigs producing oil. the previous week, the count had increased by five to 983
a year ago, the rig count was 766, baker hughes announced monday
houston-based baker hughes, an oil toolmaker, tallies the number of working rigs and the count is the widely-watched industry index of drilling activity
hughes tool co., which merged last year with baker international corp. of orange, calif., has kept track of the number of working rigs since 1940
the rig count reached a peak of 4,500 active rigs in december 1981 _ the height of the oil boom. but as oil prices plunged to less than $10 per 42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986, the count fell to 663, the lowest since hughes began compiling figures
among the major oil producing states, oklahoma gained seven rigs this week, wyoming gained five, while colorado, new mexico and ohio increased by two each
the rig count in michigan dropped by one, while california, kansas, and louisiana each lost three. texas and pennsylvania each lost four rigs and wyoming's rig count dropped by five
the stock market drifted aimlessly in quiet trading today amid concern over the interest-rate outlook
prices declined slightly in the bond market today, pushing yields on long-term treasury bonds up to the neighborhood of 8.5 percent. developments late last week raised concern that the drop in interest rates since last fall had about run its course
rates rose sharply on friday after the labor department reported much stronger growth in employment than expected for february
if the economy is robust enough to support a big increase in jobs, credit-market traders reason, the federal reserve is unlikely to take any further steps soon to relax its credit policy
given that prospect, investors seemed to be focusing their attention mainly on numerous stocks involved in takeovers and other deals
the dow jones average of 30 industrials slipped 1.49 to 2,056.37
advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 6 to 5 on the new york stock exchange, with 845 up, 710 down and 416 unchanged
big board volume totaled 152.58 million shares, down from 201.41 million in the previous session. the nyse's composite index edged up .10 to 150.53
a significant number of american companies will bolster hiring this spring, a leading temporary job service said monday in an unusually optimistic quarterly forecast on u.s. employment
manpower inc. said its employment outlook survey indicated 29 percent of respondents plan to raise employment rolls in the april-june quarter, while 6 percent expect declines. sixty-two percent plan no change and 3 percent don't know, the survey stated
mitchell s. fromstein, manpower president, said it was the strongest spring hiring forecast in four years and suggested manufacturers in all regions of the country are unusually buoyant about the economy
makers of large durable goods are among the most optimistic of all employers, with 32 percent planning payroll increases and 7 percent planning cutbacks, the survey showed
among construction companies, 36 percent anticipate payroll increases and 7 percent anticipate cutbacks. among retailers, 31 percent plan increased payrolls and 6 percent plan decreases
even in the financial services industry, which was particularly affected by the october collapse in stock prices, the spring hiring forecast was still optimistic. twenty-three percent of respondents plan to add employees and 7 percent will cut back
manpower has issued the quarterly survey for the past 12 years and calls it as a significant indicator of employment trends
conducted in last two weeks of february, the survey was based on telephone interviews with more than 13,000 public and private employers in 401 u.s. cities. the margin of error is 5 percent, the company said
based in milwaukee, manpower describes itself as the world's largest temporary service firm, annually providing jobs to more than 700,000 people through 1,350 offices in 33 countries
consumers have regained virtually all the confidence they lost as a result of the october stock market crash, but there are indications employers could be cutting back their hiring plans, according to two surveys released monday
the conference board, in issuing its monthly consumer confidence index, said consumers have been heartened by continuing strength in the economy
however, the business research organization said consumers also may be feeling more optimistic because their paychecks are larger because of tax cuts that took effect jan. 1
the consumer confidence index was 113.9 points in february, up from january's 109.9 points and 100.8 in november, after the crash
the index, which uses a 1985 base of 100, stood at 115.1 in october, before the oct. 19 stock collapse
the conference board's help wanted index painted a somewhat less optimistic picture. the index, which reflects the amount of help wanted ads in 51 major newspapers across the nation, declined to 153 in january from 155 in december
the index, which uses a 1967 base of 100, reflects changes in demand for labor and general business conditions
kenneth goldstein, a conference board economist, said the drop in the index signaled a slowdown in hiring plans by employers
recent dips in want ad volume suggest that companies are taking a hard look at their expansion plans,'' he said
help wanted advertising volume fell in six of nine regions of the country: new england, the rockies, pacific, south atlantic, middle atlantic and east south central. ad volume increased in the west north central, east north central and west south central areas
takeover news and speculation provided most of the excitement in an otherwise quiet, drifting stock market session monday
analysts said the general market was held back by new doubts about the outlook for interest rates
