livestock and meat futures prices rose sharply monday as traders looked beyond the cash market's current problems and saw meat sales improving in the months ahead
on other markets, energy futures slid lower; grains and soybeans were mostly higher; precious metals retreated; and stock-index futures advanced
slack retail demand for meat during lent led to a slowdown in slaughters last week, prompting fears of a growing supply of slaughter-ready cattle and hogs
analysts said those fears, along with the closing of at least one major beef packing plant, were largely responsible for losses on livestock futures last week at the chicago mercantile exchange
but indications of a cattle buildup did not surface monday, leading many traders to rethink their positions and look ahead to a resurgence in demand after easter, analysts said
prices went down last week on ideas we were backing up cattle (but) we haven't seen any proof of that yet,'' said charlie richardson, an analyst in denver for lind-waldock &amp; co
in chicago, philip stanley of thomson-mckinnon securities inc. said traders had turned their attention to the future and away from the industry's current woes
they're thinking that retail demand will pick up, packers will have to accumulate supplies and the cattle feeders will reap the profits by being able to sell cattle at higher prices,'' stanley said
richardson said some traders also bought livestock futures on ideas that prices for future delivery of cattle and hogs had fallen more sharply than conditions warranted
and some were betting that a winter storm moving into the great plains would disrupt the movement of animals to market, resulting in temporarily tight supplies and higher prices, richardson said
the bullish enthusiasm for cattle futures overflowed into the pork pits, analysts said
live cattle settled .87 cent to 1.38 cents higher with the contract for delivery in april at 71.55 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .80 cent to 1.10 cents higher with march at 80.35 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent to 1.25 cents higher with april at 43.60 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.20 cents to 1.85 cents higher with march at 54.70 cents a pound
energy futures prices retreated in moderate trading on the new york mercantile exchange following a slight advance in the previous session
analysts attributed the decline to speculation that some member nations of the organization of petroleum exporting countries were selling oil at a discount
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 15 cents to 22 cents lower with april at $15.37 a barrel; heating oil was .13 cent to .25 cent lower with april at 43.41 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .34 cent to .57 cent lower with april at 43.94 cents a gallon
grain and soybean futures finished mostly higher on the chicago board of trade, although soybean futures were mixed
expectations of new export business supported the markets
the agriculture department announced after the close that it had sold 1.6 million bushels of wheat friday in the last of last week's three auctions for surplus, government-owned wheat
the usda had targeted 10 million bushels for sale at that auction
the agency also announced it would hold three auctions a week, each with a 10-million-bushel target, through march 25
wheat settled } cent to 2 cents higher with march at $3.04 a bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 2} cents higher with march at $2.00} a bushel; oats were \ cent to 4 cents higher with march at $1.90} a bushel; soybeans were 1\ cent lower to 2{ cents higher with march at $6.13} a bushel
gold and silver futures retreated slightly on the commodity exchange in new york
but despite its weak tone, the market appeared to have shaken off the recessionary expectactions that had weighed on prices in recent weeks, said craig sloane, an analyst in new york with smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
gold settled 10 cents to 30 cents lower with april at $438.60 a troy ounce; silver was 3.2 cents to 3.5 cents lower with march at $6.395 a troy ounce
stock-index futures advanced on the chicago mercantile exchange, where the contract for march delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 index settled 1.10 points higher at 268.30. the underlying spot index closed nearly unchanged at 267.38
a federal judge said monday he will order a new election in the contested race for director of united auto workers union's eight-state southwest region, ending part of a 21-month legal battle
it's a victory for the people in region 5 who've had to operate without a legally elected director for 21 months,'' said jerry tucker, who lost by two-tenths of a vote to incumbent region 5 director kenneth worley in the august 1986 election
judge richard suhrheinrich of the u.s. district court for the eastern district of michigan heard arguments from attorneys for the u.s. department of labor, the uaw and tucker, assistant director of region 5 who was fired after he announced plans to run against his boss in may 1986
tucker is the leader of a dissident group within the uaw called the new directions movement, which has called for less cooperation with companies that are forcing workers to compete with each other for jobs
the labor department investigated the contest and called for new elections after it found some votes at the convention were cast by illegal delegates
it also found that worley spent $13,000 in union money on jackets bearing his name, which were distributed at the uaw constitutional convention where the delegates voted, and sent out campaign fliers typed with a uaw typewriter on uaw stationery in a uaw office
labor department attorney janet graney, who argued three lawsuits the department brought against the uaw concerning the election, said such uses of union money and equipment for the campaign of an individual are illegal
i'm going to order a new election. there have been substantial uses of union facilities'' for worley's campaign, suhrheinrich said, adding that he would issue a formal order in two weeks
the uaw declined comment until it receives the order. the union has said it is willing only to run some of the delegate elections over
in a new election, 68 local unions in missouri, kansas, oklahoma, arkansas, texas, louisiana, colorado and new mexico will again choose 650 delegates who will vote for the director of region 5 at a mini-convention
the elections will not affect terms of local union officials
suhrheinrich did not say how he would rule on one of the labor department suits, which charges tucker was illegally fired, or on a suit brought by tucker demanding reinstatement and payment of lost wages and benefits
tucker's attorney, joseph yablonski, and the labor department argued that tucker was fired illegally because the uaw constitution allows international union staff members to run for union office
they also argued that the rule used to fire tucker, which requires staff members running for office to take a leave of absence 90 days before the election, was never properly adopted by the union's leadership or by the rank-and-file
lee iacocca's second book, a meditation on lessons he has learned in business and private life and how they can be applied to modern problems, will go on sale june 1, his publisher announced monday
the book, entitled ``talking straight,'' was written with new york times reporter sonny kleinfield. a first printing of at least 500,000 copies is planned, according tom stuart applebaum, a spokesman for bantam books
iacocca draws upon his experiences he has had as son, husband, father, friend and chrysler corp. chairman to comment on the problems of wall street, washington and the world
he proposes fresh answers to some very tough questions that we face as individuals and as a nation, perhaps most important among them, how do we retrieve the values our parents and grandparents gave us?'' said linda grey, president and publisher of bantam
iacocca's first book, ``iacocca: an autobiography,'' has sold more than 2.6 million copies in hardcover; it was on the new york times bestseller list for 80 weeks, 40 of them in first place. it also has sold more than 3.5 million in paperback, and has been published in 18 languages
he has been working on the new book since october 1986
sir nicholas goodison said monday he is resigning at the end of the year as chairman of the london stock exchange, which he piloted through its ``big bang'' computer revolution in 1986 and the market crash last october
goodison, 53, will take over the chairmanship of the trustee savings bank next jan. 1
i have served on the stock exchange council for the past 20 years and been chairman for the past 12. i have been chairman during a period of great innovation and change and now feel that the structure for the future has been built,'' goodison said in a statement
an election among the stock exchange's members for a new chairman is likely in the fall
goodison in his new post succeeds sir john read, who will be 70 on march 29 and due for retirement this year from leadership of the trustee savings bank, which is a financial services group as well as a bank with 1.9 million investors
goodison has been chairman of stockbrokers quilter goodison co. ltd. since 1975
he said the stock crash of last october and november had nothing to do with his move, and that the old-style exchange could not have absorbed the wave of selling
when he became chairman, goodison was confronted with the then labor government's decision to reconstruct the stock exchange by separating market-makers and brokers into different partnerships
eleven years later came the big bang, on oct. 27, 1986, ending fixed commissions and the distinction between brokers who were agents in the buying and selling of shares and stock-jobbers who actively traded in shares at prices they quoted to brokers
bond prices fell modestly monday in light trading as the dollar drifted lower and a key commodity-price index edged higher
the treasury's 30-year bond fell ] point, or $3.75 for every $1,000 in face value, while its yield rose to 8.51 percent from 8.47 percent late friday
the bellwether issue had plunged $20 per $1,000 in face amount on friday, after the government reported unexpectedly high february employment levels, raising doubts about forecasts of an economic slowdown later this year
david hale, economist for kemper financial services in chicago, said the report prompted some investment firms to raise their economic growth forecasts. faster growth is generally viewed negatively in the bond market because credit demands increase when the economy expands, pushing interest rates up
sung won sohn, chief economist for norwest corp. in minneapolis, said the bond market was also hurt by a new decline in the dollar and a slight rise in the commodity research bureau index, mainly due to higher meat prices
a falling dollar reduces the yields available to foreign investors on dollar-denominated investments. it also raises pressure on domestic producers to keep prices low to compete with foreign products
meanwhile, interest rates rose from last week on short-term treasury securities sold in the government's latest auction
the treasury department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills at an average discount rate of 5.74 percent, up from 5.62 percent last week. another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 5.93 percent, up from 5.86 percent last week
the rates for three-month bills were the highest since feb. 1 when they sold for 5.74 percent. three-month bills sold for 5.85 percent on jan. 25. the rates for six-month bills were the highest since feb. 16 when they averaged 6.03 percent
in a separate report, the federal reserve said the average yield for one-year treasury bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, held steady at 6.63 percent last week, the same as the rate for the previous week
in the secondary market for treasury bonds, prices of short-term government issues slipped 2-32 point, intermediate maturities were down \ point and 20-year issues fell [ point, according to figures provided by telerate inc., a financial information service
the movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the price of a bond with a $1,000 face value
the merrill lynch daily treasury index, which measures price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with maturities of a year or longer, fell 0.17 to 112.97. the shearson lehman daily treasury bond index, which makes a similar measurement, lost 2.29 to 1,181.09
in corporate trading, industrials and utilities fell \ point in light trading, according to the investment firm of salomon brothers inc
moody's investment grade corporate bond index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, was off 0.64 to 283.78
yields on three-month treasury bills rose 2 basis points to 5.72 percent. a basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. six-month bills were unchanged at 5.95 percent and one-year bills rose 3 basis points to 6.30 percent
the federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, traded at 6| percent, up from 6{ percent late friday. offer</head>
american standard inc. said monday its board of directors would consider the latest hostile buyout offer from black &amp; decker corp. and indicated it might sweeten its own alternative plan a second time
black &amp; decker, which has been pursuing american standard since late january, last friday sweetened its outstanding tender offer to $73 a share from $68 for american standard's 31 million common shares outstanding, or a total of about $2.26 billion
that move came after american standard, a plumbing and air conditioning maker, sweetened its defensive recapitalization plan to $2.3 billion
the revised recapitalization announced friday would pay shareholders $64 in cash, $5 in securities and one share of stock in the recapitalized company for each old share. the earlier cash portion was $59 a share
american standard rose 75 cents to $73.25 a share monday on the new york stock exchange. black &amp; decker dipped 37{ cents to $18 a share, a decline stemming partly from an adjustment for a dividend payment
william b. boyd, american standard's chairman and chief executive, said the company's recapitalization plan already was financially superior to black &amp; decker's sweetened tender offer and advised shareholders not to tender their stock
in the meantime, stockholders should be aware that, if black &amp; decker increases its offer beyond the values we can achieve for our stockholders in a recapitalization, we would vigorously pursue other alternatives in order to enhance stockholder value,'' boyd stated
he also said american standard was ``working on ways to further improve'' its recapitalization plan, but did not elaborate
black &amp; decker, a towson, md.-based maker of tools and appliances, also has indicated it would attempt to win shareholder support for taking control of american standard's board of directors
loss-plagued lorimar-telepictures corp., which was formed two years ago by a merger but has seen its aggressive expansion plans disintegrate, said monday it is discussing the possibility of being acquired by warner communications inc
word of the negotiations helped push lorimar's stock price up $2.50 a share to $15. in the past year, the stock has traded as high as $25.25 and as low as $6.62{
i'd say the odds (of a takeover) are 50-50,'' said harold vogel, an entertainment industry analyst with merrill lynch in new york
he estimated the final price of a deal would be ``somewhere between $14 and the high teens.''
lorimar has about 45.9 million shares outstanding
in a brief statement, lorimar, a leading supplier of original television programming, said it was approached by new york-based warner and preliminary talks were under way ``to explore the desirability of a business combination.''
however, lorimar said its board has made no decision as to whether such a deal would be in the best interests of shareholders
the company also noted it has been approached about possible mergers in the past and nothing came of those overtures
the culver city-based company was formed in february 1986 by the stock-swap combination of lorimar inc., best known as the producer of such long-running television series as ``dallas'' and ``knots landing,'' and new york-based telepictures corp., which got most of its revenue from animated shows such as ``thundercats'' and such programs as ``peoples court'' and ``love connection.''
for the 1987-88 television season, the company is producing 12 hours of prime time and 16{ hours of syndicated shows, including ``the days and nights of molly dodd,'' ``mama's family,'' ``it's a living'' and ``she's the sheriff.''
for the first nine months of of its current fiscal year, lorimar posted a loss of $82.6 million on revenues of $616.8 million. the deficit included $45 million in writedowns on five movies and $22 million in reserves for possible future losses in its home-video unit
management of both its movie and home-video units was recently ousted
for fiscal 1987 ended last march 31, the company lost $58.6 million, mostly because of restructuring costs, on revenues of $766.2 million
in recent years, lorimar sought to expand far beyond its successful roots as a producer of television shows
it bought advertising agencies, sought to build a network of television stations and acquired a children's publishing unit, but it has shed most of those operations in a back-to-basics restructuring announced last june
the company has just completed the sale of the ad agencies _ bozell, jacobs, kenyon &amp; eckhardt inc. and poppe tyson inc. _ to members of their management for about $100 million, posting a pre-tax profit of $16 million
in late 1986, lorimar had agreed to buy seven big-city storer and wometco television stations from kohlberg, kravis &amp; roberts for $1.85 billion. the move would have given lorimar 12 stations around the u.s. and in puerto rico
however, the deal with kohlberg collapsed as the bottom fell out of the market for television stations, and the company has sold some of the stations it already owned and is seeking buyers for the remainder
the company also sold its children's publishing unit
warner is the parent of warner bros. studio, is a leading record producer and is a major cable television operator
warner's financial results have been strong
in 1987, its profit rose 77 percent to $328.1 million, or $2.09 a share, from $185.8 million, of $1.26 a share, the previous year
the 1987 figures included a net gain of $37.3 million on the sale of investments while the 1986 results included a gain of $48.4 million from the sale of investments and a gain from discontinued operations
revenue for 1987 rose 20 percent to $3.4 billion from $2.84 billion
its warner bros. film unit had the best year in its history, with an operating profit of $176.4 million, compared to $172.2 million in 1986
warner's music operation posted a 1987 operating profit of $213.9 million, up from $150.6 million, and operating profit from the cable and broadcasting division jumped to $46.1 million for the year from $16.2 million in 1986
although sales for the a.h. robins co. jumped 11 percent for the final three months of 1987, the pharmaceutical company reported a net loss of $1.69 billion for the period because of costs related to its dalkon shield birth-control device
robins said its loss in the period compared to a profit of $26.2 million, or $1.08 a share, in the same period a year earlier. revenue rose to $234.8 million from $210.8 million a year earlier
for all of 1987, robins suffered a loss of $1.63 billion compared to a profit of $81.8 million, or $3.38 a share, in 1986. revenue for the year rose to $855.8 million from $789.9 million
robins was forced to set aside $1.75 billion last year to help cover the costs of claims concerning women who were injured by the dalkon shield, which has been discontinued
the accrual represents the difference between the $2.30 billion provided in the company's fifth amended reorganization plan and the $548 million which remained from the reserve for dalkon shield claims established by the company in 1984
robins' results were also hurt by the costs of its chapter 11 reorganization in federal bankruptcy court
e. claiborne robins jr., the president and chief executive, said consumer products in the u.s., international operations and medical instruments were the principal contributors to the higher sales for the year
the teamsters union asked northwest airlines on monday to submit issues separating the company and its 6,500 flight attendants to binding arbitration
northwest airlines said it would not agree to arbitration but was willing to resume talks
william genoese, director of the teamsters airline division, said flight attendants were prepared to strike if the airline did not agree to arbitration in 72 hours
gov. james blanchard's administration backed the arbitration request, said state labor director betty howe, who joined genoese in a news conference at a teamsters office in detroit
the flight attendants, more than 2,000 of them based in detroit, have worked since a feb. 26 strike deadline, but no talks have been held for the past week
genoese cited economic and safety concerns as reasons for holding off on a strike this long
he referred to a federal aviation administration report friday on safety concerns at northwest airlines and said a strike would mean operating with less experienced replacement flight attendants. ``this would threaten both the comfort and safety of northwest passengers,'' he said
issues dividing the two sides include a two-tier wage system under which attendants hired after may 1984 must work five years to earn the same as those hired earlier. the airline proposes to extend the time to nine years
howe, ``without commenting on the merits of either side,'' said the blanchard administration is concerned about the detroit-based flight attendants' jobs and the potential economic impact of a strike
northwest airlines accounts for about half the air traffic in and out of detroit metropolitan airport, the largest of its three hubs. the airline operates about 248 flights a day at metro, about 227 at minneapolis, where it is headquartered, and 201 at its memphis, tenn., hub. families</head> ... to provide reaction. inserts 3 grafs after 19th graf pvs bgng: last may, ... with additional reaction. picks up 20th graf pvs bgng: jane smith ...; also moved on general newswires</note>
the federal government and rocket maker morton thiokol inc. paid $7,735,000 in cash and annuities and divided the cost 40-60 to settle all claims by the families of four of the astronauts who died in the challenger explosion
documents released monday showed that morton thiokol, which produced the faulty booster rocket blamed for the jan. 28, 1986, explosion, paid $4,641,000. the government's share of the settlements was $3,094,000
a lawyer who represented other family members called the settlements ``woefully inadequate.''
the surviving four spouses and six children actually will receive more than $7.7 million. this is because each was given an annuity, which pays benefits larger than its cost but over a period of many years
the total dollar amount the families will receive over time and the breakdown by family were not released
with the release of the documents, the justice department settled a civil suit brought under the freedom of information act by the associated press and six other news organizations. the government originally had kept details of the settlements and negotiations secret, saying it needed to keep its internal deliberations confidential and that the company and families demanded secrecy
the documents, with some deletions to preserve family privacy, included the final settlement agreements with the families and the company, some correspondence between the government and the company, and several justice department statements concerning the negotiations
the settlements were reached dec. 29, 1986, with the immediate survivors of spacecraft commander dick scobee, 46, a retired air force officer employed by the national aeronautics and space administration; mission specialist ellison s. onizuka, 39, an air force lieutenant colonel; payload specialist gregory jarvis, 41, an employee of hughes aircraft co.; and christa mcauliffe, 37, a concord, n.h., public high school teacher
scobee is survived by his wife, june, and two adult children; onizuka left his wife, lorna, and two minor children; jarvis left his wife, marcia; and mcauliffe left her husband, steven, and two minor children
among the disclosures:
_the four families had no lawyers during the negotiations. they relied instead on informal advice from leo b. lind jr., the law partner of mcauliffe's husband and executor of her estate
_the justice department did all the negotiating for morton thiokol as well as the government. lind said in an affidavit that the families never spoke to company officials
_the rocket maker and its insurers twice tried to have the settlements cover any property damage morton thiokol might have caused, such as destruction of the orbiter and payload. the government refused, and those claims are still in negotiation
_although the justice department claims it cannot legally be sued by the families of military or federal civilian employees who die on duty, it contributed 40 percent to each of the settlements. only the jarvis and mcauliffe relatives had a right to sue the government; all the astronaut families could sue the company
_even morton thiokol's attorneys said the government was being unfair to the divorced parents of mission specialist judith a. resnik, 36, a civilian nasa employee. ``my negotiations on behalf of morton thiokol have been constrained by the government's refusal to participate to any degree at all'' in a settlement the company considered acceptable, company attorney john w. adler wrote justice last july
michael d. oldak, resnik's ex-husband, represented her father, marvin, and last month reached a settlement with the company to which the government did not contribute
asked about the document release, oldak said monday, ``it confirmed our suspicion that the government had made a contribution to people in judy's situation, that is, government employees, and that we were being treated unfairly.''
marvin resnik said that settlement was ``commensurate with what some of the others got _ from $2 million to $3.5 million.''
in january, resnik's mother, sarah resnik belfer, and jarvis' father, bruce, settled with morton thiokol but the government did not contribute
last may, the company settled a suit by cheryl mcnair, wife of mission specialist ronald e. mcnair, 35, a civilian nasa employee who also left two infant children
ronald krist, the houston lawyer who represented bruce jarvis, sarah belfer and the mcnairs, said he would not have allowed his clients to accept such a ``woefully inadequate'' settlement as the four did
they would have netted more money if they had been adequately represented,'' krist said, even taking attorneys fees into account
betty grissom, whose husband gus was killed in the apollo one fire on the launch pad in 1967, said she was treated unjustly when it came to settlement of her claim against north american rockwell. ``it kind of hurts .... it hurts when i think that they're getting that much money,'' she said. she and her two children received $350,000
jane smith, wife of pilot michael j. smith, 40, a navy commander, has a suit pending in federal court against the company. the government last month was dismissed as a defendant, because military personnel may not sue the government for wrongful death
a presidential commission said the explosion occurred when hot gas leaked through a joint in a booster rocket built by thiokol and ignited the main fuel tank
a separate agreement between the government and morton thiokol asserted that disposal of the four claims in no way ``abrogates any claim of any nature which the united states may have against mti for property damage associated with the challenger accident, including but not limited to any claims for the loss of the orbiter itself,'' the document said. the replacement orbiter now under construction is expected to cost $3 billion
nasa spokesman david garrett said monday that negotiations are continuing between nasa and thiokol lawyers on the type and amount of penalties that will be imposed on the utah rocket-maker's contract with the government
a nasa statement in february 1987 said thiokol would forfeit $10 million in profit and receive no profit from $409 million worth of redesign work. but garrett said that does not end the matter
a tentative settlement reached early monday between the united auto workers union and chrysler corp., derailing the threat of a strike at a key sterling heights stamping plant
obviously, the company is hopeful that the workers will ratify the agreement and that the threat of a strike will disappear,'' chrysler spokesman lloyd northard said
sterling heights makes metal hoods and trunk lids for all domestically made chrysler cars and most trucks and makes fuel tanks for all chrysler cars except one
a strike there would soon have hurt all chrysler production, and additional strikes at a few other key plants could have crippled chrysler within days
uaw vice president marc stepp had joined negotiations between chrysler and uaw local 1264 on friday, a day after chrysler announced it would not sell its acustar inc. parts subsidiary
the union would have been the first to receive stepp's permission to strike over local issues such as health-and-safety grievances and violation of work rules
stepp had promised to give immediate strike authorization to all locals with legitimate grievances. but after chrysler decided to keep its 28,000-worker acustar subsidiary, he began moving to resolve local disputes
stepp and other negotiators bargained through the weekend and reached a tentative settlement on local 1264's grievances at 5 a.m. monday, the union said. stepp was unavailable for comment monday
the union said it was withholding details of the agreement until march 11, when the local's 3,600 active and 500 laid-off members will vote on the settlement
we saved a lot of jobs and got additional jobs,'' said fred o'brien, local 1264 recording secretary and a member of the local's bargaining committee
o'brien said chrysler agreed to add workers to clean up oil that leaks from the plants massive presses onto the shop floor and to clean and repair the machines as a matter of routine
workers had complained that because the presses are run around the clock, they don't receive adequate maintenance, particularly cleaning, and the machines and the floors around them are covered with oil and dirt
local 1264 had accumulated nearly 140 unresolved grievances since last year. other locals had been gathering grievances so they could be ready to strike if chrysler had decided to sell acustar
homestake mining co. rejected as inadequate an unsolicited $1.88 billion buyout offer from the partnership led by t. boone pickens on monday and said it wished to remain independent
the board of directors of homestake, the nation's biggest gold producer, unanimously rejected the $20 a share buyout offer made last month by pickens' mesa limited partnership
homestake stock closed at $17.12{ a share monday on the new york stock exchange, unchanged from friday's close
pickens had labeled the buyout offer a friendly bid and proposed a negotiated transaction with homestake's managers
but homestake's board concluded the offer was inadequate and not in the best interests of the stockholders, said company officials
in light of our business prospects, we are better off served as an independent company, said stephanie kushner, homestake's manager of financial services. ``we are trying to focus on the financial future of the company.''
we're really in a strong position right now with significant cash assets and a very strong balance sheet, and our management is in a better position to put that money to work for the company,'' kushner stated
homestake, one of the largest gold producers in the western world outside of south africa, owns the homestake gold mine in south dakota and the mclaughlin mine in northern california. the company also has a one-quarter interest in the round mountain mine in nevada
in addition, homestake owns a 42.5 percent interest in the doe run co., the largest u.s. producer of lead products, and a 48 percent interest in two mines in western australia
kushner noted pickens had not made a tender offer to homestake shareholders, and she was unsure whether he would now pursue a hostile takeover in light of the board's rejection
the offer was pickens' second move on a gold-mining company in six months. his $2 billion takeover attempt for new york-based newmont mining corp. was blocked when newmont's biggest shareholder, consolidated gold fields plc, acquired a controlling stake in the company to help thwart the hostile bid. writer's quote, other detail; picks up 7th graf, `producers claim ...'</note>
striking scriptwriters warned that their walkout would send tv soap operas, talk shows and variety programs into reruns, but producers said monday they have stockpiled enough scripts to ride out a long strike
movie and television scriptwriters left their typewriters and joined nearly 2,000 colleagues on a picket line at 20th century fox studios in a contract dispute over the issues of residuals and creative control
carrying placards reading ``the writers guild strikes,'' pickets five-abreast snaked in front of the fox studios in west los angeles
hollywood has treated writers like bean-field workers for years,'' said screenwriter and science fiction author harlan ellison. ``it begins with the dream. without the dream on paper, there is nothing.''
the writers guild of america rejected sunday's final offer by the alliance of motion picture and television producers and a strike was ordered for 9,000 of its 9,600 members. six hundred news writers were exempt
we feel all the issues were dealt with fairly. they went on strike on issues we felt were resolved,'' alliance spokesman herb steinberg said, adding producers were ``ready to write a check for $550 million'' for a new three-year contract. the alliance represents about 200 producers and studios
the federal mediation and conciliation service scheduled a meeting for both sides tuesday
issues include demands by writers for a higher percentage of foreign market distribution residuals, and an offer by producers to scale back syndication residuals for one-hour television shows
producers claim new shows made for independent stations have dried up the rerun syndication market. their offer includes an increase to 150 percent of current residual agreements if the show does well in syndication
writers claim the offer is not equitable with a similar deal given the directors guild last summer
actress patty duke, president of the screen actors guild, also showed up on the picket line to show solidarity with the writers, but the actors contract prohibits secondary walkouts
the union said talk shows, game shows and soap operas would quickly reflect the strike's impact, but producers said scripts had been stockpiled and that many prime-time shows had completed shooting for the season
viewers will begin seeing the effects on those programs relying on scripts on a daily basis. talk shows, game shows and the soaps will see a difference right away,'' guild spokeswoman cheryl rhoden said
a three-month strike delayed the fall television season in 1981
it's business as usual. we're prepared,'' cbs spokeswoman janet storm said. the network produces the soaps ``guiding light,'' ``as the world turns,'' ``the bold and the beautiful'' and ``the young and the restless.''
nbc spokesman dom giofre said the network's ``another world,'' ``days of our lives'' and ``santa barbara,'' wouldn't be affected soon because there were scripts already written for another month
the strike won't immediately effect nbc's ``late night with david letterman'' and ``saturday night live,'' which were already on scheduled breaks. ``the tonight show with johnny carson'' featured guest host jay leno on monday, as scheduled. but the comedian used material prepared before the strike, giofre said
on daily production shows such as soap operas, writers normally turn out scripts near shooting schedule deadlines. shows like ``late night with david letterman'' are known for ad-lib lines, but much of the monologue and skits are created by a writing staff. since much of the material is topical, it often is written within minutes of showtime
picket captain stanley ralph ross said selection of fox ``was fairly arbitrary,'' adding its size and location had a lot to do with it. ``we usually pick a major studio, and there's parking around here.''
the guild's contract expired at midnight feb. 29
producers had sought to scale back residual payments for some one-hour shows syndicated in the united states and said they couldn't pay writers more for reruns in foreign markets
steinberg claimed foreign residual payments have increased 84.6 percent since 1972, which was the last time writers negotiated that issue. writers receive a single lump sum that varies depending on what is negotiated between the writer and producer
when the business is good, they are going to share it,'' steinberg said. ``but while we're making money in foreign, we're still losing money in domestic, and that foreign distribution money has to cover those losses.''
the median annual income for writers is $40,000 a year, but about half of the wga's members are unemployed at any given time, ms. rhoden said
central bank president fernando milliet resigned monday and the government fired the president of the semi-official banco do brasil, camilo calazans, officials said
no immediate explanation was given for the dismissals
milliet, the fourth central bank president under brazil's 3-year-old civilian regime, was in charge of negotiating the refinancing of brazil's huge $113 billion foreign debt
milliet was to be replaced by elmo de araujo camoes, an experienced banker with the banco do brasil, the sao paulo state bank banespa and the sogeral bank. he is a member of the government's national monetary council
calazans, an economist who used to head the government's coffee agency, reportedly disagreed with finance minister mailson da nobrega about wage restrictions for federal employees. da nobrega favored a wage freeze to reduce the federal deficit, but calazans nevertheless granted a raise for banco do brasil employees
calazans was to be replaced by mario gusmao berard, the secretary-general of the finance ministery and closely tied to da nobrega
